text: forms a nice pillowy 2 finger head . great lacing on the glass and a lovely burnt orange color .  very smooth and not overpowering though . i wish this beer was n't so thin . i would 've liked it to have some more body .

pours a deep oil-like black with a large foamy tan head on top . retention is perfect , leaving with it beautiful lacing rings . smells average for a stout .  if you 're looking to watch those love-handels , like amstel , this may be something to consider . it lacks flavour and proves to be very bland which is emphasised by it 's cardboard-like aftertaste . one positive , is that it 's very easy to drink if you can put the taste ( or lack there of ) aside .
intense nose . vinegar notes , but not as overpowering as some others of the style . nice .  m - goes down as easy as any ipa would .
very clean . wonderful .  mouthfeel is very light and highly carbonated .

s : lots and lots of hops ! wonderful smell as well . t : just as i thought , lots of hops and citrus . i loved almost everything about this beer except the tast .  mouthfeel seems little light for a big stout the carbonation level does n't help with lightness either .
the lacing was amazing , so amazing i had to give it a top score on appearance .  m : it was watery with some carbonation .

bomber poured into a tulip . pours a semi-cloudy bright orange with an off-white head that slowly dies down to a chunky layer of foam . wonderful spiderweb lacing left behind on the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel was average but could have used more texture .
pours a black which light can shine through . beautiful creamy head that is n't going anywhere .  m : thinner side of medium in body , carbonation is medium as well but falls off fast .

locals love this beer but i cant handle it . talk about bitter beer face . it 's so bitter , you ca n't taste any of the underlying flavors or really enjoy it .  slightly darker copper appreance . nice strong stench that fills your nostrils . it has a very unique strong taste at first but leaves a nice smooth after taste . i have never had it on tap but bottled is just as good i assume . highly suggested if you have not tried and are a big bock fan ...

i had this beer poured from a can into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a light amber color , with some golden highlights and a small white head with minimal lacing ... s : the smell the best part , nice and hoppy ... t : after the hoppy aroma , i was very unhoppy ( pun intended ) to find a dearth of hoppiness . more sweet and malt than hoppy , and this is a fresh can ( from june 25th ) ... m : a little too chewy for an apa , at least , imo ... d : eh , its not bad , but i prefer snpa over this one .  mouthfeel was kind of thin for the serving style .
towering , monstrous , intimidating tan head .  palate is average , could be more carbonated .

a wonderful looking beer with its dark amber color and large white head that had a great deal of staying power .  m : a light bodied beer that has a decent amount of carbonation and some robust drying qualities , sometimes a bit too much .
huge frothy head even when i poured it ultra slow .  almost like drinking beef jerky . there is very little in the way of hops and just a small bit of malt on the back end .

behold his venom and vengeance , both sweet and tempting , enticing you , his spellbound victim , within his wings '' . the appearance is a beautifull shade of ruby red with astonishing clarity . pours with a healthy dose of white foam that 's short lived and disappointing . the sweetness is unmistakable and addicting . starts off very sweet but ends slitely hot and dry . overall this was a decent beer which had a considerable amount of age on it .  m- a little syrupy , actually ... thicker than i 'd like to see for a single ipa o- love it .

this is a *good* weizenbock with an amazing smell ! taste was a slightly above average , and even with an above average taste , after the incredible smell , even 3.5 was a bit disappointing !  mouthfeel is medium bodied , but seemingly watery with a very low dose of carbonation .

s : now i truly know what pine aroma hops smell like . wow , excellent . also some very noticeable fresh cut grass character . d , notes : i really liked this beer .  a little too carbonated for my liking . a little smoothness would help .
s : the nose is amazing . roasted malt leads to a coffee aroma with vanilla and cocoa in the background .  the palate is average for the style .

summer 2007 release poured into an oversized wine glass a- big thick mountainous three fingered off white head over a slightly hazy golden orange brew ... more lace than a victoria 's secret runway show s- awesome ... perfect ... not too overpowering but full of floral and citrus hops with a sweet caramelized orange and malt background ... a nose that most other dipa 's should bow down to t- less complex than the smell ... big citrus hops ... very oily ... slightly sweet malt background ... finish is dry but refreshing ... a little lighter than expected m- again a little lighter bodied than expected ... good carbonation d- excellent ... a dipa that does n't need a huge abv to bolden the taste i think future reviews on this will be even better ... the summer would be perfect in the summer at a barbecue due to it 's lighter qualities ... i made the mistake of waiting for the first colder day we 've had to review this and it definitely affected the review ... ca n't wait to get my hands on the winter and try it in the correct season  fault : it lacks a little body , but hay , i could drink this to i fell over ( with a smile on my face ) !
delicious smell ! i could sit and sniff at this all day .  light in body though it does n't live up to the initial crispness of the nose . carbonation seems appropriate .
nice . t - suprisingly flat .  the smoked malt is a bit harsh on the palette , and the beer lacks enough body to temper the rough edges in this department .

nose is lovely , with sweet orange and lilting pepper spice and a smooth almost creamy vanilla undertone that is cut and set off by the citric twang . an absolutely superlative witbier nose . quite marvellous . taste is also good , but lighter , as it should be . exceptionally good witbier , and indeed one of the pinnacles of the style .  mouthfeel is very thin and almost flat , which suits the scotch flavors but is a little off-putting from a beer perspective .
it pours a deep copper color with three fingers of towering head . there is a good amount of lacing .  mouthfeel was a little more watery than i expected .
app : big pillowy off white head over a very dark brown borderline black with ruby hints body . great lacing , looks phenomenal .  m - very light , slightly watery .

pours very dark and clear brown with large and dense off-white head that lasts for ages , thick patchy lacing .  mouthfeel is somewhat grainy and perhaps a little more carbonated than i 'd like this style to be .

nose was of light citrus , vanilla , oak , light apple brandy , and fresh cut pvc .  glass : two taster glasses from pib sib , and a duvel glass ( the duvel glass held the best head which is not surprising ) it pours golden with a strong off white quarter inch head ; immaculate lacing as its fingers drip softly down the glass . deep tones of pine and citrus , with subtle notes of bourbon . first sip brings hints of caramel , and the finish is dry with a slight fruit aftertaste .

smell is delightfully hoppy and citrusy , the nose is easily the best thing about this beer and the presence really makes itself known , although the aroma fades as the beer empties , the initial scent is quite good . for a cask , the carbonation is obviously low , quite low , but slight present and more-so than a typical rare lost abbey , the citrusy hop bite is at first evident , this beer pretty much pushes the pale ale/ipa boundary to the max , after a full pint the lack of carbonation starts to get to me but i wo n't fault that since it 's part of the cask experience , the malt background is way in the background and is n't something i would really note at all .  body is a bit thin and alcohol is slightly burning but nothing out of control .

s : a nice amount of yeast , wet hay , pepper , pineapples , lemons and orange peel kind of an odd but inviting mix . o : after the look and smell of this beer , i was quite excited . it was disappointing .  m : the body is quite light , too light i think . the carbonation is slightly too mellow , i would have liked it to be a little livelier and sparkling .

the nose is a delight . it has a milkshake like nose with some caramel , nice roasted malts , nice chocolately tones all over it .  light in body , but not watery . a small amount of carbonation livens the beer , but does not define it .
smell : a good deep fresh cherry aroma .  and maybe just a little bit more carbonation maybe ?

s : quite the delicious nose ... spices , peach , plum , a slight crisp hops edge , orange , caramel , and a dry biscuity malt mixed in low . t : a bit of a letdown after that incredible nose ... not bad , just much simpler than i had expected ... diacetyl , caramel , light generic hops , perhaps a bit on the citrus side , brown sugar , cream , high carbonation keeps it all fairly light . d : satisfying .  m : fairly light-bodied with champagne-like carbonation . a bit rough on the palate . the brett is a bit too dominant , and the mouthfeel is a bit too carbonated , but otherwise , quite nice .

the nose is stunning when it warms ( it was served very cold ) . the rum really shines . t : sweet toffee with notes of date and prune .  mouthfeel is hurt a bit by this beer 's charictaristic carbonation .
a : opaque black , decent tan head , good lacing .  light body that feels a little thin until the moderate carbonation helps with the texture close to the finish .
a : deep amber/mahogany , minimal head . nice lacing and plenty of carbonation bubbles oozing from her .  m- a little on the thin side , but the carbonation level is pleasant .
first impression was the darkness . it really is dark ... almost black like coffee .  the mouthfeel was thin in body , but huge in taste .

a- lovely , clear , medium amber-red with a 2-finger , dense , rocky off-white head with great retention . leaves a few clumps of lacing .  full taste , slight choc/coff flavors and no alcohol flavor , it 's buried in the taste of the beer . it 's average when the fizz goes away and seems a little watery and the only thing missing over the cumberland 's porter is the aftertaste did not last and it seemed to miss a note inside the flavor . when i went back a week later , it was n't the same porter i 'd tasted , and was more like the other ringneck beers .
pours a pitch black with a thick , frothy brown head into my glass .  feels really thicker than it looked .

smell - incredible ! ! ! very similar to gumballhead and dreadnaught . i could smell this beer all day but eventually thirst takes over and i have to drink . taste : very well balanced . i could taste the maltiness and the slight hop bitterness but they combined for an incredible experience .  i had this bozone hefe weizen first time out of a growler filled at the bozone brewery in bozeman , mt . shit tasted soo good , and i needed moore . i fancy myself a ipa kinda guy , but this hef is like none other around . maybe a couple , but its dayum goood . not only does this beer taste great , but the color is beautiful . get some and get drunk !

the aroma of this brew is rich malty sweetness coming across a bit like oranges from the hops with a sting of noticeable alcohol character that pierces the nose . dark sugary and floral sweetness lingers that smells a lot like caramel .  mouthfeel is light with less than average carbonation and slight alcohol warming can be felt .

the sharp sting of the hops shot out as i opened the bottle - i could smell it three feet away . the aroma is biting and piny , with waves of bitter citrus .  mouthfeel fell a little short , but only because the carbonation was so low . felt okay , but with more carbonation it would be much better .

cloves , sweet cherries , banana . big time yeasty , lightly sweet , bananas and cloves . good price on this , but prefer schneider aventinus .  light to medium mouth feel . tastes great.full flavor , with a little bite . for a dark beer it 's refreshing .

opens with a vigorous whoosh and despite a gentle decant , foams up quickly , forming a meringue-like light tan head which peaks out of the glass about 2 inches , and leaving sticky gobs of foam on the glass as it recedes . cloudy mahogany , near black .  it has a very thin mouthfeel .

some spices and slight cinnamon present as well creating a complex yet amazing aroma . it almost makes you regret drinking the beer when it smells this good . t : tastes very much like a heavy wheat and malty beer .  m- the carb is a little rougher than i prefer for my porters ... aftertaste is kind of burnt .

d - the malt character in the aroma is very nice , but the flavor does not quite live up to the promise .  m - good mouthfeel , though again similar to a stout . feels a little thin with the appropriate amount of carbonation .

this beer had to settle for a minute before it left a 1/4 white head . impressive ! ! !  like an overpowering mix of graham cracker , butter popcorn jelly belly 's and allspice . take everything in the scent notes and add lemon citrus notes plus the potent 8.6 % alcohol and you have a recipe for disaster . the taste lingers and lingers . i truly , truly suffered through a bomber of this . my wife had about two sips and nearly gagged . i 've never been a fan of `` pumpkin '' beers , since there is never any pumpkin/squash taste and only `` pie spice '' , but was told that this was one of the better ones . this just reaffirms my belief that `` pumpkin beer '' is a complete waste of brewers ' time and effort , but it 's such a moneymaker that they ca n't refuse to make it . do yourself a favor and steer clear of this abomination of beer .

on tap it has a very predominant fresh hop aroma with a gentle sweet backbone . they were n't over powering , but definitely made them selves known . i love fresh hops , so this was nearly heaven for me .  smells a lot like hershey 's syrup with an alcoholic backbone . i think this beer just stained my counter -- this beast is thick , too thick for me to drink .

in a line-up of nitro-tap stouts , they all look pretty much the same . the taste is the trademark irish stout as everyone else has comprehensively explained , but drinking three of these versus three guinness and you will feel slightly less full .  the mouthfeel is a little anemic , with a lingering aftertaste .

a : pours a bright , clear , bronze color with a fluffy white head , that really wants to stick around .  the body is heavier than i 'm used to for a wit , and while i 'm usually extremely impressed with great lakes approach to mouthfeel , i find this one a little too heavy for the style .

this is an exceptional looking beer !  next to no carbonation left - leaving the mouthfeel much thinner than would be preferred , even for a barleywine or a barleywine that has been allowed to sit for a while .
smell is ridiculously potent . i like .  m - on tap at least it 's a little over carbed for my tastes , but i like my beers on the lighter side of carbed . medium-light body .

some nuts , cinnamon ... awesome aromas ! t- pumpkin pie again .  taste : same as the nose mouthfeel : medium bodied , under carbonated drinkability : alcohol is amazingly absent but the lack of carbonation holds it back a bit .

was beautiful smell : loaded hops , and chocolate taste : rich and slight chocolate roasted flavors but had a unpleasant aftertaste mouthfeel : good carbonation and very tasty drinkability : ok. not horrible  m : fairly thick but not necessarily creamy . medium-heavy with a mid-range carbonation .

a bit grassy , a bit earthy , but overall just smells great ! i really dig the way this one smells . t - again , quite good , but not as great as the nose suggests . all about the nose on this one ... really smells fantastic . beyond that , a solid ipa .  before expanding my palate yuengling used to be my favorite beer . i gre up in the dc area so we had plenty of it around . i still consider this a great beer for a night full of drinking , but not one that i would drink because i want to enjoy a beer . i still love you yuengling and i ca n't wait to have you again ... stupid yuengling does n't ship to ca .

pretty pour into tulip glass at about 50 degrees . about 3-4f tight , white head over a murky orange-to-golden color body . plenty of lacing .  mouthfeel : the high carbonation is the only shortcoming of this beer .

appearance : gorgeous , swirling currents of ultrafine bubbles that coalesce into a thick , creamy , egg nog-colored head atop a clear , rusty , bengal orange-colored body .  mouthfeel takes a hit for thinness , though it 's not at all watery and would be difficult to have it be much thicker and work with the wine elements .
a really pretty beer .  m- medium , with low carbonation .

plays nicely with light -- almost glows . lovely white long lasting head , and when it goes a thick cap with proofing-bread-yeast-sized bubbles remains .  s- mmm chocolate . d- as far as taste goes this beer is delicious , yet again not complex but very chocolate and the low alcohol is completely hidden , so id have to say the low abv works in its favor m- thin not exactly watery but still thinner than i would like in a flavorful beer .

sweet honey aroma with sugar dipped fruits and happy spices .  there is a slight fruitiness going down that leaves a pleasant finish . drinkability : this is a very drinkable beer , and one of the best of bg 's light beers .
this looks fantastic . s- coffee , dark chocolate , grassy and citrusy hops , and that distinctive three floyds smell .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and kind of watery .

deep black with maybe the slightest brown highlights , and a dense , creamy , lasting brown head . looks spectacular .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel , slightly syrupy , okay amount of carbonation , some hop tingle on the tongue , a bit bitter , and leaves mouth with a sweet/stickey feel and very slight dry feel .
spicey , peppery aroma evident the moment the cap is popped .  mouth , although nicely coating , is thinner than i would have preferred .
aroma certainly in check - good ! a great deal of that distinct baltic chocolaty , tary , brandy like aroma .  m : nothing special here , light and easy on the palate .
this poured a beautiful clear copper lots of bubbles and creamy collar .  the texture was thick , and left a thin film in my mouth almost like when you eat too much syrup .

yakima hops are the best smelling hop that i have found . hops jump out . sweet smelling . a hint of floral . very enjoyable . m - fairly strong carbonation , with a bit of head .  m - silky , almost to the point of feeling oily .

pours a deep black body with a firm khaki head smells thick of cocoa , mocha and roated barley taste of sweet caramel , thick chocolate , a little dry mocha and some nice roasted malts .  seems a little thin compared to others in the style , almost watery in the finish which is the only thing really detracting on this one for me .

nitro can purchased in england a : looks a lot like a guinness but glowing amber in color with a thick creamy head that lasts the entire session . a thing of beauty !  this beer pours a dark brown but is clear enough and still enough that you can almost see through it . the taste is nice with a nice roasted malt character . i believe i can detect a little bit of a caramel malt type of flavor in the undertones . elegantly simple and extremely drinkable .

everything is under control now ... picturesque dark golden amber . mountainous beige head recedes slowly , leaving cloud-like piles of foam .  very fizzy , easy to drink . light caramel flavors dominate when carbonation has n't taken hold already.. fresh baked bread and nothing offensively bold in terms of the holy trinity of yeast , banana & clove . finishes a bit salty , leaving behind a oceanic yet grainy aftertaste which is a little strange.. and honestly , the only real drawback to this beer .

s - very unique ipa aroma . very earthy with floral and piney notes . a very unique ipa taste .  winish , also slightly floral , the start is mildly sweet , the top skimpy . finish purposeful in its acidity , the hops masterful in their spicy bite and the aftertaste long lasting and quite bitter .
this one releases with a loud crack and pours a very thick , cheerful snow-white head over a thin , straw-colored , only slightly cloudy body .  m - sharp carbonation is a little oveer the top .

very brown , not very clear ... s - very nutty . by far the most deep brown i 've had ( yes , mis-categorized ) perfect for a brown .  this is by far the worst brown ale that i have ever tried . it looks and smells ok and the mouth is decent but it just tastes bad ... i cant explain it .
a- pours a dark , opaque black with one of the darkest heads i have ever seen . leaves little to no lacing .  m : creamy , but kind of thin .

just an awesome aroma , and one i kept returning to before my glass emptied . pretty good , but a step back from the smell . closer to a 4.25 in my book , but i was generous elsewhere . d - i liked this almost as much as the berliner weiss and may just have to seek out another bottle .  t/m - starts out smooth and thick feeling with a light caramel malt flavor . a sharp bitterness and carbonation bite hit and the malty flavor increases and becomes sweeter . d - i see nothing `` belgian '' about this beer , but for a bock i think its very good .

very well balanced . taste- a bit overly bitter for the style .  medium body with the tight carbonation found in the style . this one happens to be a little under carbonated for my tastes , but perhaps it is the batch .

look is straight up orange , one inch fluffy cream colored head sinks to half its original volume , very nice lacing as well .  s -- caramel , toffee t- it probably has more ibu 's than the typical db , but the traditional/textbook db flavors are all there . m- moderate ( a little `` lighter '' than the typical db . ) d-this is a very drinkable double bock .
interesting . t : chocolate and pecans and a little sweet vanilla .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with little carbonation .
a - black body , light mocha foam that has good retention , leaving glass-coating lace behind .  i 'd call this one dangerous winter warmer .

im told by the server , that this beer is based on an ancient recipe , and is brewed without hops the beer list says it is brewed with yarrow , lavender , dandelion root , and ginger a - this beer is a ruddy , clean , crisp , rusty color , with no intrusions from carbonation , with a half finger of fizzy head that evaporates quickly s - wow , spicy , big lavender and ginger , with ambient floral notes like honeysuckle , ana amzing aroma , especially for the late spring early summer weather t - in the taste , the ginger comes to the front and is upported by the lavender , the reverse of the aroma , again floral notes and slight tea like characteristics m & d - clean and crisp , this beer is easily drinkable , feels ( not tastes ) more like im drinking a floral/flavored iced teadthan a brew , the abv wasnt listed , but must be low , im guessing mid 4 's to 6ish .  body is a little thin , lacking that creamy mouthfeel that would make this beer better .

a terrific deep and burnt umbre with tremendous clarity topped by a dense head that receded over a minute .  i had this year 's version at the brewpub and while it is not as good as great lakes ' christmas beer or sn celebration , it is still a very good beer . you can really smell the cinnamon and taste the blend of malts and spices . if you are in the toledo area it is worth the stop at maumee bay brewing co. for a pint or three or maybe a stop at the andersons or other store for a bomber .
pours out a head , 1.5 inches in my glass , that has lasting power and laces the glass as a it fades . the tan foan sits atop a nearly black body .  body is a touch too thin .

shared with two other bas at our recent gathering ; poured into my bruery tulip . deep dark brown - nearly black . a thick soft four finger dark tan head rises quickly and very slowly diminishes to one finger , leaving copious amounts of sticky lace .  nice caramel notes on the front , just hate the feel and finish ... the alcohol is hidden very well , despite the finish still easy to drink . too much harsh hops for me to love it , but this is still pretty good and worth trying

appearance : this beer looks like double bastard on steroids !  m - crisp and refreshing for sure . almost no carbonation on the tongue but the beer is still carbonated though i would n't say its `` smooth per se '' .

sampling a 2004 version of this ale , sent to me by my buddy sulldaddy . it pours a chestnut/ruby color with a slightly fizzy head that lessened to a slight edge layer with minimal lacing on the glass ; very clean looking ale , which is always nice . aroma up front is vanilla with an underlying sour aroma with dry oak aromas throughout as well ; lots of alcohol on the sniff which killed some aromas ; reminded me a lot of a bourbon or maybe even a dry sherry . i loved this one really .  sure , the mouthfeel was ok , but it did nothing to improve the taste .

it looks like a classic marzen , with a deep auburn transparent color that almost glows in the late summer light . but , unlike many marzens , this one pours an outstanding soft white head that pumps up to three fingers deep , and has great retention over a leisurely quaff , leaving a lovely diffuse lacing on the glass as you go .  the mouthfeel is average , as is the carbonation level .

i 'd drink one , get disgusted , and a couple months later i 'd think `` nah , must have been a bad bottle '' and i buy another which provides the same results . it looked great so i ca n't knock that .  smell was average , mouthfeel a bit on the thin side .
a : an golden amber body with a dense and creamy white head ; loads of lacing and good head retention .  mouthfeel was decent , although rather watery .

berklgiany floral aroma , sweet . honey . floral taste , very light , carbonated sweet taste . good but a little heavy for my taste .  m : body is on the light side of moderate . carbonation is on the high side of moderate ( a little much ) .

very clean and sharp looking bronze color with a huge , fluffy , pale caramel colored head on top .  first of all , this beer predates the craft beer era . it 's makers brew a tastey brown lager that they call a porter , and they make this delicious pilsner that they call an ale . they were doing this when our fathers were toasting our european heritage with schlitz . it is light bodied , as it should be , and very drinkable . i suppose i can understand that if someone was expecting an ale they might misjudge this beer - but close your eyes , forget your encyclopedeaic knowledge of beer names - and imagine a time in 1975 when the best pilsner on the east coast was called an ale .
the color is a charming dark straw color with a viscous , oily texture .  light mouthfeel .
very good looking ipa .  3.0 m : light body , too light for my liking .

s - best smelling ipa i have had . sweet floral . it is definitely good , but has room for improvement .  what happened pete ? ? this was once a distinctive brown/nut brown ale , but since being bought out , this beer has fallen quite a few notches . to my tastebuds this is just a mere shadow of it 's former self . i forget where i read it , but someone said the whole portfolio seems to have been `` tweaked '' , with dissappointing results .

appearance : pours with a massive 3 1/2 finger dense , white head . the beer itself is a golden honey with a massive amount of activity ; a torrent rises from the nucleation site .  the mouthfeel is strange . there is consistently this sharp little flavor in the background , but the body is medium , maybe a bit more full , and the carbonation is pleasantly on the low side of sharp .
the smell is very nelson , pungent and fruity at the same time , almost a touch sour . very nice , great use of a great hops .  feels light bodied with tons of carbonation .
pretty heavy lacing as well .  moutfeel is about right , seems to be a bit high on the carbonation for me though , but i can deal with that .

appearance : pours very dark with a creamy just off white nitro head . i got to say that when it comes to classy looking beers ... this one takes the cake , it literally pours perfect every time .  smoke lends clean dry finish to this smooth , medium bodied stout-like beer with flat carbonation .
poured a great dark coppery orange , very clean with just a touch of haze , giant thick and fluffy off white head , very sticky with nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little uneventful .

smell : complex , not overpowering . taste and mouthfeel : for me , it did n't live up to the promise of the aroma . first sweet , like pastry icing , then bready and substantial . more subtle than complex , which was a disappointment after the magnificent smell . mouthfeel was unfortunately lighter than expected . like food which smells better than it tastes , this one is almost better to sample than consume .  m - the feel is nothing special ; kind of thin and light on carbonation .

carbonation heads topside at a regular pace , and lacing left behind is superb . great looking bier !  medium bodied , highly carbonated and prickly from the hops . i 'm a little put off by the amount of carbonation and i prefer the sweeter stouts .

the beer looks terrific in this glass , like something out of an advertisement , the head and color and perfect for belgian style , it is a perfect maroon/red color with a frothy cream colored head , though not the dark color i expected .  the body is a bit on the thin side , which is n't bad for the style , but does n't do anything to set this beer apart .
a - poured into a pint glass , attractive amber body . very good head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and smooth . about par for the style .

appearance : fluffy , white head sits atop a cloudy , dark , straw pilsner . laces on one side and retains its head superbly .  and now i know why people say it tastes like chocolate syrup , because it kinda does . but this is really good if you like chocolate . probably 1200 calories in this bottle . but who 's drinking beer and watching calories ?
heavy layer of creamy white head with just a few bubbles .  m : who cares ?
outstanding aroma . deep roasted malts , toasty , rich , and deep . due to the great aroma , i found the flavor to be a let down .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , a bit drying on the back end .

appearance is quite nice , decent head , dissipation about normal for a barleywine .  m : quite creamy , but rather thin bodied ( kind of like guinness , really ) , with a slightly dry and underwhelming finish .

smell - oh my got big smell of candied apricot with a floral nose at the top of the glass . i 'm not sure i 'd want this back to back a good fruit beer with an amazing nose . i 'd surely buy this again i have alot of friends that would like it .  m : here is my biggest complaint about this beer . it 's just hard for me to get past that much carbonation . d : despite the issue with the overwhelming carbonation .
aroma is great . there 's a citric grapefruit/orange flavor in there . really nice .  m= light as hell . medium and average all around .
impressive lacing left behind , and really nice retention .  m- i would like just a tad more on the mouth feel but it works well with the hoppiness of this beer .

bottle into a dimpled glass mug , beer thanks to mikesgroove : - ) a : pours very dark brown , nearly black , looks `` burnt '' and features a big pillowy beige head .  m : at first , the mouthfeel was a bit thin .

aroma is a touch unpleasant with some funkiness that reminds me of mushrooms or manure ... but as the glass warms some more fragrant , inviting aromas come out : pear , warming spices , tobacco , wood resin , caramel malts , candied oranges . quite nice and comforting . on the palate , citric nips first off , subtle carbonation , tea-like mid-palate , sweetening as it goes along , and a resiny-sweet finish .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a imperial pint glass . has notes of citrus and pine hops plus some apricot hints in there too . first taste it has upfront hop taste like a 90 minute ipa with a smooth fruity taste on the finish . this beer is a very refreshing ipa with a not to much fruit back but just enough to make it refreshing .
dark amber-brown with a big , dense tan head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and slightly over carbonated for my tastes .

it 's pitch black . the head is the usual nitrogenous thick and creamy sort . always a pleasure to admire the appearance of these stouts . i did n't get much out of the aroma , a little bit of roasted maltiness .  the aroma is all one note with lots of sweetn raspberries . the beer is very light , it goes right down without much lasting flavor .

this is a great looking beer , but that 's one of the few things that this beer really has going for it . this glowing liquid ruby supports a nice thick fluffy white head with a decent retention and a great lacing . furthermore , the carbonation erupts from the bottom of the glass in several different spirals further making this beauty shimmer . unfortunately all other areas of this beer were kind of a let down for me .  hirter morchl is entirely different from this . my main gripes are that the body is light ... extremely light , but a lack of complexity is something rather commonplace in this style of beer . the remarkably dry finish of this beer really seals the deal for me .

color is a nice deep , dark brown with dark ruby highlights , the head is very tannish , light brown and creamy , about an inch high and holds together like vaniila ice cream in a root beer float , amazing divets and lumpyness !  the look is a see-through brownish red which let me know right away that it will lack in flavor . the smell is very sweet and dry with very little bitterness present . it tastes very much like it smells and is much too sweet for my taste . when i think of beer , i think of something that at least has some bitterness and balance but this one is pure sweetness . it also leaves a fruity aftertaste which reminds me of applesauce . really not a typical beer taste and not in a good way . i was expecting something different and original and it sure was different but i will not be buying it again .

the beer was a great , deep amber-red color , with no head . the beer was vibrant and crystal in appearance .  i thought this was a great beer . very malty . i agree with one of the other reviewers - i thought they were using centennials but none of the waitresses knew what i was talking about and the owner/brewer was n't around . drinkability was pretty good , as i downed about three during dinner itself .

certainly interesting , appetizing to me .  a bit watery actually . overall a simple classic belgian dubbel . i could drink this stuff every day , it may not be the most in your face dubbel , but thats what makes it great . just a simple session dubbel .

interesting beer to say the least . a thin tiny tan ring remains along the drink . super strong bananas and dark fruits ... some sweet caramel maybe , followed by beligian yeast . i got the belgian yeast and bananas immediately , but not much substance after that .  carbonation seems high for an ipa but head and lacing are a bit below average . at first sip it is a refreshing / light to medium pilsner body that encourages you to gulp a little more confidently untill a few mouthfuls later you are in a caught up in the aroma all the while never minding it . this is a classy beer and makes one feel classy .

ahh ... if it smells like pumpkin pie , and tastes like pumpkin pie , is it brewed with pumpkin pie ? ) by the time it got to my table it has a flat head , but a nice orange-amber color in the bar lighting .  this brew is a bit thin otherwise .

poured from standard bottle with black & yellow label . a : great deep color . good head and lacing .  i thought that the dundee kolsch-style ale was pretty good overall . not the best , but a beer that should be tried . a yellow-to-faint-amber-in-the-middle . the beer left a good 1-1/2 inch head . i could defintely taste biscuit flavors and a hint of lemon zest . the beer did not catch well in my mouth as i kept thinking of the smell .
plenty of effervescent carbonation supports good head retention and truly exceptional lacing .  mouthfeel is kind of bleh , not bubbly enough .
a half an inch of dark brown head floats for a while without sign of receding . lacing in large webs down the glass .  it is a little too light for the style . o- very good impy stout .

a wonderful hazy gold color with about half an inch of white head that laces and settles into a ring .  most pale ales leave me with a thin watery feel and this one 's no different . the carbonation is right and it 's good on a hot day .
almost duvel-esque . fantastic head retention and lacing - what a beautiful beer !  body is slightly thin on the overall taste .

nice bubbles . smell : fruity , raspberry , blackberry , biscuity malt , hops are negligable . smell and first taste are the best .  consumed on 11/8/2009 at breakwater brewing with largadeer . i saw that this was a gabf gold winner and so i immediately ordered it . at this point i looked back up at the board and noticed that it simply read `` gold medal winner , '' rather than the `` gabf gold medal winner '' that i had imagined . the nose is medicinal berries and cherries with a mild tartness and a strong sweetness . the flavor tastes like cherry cough syrup . there 's a touch of tartness but it 's subjugated by the artificial cloying sweet flavor . when a gold medal is given to a beer like this , i ca n't help but suspect one of two things : 1 . it was entered into the beer special olympics . i consumed 2oz of this and could stomach no more .
s : sweet chocolate really dominates with a slight bit of dark malt .  m - medium with light carbonation , seems a little flat .

pours out an amber color with a nice off white head that has very good retention and lacing . looks like a really good beer .  these guys are cranking out the brews , here 's another nice offering i had the chance to sample . very malty aroma of caramel , which slides over into the quaff . a very sweet dopple , i 'd think it could use a bit more hop balance - but some really like the sweeter beers . still a tasty treat , served in a 10oz pilsner type glass , since it weighs in at 7 % .
] light black , beautiful healthy head .  '' fits this perfectly . lingers in the mouth perhaps a bit too long , but otherwise a great and easy to drink beer .

very welcoming notes of citrus hops . loads of pineapple , some decent mango notes and a hint of ripe peach . very good citrus hops profile , which is nicely balanced in this one .  mouthfell was light and effervescent .

massive 2 '' slightly off-white head seems to take forever to fade to a thin film . lots of big , thick strings of lacing are left on the glass , mostly from the initial head .  because the hops and the malt do n't overwhelm you the mouthfeel is light to medium while drinkability is exceptional .

pours bright , effervescent copper with 1.5 to 2 fingers of cream-colored froth . said froth is composed of rather large bubbles but it lasts forever and sticks to the glass well , leaving rings as the beer level descends .  the first swallow is sharply bitter , much starker than an american ipa . this is woody and tangy more than the citric fruitiness we yanks have come to expect from a beer labeled ipa , unfairly . with a solid malt undertow and a nicely balanced bitterness , i feel this is a very under-rated offering . ( # 2688 , 2/6/2007 )
tan head with beautiful lacing , this is a nice looking beer .  feels a bit coarse and chewy on the tongue .
a : huge rising head that slowly fades over a very clear darker honey molasses brown with hints of cranberry red color .  m- quite smooth but somewhat thin . decent carbonation .

a : pours an actual whitish color that is as opaque as a snowy day . a two finger creamy head forms that stays around nicely . this is a good looking wit , though quite a bit of debris floats around it .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , considering the flavour .
aroma is outstanding , exceptional chocolate smell without being overbearing .  m : aftertaste is short , but lovely bitter . body si medium as well as carbonation , but it lacks some smoothness .

had this on tap at mad mex , review from notes . crystal clear garnet color , glows in the dim bar light . served in a snifter with a frothy , yet extremely silky head on it . left an admirable lace blacketing across the back of my glass .  i had tried this with the sample pack and was n't too impress with it or any of the schell beers for that matter . i went to new ulm for the oktoberfest they have and while i was there took the tour of the brewery . while most of the samples were bottles still , they just had a better feel to them . i agree with other posters that the hops hide a bit of the other toasty , bready flavors associated with this style . i really enjoyed this brew and would recommend it if you can find it on tap , skip the bottles unless they are really fresh .

appearance : mocha bomb looks awesome on the pour , very dark brown and it looks pretty thick .  the smooth , medium body ends with a very dry , astringent finish . it 's a little soapy and there 's a hint of orange peel . this is an aggressively hopped american ipa . only drink it when you 're sure you do n't need to taste anything else that day .
a big , beautiful , persistent off-white head . gorgeous . leaves not so much rings of lacing as sheets of it .  medium-full bodied , creamy , but somewhat chalky . well carbonated .

the 1993 vintage flows into the glass with a beautiful red brown/mohagony body topped by a medium thick head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  m : a little thinner than i expected from the look of the pour and for the style .

the aroma is huge on bourbon with mild hints of coffee , vanilla , and chocolate but dominated by bourbon . this is a really good stout , but the bourbon is a bit overwhelming for me .  mouthfeel was ok ( i think ) .
poured deep amber brown with gorgeous cream colored head that stayed with the brew throughout the glass .  m : medium body , lots of prickly carbonation . a little too prickly .

i just love this aroma . t - similar to the aroma but not as strong .  the bourbon is faint . watery . taste does not stay with you as long as i would desire , which is a shame , because it tastes good o- this is an excellent beer , and one that i would drink again . it goes down very smooth , and it would be pretty easy to knock back several .

pours absolut perfection . typical nitro-can pour creates cascading head ala guiness , but this one goes on for longer and looks cooler . massive dense creamy white head that does n't go away sits atop beautiful honey golden ale .  mouthfeel seemed a bit thinner than most quads , almost more like an old ale , very little carbonation .

a - beautiful , clumpy , eggshell white head that sticks so well .  this attractively-packaged ( black panther on the bottle , tying into an indiana legend ) pours ( or is it purrs ? hahah ) a deep black with lots of tan bubbles . some minor lacing . aroma is chocolate malts , with a little roastiness . the taste follows closely , with a pleasing burnt cocoa finish . quite tasty and highly drinkable !

appearance- this gorgeous beer pours a deep reddish brown , supporting an enormous four finger light tan crown that gives us a hint of red in there . as the billowy head begins it soapy demise , it remains full and puffy while dragging some of its lace down the inside of the glass . wonderfully appetizing all around .  medium bodied , with an evident hoppy prickly texture .

sampled on 5-7-10 best before 10-10-11 pours a deep brown color , as cloudy as you could possibly get . the tan head is immense , and leaves thick , chunky lacing . retention is excellent .  m : no carbonations to speak of .

a-light orange ... medium clarity.. s-kick ass fresh citrus aroma ... .love the rillo 's and cascades ... .great combo ... this smells fantastic ... juicy ripe oranges and sweet grapefruit..that is accompanied by the underlying new belgium malt similar to fat tire ... .toasty malt with caramel dripped over it ... t-not as great as the aroma but enjoyable ... seems a little light weight in flavor ... almost a little watered down ... .not bad but a little watery ... flavor is like a hopped up fat tire but with less body ... m-almost has the body of an american wheat ale ... .just seems thin for the style .  the brew was medium in body with a gusher load of carbonation which had a sweet , fruity , lacto , sugary , and out of place tart finish . drank decent but once again i 'm dissapointed at the fact how lots of shorts beers i 've had have been infected .

aroma is vinous ripe fruit and vanilla and maple and caramel and lots of sweetness .  mouthfeel is on the low to medium level with a higher carbonation . i would prefer a fuller mouthfeel with less carbonation .
m/d this drinks and feels like a lighter ipa with some really interesting smells to it .  carbonation is average .

bomber , this unique black ipa was a bitter bomb from start to finish . the cooked roasted profile hits you on the nose , with chocolate malts and broasted grains .  a light bodied feel at the front , it then gradually gains weight .

s - a very complex mix of aromas . there is a barnyard funk , cherries , oak and alcohol .  medium bodied , carbonation is very noticeable , very tame malty sweetness that leads into a somewhat `` thin '' finish .

cracked open the nitrous-charged can and a soft pour resulted in a massive head towering up and out of the glass . the head soon consolidated itself to reveal a pale-golden color beer with a 1/2 '' rich , creamy white head on top . this beer sure is a looker . which is suprising considering the mouth feel : full , thick , rich , and creamy head followed by exquisitely smooth beer , thanks to the nitrous .  quite pleasantly medium and very appropriate for a regular ipa , the mouthfeel felt short of expectations for a dipa .

huge dark mocha head forms and looks creamy like the top of an ice cream float . retention is pretty much endless and there are huge pillows of very thick lace .  this is the first yorkshire ale i have ever drank , so take my review with a grain of salt . the smell was good , but it almost smelled like a porter , which from the reviews i have read thats about what to expect . the taste was a strong but not overpowering of mault . overall a very drinkable ale , just not quite as strong or think as a porter , but i think i would have been confused if not for knowing what it was when i bought it . i 'll have to drink more to get a better idea of what it should be . nice drinkability though .
appearance : black / very dark red . just right carbonation with lingering creamy head .  m : dry , medium-bodied , overcarbonated initially though .
really does look exceptional , straw golden color and huge bone white pillow of head .  m : neutral .

brilliant yellow golden in color with a dense and fantastically retained white head . clumps of patchy white lace coat the glass .  mouthfeel was too light in my opinion nothing special , but nothing wrong . too thin for my liking .

a - a very nice deep dark brown with a half finger dark tan head .  unfortunately , the mouthfeel is a bit thin ( again - it tastes more like soda than beer ) , though the beer is quite easy to drink .

s- a fruity foreground kick fades into a background of the barley malts and a sharp , sweet wine scent . this smell comes close to hitting you in the brain , especially when you get closer and sense the alcoholic notes . t & m- the up-front herbal spiciness is complemented by a light carbonation .  m : light to medium body . medium level of carbonation .

on-tap at verdugo bar , on to the beer : hazy faded orange color , the head is soapy white on top , retains well and leaves a great amount of lacing on the glass .  pours a opaque black colour with a medium frothy tan head . aroma is creamy with some hints of coffee and chocolate . initial taste is very creamy ( milk shake ) , coffee and some cocoa . minor bitter hops in the finish . great head retention and lacing was slapped around the sides of the glass nicely .

this is my 2nd beer @ blackstones and went for the coffee stout because of it being the brewmaster 's anniversary ale . appearance- extremely dark chocolate brown color with a 1 finger head that leaves great lacing with rings . smell- all the coffee elements are there ( roast , bean , chocolate ) but there is also a high amount of roasted malt as well . they probably used a chocolate malt while brewing . taste- you can taste an old , stale coffee but very roasty . overall- they infused this stout with a `` black & blue '' coffee roast and it has nice character but falls short for me ... if this stout had more body to it and less carbonation , it would be perfect !  the mouthfeel is light for a stout , but this is a minor point .

this beer was crystal clear and looked perfect ! s : big hop aroma of the earthy , woodsy , piney variety .  heavy alcohol , extreme spice , honey , grapes and pepper . oof - this is where my `` inexperiance '' as an advocate comes in . an immediate peppery sting inflames the mouth and the grapes , saffron and alcohol kill them off . wtf is saffron ? sorry dfh .

s- rich pumpkin and spices like nutmeg and cinnamon . a good dose of caramel malt backs the pumpkin pie aromas up . very nice ; exactly how a pumpkin beer should smell . it smelled great but the taste really disappointed .  m : good , not great . i drank one and thought it was on the thinner side .

lots of dark fruits in the aroma , mainly sweet apple , plum , plus apricot and peach . i taste significant fruit notes , but these are brighter fruits than those i smelled . for example , i taste apricot and peach more so than apple , and i do n't taste the plum i smelled . there 's a sourness `` funk '' going on that the beer self proclaims .  unfortunately the beers characteristics disappears quickly . not that it should be the goal of a beer drinker or a characteristic of a good beer , but one could probably get really drunk off of this tilburg offering . it 's maybe a little too sweet for it 's own good -- and definetly more sweet than most brown ales .

s - woah hello peanuts - nail on the head . roasty , the oatmeal is there , slight chocolate . it 's hard to get past the prominent peanut buttery nose on this . i like it . t - again with the roasted flavor and the oatmeal , and the peanuts come right up on you in a stronger than expected and pleasant way .  slightly thin body for the style and the abv , just a light alcohol presence in the finish , well hidden .

pours the darkest , thinnest brown . there 's continuous carbonation , and a gently swirl leads to beads of fine carbonation that bursts forth with a thicker froth . blanket of lace .  mouthfeel/drinkability- light body and decent carbonation however the aftertaste and taste in general make this beer nearly undrinkable .
a - regardless of variety , gunniess is a beautiful beer . great head , great lacing .  m : thick body that is slick on the tongue . lower then average carbonation .

orangish brown with a gorgeous white frothy head .  m : i am not a fan of the mouthfeel . instead i got a thicker mouthfeel that coated my tongue just a little too much which is what i think gave it the not so great finish .
great looking beer .  m : average feel , clean , and dry , d : enjoyable would love to have this mid summer .
i love how the malt peaks through for just a bit mid way through the sip , then the hops take over again . great hoppy winter .  the beer seemed highly carbonated .

amazing . flavor is much like the nose with the added benefit of a bready yeast character .  a very good and heavy beer . must be sipped an not chugged , though no good beer drinker would do such a thing . highly recommended .

lots of yeast kicks up as you pour . s : smells of very sweet malts , alcohol , some vanilla , and a touch of caramel . no hop aromas to be detected .  first off , i went in expecting leinie 's berryweiss , and was pleasantly suprised that it was not that type of drink . a nice crisp berry scent , which is balanced in flavor by the malt . is it a `` chick beer '' ? maybe . yep . it 's not zima , it 's not boone 's farm , it 's just kinda ... .good .

smells wonderful . sweet malts , dried fruit and alcohol .  mouthfeel is crisp with a light to medium body . however , it is over carbonated so it feels you up rather quickly and then you are constantly burbing to make room . as is , the over carbonation is very distracting .

aroma is sweet but somewhat meaty . strawberries grapefruit floral hops . best smelling beer ever . seriously .  m : i did think this beer was a bit thin and could have benefited from a little more texture as a result carbonation was a bit high .
a : first of all ... huge head ! this is a truly gorgeous beer .  the palate is typical .

aroma is actually very nice . dark chocolate sauce , in fact almost like a chocolate liqueur as there is a nice sweet sense of alcohol . nice .  mouth feel is a bit carbonated for my likings ( macro'ish ) .

aroma is mostly delicious chocolate , aroma is brilliant . small amount of charred grains and a large amount of malt .  lightly oily and thick on the palate , but undercarbonated , unfortunately , even for a low carbonation lover like me .

the aroma is amazing and intense . belgian yeast , bread , sweet malt , caramel , toffee , brown sugar , apple , raisin , date , fig , toasted nut , banana , clove , and alcohol make up the aroma . very complex , one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . unfortunately the taste does not carry the same complexity as the aroma . it 's still darn good though . sweet malt , belgian yeast and bread , brown sugar , candied sugar , raisin and fig , and a touch of alcohol make up the taste . overall , a darn good beer .  finishes crisp with a sort of biting feeling in the back of the throat .

good retention and lacing .  the fizzy yellow stuff of the great white north , as far as i 'm concerned . that 's right , corn . prominent in the aroma and taste , along with some traces of malt and hops . i was quite thirsty after a bout with us customs , and this failed to satisfy . difficult to finish .

a- pours pitch black with a nice looking , 2 finger mocha colored head .  great brew to enjoy on warm or hot days . apricot aroma eclipses any malt or hops on the nose . taste is predomanantly apricot/peach , with just a slight bite of hops in the finish . the clean malt helps to balance out the apricot . a great , simple , summer session beer for hot days .

from the island of kauai ( the furthest island east , fifth island from the big rock ) comes a sparkling golden lager with a massive head of rocky bright white foam that holds quite well and leaves very nice rings of lace about the glass .  mouthfeel is on the light side , with a little more acidic carbonation than i 'd like in this sort of beer .
smelled of candied sugar , chocolate , and bread .  a little bit thin in the mouth , feels almost like water .

probably the best nose to a beer within the style guidelines as i have ever whiffed . taste is kind of a let down after the big nose . the spices are there but are very muted to the heavier caramel malts . slick buttery slickness in the mouth leaves a thin film . all and all an ok pumpking beer but just expected this to build up to the hype and the nose .  mouthfeel ... light , a bit watery .
another brew i have to thank dim for . the body of the brew was black as night no light coming through at all .  a little rough going down , but over all very nice .

pours a massive hearty white head that takes an eternity to diminish .  smell - cereal , caramel , floral notes , pine , grapefruit taste & mouth - there is an average amount of carbonation on the tongue and the beer comes across as slightly watery .

poured into a chimay glass from a bottle ( very cool bottle , btw ! very dark with about a half inch of head with minimal lacing .  loaded with fresh hops flavor , spicey , that good bitter smack finish . i used to prefer darker beers to american pale ales , but this beer is the one that changed my mind . this beer goes great with crawfish and pizza .

the aroma is citrusy . i get orange , lemon , and even lime . that being said , i am not a big pilsner fan .  mouthfeel was disappointingly a bit too thin and watery in the finish for such a big beer .

aroma is outstanding . very floral , like a pleasant spring day . very complex aroma , especially with the late dry-hop process .  i can only describe this as a gimmick beer , because the bottle was interesting , and the beer awful . funky metallic/brown sugar nose . malt had an odd dimension , which , coupled with the alcohol in the beer , hinted at cheap sour mash whiskey . one of the few beers i have poured out half-way through and gotten something ( anything ) better from the fridge .
a : brilliantly filtered , rich orange moving into shades of brown , off-white head with good retention .  drinkability : body is a little undercarbonated .
s - very nice hop aroma , lots of earthiness and citric acidity . i 'm excited to take a sip .  mouth is lacking in carbination expected . also a little thinner in the mouth than expected .

aroma is really remarkable . i must 've swished & swirled , sniffed and sipped this for 45 minutes . exceptional aromatic characters .  mouthfeel : i 'm used to stouts , so this seemed thin , and therefore a double-edged sword . drinkability : the thinness of this beer makes it so easy going down , you 'll want to have another .

sweet and creamy milk chocolate malted shake with cinnamon , vanilla , and essences of coffee . amazing smell that i cant get enough of ! has an interesting french vanilla creamer aroma to it . ( t ) - ample roasted malts that are lightly bittering that is followed by dusty cocoa and sweet creamy vanilla on the finish . ( d ) - a unique stout with the addition of being brewed with vanilla beans .  sampled this at the brewery ( portsmouth ) at the end of the tour which is short but wonderfully informative ( thanks byron ) . it didnt hurt that i was a few pints deep from the restaurant already . its been 2 weeks and its almost gone and i have to say its great for a stout . it pours thick and has little head retention so presentation isnt off the charts but taste makes up for it .
a : huge , foamy head that lasts quite a while . underneath , a bubbly golden liquid that looks very inviting .  m - slightly thin mouthfeel , not very viscous . fairly bitter , but very filling .

a- pours a clear reddish copper body with a 2-finger off white head that shows some good lasting power and some really very nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is on the thin side , very drinkable , & coats the mouth & throat . funny that the irish dry stout is distinct from milk stouts , because i feel the style is very lactic feeling .

a : the honey porter had a dark body with a 1-finger creamy beige head that made the beer look like candy . it pours beautifully and keeps it 's head throughout .  mouthfeel - the feel is affected by the flavor .
this brew poured a large head of fine to large sized light brown bubbles and a dark black brown bosy .  mouthfeel : medium body with smooth carbonation and a finish that is a bit gritty .
beautiful beer . gorgeous looking beer .  mouthfeel is alright for the type .

as the carbonation finds it 's way to the top , it begins to show off it 's brilliant copper color and clarity . the head is the nicest i 've ever seen from a `` bring home '' beer .  mouthfeel was average .

loads of fine bubbles support an amazing head..looks like a dollop of tan colored whipped cream still and this is 5 minutes after pouring it .  this is a decent beer . more of a i crave a new style beer type . i tasted nothing oatmeal about this beer . mainly tasted of a dark coffee flavored beer . but it was a decent fun experience .
nice copper amber coler with a whiter-than-white cream head that stayed 1 finger thick the entire time .  m. mouthfeel slacks a little . maybe a little too much carbonation and a little too thin .

pours a very dark color with a tall , creamy head that has good retention and leaves some lacing on the glass .  as a wee heavy beer it does a great job , low bitterness w/ ample sweetness mouthfeel : hmmm ... .a little to watery and at times you can feel the sugary syrupness of this beer .

pours a pitch black amazingly dark brown , very thick . great appearance . a nice solid brown head . beautiful beer . a very solid showing from cigar city  m : overly fizzy and carbonated , very spritzy .
this is one damn good looking beer .  a lot thinner in the mouth then i imagined it to be .

a : pours a dark black with a nice very dark brown head that fades to a small layer leaving a ton of lacing on the glass . beautiful stout .  my first thought when i had this beer was yum . that 's a nice smooth sweet beer . when i smelled the beer i thought it smelled like lemons or fresh oranges . it has nice golden color , the beer had about a 1/4 inch head when i poured it into a tumbler . apparently it 's hops are nobel so if i drink enough will i become a duke .

this has a pretty solidly black opacity that supports a medium-light frothy chestnut head .  yielded a monstrous thick white head.a very cloudy yellowish-orange.very inviting aroma with hints of spiceskind of smells like unibroue 's la fin du monde.a very crisp mouthfeel almost harsh like seltzer.very citrus flavor with a slight bitter finish that lingers in the back of the throat.a bit but not much lace.high drinkability with this one.very crisp , clean , and refreshing .

this beer looks great . i poured it a little too vigorously and ended up with a huge tan head that did n't fin in my pint glass . the head subsided into a film and left plenty of lace on the glass .  nice and crisp . not too much effervescence in the feel . light on the tongue .
great smell and a good looking beer .  body is a little thin for an imperial stout , although this beer is on the lighter end of the spectrum for the style .

pours a quite hazy peachy yellow into my glass with a beautiful two finger head of white foam . looks great in the glass .  the body feels a tiny bit watery . the oatmeal smoothness is nice but the watery body needs to be thickened .

set in front of me was a glass of clear , brownish-golden ale with a decently retained , thin white head . the aroma reminded me of a breakfast at ihop : maple syrup , smoked canadian bacon , and some biscuits . *drools* san juan definately makes some interesting , experimental brews ... see my review of their `` ale diablo '' pepper beer . definitely an interesting try , and one i wo n't soon forget . san juan is an underrated brew-pub . worth the ferry trip to friday harbor .  m : light to medium bodied , with low carbonation . i can only suggest more on the mouthfeel and carbonation .

very nice aroma on this beer . flavor reminds me of extremely naughty goose in that it has a roasted marshmallow-like sweetness which is delicious . i 'm usually not a huge fan of brown ales , but this is simply outstanding .  the mouth feel was very heavy , but not very viscous with only a slight carbonation . kind of felt watery . this is a very nice beer , but the mouth feel is a big turn off .

just opaque black with a prodigious cinnamon-colored head that , instead of falling , forms swiss-cheese-like holes that undermine the head 's structural integrity until the whole thing slowly collapses like the ottoman empire . very nice lacing , too .  m - the feel is a bit coarse but the texture helps to bring out the nice flavor . ~ i will suggest to mt ba buds that they partake in this foreigner .

room temperature pour into a mikasa widemouth glass creates a pitch black mass in my glass with a two finger fluffy dark khaki head extruding from the abyss that dissipates into layer of fine bubbles .  bottom line : great introduction to sour beers . very mild and subtle sour/brett flavors . extremely approachable by even the mildest craft beer fan . nice brown color hints of dark fruits . sourness is extremely mild yet compliments the malts . very little if any hop flavor . exceptionally drinkable . bottle and draft nearly identical . great go-to flanders red but seems more like a sour brown . availability makes this a great 'trainer ' . a-

thought i got a meaty whiff when opened , this poured an easy soft one inch head . ultra intense heading which is unusual for a bottled english bitter . slighty brownish orange and almost approaching irn bru in colour . clean clear sparkle to the eye . very nice .  s - overwhelming peach . that is all this beer has , and i found it to be utterly unbalanced . d - my partner and i drank many different beers over two weeks in belgium . also , i do n't think this has any lambic as in it , as that it not claimed by dubuisson on their website .

i love this beer so much i bought a t-shirt at the brewery . that said , doubt that few beers of the same price could top this in terms of taste : fruit and chocolate at the beginning , with yeasty goodness and cloves later on .  mouthfeel is firm and a bit spicy with the hops , but the drinkability is awful .
it 's carries a `` triple '' head . very pretty !  d- good for the style , especially with this abv , but still quite boozey considering how thin the mouthfeel is .

bottled in : 2011 1c a : pours a nice straw yellow with a massive 4 fingers worth of head that sticks all the way down the glass s : pretty malty and yeasty , with a grassy hop profile .  moderate body , with a little bit of a gassy , bubbly feel . ultimately , although i quite like this beer , i think it would really shine on cask ; the carbonation is a little too prickly and gives the beer too much of a mineral water feel .

did n't gush when i opened it , but it poured even at a full right angle with 70 % head . after a while the head settled down to a decent size , still thick and impressive . brilliant clarity , amber cooper color . highly carbonated , not sure if this was the brewers goal .  the feel was a bit oily and slightly metallic . this was easy to drink , but lacked the super fresh feel i expect from a harvest ale .
nice . roasted malt and chocolate as well . then i let it warm . whole different story . very nice .  mouthfeel- a little syrupy , with some sand.. drinkability- not coors light . gulp gulp , ph

smell : mostly a tart apple smell which is quite powerful , i could smell this one across the room , underneath the nose full of apples is a faint grassy herbal sort of smell . drinkability : an interesting beer , looks good , smells great , taste is ok , but the fizzbomb factor will steer me away from this beer in the future .  m : this is , by far , the weakest aspect of this beer . it 's just too thin and watery for the style . good carbonation helps save this from being a below average score .

berry and malt aroma with strong spicy hops . tastes significantly less exciting than the intense and wonderful aroma . low hops upfront that continue into an excellent bitter finish .  m - medium mouthfeel , a little lighter than i prefer my imperial stouts to be .

aromas are phenomenal , this is easily one of the best beers i have smelt in quite a while . taste is a bit of a let down , but i have to say , that is mostly because this beer smells so good , not because it tastes bad . like i said , the taste did n't quite live up to the nose , but that 's mostly because this is such a nice smelling beer .  t-this does n't taste like a double ipa to me , but it does taste like a very good east coast ipa , heavy on the citrus , heavy on the hops , no alcohol to be found anywhere . m-a bit oily , which is o.k . ) by me , carbonation is a little lacking for my taste ... still , this is a good beer if you like hops ... d- ... .wicked drinkable .

best before : 18.11.11 from : premier wine & spirits a : clear golden body boasting three fingers of fluffy white head . retention is great and leaves loads of lacing .  my main complaint is the mouthfeel , which is a little lacking given the style . a porter should be a little bit thicker , with more substantial body .
looks nearly perfect .  mouthfeel is watery with a crisp finish .
overall , poured with a large , tan , thick , foamy , frothy head and loads of lace .  mouthfeel is medium bodied .

nose : a rich malty sweetness , that leans towards a southern english brown ale . the nose on the beer is the best . the flavor tapers offs and leaves me wanting a fuller flavor brown ale .  m-medium-high carbonation overpowers a medium but forgettable body .

the aroma is funky to the nth degree , sugar cane , very sweet smell with some tropical fruits , mango , pears and champagne-soaked strawberries .  mouthfeel is thin and carbonated with a little slickness .

as dark a stout as i have ever seen . the bottle says `` pours like siberian crude '' but you have to see it to believe it . modest head that quickly dissipates leaving some lacing .  m : smooth and creamy but the carbonation is a bit too much .
a- crystal clear amber with a white head- an beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel was medium with a slightly unpleasant astringency in the mouth .
the beer is crystal clear and light yellow hued . the head is a finger thick and leaves some decent legs on the glass .  m : extremely oily .
a - pitch black almost like an imperial stout with fluffy white head .  feel is not as light as i would like but great and the carbonation is really good .

pours a gorgeous deep ruby red with almost a purplish glow to it . nice sticky off-white head that leaves a good deal of lacing around the glass .  there is also almost no after taste to be found ( weird ) mouth-feel : extremely dry with a light bodied feel .

appearance : pours wonderfully and has a slow-developing head ( very similar to guinness ) .  this has got the same funky yeasty flavor of the balcones fault pale malt whithout any of the body to back it up . leaves a bad aftertaste . i can actually see the other guy saying it was watered down with pickle juice , but watered down with watered down pickle juice . it 's got a lot of flavor , but it 's a bad flavor .

i love this beer . the appearance is light , golden color .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side , which is my only real complaint about this beer , and there 's a bit of warming in the back of the throat .

22 ounce bomber . intense hop aroma . pineapple and citrus dominate , backed up by sweet pine . caramel malts are off in the background . my mouth is watering from the aroma alone . taste follows the aroma , with a wonderfully bitter finish . mango and pineapple tropical hops coat the tongue first , with spicy and pine notes in the middle . this is one yummy and refreshing double ipa . highly drinkable , especially considering the high abv .  this brew poured a medium head of small to large sized white bubbles that left very little lacing . it has a wheat yellow body with a mild if any aroma . it has an initial bite that lingers slightly into the aftertaste . it has a mild hoppy malt flavor .
d - the aroma is great , but the rest of the package is somewhat middling .  mouthfeel is light-bodied , a bit watery , nothing special .
beer poured deep tawny with a nice beige head and good lacing .  mouthfeel - low carbonation and lighter than i expected . a little sticky .

bitter chocolate and spices follow with a hint of sour roatiness - excellent . the taste is n't quite as pungent but it is wonderful - a conglomeration of cinnamon rolls with chocolate drizzled over top , spices as well .  m : a little light on body and sharp on carbonation . nothing special on this front .

good head retention & lacing s : cherries , figs & raisins in abundance t : follows the nose with a touch of molasses & licorice up front .  it was watery with some carbonation and a slightly bitter aftertaste .

aromas of caramel , toffee , bourbon , oak , bradiness , and spices . the appearance and nose were definately the best aspects of this brew . taste was the same as the nose w/ an extremely heavy bourbon booze character .  mouthfeel - it does n't really differentiate itself . the carbonation is low , as is normal amongst dark , high alcohol beers . it 's particularly dense , milk is probably a good comparison , and it feels like it sticks to the inside of your mouth somewhat .

appearance - pours into a frozen mug ( hey , when in texas ... ) with a brownish amber color . thick , foamy 2-finger beige head , very creamy , nearly like guinness , and slow to recede ( due to the coldness ? ) . leaves thick dotty lacing .  mouthfeel is very crisp with medium-high carbonation . lite bodied , and it goes down a little thin and watery .

you need not even bring to your nose to pick up the sweet maltiness accented with caramel , toffee , and a subtle buttery aroma . an ever so slight hoppiness to the nose .  mouthfeel : light to medium body , a little alcohol warmth .

appearance : a deep inviting reddish brown with a tan head smell : sweet and with winter spices taste : sweet and malty , with aftertaste of peppermint and eggnog .  thin of body , which is somewhat disappointing . carbonation lightly massages the tongue and causes moderate fizziness in the beer as it moves .

fascinating nose : sweet mandarin , light orange rind bitterness , citrus ( and mango ) hop tang/bitterness [ think amarillo ] , and a light woody funkiness . i really like the nose here . very unexpected . super dry and dusty . interesting , but not a huge success to me .  mouthfeel/body is light/medium , it seems a bit thin and is well carbonated .
clear copper body , very appealing smooth off-white head , almost bone in color ( seemed an unusual shade to me ) . excellent lacing .  the mouthfeel is full , but the carbonation is a bit high .

the color matches the gradient on the label perfectly . the head is a white foam , average , and pleasantly lingers and holds at the top for a while .  medium bodied but with a rather thinnish , pallid mouthfeel .

as you can tell from the blood swelling under his right eye . pours a cloudy dark amber color with a huge , frothy beige head with great retentive lacing .  purchased as part of the 12 beers of winter sampler case . it smelled like cranberries and soap . not enticing in the least . the flavor was n't much better . the label claims a number of spices found in this beer , but i was hard-pressed to find them . extremely bland . the base of the flavor was that of acidic berries . i tasted slight hints of nutmeg and some hops , but that is about it . it was a fight to get through it .

really pleasant . fudge batter brownie soaked in bourbon . more enjoyable bourbon that the oft-compared to gibcs , with more depth and complexity . chocolate cherry soaked in a creeping booziness .  m - feels slightly thin .
perfect clarity . pretty much what a pilsener should be .  the carbonation is medium-high and body is medium to medium-light giving this beer a very high drinkability .
smells really good . a little roasted with more chocolate than vanilla , and dried fruit .  kinda thin and tinny .

s : quite fragrant for a 5 % beer , fresh fruit and yeast run the show . d : an interesting wit , though at times , just a little too strange , but i bet a lot of belgian fans will get a kick out of it .  mouthfeel is ok , suitable for this type of brew .
not many streams of carbonation , but the head is very slow to form , but is large and has great retention .  m - a little soft on the carbonation but with a decent if not great finish .

a very sticky wall of lace remains on the sides of the glass , nice looking brew for sure .  medium to full bodied with a very water type mouth feel at first that ends with a bit more girth in the finish .

the aroma of this one is nearly intoxicating ... cocoa , dried fruits , molasses . there is a toasty , malty character that carries through here . a little one dimensional though . this is n't a bad beer , it just seems unpolished and way too bubbly . worth trying .  tart mouthfeel with slight thickness .

the poured color was cloudy yellowish , looked like a hefeweizen . smelled very hoppy , just like how a west coast ipa would smell . if not for the color or the described style i would say this is an ipa just by smelling . it 's hoppy , but there were something underlying there that separated this from an ipa .  a very smooth and well integrated taste..the buiscuity malts and hops blend near seamlessly . ok palate for the style but the extreme balance gives the impression of boredom ! but overall this is a charming and very drinkable pnw lager

the pour a perfect deep brown to black color , the way i like to see my beer . light chocolate head that is adequate in size , creamy in its texture , the lace a latticework clinging to the glass .  m - the mouth feel is softer than the german original is is dryer than many hefes as well .

post mibgf party , thanks chris for getting the `` growler '' of this brew : a- deep brown with reddish highlights topped by a beautiful creamy tan head that left very good lacing upon the glass .  thats the only thing separating this beer from chocolate milk , well , also without any of the heaviness associated with milk . this is a beer you can drink and drink , so it 's my wednesday night drink of choice .

it had a nice spiciness together with a pleasantly musty , yeasty aroma .  i work at a distributer that sells this beer so i had to try it . at first open i thought that the high alcohol smell would make for a bad beer . after a couple sips , it was actually pretty good . i would compare it to miller high life ... .except that you get smashed after two or three beers . since beer is for the purpose of getting drunk ... this is the right one . if it taste good and serves it 's purpose , why not take this one . since i do work at a distributor that sells high end beers , if anyone ask for a good beer that will serve its purpose , i will highly recomend camo & gt ;

smell- piney sided hops , with light citrus , slightly resinous . taste- very hop forward , surprise ! the blend of hops is great , but the malt balance is almost nonexistent . this is an extremely bitter beer . mouthfeel- slightly slick , abvs hidden fairly well .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .

overall : i enjoyed it , although , the flavor profile did not provide the depth that the aroma provided it was still enjoyable .  m - coarse throughout ranging from a small to large graininess . certainly a sessionable brew and another notch in the winner category for the folks at new glarus .
pours black with a ring of tan bubbles .  then the aftertaste.. i have now experienced the dreaded `` band-aid '' sensation .
