two and a half fingers of frothy/creamy tan head with great retention and a thick ring of lacing . good looking brew !  m -- -fine , i guess .

looks the part . nice cap of dense beige froth . retention is great as is the lacing .  great session brew . burnt flavor that lends an espresso taste with some chocolatey notes . good hop bitterness in the finish . my only gripe is that this brew turns watery in the finish . still , went down easily and quickly , def . worth a try .
a : dark mohogany ; light tan head is fluffy ; great retention and lace . exceptional for a porter !  just mildly bittered and the flavor is really great despite being a tad light bodied .
s : lots of sweet malt . sort of smelled like a marzen .  m : medium-bodied , carbonation stings the tongue early on .

a popular and very classy beer , especially when served in the tulip shaped duvel glasses . a cloudy golden color with a big white foamy head .  thinnish initially . sturdies itself somewhat as it rests , but remains airy and light . nice enough .

very disappointing . almost like a dry ris , which wasnt unpleasant , just unexpected . lots of raisons and plums in the quaff also . a full bodied brew , it came across like a sour champaign .  whatever , it 's tasty and pretty nice to drink . overall , its smooth , but almost slightly sour porter . definitely worth a try .

aroma was heavenly ; candied sugary malt and grain , with some dark fruits and yeasty notes . wow . taste was very complex and enjoyable ; fermented grain , dark fruits , molasses , wood notes , warming alcohol , mild yet solid hops .  as with most nitro cans , great head , and as always , watching a guinness poured right settle is pretty satisfying . the usual guinness metallic taste , not a really strong smell or anything . nothing too overpowering , this remains an extremely drinkable stout . much better compared to that guinness draft bottle junk that 's supposed to be drank out of the bottle . to me , the exceptional part of the guinness is the appearance , and you miss that with the bottle . better from the can .
outstanding . taste is just like the smell , only more intense .  the mouthfeel was a tad below average .

pretty sexy looking beer going on here s some funky yeast with lots of wood very earthy but not what i was hoping for t some hops on top of what i smell but a little disappointing after looking at this one m feels like sandpaper in the mouth , very coarse and seems to leave something behind d not at all what i was expecting from this one a bit of a let down , not a bad beer but i had high hopes i guess i doubt i 'll be drinking this again it 's pretty average  the mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . i like gueuze to be effervescent , or at least moderately carbonated , but the carbonation i find here is quite low .

pours a clear , mahogany topped by a thick bubbly head that lays down intricate webs of lacing . there is n't any way i can think of that this could look better .  a bit surprising then that the flavor is what it is ... the first sip : a bit thin . the last sip : quite thin .

poured to a bright golden color , with possibly the thickest , most pillowy off-whte head i have ever seen . head lingered thru entire glass , and slowly reduced to excellent lacing .  mouthfeel the high carbonation makes this one a little rough .

fantastic retention . a thin film stayed around until the beer was nearly finished .  it 's really malty , which probably makes it seem so highly carbonated . the carbonation and sweetness would probably prevent this from being a session beer .

the smell is hoppy as an ipa should be . impressive . this is one of the biggest ipa smells that i have ever had . instead it is decently balanced for a ipa . big aroma taste and not much bitter at the end .  m - a little slick for my liking .
big roasty aromas and also some notes of dry , unsweetened chocolate .  thus one can use a more substantial body , but the hops drove this one . solid beer
the beer is opaque and black with a big creamy nitro looking light brown head . beautiful .  m : the feel is a tad watery and a weak-point of this brew .
deep reddish brown head which is absolutely decadent .  mouthfeel is some-what sharp .

( a ) - pours a near pitch dark brown ; almost black color with the tiniest maroon highlights . produced a huge foaming eggshell colored head that is taking forever to dissipate .  i do n't get the big deal . my friends are always so excited about # 9 , but this is one of my least favorite beers around . i 'd rather have a coors light . the apricot flavor is boring and frankly just gross . of all the fruits . the first sip was almost okay , and each one after was worse .

2011 - 4646 bottle into chimay goblet . aromas are heavy on the bourbon and oak/vanilla , but backed up by molasses and maple syrup sweetness . inviting . thick on the palate .  almost bad enough that i thought about just dumping it out . but i 'm a huge mikkeller fan and could n't believe that they could make a beer as bad as this one smelled . this is one terrible beer . i 've had the bourbon and red wine versions in this series and they were both outstanding . the taste is very complex in it 's awfulness . it 's just a combination of toxic flavors that you do n't normally identify with beer . burnt rubber , iodine , paint thinner , magic marker . truly disappointed by one of my all time favorite breweries .
it smells very sweet and very much like banana .  the mouthfeel was a bit sharp at first .

the aroma is very nice . it promises a beer that is a balance of sweetness and roast and floral notes , the beer however does not quite deliver like i had hoped .  taste : extremely spicy top note with intense ginger and nutmeg notes are balanced by slightly dry , caramelized wood and some citrusy coffee in the mold of a yergicheffe that 's at city roast levels . ripe currants , molasses , and fruit skin bitterness with a hint of cider flavors emerge as it warms and opens up . definitely not as roasty as one would expect from a black ale . finish is grassy and citrus bitterness , a little dry , quite spicy , a little yeasty with a touch of banana . notes : awesome , amazingly drinkable and unique beer .
pours a two finger rich brown head over a clear dark dark ruby mahogeny liquid . gorgeous . some attractive lacing left behind .  m : a little too much carbonation for my taste .

aggressive head that dissipates slowly and leaves excellent ring lace . the color is pale amber/gold and slightly hazey .  mouthfeel : good medium body but just a tad under carbed overall impression : its surprisingly good for a gimmicky beer ; very nice taste and very drinkable .

krampus is an imperial helles lager that does not look like a helles , does not smell like a helles , and it definately does not drink like a helles . well hopped up aroma . pine and floral hop aroma with a little medicinal qualities sums things up .  not a whole lot of body or mouthfeel to this .

full copper colored head with excellent lace and retention .  i actually like a few of the canadian brands better ( as some have the actual raisins and what not in the bottle still , and better carbonation levels and lower abv ) . taste is great malty , sweet , and very filling ( it 's nutritous to boot ) . i only generally drink water , tea , coffee , beer , wine , spirits , juice , and dairy ( kefir , etc ) . this is the noly soda type beverage i drink and it is absolutely stellar hangover relief ...

i get maple notes , right off the bat . subtle , but unmistakable . lots of butterey caramel notes . a very deliciously inviting nose ! loads of rich maltiness , along with mild chocolate and some light traces of coffee , give this an almost porter-like taste . this really follows the nose quite well , actually .  very good mouthfeel , maybe a bit too carbonated , but very drinkable .
appearance : deep black pour with a tan pancake batter head .  m : thin body with a medium mouthfeel .
appearance : poured with an exceptional 3 finger head of some of the thickest and richest foam my eyes have ever seen .  mouthfeel is slightly stringent and a bit on the thin side .

poured a deep golden colour with redish hues big off white head that lasts nice thick small bubbled lace that clings aroma huge malt with bursting fruity scent peaches , nectarines a real honey like aroma absolutely loved it very impressive mouthfeel is nice and thick syrupy goes down very easy taste malt , malt and more malt than with a lovely hop bitterness that pulls the malt through also with slight grain and doesnt upset any of the flavours you were able to taste.also noticed a orange rind flavour within the bitterness which i enjoyed i love this beer if your gon na try something different and all you drink is macro lagers and want something a little more adventurous than this is it , an explosion for the taste buds with a big bold flavour great beer .  the flavor is nicely malty to back up the yeasty fruit and spice but the body is a tad thin .

perfect pour . clear amber with everlasting lacing - even small globs of foam remain on the glass .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with pretty high carbonation , remember it gushing , and the carbonation is the only thing that stops this from being higher .

a : appears an attractive dark purplish pink with a big frothy dark pink head . nice retention . great color in the body and the head , and great clarity .  the main surprise hit me with how light the mouth feel is for something so dark and with such a rich aroma . great taste that did n't weigh on me and created a nice appetite .
app- big bottom up filling two and a half finger head . lighter brown with some dark brown to amber highlights .  mouthfeel seems a little oily , yet at the same time , a little thin .

pours an absolutely beautiful golden color with a huge head .  for real , closest mass-produced craft beer to snpa . coppery , high crystal malt appearance with nice head and typical bottled carbonation . grassy . flavor is a bit bitter at first followed by some mild hoppy/flowery/cascady flavors . bite at finish . not too much but bitter enough to say this is a pale ale . fine everyday drinking pale ale but nothing exceptional or cheeky . b+

i recognize multiple brews here , particularly a tripel with a strong floral component melded with a strong dark , something from the medicine cabinet or something from a thai dish is in the distance on top of cedar . unique combination . unique nose , unique flavor . smooth mouthfeel with momentary prickliness .  the mouthfeel is average for the style , medium bodied , slightly creamy , and of course rather oily .

pours a deep , honey gold color . gooey , bright white head is very dense and recedes quickly leaving spatters of lace behind .  m - a little chewy , a little thin and watery , however it is silky smooth as it goes down d - really impressed with this imperial oatmeal stout .
deep amber color . ruby highlights . clear .  m - mouthfeel is a little light .
pours beautiful . poured hard several times , a beautiful dense head will form over the pils .  m : feels a tad thin , i 'd say its light-medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

a : pours a bright golden yellow with an amazing white foamy head s : slight earthy smell , with a hint of licorice t : very floral taste , with slight caramel notes m : light bodied , dry finish , high abv d : unbelievable brew , especially for the out of the box thinking of brewing a beer sans hops .  m- light in the mouth , but could use more carbonation seem to be lacking here .
the smell is extremely malty with little else apparent .  mouthfeel is a bit thin for a beer that has this much flavor , i like it now , but would like it better with a bit more body .

amazing aroma . one half is of citrus ( grapefruit , grape , orange ) , and the other half is primarily toffee . one of the best beer aromas ive smelled in a long time . the taste is great , though a bit less exciting than the aroma . this is where the hops outplay the malt profile a bit as the bitter hops outline a caramel malt center . overall i loved this beer . as mentioned , the aroma was better than the taste . overall this is fantastic , and something ill be looking for again .  m : not quite as smooth as some stouts , has the right amount of carbonation though .

a - pours some nice deep amber brwon color , pretty opaque , cloudy . the head is amazing . super thick froth that does not die . that 's a full 5/5 star looking beer baby !  smooth entry - softer and thinner mouthfeel than tradition for style . while the mouthfeel detracted a bit - i enjoyed the flavor profile .

this displayed excellent retention , lasting the duration of the pint and laced the glass with rings from start to finish . the best looking nitro beer i have ever seen .  i poured this beer into my tumbler at 50 degrees then poured it out of my tumbler and into the sink . the bber was a light mahoganny color with a light orangy looking head . the smell was of sour something with a bit of a caralally smell . the taste was sour gross sour yuk ... too me . the sourness was just overpowering of rotten fruit and bout gagged me . i will not buy again .

the smell is quite bitter for a porter , yet gives hints of a semi-sweet chocolate . i was quite deceived by its aroma .  i have not been a fan of most pumpkin beers i 've tried , but this one was a very pleasant suprise . the taste was very much like pumpkin pie as well , and while it 's more heavily spiced than some others i 've tried , schlafly managed to not over-do it . this beer would be perfect right after thanksgiving dinner .

pours a nice deep orange/red . some floaties/carbonation . nice thick head with great lacing .  this rating is for the green bottled version . i was sorely disappointed by this version . i 've had the brown-bottled .5 liter version in the past and liked it a lot , but this version is terrible . i can only assume this is horrible because of the green bottle and the associated skunky flavor . why in the world is the brewery sending us this inferior version ? i just do n't understand making a world-class beer , but then ruining it by putting it in a green bottle .
pours a deep , dark red with a decent head . one of the nicest hues i 've seen .  nice and drying , though the carbonation is a little lacking .

beautiful pour into a stone ipa glass . large , 3f cream colored head over a rich amber colored body , with tons of sticky lacing .  was light on tongue , still there was carbonation that froze the tongue .
front nose was big , very floral . baked pear and apricots .  m - high carbonation and medium to full body .
appearance huge fluffy beige head on straight pour .  thin mouthfeel with light to medium carbonation .

however , the aroma of this beer is amazing . caramel cream and sugary cinnamon , mixed with the smell of aged wood and dry bread . smells so good .  christ , the taste is skunked too , i really do n't know if i can get past this , it seems kind of outrageous . the untainted part of the taste has some vienna or munich malts , tough to tell . just a bit of nobel hops in there as well . it 's absolutely ruined by the skunked flavor . i get that the skunkiness can be somewhat appealing to some people , but thats for a pilsner or a euro pale lager .

the smell is big on roasted coffee and chocolate malts with a hint of hops - really nice aroma on this one .  the mouthfeel and malt profile is just a tad lacking when compared to good ( unskunked ) european pilsners .

this beer has got a great roasted malt/chocolate/coffee nose . they bill this beer as a polish porter and it comes damn close to authenticity . but in my book , it is better in many ways due to the extra bit of coffee/roasted malt character that a lot of baltic porters do n't possess & gt ; but it also has the nice smoothness associated with polish porters .  was interested to try this beer as it is advertised as `` america 's original '' or `` oldest '' lager . tasted like a typical american macro lager , not much now to add .

it was a very complex and pleasant aroma . tasting : a strong malt presence came across up front , followed by alcohol warmth and slight fruit flavors .  smell : malt , caramel and a hint of smoke taste : again , malty , not much bitterness or hops detectable , carmel and smoke in the background mouthfeel : a bit thin ... i had expected it to have more body drinkability : yes , i would drink it again .

smell : awesome . tasted this beer 4 months after it was brewed and bottled , yet it still had an amazingly fresh hop aroma .  i had this at isaac newton 's in newtown pa.poured from a bottle into a snifter.pours a cloudy light amberish color with ridiculous white frothy heading that stays bubbly to the very end.smell is very faint light hops light malt nothing to get nutty about.taste is very sweet like a soda i took a sip and ended up with a mouthful of foam . i would have guessed this was a light beer but with 6.9 % alcohol ( stated on bottle ) this kind of a heavy hitter .

the similarity stops there , though , with the aroma being packed with a fresh and bold combination of floral and earthy hops . it honestly smells like slicing open a vacuum bag full of hop pellets for a new batch of home brew .  m : oily texture with average carbonation and a bitter finish . the mouthfeel is the weakest aspect of the beer .
a : enormous , rich dark-dark mocha head that slowly sinks to about half a finger .  mouthfeel : nice mouth-coating , but a much weaker carbonation than i was expecting ( the tap ? ) .
served room temperature , this beer had a dense , whipped-cream head that took a half an hour to melt .  felt a little too light and watery .

poured in a new belgium tulip . a : shiny gold beer with a white , towering head . it does settle down , a bit , but a foamy pillow floats on the surface down to the last gulp . wonderful brussels lacing .  i think this is one of lost abbey 's better brews , most of the others i have tried had low carbonation which took away from there overall enjoyment .

a= pours a depp black with a perfect two finger head that 's a dark tan almost brown color . great thick marshmellowy retention and lacing .  i get orange and coriander on the finish , which is a bit weird ... i wish it was a bit thicker , but i 'll take what i can get .

fantastic aroma with an intnse floral hop presence .  when i first picked it up i thought belgian dubbel right away and it made sense to me when i found out it was rye ale . the beer is thin , at 6.3 abv a very sessionable ale and i bet this is really something fresh on draft .

especially nitro stouts , with their cascading after the pour and thick , creamy meringue like heads . in a pint glass or snifter these brews have an uncanny ability to look amazingly inviting .  body is between light and medium , a tad too thin .
this is one of the first scotch ales i have ever tried so i was n't sure what to expect . this led me to try many other scotch ales .  light body and aggressive carbonation .

the smell hits you right in the nose . strong aromatics - hops , esters , permanent markers and lots of nose stinging alcohol . the hops are earthy and piney - similar to sticking a pine branch and needles up your muzzle . trying to balance these monsters must be a tough job but those arrogant pricks did it ! sweet , sticky and downright bitter as hell .  5 it 's a bit thin and the carbonation works to emphasize that .

poured into a tuilp snifter , revealing deep brown clear body with a thick dark beige head . beautiful to look at .  m : the medium light body is semi-dry and could stand quite a bit less carbonation .

a - light copper colour , clear , creamy off-white head , persists , sticky lace s - clean , light pine , grapefruit , not a huge aroma , but pleasant t - honey sweetness dominates , hop flavour and bitterness is low , there could actually be more hop flavour and bitterness present , but the sweetness is getting in the way , even lingering into the finish m - med high carbonation , medium body , results in a mouth filling creaminess that really does not fit , carbonation also seems to increase alcohol burn d - rather disappointing from a brewery that gets great reviews .  body is very flat and smooth .
poured a beautiful mahogany with a creamy light brown head that clings well to the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel was quite average for a belgian brune .

fairly decent head , two-fingered and off-white , sticky , leaving a decent amount of staining around the inside of the glass . pretty good looking , in my opinion .  the mouthfeel is neither here nor there . carbonation starts high and fades .

smell is simply wonderful . lots of green hops smell . i want to take in deep breaths of this beer . very assertive but not too unbalanced .  m- somer orange honey ale is thin with a light carbonation , slight snap of carbonation at the end .
dark brown , coffee color , light barely makes it through , with a rich tan head with large bubbles .  the mouth feel was pretty average , has a slight alcohol bite at the end of it .

pours a thick black color with a huge sturdy brown head . the head is solid and dissipates slowly .  when i first saw andygator after it had been transferred to the growler at the abita brew pub , i thought what a beautiful bronze to golden color . just a hint of hops comes out when you sniff it . then the taste , i told my wife it was like liquid gold . this beer is a the top of my list . now that could be because it has n't been easy to get or because it is so very good . we soon went by the bulldog on magazine in new orleans . i had the andygator on draft , my what a killer brew .

milk chocolate , deliciousness . touch of vanilla . i wish i could turn up that coffee chocolatey taste i got in the nose since it is so nice , but much tamer than the nose .  m - a little like bodied for a stout , but still light and creamy .
huge three finger thick head with insane lacing . nice amber color .  mouthfeel : fizzy and frothy . light and very very dry .

bottle into a tulip . a : gentle pour yields a 1 finger , dense , off-white head that sits , immovable , atop the brew . beer is a semi-clear ruby red . lacing is thick , frothy , and ringed with great stick .  the texture is smooth and a little bit thin on the palate with a good carbonation and a medium body .

okay so its already been stated more than once that this is not in any way shape or form an imperial stout ... it is most definately an american style stout , most likely milk/lactose based ... appearance is rather average minus the kickass retro looking stubby ... smell is awesome , sweet milk chocolate eminates , this is like smelling a cup of chocolate mousse ... also a somewhat generous touch of toffee/butterscotch on the nose , which means a touch of vitamin `` d '' ... taste is dry , light/medium bodied with milk chocolate on the palate ... sweet lactose-like finish ... a very drinkable stout and extremely interesting , especially taking into mind where it comes from ... cheers !  sweet with decent carbonation . no real aftertaste mouthfeel : very thin and lacy , not one to linger on your tongue for long .
dark as night smell & gt ; chocolate , roasted malt , molasses . drinkability & gt ; good .  moderate hoppiness . slightly thin tasting , but not in a bad way . highly drinkable .

a - two-finger head of dense , light-khaki foam that collapses under itself , leaving rings around the glass . deep amber red/orange and decently opaque , but not cloudy . when the head finally finishes , there 's a thin , but almost solid layer of lacing across the surface that stays longer than i have patience to see if it 's going to clear .  has a very rough bitter mouthfeel , very carbonated , but the flavor is definitely there to make up for it .

appearance- pours a brilliant , very clear , orange body with a huge , foamy , light beige head on top . excellent head retention . excellent lacing .  lighter than expected on the palate . crisp . the low hop content ( 33 ibu ) is lost in the malt and alcohol . in fact its all malt and alcohol and a bit too cloying at that . i often wonder if some brewers actually taste their beers before they release them , because not only does this taste like one of my first homebrew bombs , but i agree holy jesus , what are these goddamn beers ?

big aroma . plenty of banana , just enough clove to balance , a little bit of other spiciness going on underneath . still , the flavor comes short of the aroma 's promise . excellent hefeweizen .  m : fairly light body with matching carbonation . a little less substantial than would be ideal .

bud american ale has a beautiful red/amber color and a smooth crisp finish . some may think im crazy for saying this , but i found it to have the same taste as a very very weak ipa .  citrus and spiciness to the nose . malt sweetness ansd hop bittering very balanced . dry finish . smells get even better as beer warms . oh yeah , i 'm not so fond of coors either , but this definitely is not a coors lite . if they marketed this beer with scantily clad fine chicks it could become my favorite .

appearance : deep red with a foamy , pink head . nice , almost champagne level of carbonation initially , which decreased fairly quickly .  ambrosial at the front , the top quite thin and the finish minimally carbonated , hops all mingled in with the other spices , different '' for sure , pleasant to the palate , and the aftertaste quite dry and bitter also long lasting .
the color is awesome ; dark orangey brown , with a thick head on the pour .  feel is ok , a bit on the thin side . i think a bit more carbonation would help .
it 's opaque black/brown with a strong , two finger beige head . looks like a stout .  fine mouthfeel .
beautiful white head and golden color . heard great things and was so stoked to try this one .  liking the medium-high carb , but the mouthfeel is a little watery for my tastes .
boddingtons pub ale head : verry nice texture and color , no taste .  there is a creaminess that helps the mouthfeel but the carbonation is low which makes this beer seem watered down .

l : hazy burnt orange , huge carbonated head that dissipates to 1/4 inch . great lacing .  this is a thick creamy beer and if it had less carbonation i would feel like i 'm drinking a glass of hershey 's syrup .

pale straw color , brilliant clarity . large , thick white head with excellent retention .  mouth -the beer leaves quickly and body does n't add much to overall characteristics , but nice tingling on front and clean but not dry finish .

very black body with a stunning brown head.spotty lacing on the glass .  i noticed to yeast in the bottom of the bottle after i read that it was bottle conditioned on the label . the malt comes through as i drink . there is the malt backbone with some hops . i guess i 'm just so used to ipa 's and dipa 's . this is a really drinkable beer .
a : pours a completely opaque jet black with a three-finger tan head in my nonic . i get lots of nice lacing as the head dies down .  the palate is average for the style .

fortunately , the aroma of this beer is much more pleasant than the appearance . huge silky chocolate malt presence with hints of roasted malt , coffee bean , burnt toast and oatmeal . this smells excellent ! soft carbonation tickling the tongue up front followed by a silky , slight viscous chewy mouthfeel that thins out toward the finish which is hot and dry . the silky chocolate malt notes from the aroma are very faint and are completely overpowered by the overwhelming heat . the earthy/oak barrel notes are also faint and the vanilla hints from the aroma are absent .  it is a little on the watery side . the carbonation is good though .
great looking mahogany body with a nice off white head .  mouthfeel is good . almost completely non-existent carbonation .

the smell is what hop heads live for . it 's full of citris , piney and spicey hops . not much malt , just smooth high end hop flavors dancing throughout your nose . taste starts out wiht some caramel and hop notes , then turns into a blindingly bitter hop blast .  ... but good for the style m- a little bit of stickyness to this light bodied brew ... medium carbonation d- probably the easiest 40 i 'll ever finish
pours a most excellent dark bronze color , with an appealing ruby tint and a nice almost beige head .  m - surprisingly light mouthfeel for a porter .

we poured it into snifters and were greeted with a slight white head that sat on top of the most awesome caramel honey colored brew i have seen in a while .  m : a little flat in the mouth , sticky and slick in a disquieting way .

a : nice amber , crazy hardcore strength head that lingered to the bottom of the glass .  looks the part ... .pitch black ... no light shines through ... very slight tan head ... sweet chocolate for an instance then a soft whiskey aroma emerges and mixes in ... .good not great flavor ... some nice burnt malts ... also a hint of sweet chocolate ... the bourban aging adds a nice bite on the finish ... i wish the flavors were more intense ... .this is a subtle beer ... mouthfeel is creamy , easy drinking and smooth ... a bit too think for my liking ... needs a bit more body ... creamy+ velvety+ thinnish= a stout that slides down easy..problem is that is not exactly what i 'm looking for in this beer .

s : present in the smell is sweet tropical fruit , lime and grapefruit citrus , and a faint mineral edge . the lush hops fade quickly revealing some sharp toasty malt . t : begins with toast and delicate floral hops , son joined by bright lemon citrus .  m- a bit thinner than i would like in my stouts and missing the creaminess or carbonation levels i expect but still a bit of chewy character and the flavors do fill the mouth well .
very handsome light copper/amber , thick , full off-white head .  very crisp and a little dry but with oiliness in the end ( if that makes sense ) .
pours a gorgeous bright glowing orange color with a lasting offwhite head .  the mouthfeel is fine for the style . carbonated water , basically . overall , this is , well , carbonated water .
great looking beer , deep ruby red when held up to light .  m - a little thin , but highly carbonated .

poured a translucent pale , yellow-gold with a two inch frothy head honeycombed with holes . head retained decent consistency and left behind cloud-like bands of lacing as it receded and the brew was consumed .  this one was probably made when hops were fresh last fall . aroma is very much hops , but not overly annoying hops . flavor is also quite nice and pleasant , hops are strong and clear , with a mix of the fruit flavors mentioned before and herbal/oily/piney that works pretty well . however , the end of the swallow is like choking on weeds- almost like an alcohol burn , but it 's a hop-oil burn . but other than that , this is a very nice beer .
i was very excited to drink this after smelling it , but the taste did n't pull through how i would have liked .  mouth feel - mouthfeel was good but nothing special .

color was a bright ruby red/orange .  seriously , is this beer or just a bad soft drink gone bad ... der ? i could n't quite place the smell , but from what i can remember , this is what malta smells like . does n't even resemble malt or beer , just a sickly sweet sort of caramel . i took maybe two sips and gave up . did n't taste like beer , let alone porter , and certainly not like a real baltic porter . waste of $ 2 .

pours into my tulip glass a clear luminous golden peach color . great fluffy white clouds of head laze about the glass for what seems like hours , finally sinking to swaths of sticky white cotton candy lace .  this beer has a lower level of carbonation with a slightly flat and watery mouthfeel . overall , this is a good beer with some nice smells and flavors but the mouthfeel is a bit lacking .
this is the best part of this beer , it looks awesome ! the nose is a little off putting .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied .
some ripe pineapple and candied sugar also . wow major letdown .  m : a hare thin for the style , a bit hi for the carb .

pours out a hazy , pale yellow with an insane head that is dense , rocky-topped , and retains like nothing i 've seen before .  the mouthfeel is medium-light , and actually about the only thing in this beer that is sorta ok .

poured carefully into a pils glass it forms a huge creamy loose head that has amazing staying power . the appearance is very appetizing and the crowned mountainous head is a sight to see , like a lump of mashed potatoes sitting atop on a float .  mouthfeel -- nitro has none of the joys of spot on carbonation , and at times the lack of it ruins the drinking .
pours out to a sparkingly clear rich amber , forming a voluminous creamy head with superior retention and very nice lacing . great looking beer .  slick mouthfeel is thin for an imperial .
pours a golden wheat colour , big , beautiful white head takes up a good half of the glass . looks like a saison to me !  moutfeel is pretty thin .

poured out a slightly hazed golden color with one of the most attractive heads of foam i can remember .  nice clean alcohol as it warms or as i feel it ... not sure which is having that effect on the taste : -/ dry , mildly carbonated and very much the viscosity of water .

on tap at the brew pub as part of a taster , 5oz glass ... pours a super clear straw with good retention and lacing ... the aroma is downer , super sweet , corn with skunk ... the taste is more of the same , lots of skunk , most of the rest is tasteless , just a boring beer .  i like this hefe . not as spicy as a schnider but still a good beer . pale/white in color . great wheat head . banana frutiy esthers are not over done .

deep dark black leather with a brown tide churning in a mercurial pattern . couple stacks of paper thick head .  very little carbonation ( too little as the matter of fact ) . medium bodied ( which is thin for the style ) with almost no carbonation .

smell is very good . smells of roasted nuts , caramel and coffee .  might as well have drank a miller light and put some food coloring in it.poured a dull pink collor with excessive carbonation . tatsed like you would expect a bad pilsner to taste . i would wright more but the opening statement pretty much sums it up .

'' a : motor oil with satanic red head . i love it already .  hops - wheaty/earthy/spicy mf 3.0 medium body on palate , semi watery on finish for an ofest beer d 4.5 - i dig this stuff , the brewer , the facility and the whole vibe .

a lot of grapefruit and sweetness in the scent . the flavor is nice citrusy resinous hops with a hint of honey or maple syrup sweetness .  initial flavor is very much cream , almost like chocolate milk . low hop flavor does n't get in the way of all the malts . very drinkable beer . while the complex malt profile teases the tongue , it still in some ways is just another cream stout , just a more expensive cream stout . worth a try , but would n't want to spend too much on what could be more affordable in other brands .

it was completely black until held to the light ( got a few stares ) , then a tiny but of ruby came through the black murk . had a great head that lasted and left lacing .  really yummy - would be great with meat or fish . m..just average here . a bit drying , but not as much as anticipated .

the smell of the beer was amazing - banana like with a hint of clove . the color was nothing special , but formed a nice head .  taste & gt ; sweet , full body with a huge punch that softens , leaving in its wake a honey and resin hang . it is delicious mouf & gt ; easy , but not amazing drinkability & gt ; great !

a- a sweet dark orange nectar pours into my tulip glass . a two finger fluffy , honey tinted head floats , grabs on , and gets sticky as it slowly fades away . this is brilliantly sticky lacing ... it does not wan na let go !  medium to thin body with smooth mouthfeel .
really interesting look . ridiculous retention .  m : feels a bit viscous .
appearance - burnt orange in color with a thick 2 1/2 finger head . leaves a ton of lacing on the side of the glass .  m- the mouth was ok , again really unremarkable and watery light .
wonderful aroma !  mouthfeel is a little thin and watery , with a rather low carbonation level .

the aroma is a citrus almost so complex , my nose ca n't comprhend it . wow ! ! very interesting dipa . highly recommended ! !  m - a little harsh on the palate ; only average part of the beer in my opinion .

pours a beautiful clear , copper red , with a thick inch of tan head that is leaving behind gobs of lacing . bubbles are very easily seen racing up the edges of the glass to keep the head lasting . excited for this one .  a light to medium mouthfeel . so drinkable !

a : this is an amazing looking beer . dark brown in color with a 1.5 finger mocha colored head with excellent retention and lacing .  light in body , almost thin , the carbonation is nice a little light though .

this smells amazing . the smells are so bold and assertive , yet smooth . it is good but i assume past its prime .  m : light as it gets . crisp , refreshing beer . overall : light beers are why i thought i did n't like beer in my early drinking days .

it pours pretty much the qiuntessinial way for a ris thick , inky black body with a huge fomay tan head that sticks forever before receding to some nice thick-walled style lacing .  mouthfeel seems dominated but a fast carbonation , over a thin to medium liquid .

amber-orange and slightly hazy color with a towering foamy white head sticking way outside the goblet and forming a peak . insane level of carbonation keeps the head alive for a long time .  while this beer did n't disappont me it did n't meet my expectations of it . of course being a hophead rarely can a beer more hoppier than usual surprise me . it did have more hops than the average beer drinker would prefer imo . the taste was hoppy yet with a good malty balance . went well with the food and was very drinkable ... ... ... ... ..cheers
super carbonated , tons of bubbles w long lasting white head . very sticky , leaving tons of lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but not exceedingly so .

the body is a darkish hazy orange and the head is frothy and plentiful . the lacing action is fantastic and it actually made me want it more the more i drank .  taste while similar tends to be swayed by the aggressive mouthfeel . one thing i did n't like too much is the cakey dry mouthfeel that leaves a coat to remember .

pours a luscious looking deep , clean ruby color with a fat , dense pillow head that descends into net-like lacing down the sides of the glass . this is a beautiful dipa .  i love octoberfest beers and i love flying dog , i think they are one of the best micro 's around . their version of the octoberfest is not anything impressive but it is pretty tasty . you may drink one and not like it , but give it a second try . it has a great taste and has great drinkability for those fall football days .

a very proud head atop a beautiful amber body sets it a world above its irish counterparts .  disclaimer : i do n't drink yellow beer very often . started out my evening with one of these , as one of my friends who prefers a sharp pils to just about anything else has had very positive things to say about this beer . overall , this was drinkable , and had a surprisingly noticable saaz hop flavoring to it . at the same time , the sourness left on the palate reminded me of why i do n't venture into euro-lager/pils land too often . but , i still enjoyed this beer , and would have it again if i was feeling pilsy .

the nose is sweet , earthy and bready with some dark chocolate mixed in at the end with some flickering hop notes . the aroma is very involved and bodes well for the future .  had this beer tonight at the flying saucer , fort worth , texas , on the `` buy the beer , keep the glass '' night . i may be biased a little here due to my liking for whit biers , wheat beers , and hefe-weizens , or it may be that i got there before the `` buy the beer , keep the glass '' night oficially started at 7:00pm and drank a guinness while i waited , but i really liked this beer . my server brought out a 500ml weizen glass from the brewery , and a 500ml bottle of beer . the label states it was bottle-fermented , so the proper hefe-weizen pour ( pour 7/8 of it , swirl the bottle to rouse the yeast , dump it on top ) was required .

smells of bubblegum and a citrus hop with sweet caramel/toffee aromas .  in terms of the mouthfeel of the beer , that 's probably the best point . the carbonation is what you 'd expect of a macro beer , and rather well-balanced .

interesting fruity twist on a bsda but a bit too sweet . the flavor is just a bit too sweet , throwing the whole package off a bit for my tastes . i 'm not saying it 's terrible , but i think the beer could have really benefited from more attenuation .  this beer pours a crystal clear red-orange jewel with a thin , frothy white head that 's mostly diminishing . the aroma is like sweet baked goods in the oven ... maybe apple crisp ? once in the mouth , the medium-bodied ale starts with the twang on malt that turns into green apple and perhaps melon ... with the slightest hop bite to set it off . it has a very fresh , bright aftertaste of small , shiny green apples . nice ! ( rated jan 30 , 2007 )

this beer seems to totally define schwarzbier , but i 'm not entirely sure what the fuss is about . color is dark , virtually black . head is nearly white , and had pretty good staying power .  tastes hoppy but much smoother and more nuanced than expected . this is not your average hop bomb even if it claims to be . it 's a little blah on the pallat though .

aroma was excellent ; a great array of floral and citrus hops , a slight sweetness , and an earthy grass smell . very nice . unfortunately the smell does n't translate quite as well to taste .  m - pretty light bodied and real smooth . this is probably the weakest part of this beer .

smell : for me this was the best part of the beer . the was loaded with malty spicy goodness . there was loads and loads of cloves , cinamon , cardamnon , lemon zest and apples . none of the spices particularly stand above the chamomile . the beer has a nice malty base . mouthfeel/ drinkability : the beer is a very drinkable medium bodied beer . this beer is predominately an aromatic experience . the beer is highly quaffable .  m- a little thin and watery with little carbonation .

a : beautiful deep golden , best feature of this beer s : sweet lemon , grassy , citrusy t : i 've come to expect a certain taste from a pale ale , and this does n't measure up on draft at the home kegerator , pint glass  nice clear beer . they filter well at this brewery . the taste is caramel notes finishing with hops on the tongue . is this a winter warmer asks the alstrom brothers ? i think not . a drinkable red ale that delivers the goods .
a - very very dark amber color . the head poured a nice 1/4 inch , and lacing is very good .  the mouthfeel is really thin and i just ca n't get over that , unfortunately .

a very mellow beer with increasing complexity . i didnt realize the age when i bought it and i would say this really went past its prime in carbonation . really a very smooth and flavorful beer nonetheless with an increasing nuance even after swallowing .  the hop that is there sure is pretty t - so much different than the smell . a really sweet malted barley starts up front and than a boat load of citrus , pine and floral hops punches the malt in the groin grassy and loads of citrus m - light , but not unpleasant and actually it is super nice .

smells very fruity and floral ... which makes sense seeing as how this is made with edible flowers . enjoyabley fragrant . unfortunately for me , this tasted too much like grapefruit juice .  as far as feel goes , it was a little bit light . the flavor was pleasantly intense , but it ended up feeling a smidge watery . however , with that less substantial body came superior drinkability .

12 ounce bottle from total wine , on to the beer : in my eisenbahn weizenbock glass , it looks great . huge white , billowy head looms over a sparkling pale golden body of beer .  mouthfeel is a little dry once you kill one or two of these bad boys , but the taste and smell definitely makes up for it .
a : yellow-gold with flawless clarity , two fingers of dusty white head , copious lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , with the alcohol running to the back of the throat .

succulent and alluring aromas of fruits and berries swirl around a molassas aroma for a fantastic balance and seductiveness . where the aroma in this beer is fantastic , the flavor hardly measure up and the mouthfeel takes a severe nose-dive . if the other beer components were up to par with its aroma , we 'd have a superb beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit light for the style , though drinkability is excellent considering the abv .

smell : wow . this is a whole new realm for me . it literally smells like a sweet cup of fresh coffee . wow . taste : roasted malt , dark chocolate , and plenty of coffee flavor .  had a pint glass of this from the bottle . a-gem brown , rocky beige head , very dense . s-malty , metallic and some vanilla t-smoky , malt front , snap pea flavor in the middle , and some hop bitterness at the end . very little vanilla flavor at all m-medium d-very little vanilla flavor to this brew . the other competing flavors were some what off-putting

aroma always greets you with a big time flowery hop kick . i mean , this pale ale has an incredible floral hop scent to it . fresh , clean , & crisp in the mouth the mild biscuity malt background is dominated by - yes - more floral hops . medium to light bodied & finishes cleanly . unique & well-crafted , one of my favorite pale ale 's .  the mouthfeel is thus fairly thin , but finishes with a nice clean dryness .

the best inheritance than learned the americans of the british , an excellent formula done by one micro of the best ones in the usa , incomparable , special flavor , defined , feel as if they were chewing `` literally '' hops , exquisite for my taste , of the best thing than the gringos do , special for great occasions , recommendable 95 % .  even though its a little thin , i consider this the tastiest beer i have ever had . ) that makes your mouth water . except for my homebrew , i have never tasted anything like this in a beer . it almost tasted like grapefruit juice with lots of hop flovor and not much in bitterness .

aroma : huge hoppy aroma . mainly pine with hints of citrus .  mouthfeel is defined by the linger dry bitter booze burn between each sip , it 's not very pleasant maybe even a bit abrasive . medium bodied hop oils textured with moderate carbonation , probably the biggest turn off so far .

wow , the first bit of pour looked like orange juice and as i poured more and more in to my snifter it took on the color of orange soda , maybe a shade darker . there was a beautifully thick one finger white head that leaves some of the most beautiful lacing on the glass i have ever seen .  bottled september 2007 , batch 02565. pours oil like , midnight black with a thin brown head , and some lacing . smell is of cocoa , wheat , some vanilla , and a touch of caramel in the back . taste is a little flat , cocoa , vanilla , a little smoke , some nuts , and slight coffee , ends on the dry side .
the smell is amazing -- really strong raspberry .  mouthfeel could be a bit smoother , as the beer has a slight syrupy note as it slides down the tongue .

2011 vintage , bottle # 164/650 , into darkness snifter . a - pours black , mocha-colored fluffy head , spotty lacing , thin cap remains on top .  the only thing i mark this beer down for was it mouthfeel . i tought it had a very light mouthfeel and certainly no creaminess .

bell 's amber poured a golden amber with lots of big flakey particles , and a nice creamy thick head with nice retention - almost stout-like .  i find it rather thin for the style . carbonation is borderline too high d : this is a very smooth drinking beer with a very minimal alcohol presence .

pours a deep red gold and amazing clarity , 2.5 fingers of marbled ivory head with tight bubbles appears and never quite leaves , active small bubbled carbonation continually rises . nice lacing throughout .  m : medium and dry but a bit watery .

prostel pours a clear brass-gold body beneath a full head of frothy white foam . the head retention is excellent , as is the lacing .  grapefruit and pine explode on the palate with a great full bitterness for a floral and slight cookie finish that is fairly dry . full prickly carbonation , though a tad on the lighter side in body , the only issue that prevents this beer from being a straight up `` a '' quality .

review from notes on 2/13/10 a - poured crystal clear deep amber with a towering , fluffy , and well retained beige head . lovely lacing all over the place .  the mouthfeel is a thick , sweet molasses that coats the mouth and seems to hide some of the flavors if it is n't sipped and had with food .
cloudy pale orange-yellow with one finger of cream colored head . this is a good looking beer .  positively wretched . mouthfeel : light-bodied . medium carbonation .

my favorite part is the smell , the head on this beer is amazing . definitely not as smooth as the nocturnum , i would say it deserves just as much appreciation .  m - this one coasts all the way down .
this is a gorgeous beer . i 've got thick lacing and nice red body .  thin watery mouthfeel with a medium dose of carbonation .
pours a beautiful black color with an wet , stick , and quite dense brown head .  the mouthfeel is ok does n't really stick to your mouth , but the taste lastes awhile .

bottle courtesy of secret santa : poured a pitch-black color stout with a super large dark brown foamy head with great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel is a little more thin than one would like but i think that is part of what makes this beer extremely drinkable as it leaves the mouth feeling clean .
this beer looks fantastic . it poured a midnight black with a two finger dark khaki head that sat atop the beer like soap suds .  it is very drinkable but a little light in body .

aroma - great bouquet of mango , grapefruit , and pine . very citrusy and zesty . taste - biscuity caramel malts have a twang of sweetness , segueing to the citrusy fruitines of the hops . mango and pineapple at first , then going more bitter , like grapefruit rind .  aroma- light alc . smell , tons of clove ( well for me @ least ) maple is right on the nose , sweet potato , pumpkin . i do n't know if the beer is barrel aged but i get hints of oak and maybe sherry . a very drinkable fall brew , for a 10 % plus brew .

the smell is extraordinarily fresh and shows a great bouquet of red fruits with a very enjoyable sweetness . the very dry hoppiness invades and conquers the mouth with together with some oily notes .  smooth porter richness nicely balanced with light hops m : a bit thin for my taste but fits with the balance and delicacy of the flavor d : balanced flavors and delicate mouthfeel make this a very drinkable porter ; i definitely want another

pours a slightly cloudy pink color with a huge fluffy white head that recedes slowly but sticks itself to everything in site .  i had a bottle of this at the church street deli and pub in swansboro , nc . the straw smell of the beer which is one possibility for pilsner really stands out and is more enjoyable than many pilsners . there is almost a light fruity sweetness about the flavor . i would probably call this a `` straightforward '' beer , but there are enough tantalizing things going on in the nose and the flavor to keep you sniffing-sipping , sniffing-sipping . i am not typically a pilsner drinker and i found this one to be quite enjoyable . this sight lists it as an american blonde , and while i wo n't get cantankerous as i do n't have a bottle in front of me , i swear it said `` pilsner '' somewhere on the label . it would n't be the first time i got tricked by a label though .

the smell has a wonderful biscuit caramel body to it . i was surprised at the 6.8 % abv .  the dark fruit and roasted malts really come out in the taste , bit of marshmellow as well but it has a rather average mouthfeel and the ash flavor i detected in the smell just lingers a bit too much .

s - floral hoppy boquet complimented by a very sweet , malty aroma . awesome ! t - for an ipa this guy is very malty balanced pretty well with a boquet of hop flavors .  m- actually a little thinner than i would prefer o- really good , surprising beer .
heavy lacing is left on the glass . looks beautiful in the glass .  i would like a bit more carbonation to match the style better .

well ... app -- truly a beautiful beer . a nice thick head with decent lacing .  12oz bottle with `` best by '' date of 3/30/05 , i tasted on 7/29/05 . aroma is citrous and very nice . bitterness is low , but fits very well with the malt profile . althought this bottle may have degraded somewhat by age , i 'm guessing fresh from the keg this would really be something special .

lacing is amazing ! aesthetically , an amazing beer , but maybe also , biased due to the view i have of the city as i drink this .  fairly light and chalky in the mouth , adequate carbonation . just a bit watery feeling to me , still at about a medium body .
appearance : awesome multi finger head that lasts .  watery iced tea body with some carbonation .
this particular stout poured black with an off white head .  m : medium body , medium carbonation , extremely oily in texture , it literally coats your tongue leaving a somewhat sticky finish .
very appealing . a moderate strength aroma . i quite fancy it .  mouthfeel : medium , oddly very neutral .

pours a vigorous half inch head which settles to an 1/8 '' ring with quite good lacing . this is a truly beautiful beer .  medium-light bodied , a bit spritzy ( somewhat soda-like ) , and not quite creamy . lightly warming from the abv .

) isid'or pours a deep tangerine hue with a core of caramelized iced-tea . a big , frothy head holds court up top , rich custard in color and creamy in its consistency .  fairly full with a decent body , but does feel a bit watery for a 7.5 % drop . slick , i would say , but a bit thinner than i would like given the flavours .

poured into a stemmed tulip : totally black , with a finger of tan head .  m : thinner and not as heavy as i would have assumed from the appearance and smell , still leaning toward a medium feel however . very pleasant . d : the thinner than expected mouth feel and very smooth taste make this a very session-able porter .

a- ruby , purple foam s - fruits all over the place . pleasant smell ! t - woah , my tastes have changed .  m- light and watery - not much body at all d- smooth finish i recommend this one on taste alone .

a - pours black in color with a 1/2 finger taupe head s - smells like i opened up a fresh bag of coffee with hints chocolate . awesome coffee aroma . t - taste follows the nose - loads of rich , roasted coffee is the predominant flavor on the palate . this is a really , really good coffee stout .  yes , burnt , they did n't just roast , they turned the malts almost into charcoal . i ca n't say i really like this burnt aftertaste . it is too bad , because it could otherwise potentially be a very nice beer . the burnt flavor overpowers the hops , so i ca n't say anything about them .

t- sweet sweet malts up front , middle to back come the rush of hops , grapefruit here less citrus than in the nose , hint of pine in the back , definitely feel the heat , not as dry as i was expecting ... .citrus hops , heat , sweet m - more than medium not quite full , hops remain on the palate , minimal carbonation o - there are not a lot of brews that give off such an amazing smell but the taste was just a bit too sweet for me .  i 've been just over a year now getting to know all different kinds of beers , so with this being my first official review please bare with me . the smell was probably what the minimum should be for a good pils . i very much enjoyed the crisp hoppy tast which lingered in my mouth for a bit . i would say that being one who tends to lean towards the darker and more bitter , i was pleasantly suprised and do intend on purchasing prima in the futer .

superb . taste -- chocolate malts and bourbon up front , along with toffee sweetness , caff macchiato , vanilla oakiness , guajillo chile , and red pepper flake .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp with an average carbonation level . overall , a good appearance and aroma , but the dryness hurts the feel a little .
looks awesome s : smells pretty good .  m : decently carbonated and has a little bite .
pours a ruby-brown colour with huge off-white head . lots of lacing , great head retention .  mouthfeel is a bit heavy and thick , leaves your mouth a bit syrupy .
produced a giant fluffy tan head with great retention .  the only dissapointment was that it was deffinitely thinner on the tongue than the pour led me to believe .

this is one of the best smelling ipa 's i 've ever tried , so clean and fresh , hops at all their best .  taste : starts with a sweetness that is cut by the carbonation . mouth : smooth carbonation not harsh drink : its malty start and earthy bitterness makes this beer more enjoyable the flavor from the finish and the start mix quite well .

black with brown around the edges , big 3 finger fluffy light chocolate colored head adorns .  finish is dry and clean . body is light , waifish , bubbly . acidity is a little much on the back of the throat ; unpleasant bite . decent beer ; mild complexity and somewhat challenging .

huge flowery hop aroma that is almost overpowering each time i bring the glass up to my mouth . the taste is n't as quite as hoppy the aroma but is still extremely strong . slightly metallic at first but as i continue through the beer i become more accustomed to the taste and it seems to be better balanced .  the mouthfeel initially struck me as too thin for a bock , and so i recommend letting it warm up some .

compared other commercial brews that contain them , this one is much better . spicy , hop flavor , bitterness with a nice balance of malt sweetness .  mouthfeel : light to medium , but i swallowed as quick as possible to stop the overload .

decent strength here as well . quite nice . taste : toasted and wheat malt again with nots of caramel and sweet candy sugar as well .  feel is light-medium bodied , a bit watery and low on carbonation .

a=frothy foam and rich dark brown color ... very inviting .  light bodied , a bit thin , with a clove-like wheat-ness and a tingly orange peel backdrop . i do not like buying any wheat beer without a freshness date on it but ayingers ' are great no matter . this weizen is nothing to snub , however , as it is an enjoyable beer anytime of the season !

the taste is a mix-mash of yeast , oak , and brett , has a sharp acidic bite i 'm not a huge fan of . interesting profile but not a flavor i enjoy .  mouthfeel is thin to medium bodied with plenty of carbonation .

aromas of pine , winter spices ( nutmeg , cinnamon , and some others ) , and citrus .  the waimea brewing company sits on an incredible piece of property on the southern end of kaua'i and is worth searching out after exploring the waimea canyon area . i came in parched and wanted to save my taste buds for a tasty-looking ipa the bartender was pouring so i started with a thirst quenching cane fire red . the red pours with a generous inch-tall creamy eggshell-colored head that dissipates to an eighth-of-an-inch with incredible lacing . cane fire red throws a malty nose with surprising yeast notes . on first sip , the crystal malts come to the forefront and are followed by a spicy hop finish . this beer is dangerously quaffable and just the ticket after a day spent in the island sun .

the aroma wafts from the glass and the sweet malt can be detected from a foot away . very palatable , easy to drink , and just enough character to re-visit it .  it was crisp and refreshing , with hints of earthy clove and allspice.. similar notes on the nose . very clean flavors overall , and highly drinkable . i would highly recommend , as it seems this beer is the best of it 's style .
awesome looking brew .  mouthfeel : a little thin then what i prefer for the style , but that does add to its drinkability .
the head is dark tan with good lace and kind of glitters . good lace .  m - medium bodied but very thin and watery overall , even for a cask pull .
really unique and awesome smelling . there 's nothing out there like this !  mouthfeel is on the light side and i sort of wished for a more solid feel but it 's still good .

s - rich , mocha aroma with an excellent balance of chocolate and coffee . d - complex and enjoyable . very dark flavors bordering on carbonized . the flavor is quite nice , but the aroma is really the most successful aspect of this beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh and overcarbonated .

pours a clear light golden color with a huge 3-4 finger fluffy snow white head . nice head retention and excellent lacing .  it has a slightly flat mouthfeel in the beginning but this seems to diminish as the beer warms .

was excited to try this beer but as soon as i opened it got a blast of a non-appetizing smell , idk maybe i had a bad batch.it was drinkable but i thought that it wasnt hopped as well as i personally like it a friend of mine who also tried it felt the same way . i personally would n't recomened this beer but dont get me wrong duclaw has some awsome beers .  the alcohol starts to peep through on the finish but is in check m : the body on the finish is a little thin for my liking but the carbonation is pleasant and tingling d : this is very very drinkable for the abv
smells of plum and cherry . also very sweet and malty . hope it tastes as good as it smells .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with carbonation being high .

smells delightful . sweet and chocolate malt presents are strong .  its major drawback is that it seems to lack a thing called flavour . now light beer is bound to have some downsides , but why bother to drink any alcohol if this is what you get . a have run out of positives for crappy beer i am afraid .

this is really a nice smelling beer ! band-aids and bubble-gum ! spicy , sweet , and phenolic .  t - hot taste slides into apricots and almost melts back to the hop taste on the back end m - some lingering meld of both tastes , but nothing spectacular d - i could drink this all day !
prodigious amounts of rocky foam , leaving nice patchwork down the glass .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is slightly watery .

a : the beer is a cloudy orange-brown color with a big foamy off-white head that fades slowly and leaves a thick lace on the glass . the pour also creates a nice guiness-like cascade of carbonation , which i havent seen too often in this style .  m/d : a medium body with a high amount of carbonation . thin and watery .

a - this deep brown cloudy beer looks ruddy brown/red in the light and supports a massive three finger khaki head that deposits lots of thick foamy lace on the glass . the head sticks around for a long time ( never falling below two fingers ) , and a quick swirl spatters more foamy lace around the edges on my big brandy snifter . this looks creamy , dense , and thick . were off to a damn good start !  m - easily he goes down giving a scrape along the way at the roof of my mouth and outsides of my tongue . ~ i like this brew .
smell is strong with citrus and hops .  it does have a crisp flavor and mouthfeel to it . lucayan lager if you can find it .

s : lots of different fruit notes in the nose : apples , pears , lemon peel , and oranges . the spices come through quite nicely as well , as does a bit of dry brett and some earthy funk . t : unfortunately , the flavor does not live up to expectations .  mouthfeel : very smooth , but a little more carbonation than i would like to see .

this beer is a bit different as wild ales go , having said that i 'd take this over la follie this worked better for me pours an effervescent apricot with fast fading white head . retains a viscous appearance once the head breaks down s : funk by the bucket , hay , horse blanket , sourness & vinegar t : grassy , greasy , & some hay notes up front . finishes with dirt , lemons , honey , bacon fat & tartness .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied and kind of watery .

poured an intense dark copper/rust color with a frothy head that just sat there for a few minutes leaving behind plenty of lacing . full of carbonation with tiny bubbles speeding to the surface to join the party .  thin body , light carbonation .

with a name of red rye , go figure . has a ton of head , and amazing lace retention on the glass .  this brew is just a little too carbonated for the style , and not as smooth as most british brands .

smells like fresh fig newtons dipped in chocolate . very appealing nose for sure ! a bit of a chalky , yet silky finish . intense and hearty . i 'm full .  medium to thick body , spirited level of carbonation , sweet bubbly mouthfeel . that said , i would have like it a bit lighter on the carbonation .

very clear and very dark . two finger beige head melts away to a nice covering film that is good at placing sticky lace down the glass .  mouthfeel : surprisingly lighter body than i expected ... the beer version of a meringue ? the lighter body makes it a bit easier to have more of this than a similar stout .

if i could n't smell the dark fruits during the pour , i 'd guess this was a stout . smells great . i 'm a big fan of this style and they can vary greatly ... i dig the ones that are more on the grape side of the flavor spectrum , like this one .  mouthfeel is competent . worse than corona .
for one this beer is the perfect color amber , if it crystalized i could sell it as jewlery .  mouthfeel is a little thin which is my only complaint but other than that this beer is great .

a- as of this review , this is the best looking beer bottle out there ! the product inside is decent looking as well ... clear , dark brown/chestnut color and a thick brownish head that turns into a thin layer that actually sticks around .  a-fingers worth of off-white/eggshell head , clear light brown color with some hues of orange , some light lacing throughout the glass s-unfortunately i am getting over a cold so my nose isnt going to be up to snub , from what i can gather though , the citra and falconer hops seem to jump right out , a lot of citrrus and tropical fruit characteristics come out in the nose , also some resinous pine , and bready malts t-really nice balance of flavors here , starts out with dry and malty , that signature grainy , earthy half acre flavor here , it then moves to the citrus flavors highlighted by a very nice grapefruit character m-a little thin , but not crazy watery , has good carbonation that comes off almost grainy d-really liked it , it didnt blow me away like the first time i drank daisy cutter , but this is another solid addition to half acre 's arsenal , hopefully we will see this become a seasonal or even a year round

s : wow - all about the saaz aroma , though the malt does manage to make an appearance underneath . t : way up at the hoppy end .  a roasted and smoky taste at first with a watery finish . a light bubbly body makes this brown very drinkable .

cloudy , golden with a copper tint . forms a huge , off-white head that holds quite well and leaves some lace .  served out of a can , which i was glad to see more breweries moving towards cans . not sure when the coconut is added to the brew , but i might guess at the end to give it the sweetness , but this would require filtering to make sure no yeast went to work on the new sugar . this beer goes for $ 14+ a 4 pack on the island , but it is quite good .

what would you expect from nitro and old rasputin ... .well the appearance is lovely , dark , rich , frothy , excellent retention ... etc .  m - the feel starts smooth and moves consistently toward an aftertaste with some disruptive character .

a - pours a deep copper red with a fluffy pale tan head that sat about a half inch over the beer but dissipated pretty quickyl . like a blazing fireplace , looks warm and inviting .  m : very light and delicate mouthfeel . lighter body than i prefer , but it does not bother me whatsoever , all things considered . very slick , almost oily mouthfeel .
hazy golden body highlighted by shooting strands of bubbles rising to the outstandingly sturdy head .  like a watery summit almost . m= high carbonation and overall pretty average .

once the foam subsided , the wonderful smell of chocolate and caramel came forward .  m : the carbonation level is acceptable ( albeit perhaps a tad high ) , but i am at a loss as to the `` double cream '' nature of the beer .
bitter , boozy bomb ! nose was fantastic , but the booze and hops were too extreme for me .  the first sip reveals an average body with little carbonation that is gentle and caresses my palate .

poured a black as night shade with a huge tan head that took a while to dissipate . lots of lace left behind .  m-a bit thin for the style with more of a harsh carb bite than i typically find in a stout . overall , the mouthfeel is very , very average .

poured from bottle into pint glass a- aggressively poured java head to give create the desired foamey head . a dark chocolatey look with a rocky mountain type head .  hopping is present , but totally overmatched by latex . this sucks . the body is decent enough , clocking in at a sturdy medium .

zesty orange and citrus aroma , sweet , dank , and resiny . as it sits , it has a pleasant woody , leafy , vinous scent that emerges . really fresh and appealing . full bodied and almost viscous , with a strong bitter hop edge . very potent stuff .  very nice m- this is what i do n't like ... the body is really thin .
very dark mahogoany beer with large milky tan head .  m - ok mouthfeel but it feels a tad over carbonated which slightly reduces the overall experience .

i was excited to open my painstakingly acquired white oak ( and black tuesday ) . for me , a beer as delicate as this is just not appropriate for bourbon bbl aging . the poor beer was completely overwhelmed and it was just a boozy bourbon bomb . i had the same problem with allagash curieux before they toned it down ( or maybe it was just more mellow on tap ) .  crispy , mouth watering . tastes good & is n't watery or light . medium to heavy body .

pours out to a semi-milky pinkish light amber , forming a billowing , peaked meringue pink head which rises over the top of my new belgium `` worthy '' glass . retention is amazing . carbonation is brisk , forming spiral streamers with active eddies of bubbles .  medium-light body with moderately-high carbonation .

a : very dark black , had some nice head on it , but is has since dissipated while the webpage was loading.. s : carmel and chocolate , but mostly roasted coffee.. mm mm good .  m/d : a medium body that is over carbonated for my tastes .

i smell dry-hopping ! aroma is a full onslaught of american hop goodness , bright , floral and citrusy , with loads of grapefruit and orange . quite delightful and very inviting . light-to-medium in body with a bit of a lively carbonation . sadly , the flavors are n't quite as delightful as the aroma . slight caramel sweetness shows itself up front , moving into a mildly bitter middle with rather one-dimensional herbal hop notes ; develops into a slightly bittersweet , medium-dry finish with a bit of lingering caramel sweetness .  could use a bit more carbonation in my opinion ... but the body is light enough that it works as it is .

the head is dense and sticky and the a nice milky tan color . good staying power and lacing .  this one remindes me of rich black coffie and hops mixed . this one is an almost black amber/brown brew that is big and malty . the mouthfeeal is heavy , almost like liquid bread . this one is realy good thank hevans for good bock i wish that this one was avalable all year long but i will get more in spring

appearance : a beautiful clear orange-amber in color with a towering tan head that lasted a long time and left exceptional lacing on glass .  m : the sweetness of the honey is a bit too much at times , even though it tastes great . the low bitterness makes the beer a bit unbalanced , and gives you more of a smooth feel than a crisp feel . it 's a bit like drinking lemonade , easy to drink and very sweet .

smell is fantastic , tons of vanilla with some chocolate .  the taste undergoes a similiar transformation , but dark chocolate mostly holds court with roasted malt , with a surprising hop element circling around the periphery . not much body to it , but a nice balance and an easy drinker .

pours with a big , fluffy head reminiscent of frothy egg-whites and lacing is left done the sides of the glass as the foam settles . the color is very hazy yellow .  m : light and corbonated d : very drinkable pumpkin ale that is not overdone at all .
the smell is amazing : arizona or snapple peach ice tea .  the first thing i notice is the light body this porter has . too low in my opinion . carbonation is appropriate .
pretty good fruity and hoppy smell . hoppy bitter flavor that gets worse on the second sip .  a little thin on the palate with hop oils and average carbonation .

appearance : black like the back ground on this page smell : chocolate , coffee , malts and cookies taste : not as heavy as u think it would be taste like it smells butit is not a strong taste mouth : thin and creamy no carbanation drink : dont really like it that much i usualy only have one or two of these when i go out to eat .  is lighter than it appears and taste . i have to say that i am partial on the review since i got a whole 1/2 barrel keg for ... uh , free ! at first i thought this kind of tasted like a `` fat tire light '' if there was such a thing .

a - perfectly clear , crisp body that plops down a thick white head oiver topo this fizzy yellow body . extraordinary for an ipa . s - the constant carbonation consistently releases strong grapefruit ( not ruby red , though , rather the more bitter variety ) overtones and the head keeps them there for you after each sip . i appreciate an oilier brew in an ipa .  medium bodied with a medium amount of carbonation . ends sticky .

pour is stand porter pour , deep nearly pitch black with a khaki colored head .  on tap at the brewery 07-10-09 . pours a beautiful dark brown with nice tan head . great looking beer with a really unique aroma dominated with chocolate and orange . would have love to tasted this blind as the aromas were a bit confusing to the senses . pretty well balanced with a nice bitter chocolate finish . my notes are also saying that there was a nice woody aroma and touch of dry wood in the taste , though i 'm not sure how that came about .
the arouma was unreal , excellent smell of hops and hints of fruit .  mouthfeel is a little thin for my taste , but overall a very interesting beer with lots of distinct fruity characters .

the pour an indefectible ebony color , the head preposterous in size , frothy in texture and the color a light chocolate brown with a sticky covering of lace after the head has dissipated .  mouthfeel : medium body , sticky , sweet , and carbonated .
beautiful to look at and very easy to drink .  taste : bit thin , bit oh water . mf : thin drinkable ? : yes , very much so

ordered on-tap at dogfish head alehouse in fairfax , was very interested to have it on tap fresh . appearance- at first glance , a very dark color , dark brown with a very fluffy head , great appearance , served in a tulip glass at the alehouse .  m : the carbonation gets in the way of the flavour too much sometimes in this one , but not bad for a bsda , medium-bodied , smooth .

quite a beautiful beer to look at here , with it 's brown body and huge head that does n't ever go away and the nice lacing left throughout the glass .  rich aqueous body with virtually no carbonation ( i wonder if that 's intentional ? ) , but this beer pulls it off like few could . as drinkable as such a rich beer could be , though arguably a carbonation presence would improve things .

pours a murky amber , fading to gold at the edges . head is unbelievably massive . the foam is super-dense , bubbles are near invisible , and the head fades extremely slowly , in sticky , wet patches . glorious .  smooth medium plus mouthfeel , though it is a little thin compared to expectations for an imperial stout .
this beer pours a perfect look . just the right shade of golden with a nice thick head .  m : the body is thin and slightly watery with a low to moderate carbonation .

the smell is amazing , caramel , toffee and vanilla . tomme could easily sell this as a perfume to beer geeks . note ... do not fret if you can not get your hands on this beer , while i really liked it , i found it to be very similar to a standard as .  am impressed m- lightly carbonated , not much bubble coming through , although perhaps not as thick as i was expecting from the type and abv .

well , a bit of letdown . good coffee and bitter chocolate edges , with decent dark roasted malt . some misfires , but still likable . worth a try .  recommended by shady at the waterhuis in ghent , thanks . appearance was chestnut brown with a medium tan head and slight lacing . smell was of freshly cut hay and light spice . taste was hoppier than most browns , a good balance of bitter and sweet . very good choice , quite enjoyable and unique .
poured from the bottle to a highly carbonated orange-yellow with medium thick white head that lingered long and left good lacing .  only complaint is that it has a little thin feel to it .
great aroma of whole coffee beans and chocolate . good stuff .  m-is sort of thin , much more than i would expect . d-is very nice .

i did n't have to put the glass to my nose to catch a whiff of lovely hops .  first thing i notice upon tasting is again the carbonation , there 's way to much fizz , seems to be overpowering some of the beer flavor . body is on the lighter side of medium .

on tap pizza port carlsbad , ca near black with ruby edges and a thin light brown head . perfect for the style .  while average enough , the mouthfeel ca n't save this sinking ship worth a damn , it 's doomed from it 's key structural deficiencies .
the smell is amazing mostly hops like a black ipa a little malt an some coffee . it 's good but not great .  moderate carbonation does help to give some body however .

smells terrific ! chocolate and cherry are most of the smell , like a brach 's chocolate covered cherry . just a touch of a root-beer like aroma rounds it out . a little thin but still enjoyable .  a lovely seasonal offering from our pals in jp . readily available on draught , which is a grand thing . a clear dark amber pour with a fluffy but not bubbly off-white/beige-yellow head with nice lace retention throughout . the aroma offers a spiced caramel malt as does the taste , although with a fine & not overwhelmingly nice hop floral bitterness . very drinkable . very flavorful without gimicky sweet 'flavors . '
