lacing is incredible and the retention is stellar .  mouthfeel is slightly diluted and flat but the overall feel and enjoyable nature leads to a quite drinkable brew .

a - extremely good pour with a solid two fingers of head that kept a lacing all the way down the glass . color is a crystal clear burnt sienna and there were more bubbles on the pour then some champagne i have had !  mouthfeel was super dry , yet still drinkable enough .
appearance : a crystal-clear golden-straw body capped by over two fingers of bubbly white head that fades slowly and leaves good lacing .  mouthfeel was average .
a : very nice clear amber with a thick white head .  m- i 'd like a bit more body . carbonation is good .
very nice nose on this . 4.0 t : the taste is good , but it 's missing the thick , aggressive sweetness that defines the style .  carbonation a tad light .

quite nice , although the alcohol is surprisingly present after nearly three years .  on the palate the beer feels light and thing , and a subtle malt flavor yields to a building , albeit , not overpowering bitterness that is highly drinkable but nothing special .
s - smells great . nice mix of fruit , flowers , & malts .  mouthfeel- decent carbonation on the front of the palate . fairly light and slight watery mouthfeel . drinkability- very high .

a-pours completely flat , looks almost like soy sauce in my glass , a mix of dark brown/black , no head whatsoever , completely opaque in transparency s-probably the strongest part of the beer , the apple brandy is lush and prominent in this , so much so that i can smell it across the table when the bottle is opened , some brown sugar t-having a tough time describing this honestly , there are themes present , but none stick out obviously to me , some apple and caramel , a weird earthy dryness to it , i am reaching here ... just kind of a muddled mess to me really m-completely flat , a little heavy on the palate , a little lighter than cough syrup to me o-no idea how this rates out so highly , this beer was kind of a mess outside the nose , it makes me wonder how much i would enjoy it if the bottle was properly carbed  m=medium bodied , a bit watery in the aftertaste which brings it down a little bit .
smells amazingly smooth and tasty . t : very surprising . i love the taste on this .  the body is decent , but a bit thin and over carbonated .
very nice looking beer !  some carbonation .

the nose on this beer is great . rich chocolate malts , roasted malt , sweet milk chocolate , there is a hint of tootsie roll and powdered cocoa . very nice chocolate taste , but i dont think you would think this was beer in a blind taste test .  the cinnamon is left lingering afterwards and really helps to cut the sweetness . dr- pretty .sweet , not sure if i could do a whole pint . ov- find myself comparing this to belgian red and liking this more
smell : some wonderful character here . a tasty beverage that smells amazing !  unfortunately , the mouthfeel is pretty thin , although the carbonation is decent .
this is one nice ipa . hops make their presence known , but not overwhelmingly .  light and thin mouth feel ... medium carbonation .
pour a golden colour brew with a nice big head that persisted for a long time ( i had n't had a great head like this in a long time ) .  pretty light mouthfeel .

getting to the beer : poured a viscous , opaque , black color with an incredible light mocha color that seemed to grow and bloom into an entity entirely separate from the the beer .  m : really light bodied with a bit of carbonation , the only not awful thing about this beer .
s : fresh brewed coffee , maybe a hint of chocolate , maybe some orange juice notes ? very tasty smelling , almost `` natural flavor '' coffee smell though .  m : medium in body , pretty dry .

smells : incredible . very floral , with rose petals and pine along with pears , white grapes and hints of banana . i want to make it into a candle and take it home with me . a lager-like finish rounds out this sneak attack . i liked it better as an aromatic than a beer , however .  the beers appearance is average , lacks in color to be above average ( looked a little watery to be honest ) . the taste is great , smooth , hoppy , fruity all i expected and more . this is a very drinkable beer in fact i killed a 4 pack when trying it for the first time ... .great job dfh .

poured from the black bomber into a pilsner glass the beer was a rich golden color with copper hues throughout .  poured from bottle , this fruity concoction from the smith master wields an incredible fruit aroma of pure fresh raspberry . minimal to no head , dark red in the glass . this fine example really pulls off the definition of a fruit beer , with authentic fresh flavors of pure , tart raspberry . lively and fresh acidic profile with pure rasp-o-goodness with a slightly bitter finish . excellent , well done genuine offering .

fantastic aroma is spicy whith clove in the foreground and offering notes of sweet bready malt and belgian yeast . the yeast is really coming to the nose at it warms . medium bodied and the mouthfeel is smooth with an airy like quality as if it 's floating in your mouth . some sour fruit , green apples , pepper and caramel also come to mind . overall a great saison .  a little bit over-sizzling on the feel is a drawback , it detracts from the fact that it 's otherwise velvety smooth .
looks great with its chunky head and deep orange color .  mouthfeel is near average , a bit more body and flavor concentration would be welcome .
lots of smoke and wood in the nose . smells like bacon & smoked meats . i love the nose , and the flavor , but it 's not 100 % satisfying .  m - tons of carbonation , to a fault .

dark black hue , it was midnight in my glass while the sun shined outside . numerous tiny bubbles forms a light beige head , more than a finger in height , foamy and long lasting from the nitro-gimmick-widget .  light orange color ... awesome aroma ... just like fresh pumpkin pie out of the oven ... big cinnamon element ... the taste is more subtle than the nose ... nice pumkin flavor also strong cinnamon and some nutmeg ... mouthfeel is light and slightly watery.. decent pumpkin ... i 'd prefer to see it bigger in body with a little more assertive pumpkin taste..still pretty decent overall and a solid seasonal offering .
2007 bottle poured up into a weizen glass . beautiful iron color with bubbles racing to the surface .  a bit light in body , perhaps somewhat thin .

interesting complex of aromas emanates from the glass , beginning with a judicious balance of coffee and blackberries upfront leading the way for hints of smoke and homemade jam to express themselves . velvety liquid enters the mouth and releases flavours of roasted coffee , blackberries , and faint but very perceptible mustard seed . hats off to magic hat for such a creative beer .  mouthfeel is pretty average for this sort of beer .

a ) pours a 1/2 '' head . white , thick and slight billows . considerable lacing along the sides . crystal clear , with a light , copper-orange color .  mouthfeel : delicate to no carbonation but the beer feels pretty foamy and creamy , which is n't bad but does n't quite mes overall : i think that this beer is pretty good despite the weird mouthfeel .

huge 3 finger white head bubbles up on the pour into my sa pint glass .  taste - wheaty and yeasty , with typical yeast derived spiciness mouthfeel - light body , but not watery . a little more oomph in the body would have been nice . more carbonation would have been good .

a beauty of a nose ! raisins , cotton candy , sweet fruit , grapes , plums all found here . up front , this is big and bold , not to be messed with . intimidating . big , hearty and in yer face .  bland appearence and no lace . i do n't have a lot to say about this beer except maybe a glass of water would have been a better idea.very bland in every feature.that being said it 's not revolting but there are a thousand beers out there of this sort . update a few minutes later : i really resent this beer .

the smell is enticing . taste is mostly just some strawberry sweetness , a hint of tart , and a touch of malts .  extremely mild , even for an english style , however it had an interesting coffee finish , which i do n't think i 've ever found in a nut brown before . particularly curious , since the malts were not all that roasted . hmm .
pours an nice dark mahogany , with a nice single finger of head that sticks around for a while , leaving a small amount of lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and slightly watery .
nose is surprisingly nice , caramel and toffee with a few dallops of sugar . malts are nice , bold and varied .  m- mouthfeel is fairly thick for a macro and very fizzy .
this stuff is cheap in italy if you can find it ! beautiful color , like dark stained mahogany with ruby . not much head to speak of , but a bit of lacing .  poor carbonation , mostly foam .
this beer pours a classic porter look : dark brown bodied with a light brown head .  4 m : a little flat .

a - definitely the best thing about this beer is the way it looks . a pale golden color with a great head that stays throughout and leaves layers of sticky lacing up and down the glass .  this beer almost goes over the top with spices - but holds back just enough . cinnamon and nutmeg blast out of the malt - like they stuffed a mincemeat pie into the bottle . must be brewed by little elves at the north pole . one bottle at a sitting is all i care for of this beer , but this is a great change of pace - ho ho ho !
dark brown body with a nice dense cap of cocoa colored foam . nice lacing and retention .  m : very bubbly if there is one knock on this beer i would say it is overcarbonated .

poured from a 12 oz bottle into a tulip glass . a-utterly beautiful . warm garnet with filtered clarity . a puffy , creamy eggshell head that laces nicely . this is how i like my beer to look . s-rather subdued nose .  taste : a true witch 's brew of vegetables , raspberry punch , and a thin maltiness . finishes tart and watery . mild carbonation .
very exciting aroma . a very distinct and mellow chocolate nose .  slightly dry in the mouth .

this is one beautiful friggin beer . sure looks pretty though ...  even if you have tried other wheat beers this is the one is different . the pale ale influences defiantly show through with a good hop finish . i will drink this seasonal brew again soon and often as soon as they make more !

pours exceptionally well . there is about three fingers of clumpy light tan foam , along with a clear dark copper colored body .  the mouthfeel is maybe a tad thin for my liking , but drinkability is good .
very good presentation , dark with about a half inch of fluffy foam .  mouthfeel - a smooth mouthfeel , a bit on the watery side but crisp .

big aroma -toasted , dark chocolate , strong , bitter coffee . unfortunately , the aroma and appearance did not live up to the taste of this beer .  12 oz twist off states it is in the `` burton style '' poured copper amber ( darker than i expected ) with a small head smells of homebrew with stuck fermentation , residual maltiness and mineral caramel flavors and that same malty residual , no hop finish , no bittering a bad experience and reading the reviews , i was not alone wife poured it out . i struggled through it
the smell of this beer is terrific . as soon as i popped open the bottle i could smell the floral hops .  m : heavy for a pale ale , low carb . substantial slick on the finish .
really great looking beer !  m- the body is a little on the light side .

the smell is nice and aggressive .  you can definitely taste the hops . spicy as expected from typical winter beers . m- as i said , it 's a bit bitter . it 's not a beer you can drink really fast . good beer to have a good steak with .

drank from the can while out on a little camping trip and when i opened the bottle i was loving the heavy coffee aroma coming through but i did see something i did n't like ... the beer seemed a little watery ( not the tast but the thickness of the liquid ) and i prefer my stouts to be a little thicker but the actual taste put that to rest ... this reminded me a lot of a toned down breakfast stout with the heavy coffee aroma and flavor taking and up front and center part in this beer and the sweetness and smoothness was outstanding ... would have liked to gotten this when i had appropriate glassware available for use but it seems to be readilly available near me so we will meet again ... .  m : this one has a little more carbonation than i like .
pours a clear gold color with a very impressive head of frothy lemon merengue pie like cap -- 2 finger thickness .  mouthfeel : not a lot of body , a little thin .
tall creamy dark tan head . d - maybe one ... but would rather have a slice of pumpkin pie and a good stout served separately .  m - mouthfeel is where this beer is lacking for me .

poured from an 11.6 oz bottle into a snifter , the dolle teve is a hazy pale yellow , with lots of bubbles and a huge , frothy white head , which keeps rising out of the glass as it settles , holding firm and tight , leaving foamy lace .  m - reasonably full mouthfeel . average carb level for the style .

341 ml brown bottle poured into a perfect pint glass around 45f a : deep copper with a solid white head that dropped a touch too quickly , though it was still leaving lacing from its small ring later in the session .  the color was yeallow hazy 'wheatbeer ' ; and the mouthfeel was light .

appearance : black with rich brown marbling in the light . it 's khaki head has ruby tones to it .  it lacks a smoothness because there is too many bubbles on the tongue it takes away some of the nuances away from the flavor . this is a tasty beer and the drinkability could be better if it was n't so overly carbonated .

from notes : pours a dark copper amber color with dark golden orange hues when held to a light source and a to finger frothy yellowish beige head . excellent retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with chunks of lacing .  m - light in body . carbonation is a big strong for my taste .

like afternoon sunshine in a glass , the nitro-tap produced an incredibly creamy three finger lingering head with great retention and lacing .  it is very carbonated with lots of bubbles coming up throughout . my other major complaint is that the beer itself is a light in feel , i want it a little more robust . overall , this is very good and reminds me a lot of insanely bad elf . a highly drinkable winter ale that packs a great alcohol punch . needs a little tweaking on the feel and to give the aroma some oompf but so close .
a- pours a massive billowy white head with nice lacing above a hazy yeasty body .  the body is pretty thin but the feel still comes across as creamy to some extent .

presented with an incredibly luscious foamy mocha-colored head and generous belgian lacing ( unfortunately , this was the best part ) throughout the tasting .  the mouthfeel is dominated with alcoholic burn , beginning and a the finish .

poured in my struise glass this beer is perfect . perfection in a glass !  a - deep copper . light tan head with some of the best lacing i 've seen . s - grassy hops and caramel malts . t - very strong but nicely balanced . strong hop bite with rich coffee like roasted malts . d - very drinkable , but it more of a sippin beer at 10.5 abv .
appearance : pours a nice clear red with a great deal of head that fades somewhat quickly . does leave behind some nice lacing .  mouth seems a hair thin and the carbonation is a bit prickly .
super dark body with a tan foaming head and impeccable never ending retention and webbing .  m - even . not thin , not chewy , not thick ... just average .

the beer poured out a bright copper orange color with a lively white head that laced the glass nicely .  very nice offering and a cut above the perennial lineup from summit . aroma , floral hops and some malt taste is dominated by bitter hops , a nice floral character also , not the ubiquitous grapefruit bomb that most american ipas are . very highly drinkable , overall a welcome release from a local favorite , summit 's special releases are worth giving a try .

love the color ... , nice dark cherry red color with a thin tan head , little carbonation . the only negative ( and this is coming from my wife , who usually does not sample beer ) pertained to the orgy art work on the beer case .  m : a lot of carbonation , maybe too much but otherwise full bodied with some creaminess .
a - dark black and brown lacing with a tan head .  m - good coating but only a mild tingle on the tongue .

decent half inch of head . large bubbles , great brown color to the head .  scent is of fresh earthy and grassy hops , not overly powerful but they dominate ... hints of caramel and yeast in the back end . the hops are not overly bitter or flavorful , but the freshness works . the body is medium , although the oily hops contribute more than the malt ... slightly watery . a nice tasting beer which isnt too complex and just lets the fresh hops star .

pours with a healty tan head over a clear , ruby-to-garnet colored body with some carbonation flowing up . really nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and dry for my taste , but it is also very drinkable .

poured into pint glass and this beer looked beautiful . dark , solid brown color , dense almond color head that stuck around for awhile and left very nice lacing .  medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , the flavors throw back to the aroma , with a pronounced hoppiness that is balanced well by a base of biscuity grain .
a- black color brown head with some lacing overall a nice looking beer .  m : a little thin with moderate , prickly carbonation .

poured from the bottle into a tradional beer mug at the moan and dove a- black as night with an off white head , tons of lacing on the glass s- some roasted malts , with hints of black coffee t- roasted character upfront some bitterness in the finish m- balanced , but as this is a stout it could have used a bit more body d- a solid stout from a great brewery .  it was a little fizzy , but that was a minor problem .

excellent aroma , a very clean fresh cake-y malt , a bit like stepping into a bakehouse .  m : sometimes bottles from portsmouth seem to be a little under carbonated . aggressive , peppery carbonation would have been perfect here . some extra carbonation would have put this over the top .

a - black with an enormous head that takes an eternity t fade and leaves thick webs of lacing everywhere on the glass . a mountain of head rests in the middle over still half an inch of head . very pretty .  m : a bit watery , though fairly bubbly and lively .
head stays in for the long haul , and looks beautiful all the way .  finishes a bit dry . too light bodied for the style though .

second , this is the ultimate banana beer . ive never in my life encountered a beer so thoroughly driven by banana esters . they should call it banana weizen . the nose and the taste are both impossibly flush with banana essence . it actually smells more like bananas than a banana does .  m - thin and crisp , but not watery .

the smell is very spicy . it is extrememly spicy , and probably will not satisfy the trained palate looking for a more complex , bigger winter warmer .  nice amberish honey color fruity smell great blend of hops , very citrusy and fruity , almost floral type flavoring ( hence the name ) , very crisp taste average mouthfeel , smooth , not to thick , not to light this is by far one of my favorite ipa 's .

rogue 's shakespeare stout pours a hot-asphalt black with a leathery , milk-chocolate head . i peer through the proclaimed `` ebony '' only to see the blackest night . impressed already .  mouthfeel : a little sharp on the tongue , but goes down smoothely .

s : heavy on the malt , with vanilla , creme brulee , and dulce de leche in the nose , t : sweet , with huge caramel , raisin , and fig notes . this is fairly sweet , but is n't cloying . d : a great find .  m : the kinda thin and the lack of carbonation will drop the score for me to average .

poured this into a guinness extra stout pint glass , and perfectly it does so . mounds of dark tan colored head , and an opaque black colored body that allows some ruby red highlights on the edge of the glass .  very low level of carbonation .

smell : aromatic black treacle with dark fruit similar to prunes and raisins some bread qualities as well . black treacle again along with the same bread and dark fruit qualities that were in the nose . i ca n't really make out much in hops except for a slight hoppy type dryness toward the end .  whenever this touched my mouth i got a sensation of flatness . this limited my enjoyment but it was actuallly well carbonated .

the beer 's very cloudy for an ipa , but this one 's unpasteurized . nose : the aroma is so strong it kept wafting towards me as i regarded the appearance . lots of fresh dough , heavy in the yeast , and caramel . seems to be very well balanced . mouth : sour and hoppy , all around grapefruit . after swallowing it 's like sending some hops olympic boxing team down my throat , pummeling my rear taste buds with its bitter finish .  body is on the heavy side of medium and drinkability is good .

opened with a strong pop- from which i suspected overcarbonation- but the carbonation level is perfect . pours golden yellow with a medium-thick head that slowly dissipates but never disappears .  taste : begins watery and subdued , velvety but light ; hops are light yet floral , finishing crisp yet tangy . overall : very enjoyable overall , i was n't sure what to expect as a result of the aging process , but my expectations were not in line with my actual experience , but that is not a bad thing , lighter character was indicative of age , but i was expecting more complexity from the scent than what i got in the taste .
impressive three-finger head that lasts a long time and recedes in a rocky fashion .  mouthfeel is much thicker than you might expect .

ahhh , the nose , the delight of big pine oils - spruce - ( pine of a midnote vs. the divine loft of silver pine ) ; this married with sweet of both malts and pine resin , a delicate but detectable citrus mix , softened with a mere touch of butter . this dreadnaught poured a hazed ( cleared midway through ) golden orange with a hard pour settling to a 2 finger creamy topping . they remain there to enjoy for a near endless time , sometimes yielding to a bitterness .  mouthfeel : this is a little thin somehow .

aroma : fresh fresh hops ! wet dripping goodness ! wow that smells great ! appearance : hazy gold , thin to no head but a swirl will produce a nice white cap that rises and falls leaving lace in spots . flavor : matches the aroma perfectly ! ) hops heavy on the aroma and taste side , not so much on the bittering , coriander and clean . wow , ive drunk the kool-aid , ive seen the light .  the mouthfeel like most rogue ales to me seemed a little on the thin side .

smell is sweet and malty , but there is more chocolate than oatmeal in the aroma . unfortunately the taste did n't deliver on everything that the smell promised .  it had a light feel on the palate with medium carbonation . my only gripe is that the mouthfeel was kind of thin based on my preference for the style , but that is just me being picky .
it has great retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel was a bit thinner than i would have hoped .

a : pours black with two fingers of dark tan head that fades into a thin cap with a solid sheet of lacing .  feel is good but could be better , a little thin for my tastes , but i like thicker beers .

a nice initial two finger light tan head forms that recedes fairly slowly leaving an amazing cap and collar with quite a bit of lacing . the beer looks great in the glass and tastes even better .  had this in a small plastic sample glass at the brewery beer garden in boston . a-off white head , dark walnut body s-candy , citrus , ice cream t-ice cream and floral hops m-medium d-really full of flavor . i would drink it again though if given limited choices .

a- dark dark black , with only the slightest of brown highlights . head is thick and tan at first , and given the abv/style , i 'm impressed by how much stays around .  mouthfeel : pretty light bodied brew , almost watery .

a- pours a booming three-fingered white head atop a dark amber beer into a tulip . effervescence aplenty ! great head retention and thick lacing .  warming opens the palate up a lot , the malt becomes more prominent and the hops keep coming through , seemingly more balanced than when at a cooler temp . this light ruby barleywine is definatly mild , with a medium-ish body lacking the explosive punch of others in the style . flavors seem to hit targets on the palate rather than coat it with complex flavors .
nose was great , but the rest was just pretty good .  mouf & gt ; easy drinkability & gt ; good .
dark body , dark khaki head ... looks awesome .  bit foamy and dry in the mouth , feels maybe both over-attenuated and over-carbonated .

malts are n't quite enough to balance an otherwise fantastic bouquet , though . with balance , this aroma is exceptional . the flavor in this hop monster is pinw qith a big resinous aspect though it goes a tad `` rindy , '' the rind flavor adding a hint of saltiness before an astingently bitter floral finish .  m - too carbonated , but then again , thats the way most japanese like their beer .
pours black with a massive foamy tan head with a very nice retention time .  medium full feel , but the carbonation came across way too harshly initially .
the overall appearance of the rest of it was fantastic though ; a beautiful golden orange , sort of amber color .  mouthfeel : medium-thick with a little harsh bitterness at the end .

this beer 's best attribute is its appearance , dark brown-orange color with a thick creamy fine-celled foam ( guinness-style head ) .  tingly mouthfeel brought in the flavor of more hoppy fruit-sweet malt mix .
light tan head that boasts tons of character . also great frothy lacing .  mouthfeel : full to medium body .
( 6.8 % ) poured into a tulip glass . a - faintly hazy medium amber pour with a towering rich frothy head , superb retention , nice surface memory and lacing .  highly carbonated feel to it .

pours perfectly . a thick , muddy black/brown with .5in of tan head that has awesome retention .  the mouthfeel seems to be a tiny bit weak to me , but this is obviously a forgivable trait for such a fine beer . it 's a little bit creamy and grainy , but the body lacks oomph .
very powerful hops aroma that i could smell from almost two feet away .  d/m : light carbonation but its a really big beer .

s : tons of citrus , tropical fruits , pineapple , honey , and slight burnt honey malt . i could smell it for days.. t : tropical fruits , citrus ( pink grapefruit , ripe tangerine and tons of lemon ) , pale malts , and a slight alcohol flourish in the finish . i was really disappointed by the rating.. either the best or second best rated beer on here . i was very disappointed by its lack of mf.. overall : the most overrated ipa of all time .  mouthfeel is a bit over carbonated .
it smells fantastic . so many different things going on .  if any faults to be found i would pick on the body which seemed too light . its easy drinking .

pours the deepest black i 've ever seen- not a tinge of amber to be seen around the edges of this glass at all . head lingers , minimal lacing .  tasted the hint of caramel-like characteristics which probably contributed to the sweet smells ... enjoyed the strong hops of this brew ... bittersweet comes to mind while tasting this beer ... overall , very enjoyable blend of hops and barley and was informed the aging of this beer contributed to its tasteful experience ... m - not sure what exactly is was which did not sit extremely well here , possibly a little coarse ... d - i would def .

gorgeous beer . sailor 's delight sunset red , with a persistent head that 's getting in the way of my immediately enjoying this beer . carbonation slow-rolls to the top like a well-fished spinnerbait .  med-full bodied and prickly carb . blvd pale ale used to be so much better before they started brewing for dollars .
s - strong floral aromas , hops are very prevalent but does not imply bitterness t - initial flavors are very strong and bitter hops .  the mouthfeel is a little light , but not horribly so .
poured a deep mahogany .  ca n't descrbe the mouth feel because of all the spices ! ! !

smell is exceptional , the hops are there but there is something else too ! whatever it is , it smells glorious !  smells of brown sugar , mollasses , alcohol , and smoke tastes of sweet tobacco , smoke , pork and whiskey medium light body , light carbonation i would very much recommend having a taste

enormous white frothy head .  nice balance between the light chewy butterscotch flavor with a mild yet intresting hop finish ( the finish got better in the terms of complexity as a drank more , up front it was a tid un intresting ) .. mouthfeel : avg . nothing wrong with it i suppose , maybe a tad oily .

appearance - a robust pour into the sam adams curvy glass yields a nice two finger manila head atop a clear , dark amber beer . crests and lattices of lace form as the head drops back to a thick cover .  m - this part is a bit underperforming , but only relative to the rest of its strengths ; it just does n't have the substantive feel that i want , but it has proper carbonation and relative weight .

smell is aromatic hops , fresh cut grass , perfume , unripe banana , clove , bubblegum , pear and apricot , light phenols , baking sugar , ethanol , and powdery , doughy aromas . so complex it 's breathtaking ! taste is sweet wheat malt , strong spiciness , more banana and clove , warming alcoholic edge , mildly bitter and earthy hop finish . good god , this is some crazy shit ! an enthralling , satisfying , and nuanced beer . just try it .  m : light body , medium carbonation , starts crisp but thickens and becomes creamier toward the finish .

pours a beautiful ruby-amber with nice clarity and a nitro-induced finger-thick head of billowing , creamy , cake batter-like foam that just wo n't quit .  mouthfeel : light for the style , high carbonation , sweet , moderately smooth , with a really sweet aftertaste drinkability : this is refreshingly different for a dopplebock .

bright , clean fruity esters : lime , pear , green apple , apricot , and honeydew . bright citrus and tropical fruit : melon , apricot , lime ; swarmed by a slick and oily hop character . the hop profile is best described as juicy , with no astringency or mustiness . slick , warming alcohol is certainly evident , but not as overpowering as expected .  mouth feel seems a bit off .

the aroma is utterly fantastic ... and assertive as hell , considering i got a full whiff of it as it was held six inches from my nose . excellent aroma , the flavors are quite nice too , but the mouthfeel is strange .  m - somewhat thin , as one might expect .
clear light orange in color with a head bubbly in texture , gigantic in size , and sticky in its falling .  medium body is a bit light in the finish .
wonderful aroma perfectly hints at the flavors to come .  mouthfeel is on the lighter side and sticky on the finish .
it has an amazing feminine smell to it that i have never smelt in a beer ... a little weird at first , but it really makes you want to drink it .  m - feels like a normal ris .

very nice head retention and lacing . great looking beer overall .  good drinking for a spiced brew , 100 times better than buffalo bills pumpkin pee . i think this beer is better now that brooklyn brewery has it under its wing .

pours with a magnifico head , lacing is supreme ... smell of sweet maple syrup malt ... damn smooth . .  i think i might even enjoy just smelling this beer as opposed to drinking it , actually . built on a malty brown ale base , the spices fill this beer out , but all pumpkin ales are inherently unbalanced because of this , imo . you have a great variety of tastes in the same spectrum competing , and there 's just no way to let one win out , even slightly . the finish is great , but there 's just something overwhelming about the initial taste that bugs me . a beer to drink a few times every fall . it 's better than most of the other attempts at pumpkin ale . this is one case where dh 's overattention to detail definitely pays off .

poured cold and black as night to a founder 's brewing goblet with a super foamy and long lasting dark tan head that 's leaving lace to the rim after each sip .  tasting the beer , there is surprisingly not a strong wheat flavor but enough to really justify it as a wheat ale . only downside , and this is more of a personal note , wheat beers seem to me to have a bit of a grainier ( no pun intended ) fluid taste .

above average head retention & average lacing s : grainyness & some breadyness , pepper & caramel as this warms t : breadyness/biscuitty malt , caramel & slight peppery rye flavor up front .  hops are up front . anybody know what kind of hops these are ? thin but decent hint of malt . label claims 5.2 % abv . not excessively hopped but definitely one for the pale ale drinker .

the smell is the best part of this one . awesome . the flavor is tart , sweet and tangy , which is fine but made a bit too dominant by the abundant carbonation . for the style , it 's just too effervescent , dangerously close to being a beer soda than a beer ( i have the same problem with unibroue 's ephemere ) . despite the problems , it 's highly drinkable if this style of beer is a favorite , but it 's got nothing on the true belgians in this style .  i took my first sip and was shocked , this tasted totally like an ipa . seemed overly carbonated and gassy . 21st amendment is a great little pub and they have a fine addition to their solid line up with this one .
twin sisters pours a golden straw color with moderate head .  as noted , the mouthfeel is both on the thin and flat side .
pours a deep brown/black with a nice sized long lasting rocky tan head that leaves lacing on the surface and sides .  mouthfeel : average carbonation level . body is decent .

aroma : green hop , maybe a bit of fuggles , a good dose of vanilla , and a bit of clean yeast . some deep roasted malt and chocolate rounds out a very nice nose . appearance : deepest brown bordering black with thick ruby edges that show good clarity . overall impression : great nose fails to deliver on its promise .  hhaw : chemical sweetener , one-dimensional brownness , overweight body for the profile .

pours a light orange , quite clear , with a smooth white head . the retention is good , and a half-finger head remains till the end of the glass . the head clings to the side of the glass , leaving lacing from the top of the pour all the way to the bottom of the glass . impressive .  m - very carbonated , almost to a fault . thinner than it appears , and somewhat disappointing .
helluva head !  '' the body is a little thin , but for only $ 6 a bomber , this will be a common dessert beer at my house from now .

it then kicks up a tall creamy head that throws off a profuse malty fragrance . the nose has banana and allspice and the mouthfeel is full and sensual . the taste trails the aroma somewhat , never fully realizing that which the aroma suggests .  m- a bit thin , slight astringency , slight carbonation bite , nice warming in the finish .
great retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little watery and thin .

dark as night and not see through at all . coco color head that dissipates quickly . leaves tiny bubbles on the glass that form a nice lacing .  poured from a 12oz bottle ( shared with coastiefish ) into a tulip glass a= rich mahogany color with very thin off-white head s= sweet , tiny bit fruity ( fig ) , a little biscuity , alcoholic t= round fig/raisin at the front of the mouth , quickly tapers off to thin , alcoholic sweet malts m= complex ( see 'round ' and 'thin ' comment above ) , very tightly carbonated and dry d= very drinkable as it well balanced and not too `` extreme '' .

dark ruby with a brownish white head that lasts well & leaves a little lacing .  it 's a smaller brewer , but sometimes , big things come in small packages . we enjoyed a growler of this bad boy and it delivered smiles all around . had a good smokey/malty taste mixed with an ever so humble bite of the hops . if i were going to brew an amber , this is what i would go for , espcially for how refreshing it was . try it if you stop by the brewery .

pours a clear golden amber with a big frothy white head hat sticks to the sides and leaves a soapy cap . aroma is great with lots of juicy citrus , oranges and pineapples come to mind . the aroma promised great things but the flavor was just too light and watery .  this continues into a palate that i hoped carried a little more density . while a very nice beer i came out with the feeling that some barrel aging would smooth and fill out the midpalate .

new label , dictator series , batch 13 , march 2011 pours a majestic crystal clear deep orange/red with a thick fluffy white sudsy head . gorgeous richness and clarity on the appearance .  a nice beer that is easy to drink , but a little thicker body would be an improvement .
nice nose . t : sweet caramel like malt and honeycomb .  m - thin , carbonation is a bit high , mildly refreshing .

a : bright orange color , translucent , very appealing s : imagine shoving some hops up your nose , very floral , spicy smell t : initially very citrusy and spicy .  it has too much carbonation for the style ( a bit over medium ) and has a little watery mouthfeel .
beautiful and would be perfect with more head .  mouth is heavy and bitter with a cloying finish .

poured a beautiful copper reddish-brown . the fluffy head left copious amounts of lacing .  m- im used to some more carbonation from my belgians , thats the only serious complaint i have about this brew .
beer looks awesome . a nice lacing formed as the beer went on .  i think i would have liked this beer even more if it was a bit lighter in mouthfeel .

big thick dark brown head that coats the glass with every pull . you could use this as sun protection as light does not penetrate without a ton of effort .  m - the carbonation is starting to weigh on me as i go through the beer .

ok so i love the color of this beer . its black , thats it just solid black . the head is similar to the crema of a shot of cappicino , very thick and caremel colored .  mouthfeel is on par for the style .

very nice . flavour was , as you might expect , a bit woody , with a nice velvety sweet maltiness and a nice licorice hint .  mf - kind of thin - but i think it 's normal for the style . this one has a stronger flavor but a watery mouthfeel like the other two altbiers i 've tried .

appearance- an almost overwhelming head that just barely exploded oput of the glass upon the first pour . great , and thick head retention . great deep amber , almost rust related color . awesome bubbling combined with what i would the slide fade lacing .  mouthfeel : bitter drinkability : goes down easy , great aftertaste . this is by far the best american macro lager that i have ever had !

had this on tap at the depot a : dark black with a thick beige head , the head recedes slowly and leaves lots of lacing s : piney and citrus aromas with undertones of malts .  not much carbonation , which is strange for anything with hefeweizen yeast .

the smell during the pour in really enticing . wet sweet with piney floral hops and mango . some kind of frutiy ester mixes with the hop sting to make a really delicous aroma . noticable mostly , but poking it 's head up for a view on occassion . fruity esters are difficult to find .  not bad at all ... mouthfeel is ok . it feels nice and full on the front , but the finish leaves the beer with a lighter feel to it .

it has strong roasted coffee aroma that 's maybe a touch sweet . it smells delicious . it 's medium bodied with a quick , dry finish that gets slightly gritty afterwards .  lighter mouth feel and for me extremely drinkable .

appearance : blackish-brown with a tan head . the head left some lacing up top and then seemed to wholly stick to the side of the glass the rest of the way down .  m : definately this beer 's shortcoming . little to thin for the bold taste .

the nose is quite pleasant and not too bold , but still enough hops .  it 's a little black , a little viscous , a little chocolatey sweet , a little smokey , a little creamy , a little meaty , and a little carbonated .
bottle poured into a tulip glass . appearance-yellow-golden in color with truly brilliant clarity .  the mouthfeel is lighter-medium bodied with a very easy carbonation in the mouth .

s - quite a `` stinky '' ipa . o - overall it had great hop smell , the maltiness of the beer threw me for a loop , again it reminds me of some scotch ales .  rogue ales are easily becoming more present in my inventory.this one is no exception.i expected more malt out of this , but i should of known that the rogue in all of us loves the hops.slightly weak aroma until warmer , a lighter-bodied feel for an ale , but the finish and drinkability makes it great sports beer.looks great in a big , fat mug too.i will consume many .

aroma : a nice belgian yeast nose with the orange and coriander coming through nicely . smells just right appearance : hazy yellow glass with a fluffy white head that laced like grandma .  m : immediately strikes me as having a buttery smoothness . slightly thin in the mouth but satisfying . could use a bit more carbonation .

a- poured a hazy orange/amber color with a great head that lasted for awhile s-pretty amazing , very inviting aroma . citrus but not grapefruit bitter fruit more like an orange-tangerine type smells , not much on the belgian yeast aromas t-a nice citrusy hops up front but a nice malty sweetness at the end ; i did n't notice much on the belgian side of things , i was hoping for a drier finish , but this ended up being a bit sweeter than i expected m-not too bad ; nice carbonation d-at 8.3 % its approaching most double ipa styles and usually one is enough for the day , but it was well balanced and two could easily get finished .  medium light body , a bit thin for an h-w : more like a witbier .

on smelling the beer it seemed if i was smelling a bouquet of wildflowers , with just a small note of bourbon . most definitely an american style barleywine . i had two of these last night and was feeling right , but it took me an hour and a half to drink them , so this is a sipper , but a delicious one .  as for its mouthfeel , it was far thinner than i 'd expected , which might make it more suitable for session drinking than an average stout .

no funk , some hay . rich and spicy . the nose gave much promise not delivered in the flavor .  the body is somewhat awkwardly light for the heavy roast and dried fruit notes , but i 'm of two minds about this because it also improves the drinkability .

a : pours a syrup black with the slightest of head . this is just massive with intense smells . the first thing you notice is intense oak and vanilla that warp around in your nose . whiskey comes next followed by chocolate , molasses and some brown sugar . tastes extremely , extremely complex with oak and vanilla coming to the forefront . whiskey then makes its way in and tackles your taste buds .  in the mouth it 's got some body , but i 've had better .

appearance is very impressive with an amber color and very nice head with great retention .  mouthfeel is crisp and refreshing . i like this beer , the hops are a little over the top , there is n't much balance there , it 's kinda thin , but good and refreshing .

appearance : pours a rich black with billowing , cascading rich tan head that leaves lots of lacing as it subsides slowly . like a big ol ' stout .  lots of carbonation feels a bit prickly on the tongue .

beer is reddish peach in color with very light carbonation .  poured from a bottled into a belgian style tulip glass . nice head formation torward the top of the glass . citrus and coriander on the nose . formed tiny ( champagne like ) bubbles that lasted until i was done with this 11.2 oz bottle ( not long ) . nice lace . smooth and well balanced . wonderful golden color . easy to drink . perfect summertime beer .

beautiful pour from 12 oz bottle . deep brown/black color w/two finger brown head .  m : thin to medium viscosity , slightly acidic on the palate into the middle but then becoming smooth , with low carbonation .

serving glass : poured from bottle into tulip . appearance : extremely dark ruby with massive , billowing tan head that leaves bubbles sticking to everything it touches .  felt of in the mouth , but was slightly bitter and acidic .
lots of mango and slightly woody . t- i wish it tasted like it smelled . definitley mango and a little bit of hops .  mouthfeel : not very thick . lots of carbonation .

pretty cloudy which takes away from it in my eyes s : wow , this is an amazing floral bouquet coming from this one . does finish dry and clean o : this is a good ipa , its reputation may be better than the beer itself but i liked it and would definitely try another .  full bodied , rich , sharp carbonation and pretty hot .

poured into my pint glass the beer is a dark brown almost black color with crimson edges . it just sits there staring at me . however after receding it leaves just a trace of slick lace .  light-medium bodied with very high carbonation with a prickly mouthfeel .

the aroma was amazing and intense . super strong coffee notes dominated and were followed by a robust , oaky , roastiness . barrel aging at its finest ! the taste was similar to the nose initially . smooth and creamy up front . a touch sweet with strong oatmeal and coffee notes . the finish was hugely acrid , roasty and bitter with an almost hot alcohol ( bourbon-like ) presence . super dry and pithy . if i had to guess the abv of this brew , i would estimate it to be in the 9 % -11 % range . it was simply too bitter , acrid and hot for my liking .  m : the light body is thin and dry . carbonation is about right .
pours to the archetypal lagered clear golden stacked with a healthy and sticky pile of ivory .  mouthfeel is a bit disappointing .

dark mahogany swirled at the bottom of a deep amber hue on top with a thin tan frothy head with excellent retention . i do n't say it too often but this is a beautiful looking beer .  poured out a nice dark gold hazy beer , moderately carbonated . smells of banana / alcohol esters . a semi sweet beer alcohol is very well hidden.mouthfeel is so so . very drinkable for a tripel , this is the type of beer that could totally sneak up on you .

appearance : this ris looks amazing . a perfect layer of creamy light brown head sit on top of the opaque body .  very cloying . it just does n't seem like beer or ale or any other above average abv malt beverage ... more like a weak apertif .

a - pours a dark black with a thick and luscious head of mocha-colored foam that never fully dissipates , leaving behind sticky lacing as it recedes . beautiful !  s-hay , rust t-sour , citrus peel , fruit stone , m-medium , somewhat gritty d-nice but not the best in this category . would pair nicely with food . i would drink this beer again .
the pour is amazing ... pours a nice murky yellow , and the head ia simply amazing .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level . overall , good appearance , body , and blend .
for enjoyment , i 'll give it a c+ , y- extremely sweet smell . as expected of a sweet smelling beer it starts off malty .  spices , and a dry carbonated finish with a touch of grassy hops .

s- wow , pumpkin and spices are quite powerful in this brew and i love it ! cinnamon , nutmeg , allspice , slight hops and malts . pumpkin and spices take over all other smells . the spices are most definitely there and it is nice . m- the spices and carbonation has a nice bite and it goes down pretty smooth .  mouthfeel is thin and light .
pours jet black with a dark brown foam crown . exhibits moderate lacing when swirled .  mouthfeel - leaves a little to be desired .

obviously a nitro tap pour from the guiness like carbonation . extra creamy head that lingers forever . once the carbonation fades the beer is a dark gold with excellent clarity . but i ca n't truly see making this a choice vs a stellar beer line-up  m : thin viscosity with a low level of carbonation .

s-man this stuff smells amazing rich roasted coffee and esspresso notes with a rich malt note .  m : overly carbonated which made the flavour hard to find at times , swirl it a bit before beginning the drink , overall medium-bodied and relatively smooth .

i smell the hops first , then the yeast and finally some twinges of malt . yea ! perhaps some wheat was used in this one ? belgian yeast adds a very cool fruity aspect . its avery , what can you say ? !  mouth feel - creamy and slightly astringent overall - this is a good beer , but i prefer the un-oaked unearthly .

appearance : it poured a beautiful three finger head that is somewhere between off-white and khaki colored . it is very sudsy with craters forming at the top of the cap .  m - light to medium bodied . it tasted a little watery for me .

( s ) - a really nice array of fragrant pumpkin and rustic-like spices . ( t ) - not quite as nice as the smell , but still good . has a potent wood/bark note that carries through the entire sip/swallow .  mouthfeel : medium-light body . medium carbonation .
very nice . t : immediate apricots and dried dates .  i feel it is a tad thin as are all the lagunitas offerings i 've tried . very good , but with some more body could be fantastic .

tremendous . smoky aroma is seducing . amazing smell . intense smoky , spicy ( mexican food spicy ) flavor in perfect harmony with the burnt stout malt . strong , which could prevent repeats , but that aside it 's a very good beer .  it 's a light bodied and fairly highly carbonated beer that is meant to be served cold , but iunlike typical macro lagers can be enjoyed at 45 -50 degrees .

thick head lasts very nicely , with tons of sticky lacing .  what a name ! good thing this one lives up to that mouthful . a cloudy ( unfiltered ) straw gold extra special bitter with orange hues . developed a creamy , glass-crawling white head with good retention that left some nice lacing . strong , hoppy aroma with a medium-heavy body . malty bread , apricots , butterscotch , citrus notes . yum . a great example of their extreme series , bold and complex .

score : 8 of 12 appearance : beautiful ! mahogany brown , brilliant clarity , and velvety tan head which lasted beyond expectation . score : 16 of 20 mouthfeel : medium bodied , accurate carbonation ( just tickling the palate a bit ) , palatable creaminess , some warmth score : 4 of 5 overall impression : pleasantly surprised with this one , a very inviting brew ( `` more-ish '' ) , the aroma and appearance were backed up by a well-matched flavor profile .  mouthfeel : the body on this beer is fairly thin .

pours a clear , slightly orange amber , with a big , puffy white head . head settles , taking on a pocked , billowy appearance and leaves a clingy lace on the glass as you go .  m : a little thin , nothing remarkable here .

a- beautiful clear caramel , reddish brown . started with a 3/4 '' head that dissipated quickly . nice lacing on the rim of the bubble glass . low viscosity on the pour and moderately carbonated .  t - rich , nothing really overpowers here , a good balance , alcohol on the back end though , really comes through surprisingly for only a 7 % brew m - alcohol finish , can really feel the burn , strange o - pretty good pumpkin brew for sure , just need to mellow out the alcohol burn on the back end

welll for a am macro this baby showed head retention and lacing that could teach a good euro pils/lager a thing or two . i was impressed by how good this beer looked right out of the fridge .  body is a little light for a stout .

the creamy finger of foam stays around forever , creating an almost artificial-looking image of beauty . there 's just no use denying it : guinness is gorgeous .  sweet to start , wheat , a little honey , coriander , oranges , a little ginger ... .feel is nice to start but a very light and watery finish ... easy to drink .

it 's already too awesome that a beer with such an awesomely designed , screen-printed bottle has my name in it , but it 's actually good too . good level of carbonation feeding fantastic retention with lots of lumpy , sticky lacing .  feel was medium-bodied , smooth , and oily . in a word , crap ( spoken with a good scottish brogue accent ) .
appearance : a murky , bright , burnt orange with a small but frothy head . overall , a traet for the eyes smell : fresh and hoppy ... .but nothing to prevelant .  light carbonation .
s- smell is great . raisins , rum , booze . nice one dfh and thanks mammothbrew !  m- a little thin .

a : pours a light honey body with moderate carbonation and a dense , dense , rocky 2+ finger head .  after i got over the flatness characteristic to the style , the beer really started to grow on me . each sip i enjoyed the beer more . there really is n't much aftertaste at all as i finish through the beer . i really enjoyed this and might go out of my way to try this again .

a- nice appearance , soft , pale coloring with lurking sediment s- very nice hoppy smell with a hint of sweetness t- starts off great , just the right amount of hoppy bitterness mixed with sweet malts .  lots of hops in the taste , more than expected actually , along with roasted malts , coffee , and hints of bitter chocolate , and carmel . lingering bitterness on the palate . recomended .
pours a dark ruby-brown colour with huge foamy tan head .  consistency is a bit watery . light carbonation moves the flavors , but not much flavor lingering .
the beer poured a very nice translucent red into the glass with a small white head .  medium body yet very drinkable .

toaste ruby and caramel in color and a nice medium khaki head and foam . good lacing after each sip and great foam retention .  the mouth is nearly overcarbonated , which is kind of common , which lends it to feeling thin .

a very heady , spicy , warming , yet also very cool and calming , aroma profile . after the first few sips , the aftertaste was n't as acrid , but it was still pretty obtrusive .  mouthfeel : light-bodied -- a bit too light , i think . very minimal carbonation . i would like it a lot more if it did n't feel so light-bodied and if it were n't so lacking in carbonation , but it 's still one of the better american ipas i 've had .
very enticing and cool look .  mouthfeel loses points because the carbonation is too soda-like .

has a nice sweet smell .  this beer has a medium amber color , and creamy but light and airy head . domion has an even , almost wood-like flavor throughout . this beer was *not* to my liking , but you might enjoy it . - backdated tasting : i first reviewed this beer on 01jul03 , this post is based on notes from that review .

insane lacing & very good head retention s : slight iron & chocolate notes t : a little iron up front , then some roasted malts .  smells of thick syrupy caramel and citrusy hops , as well as a faint roasty characteristic . the roasted taste is a lot more prevalent than the smell would suggest , and plays well with the perfect level of hop bitterness . a little lighter-bodied than i feel it should be , but the drinkability is very good .

a - pours from a can into a glass with 2 fingers of quickly fading head . body is jet black with light ruby tones around the edges . perfectly opaque with no visible carbonation .  m : thin and average for the style .

nose is a kick in the nuts aroma of bourbon with the merest suggestion of vanilla . huge bourbon taste ; the most i 've ever experienced in a barrel-aged beer ( it 's like drinking boutbon ) . drinkability on this one was tough - way too much bourbon .  it dries out pretty quickly though , giving the impression of thinness . its a bit spicy , with modest carbonation .

a- pours a beautiful copper/orange with a huge , spritzy , white head . amount of head makes me think this scratch beer is overcarbonated . decent lacing .  what balance ? ! this is typically not the style i chase after , but being in switzerland , this was one of the few beers that i could find plenty of . the name sounded nice , so i risked trying a 1l as it would be cheaper in the long run , and i did n't expect this brew to be too offensive . it 's smell was n't rediculous , but the head was big and frothy , yet not long lasting . i would have to say this is a nicely balanced beer that i believe anyone could enjoy . if you are stranded in switzerland and see this brew , give it a try as it is quite tastey . after having another swiss beer , this one gives me hope . i look forward to trying more swiss lagers in the near future .
nice retention , great lace .  m - nice carbonation . decent body that 's on the thin side with a respectable structure . short finish .
the aroma is delicious . it has a very full aroma of pale hops and is quite refreshing .  mouthfeel - medium carbonation , light body .

chestnut-brown colour , and thanks to the widget inside the can settles to form a perfect looking white head that has excellent retention and looks very creamy.leaves some nice lacing on the glass .  m : light body with moderately prickly carbonation .

big belgian sugar aroma which captures a nice mix of clover honey and fresh , tart apple juice scent . a good sipper .  this is a great beer for a reasonable cheep price . its one of my personal favorites . it accentuate the taste and sell of the beer and makes it easier to drink b/c without a lime its not as good . i dont think you need to pour it out of the bottle b/c i think the bottle adds something , but either way its still a great beer for eeryday drinking and ecpecially by the pool or beach !

smell : rich chocolate and bourbon aromas swell upwards . coffee , blackberries , and vanilla are noted as well . this has very complex and mouthwatering aromas . coffee and vanilla are there for sure but i cant help but think that this is overly bitter and a bit unbalanced ( as if ads is known for balance .  mouthfeel is a tad too sticky but the drinkabilty is excellent .

smell is strong yeast aromas with a bunch of sweet fruit : apples , pears ... yum . quite nice , and the highlight of the beer for me .  i poured a 12 ounze bottle into a pint glass and immediatly noticed the beautiful color and head . the heaed left much lace which was nice and sticky . there was a stong hop aroma and a strong hop taste . neither was overpowering and both were artfully crafted and mixed . do n't drink and review .
a very robust and enjoyable nose . t - taste is very interesting and unique .  a lot of carbonation overall : i actually really enjoyed this beer .

8.5 % , on tap at amherst brewing company super sweet aroma with honeysuckle and candy apple notes . slightest bit of hop freshness adds a giant pepper-sneeze effect to the deep , sugary breaths . marshmallow and rose petals show up with warmth in the nose . first sip screams maibock , drier . it 's good , unique , green , and confused . oh , and absolutely nothing like steel rail .  m : light bodied with moderately-high carbonation .

poured from a bomber to a pint glass appearance : lots of carbonation and a thick off-white head with medium retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel was probably the worst aspect of the beer ( still not terrible though ) . a tad thin for what i want from an impy stout .
pretty nice . smell : rich chalky , wheaty aroma . it 's got a light flavor and abv but does n't skimp on character .  m : pretty moderate carbonation on a medium body .
the beer smells amazing , but the lack of carbonation .  mf : average . carbonation is pretty good .
poured a solid black color with a thick cream colored head that lasted the whole brew .  m : a bit harsh , and difficult to even sip , think champagne all the way .

huge floral/ citrus aroma . distinctive grapefruit & pine . the hop flavor was as big as the aroma , but was not egregious . i really like this beer , although it 's not a session beer by any stretch of the imagination . the pine/grapefruit combo totally comes through in the flavor and you can actually feel & taste the hop oils . i 've now had 3 of the port brewing offerings and they are all very good .  medium to light bodied .

really an amazingly intense aroma . taste : creamy upfront with a strong , but not enamel eating , hop spiciness ; resiny pine with grapefruit and floral flavors .  but , thin and slightly gritty in the mouth . not a bad stout , but lacks the fullness and breadth to be an imperial . an excellent stout overall , and many no doubt will overlook the thinness in deference to its amazing sweetness .
07 vintage on tap pours a pitch black with some aroma - mostly a smell of hops . has a nice head that laces the glass well .  could use a little more heft in mouthfeel .

pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the slightest bit of lighter color when held to a light source and a two and a half sldark mocha head . excellent retention , only slowly fading into a thin lasting cap .  mouthfeel is a bit soapy .
smells great . solid malt with a dark bread feel to it .  mouthfeel - light smoothness , carbonation is a tad low . average weight .

drank and reviewed on 7/10/11 a : black . opaque blackness that is devoid of light . with a thick tan head . beautiful .  medium carbonation , very light and crisp with a slight malt taste mixed with a nice strawberry flavor . it 's sweet , but not a bad overpowering sweetness and i think the brew is just the right mix of fruit to give it flavor and still be a good beer . this was very tasty and refreshing , went down easy ( almost too easy as i drank 2 in 15 minutes ) , and is the type of beer i could drink all night when it 's hot outside . overall a good summer beer !

smells really very lovely . huge citric hop whiff with lots of tangy lemon , orange , pineapple , sherbet and passionfruit . lovely , as i said .  m - watery soft in the feel which is surprising when i consider it looks like motor oil in the pour .

appearance : huge head , dark black , chocolate colored smell : molasses , dark coffee , and chocolate taste : molasses , coffee , chocolate , alcohol , and cream mouthfeel : smooth , creamy , a sweet start that lasts through the middle part with an alcoholic tasting finish , very heavy drinkability : this is not as sweet as other riss .  mouthfeel is smooth , but a touch watery and thin .

huge white head that get very rocky and has great retention and lacing .  the carbonation is a little weaker than most weissbiers ; the bubbles are small . the liquid is very smooth and a little thick . a textbook example of a hefeweissen , maybe with a slight reservation for the weak carbonation
appearance : really cool . neon yellow and very brilliant .  m/d - mouthfeel is a bit thin , but that 's not unusual for style .
three fingerd of light tan head form up slowly , thickly . a nice looking lacy weave around the glass as it recedes .  m - lacks a bit of carbonation for the style .

't is but minimally carbonated as well , me hearties ... super-robust sweet aromas of figgy pudding , allspice , pumpkin pie , and black cherry ... awesome ... .flavor is not a huge as the nose might think it is , and i get some dense and chewy fig right upfront . $ 4.49/11.2oz . very nice and well-rounded , and not nearly as sweet as one would expect from the nose . pretty good beer , but not elite .  the flavor is rather nice sweet roastiness medium feel in the mouth and a little to much carbonation for the style for me .

a : brilliant gold with 1-2 finger frothy off-white head with good retention and several lace rings s : bursting fresh floral and citrus hops aromas of lemon and orange with a bit of spiciness with a light caramel cookie malt sweetness t : the malting is superior with a caramel and toffee character followed by hops that hit you over the head with fresh orange and lemon citrus , pine , and floral flavors . d : an exceptional brew that misses the not so pleasant grassiness that some harvest ales are overpowered with and instead delivers fresh , sumptuous citrus and floral hops on a delicious substantial caramel and pale malt cookie-like sweetness . another big winner from founders .  the mouthfeel is on the light side , but like i said , this is consistent with it being a wonderful session beer .

s_fairly strong smelling . a nice mix of roasted malt and caramel .  the mouthfeel could be said to be a little thin , but it 's not a big issue , but the beer is definitely too carbonated for the style . lackluster mouthfeel aside , this beer drinks nowhere near 13 % .

looks great , deep ruby color and a massive head that leaves the glass looking almost destroyed .  mouthfeel seemed a little lighter than i imagined after the beer was in the glass . maybe it was a lack of carbonation or something but it seemed like nothing was there , a little watered down but still average .

poured a deep oil black with an enormous cream colored head that stayed around forever .  on the other hand , it does a great job of capturing the `` black india pale ale , '' what with the paper-thin mouthfeel and big bitterness .

smell is fresh hops , very floral and citrusy and even fills in with some piney notes for good measure . taste is a little bit of a let down after the strong smell . mouthfeel is a little oily .  m : considerable carbonation , medium body , and bitter ending .

a : poured a deep amber ( brown bottle ) color producing a cascade of effervescence along the insides of the glass reminiscent of sparkling fountain fireworks . this one filled the glass as a dark black but when held to the light it shone with ddep burgundy accents . the thick almost caramel colored head fizzled out slowly leaving huge amounts of residual lacing .  m. mouthfeel is actually slightly refreshing and similar to a seltzer .
pours a rich cedar color with a silky white head . excellent lacing and retention .  a couple sips of this and i 'm done . it drinks sticky and dry and leaves that godforsaken after taste behind .

pours very dark red . being this is my first anniversary beer from firestone walker i ca n't compare the 14 to the previous vintages but then again every year might be different but i 'm not sure .  bland overall , but what is there is n't particularly pleasant . dirty malt flavor with very light bitterness and not very good at all .

smell - cream , chocolate , sugars , vanilla , carmal , butterscotch , some malts . taste - sweet , vanilla and carmal overload , but not quite as bad as i was figuring .  mouthfeel was on the thin side , but the flavor was a riot of spices - nutmeg , cinnamon , pine and clove along with dried fruit - plum and raisin as well as chocolate !

12 oz bottle - `` vintage 06a '' a : pours dark brown with a big tan head that erupted late into the pour . lots of thick lacing and a head retention .  the body is moderately full , the carbonation is kind of hard to predict , but is a little low .

tobacco , cherry , spices , earthy . very ipa . overall- taste was a slight let down from such a beautiful appearance and aroma , but in no way is this a bad beer ... just not an excellent one .  mouthfeel : creamy with medium body , but the bottle i 'm drinking is a little flat .
the brew pours pitch black into my snifter . a rich frothy brown head foams up easily to an inch .  body is a little light .

a : into a pint glass , the 12 oz bottle poured a coppery-amber with a 1.5-finger bubbly khaki head . lots of carbonation as tiny bubbles rush to the surface to fortify the head , allowing it to linger nicely . some lacing as i drink it , and some sediment settles to the bottom of the glass .  smelled of raspberries of course , but with a nice yeasty undertone . taste was very sweet , like raspberry pop . we had this as a before-dinner drink , and everyone was pretty happy with it . my mother ca n't believe it 's actually beer . i recommend as a dessert beer or a beer to give people who do n't think they like beer .

the soapy head on top is billowy with low density , the body being brilliant and gold in color . beautiful !  it was a very refreshing beer , but due to the fairly high carbonation would be difficult for me to drink more than a few .

very nice looking 750 ml bottle poured into a snifter . appearance of the beer is a perfect for the style . opaque , thick pitch black with a retentive fluffy fine bubbled mocha colored head .  once it hits your mouth , the carbonation in it kind of picks at your cheeks . that 's why i marked it down a bit on mouthfeel .
the cascading dark beer is one of the coolest things i have ever seen .  feel is a little astringent from the depth of dark malts used .

the beer poured into the duvel glass ( do n't know why , but it seemed appropriate ) inky black with a froth dark brown head that was everlasting and made the glass scream for mercy as it coated it with lacing and foam .  mouthfeel-medium low body , medium low carbonation . if i had one complaint about this beer , it would be that the carbonation could be a little bit higher ( or more towards effervescent ) .

the smell reminded me of cooking marshmellows over an open camp fire . as i poured the brew into my pint glass the aroma proceeded to get stronger and i had to put down the bottle to stop and enjoy the moment . the taste was a little overpowering , but well rounded . a very nice rich , brown head surrounded the circumference of my glass each time i took a sip . as the beer warmed the chocalate and smoke characteristics appeared to grow stronger .  the mouthfeel is a little watery .

poured into a pint glass a - good looking deep red with a one finger frothy head and pretty good lacing s - caramel smell up front with a little alcohol pushing through . mixed fruits t - blunt and to the point , it is an interesting mix of sugary without being sweet and a dry finish d - do n't know if i would drink several but it was an interesting ale to say the least and it looks damn pretty in the glass  dryness & oakyness , vanilla , a touch of caramel in the finish mf : chewy , low carbonation , richer with each sip & warming as well drinks great for the style & abv , not as good as ba boris , but nice .

nose is beautiful with a lovely orange pith/peel character , almost pure orange essence , joined by nice floral hops , some orange blossom honey , and a very faint hint of that cheesy-pungency i get in highly hopped beers . very impressive nose followed by a solid delivery .  m : a nice fullness to this beer .
little malt character comes through , but the hops are excellent . strong bittersweet floral notes . mouthfeel : ideal lever of carbonation .  impressively , no heat . fantastic feel .

aroma-holy fucking hops this is insane . the hop aroma is impressive and unreal . fruity , orange , lemon , grass , hay , catty , strawberry , pineapple , herbal , and sticky/fresh marijuana . that said , i think it 's worth purchasing just to smell it-the aroma is actually insane .  m : medium-weight , ultra-creamy texture , the carbonation is plentiful and helps cleanse the palate for a perfect finish . exceptional .

aroma is mouthwatering with sour green apples , dusty basement , and a slight amount of skunk . mouthfeel is spritzy , lively , and very tart with a light body .  mouthfeel is extremely robust and creamy . amazingly sort and delicate , almost velvety ... in this aspect , the beer is perfect .

12 oz bottle poured 2/3 , swirled and finished into imperial pint a : huge fluffy off-white head that slowly dissipated a and left good lacing , golden honey color but very cloudy with the yeast , a beauty s : musty straw , clove , and yeasty breadiness , no hops to speak of ... to style but not mind blowing t : bubblegum and bannana with a small amount of clove and alcohol flavor at the end ... m : carbonation has a bit of a bite but swishing in the mouth makes that same carbonation turn creamy ... maybe the yeast is part of the scenario .  m- very smooth , silky texture makes this beer go down almost too easy o- overall this is a very good beer , a delicious flavor and smooth mouthfeel make this beer very drinkable without any of the heaviness that usually accompany a beer of this abv .

smell is real tart , but the taste is mildly tart with kind of a woody caramel malt to it . highly carbonated giving it a real spritzy mouthfeel .  hops , fruity esters and warm alcohol spice up the biscuit flavor m- very fine carbonation and a relatively light body make for a perfect mouthfeel .

very appealing aroma of sweet roasted malt , with huge notes of vanilla bean , bourbon whisky , and light chocolate . palate is more of the same - nice , sweet roasted malt accented by mild bittering hops , along with notes of vanilla , pepper , and a faint hint of clove . good , sturdy body lingers on the palate , helping to keep this tasty beer a slow-sipper .  mouthfeel is very crisp and very clean and bright .

the aroma is plums , bourbon , brown sugar , black treacle , coconut , coffee , and oak . the barrel presence is quite real and stronger than the bottles i have tasted from time to time , as this growler would be fresher out of the oak . quite a nice beer , somewhat boozy , though i like some nice bourbon flavors .  wonderfully thick and viscous in mouthfeel , slick with a subtly prickly carbonation teasing the tongue .

aroma : hoppy , spicy , dazzling array of fruits , grapes , cherries . sits wonderfully in the mouth . tangy , sour taste . although , to be fair , the `` winter beer '' style is increasingly a broad one .  mouthfeel is fantastic , and the beer looks amazing , but the taste and drinkability could be better .
smells just like fresh squeezed lemons , not the chemical flavors you get from some beers .  the mouth feel is spot on baby , full , grainy , just like fresh bread . nice .

s - hops ! ! a beer meant to be a testament to hops certainly lives up to its potential . all i can think is `` wow , hops '' t - a lip smacking of hops . m - nice light carbonation d - very drinkable , reminds me a lot of victory 's hop devil in that it 's all about the hops .  m : the mouthful is excellent . the beer is so smooth and rich .

as i smell the beer , my taste buds dance with a delictable sense of delight . an almost candy-like raisin plum tantalizes my nose creating a sensation that my senses are dancing with the universe and harmony has been accomplished in the universe . as i taste this beer , ihe sensation of my nostrils is disappointed , like when you take a chick home from the bar who looks good , but then her boobs are kind of flappity and you 're all like , well she 's really cool and has a good looking face , so i 'll go through with it anyways .  the mouthfeel is exceptional - thick enough with soft carbonation it just feels super rich .

the aroma is very nice . as i 'd imagine a czech hop garden to smell like .  medium to full bodied , with gentle , small bubbled carbonation . a very mild , smooth mouthfeel , yet robust and strong . extremely clean , particularly for an american brewed beer .

its a fairly strong scent . smells nice ! t-tastes pretty much how it smells .  mouth : this beer is very smooth yet unexpectedly strong flavored ( compared to the relatively weak smell ) . it embodies the mouth with earthy , raspberry flavors and a very compelling bitterness that hints of wood smoke upon swallowing . also , surprising for a cask ale , there is a touch of carbonation that tickles the bottom of the tongue if given a chance to rest there .

s- very `` oaty , '' smells like a great breakfast stout . very roasty with some subtle chocolate notes and some bitter coffee .  t/m : the taste is a citrus , grapefruit hop dominance , but the mouthfeel is as creamy as a glass of milk . a very interesting brew that works out very well .

the smell is off the charts , consisting of earth , green tobacco , huge hoppy bitterness and wet hop perfume . of course no ipa is going to taste as good as this beer smells , though there is good bitterness on the palate .  the mouthfeel is remarkably creamy and silky with a low carbonation .

the nose is super diverse and very appealing . especially factoring in the mint . works nice .  m : full-bodied with perfect , low-moderate carbonation ; sublime mouthfeel on this beer ; viscous ; smooth .
appearence : pours a heavy , dark almost-black brown with a giant , frothy beige head .  the carbonation is perfect giving this beer a creamy texture .

fantastic sipping . o- top of the line barley wine .  mouthfeel/drinkability- clearly the highlight of this beer 's attributes , the mouthfeel is perfection . responsive , slick , smooth , and very much alive , it showcases the finish better than any other beer in any category from recent memory .

smell is very belgian hops , fruity with notes of apples and grape . a subtle caramel is in there too . aroma reminds me of a dry wine , with lots of complexity and a hint of alcohol .  the taste and feel to me are perfect . not super thick , but still able to coat and linger . a well balanced flavor not too sweet or bitter , and carbonation that lasts to the bottom .

very nice . t - taste is dark fruits , roasted malts , chocolate , and a whole lot of alcohol .  the mouthfeel is excellent , and feels fuller than its weight suggests with a delightful slickness - great lakes always seem to nail the mouthfeel category .
amber-orange color with a thick lasting head and lots of lace .  mouthfeel is delightfully deep and rich , round and full , slurpaliciously smooth .

very good ! after the scent , i was so excited . a strange boozy mess . a very odd blend of flavors .  m- medium to full body with a nice creamy carbonation . d- a pretty good stout , alcohol was a little too hot but the feel of the beer was really nice .
smells very floral and lots of yeast .  m - this one feels zingy and electric on the tongue , and the hoppy aftertaste is really nice . wow ! d - this could become a summer staple in my beer fridge .

carved in the west-coast `` in love with grapefruit '' mold there are a bunch of strange hints bubbling under the hop attack nose . marshmellows . reminds me of lagunitas ipa . all of those hops somehow gave this beer the most marshmellow taste i 've ever experienced , which was not pleasant .  m : excellent mouthfeel , dry , substantial , crisp , perfect really . the mouthfeel pushes this beer into fantastic treat territory .

s : the nose is another story . the berries are there , but they are subtly concealed behind a veil of brett , oak , and a puckering lactic sourness . the usual scents of barnyard and leather are unmistakable . t : the brett has really taken over this beer .  finishes like a sherry or port , really dry , fruitty ( apples ) & boozy mf : rich , subtlely carbonated as it should be drinks pretty well considering the heft .
