smell is strongly hoppy with a strong grapefruit and mint aroma . pine scent and the scent of carrot you get when you mix c type hops with patent malt . unexpected aroma of orange .  mouthfeel is very full bodied and chewy which suits it well .

aroma is an immediate blast of fruity citrus hops - i would not be the least bit surprised if centennial hops where in here .  mouthfeel is rich and velvety , just superb . i have n't had a porter like this in a long time - rich and roasty , a pleasure to savor .

nose is awesome ! lots of dried figs , dates and prunes . the nose makes this super promising ... but that palate is trashed by what must be over-malted malt .  the mouthfeel is as full as can be , with a massively creamy feel up front that coats the back of the palate . thick , sweet , and gooey , this is the rare feel here that 's up there some of the best imperial stouts .

the smell is outta this world great ! i can smell so many different things and spices .  mouthfeel is on the thicker side and slightly creamy , the carbonation is relatively low giving it a very nice mouthfeel for the style .

the nose is a powerful mix of kahlua , dark roasted sweet malts , chicory coffee along with anise scented milk chocolate . such an interesting nose yet so out of balance when drinking is disappointing . i love dfh but they are really hit and miss for me - i much preferred tokio to this beer .  f : excellent carbonation and very creamy .

pours a dark whiskey colored amber into a frozen pint glass with a spectacular head . looks like a handful of shaving cream , or , like flying over the north pole in a helicopter .  very thick mouthfeel right where i want my ris .

has notes of vanilla , peat , whisky , and alcohol in the aroma . the flavor consists of heavily roasted malt , vanilla , smoke , tobacco , peat that lends an earthiness , and a little whisky and alcohol .  m : thick , creamy , considerable carbonation . 9.6 % abv plus the thick mouthfeel make this a beer to be consumed slowly .

excellent pale malt smell , with some strong , surprisingly bitter hops . the nice malt calms the angry hops . wow .  very smooth , full body starts out sweet , moves towards a dull bitter , then gets sweet again at the end overall impression and drinkability are very good .

the smell is the one great thing about this beer . has some strong raisin , fig and grape aroma along with so much fermentable material that the beer smells almost like cotton candy . still a bit grainy with the suggestion of hops . surprisingly , it does n't smell too boozy .  full bodied with minimal carbonation .

the color and pour were pleasing , with virtually no head .  otherwise the malt is good , and the hops come out and play a little under the light fruity taste , gives it a little complexity m - this is the real star here , super smooth and slightly tingly from the carbonation , very very nice d - this is definitely worth the money , would recommend as a stepping stone for someone who was n't sure about ipa .

aroma : super strong coffee aroma with a little vanilla . definitely worth trying but i think the aroma is much better than the taste .  the mouthfeel is full with tongue tingling and a hint of syrupy , but not in an unpleasant way .
a - dark orange with an amber hue . a big yellow tinted head rests on top . lots of sticky lacing .  nice rich lush mouthfeel .

excellent aroma for saison .  m. i do not notice the over-carbonation of other reviewers , all i can focus on is this silky mouthfeel , its amazing . it does coat the mouth a little bit , what i do it jsut drink more of the beer then , leading nicely into the next section ... d. oh yeah , getting this one again . with that silky mouthfeel , i would gladly accept many waves of this ruby-black ambrosia .
it was just so powerful and bright of the spice and herbs and of just an overall very nice smelling saison .  great luscious creamy mouthfeel .

very interesting . not super tart , only a little sour , but definitely is dominated by the funk . while the smell is quite interesting , the taste once again falls short for me of the excitement i crave .  mf= nice heavy feeling on the tongue . coats the tongue and throat with a thick layer of hop oil leaving a wonderful alcoholic warmth behind .
s- the smell is fantastic . coffee and dark fruits .  it 's quite smooth and creamy in the mouth with a full body and a very fine-bubbled , natural carbonation from bottle-conditioning .

an intense sweet complex aroma with raisins , brown sugar , mollasses , coffee , dark chocolate , trace of horseblanket . well balanced , with elements of espresso , chocolate , nuts ( almonds ) , citrus , sour cherries .  the mouthfeel is very fluffy , dry , and fruity . exceptional .

a wonderfully dark reddish/brown body sits like a shy kid in the corner , refraining from any attention underneath the massive and menacing head .  mouthfeel - 5.0 simply luxurious . the low , fine carbonation , coupled with a thick , heavy feel over the tongue makes this beer silky smooth . a - 4.0 , s - 4.0 , t - 4.5 , m - 5.0 , d - 4.0 .

extremely unique and intriguing . t- very light flavors of strawberries and peaches mingle in with a light caramel backing .  boddingtons pours super smooth and creamy with 2 fingers of head . no complexity , but oh so smooth . a great beer if you 're looking for a thirst quencher that 's incredibly smooth , consistent in flavor and easy to drink , then boddingtons is for you .

smell : huge pumpkin pie aroma with a nice toasted nuttiness and a touch of alcohol . smells better than any pumpkin ale i 've ever had .  creamy to the point of being syrupy , carbonation is perfect at a smooth moderate level .
appears almost black without light behind it . a massive , frothy , firm light tan head last forever , leaving big clumps of lacing . it really does n't get much better .  this is perfect imo .
the smell was of chocolate milk , and coffee .  really very nice m - this is what a stout like this should feel like . full bodied with moderate carbonation .
it pours a beautiful dark amber color , somewhat like a strongly brewed iced tea .  m - nice and creamy , whole lot of body .

winking lizard tour beer ohhh sweet coriander . spicy aroma with more zing than other wits ( cinnamon or allspice ? ) . hazy straw color with a haze of spotty head that once was a solid creamy strata the flavor is n't as exciting as the nose . in fact , i do n't have any reason to think what i smelled and what i tasted were the same beer .  the mouthfeel is undoubtedly the greatest aspect of this beer , with its full , creamy feel , which provides a luxurious decadence .

s- dark roasted coffee and cream , bakers chocolate , brown sugar . beautiful interplay of roast and sweet . malts are rich and deep . some dark fruits buried in there . lively active carb that lightens things up even more .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .
poured nice deep orange with a small white head , smelled and tasted less than great .  mouthfeel is quite thick and creamy . awesome .

s- very great smelling beer . smells of subtle apricot mixed with grapefruit and orange peel . very delicious smell . t- i found the apricots very -- almost too subtle -- but present .  the mouthfeel is really right on .

really impressive . t : tart cherries up front .  in the middle there is a dry briney sort of flavor with just the slightest hint of salt , which just tingles on the tongue because of the delightful carbonation . this beer is delitefully light bodied with a zesty sort of carbonation that just feels great on the pallate .

aromas are wonderful . very green , resiny , and dank . while this is a nice beer , i ca n't help but wonder what the hopsichord would taste like bottled .  there 's some hints of vinegar in the background that , surprisingly , seems to fit right in with everything ealse going on in this beer.. mouthfeel/drinkabilty ; the mouthfeel on this one maybe the fullest , and mostly velvety of any beer that i 've ever had . between the raspberries , chocolate , nuts and very full mouthfeel , this is like drinking a chocolate raspberry cake with a some walnuts or pecans sprinkled on top .

s : loads of citrus and pine with plenty of resin . lots of acidic grapefruit , lemon , orange , pineapple , and maybe some mango . more of the massive citrus with the strong acidic line . pine and oily resin 's are also prominent . d : abv is very manageable but it is a very bitter beer .  extreme smoothness and finishes malty sweet .

the aroma was nice a strong smell of spice , nutmeg , cinnamon , and cloves are present .  mouthfeel and drinkability are superb . could drink many of these , nice to see fff does something besides the in-your-face brews we always hear about .
hardly any clove , but incredibly enticing . i can hardly wait to taste it .  nice weight , carbonation , and roundness in the mouth .

aroma is yeasty in a light way , nice cinnamon and peach notes , almost like a spring day in the country . nice look and aroma , the beer calls for some wheaty tones and sweetness .  the mouthfeel is extraordinary , easily the thickest beer i have ever had , and it helps bring down the almost excessively intense roast character .
pours with a two-finger light brown head that stays and leaves a nice lace . black as coal , totally opaque .  mouthfeel is awesome . feels so full and thick , especially upon first sip .

notes : amazing aroma , but the beer was fairly bland .  mourhfeel is full and creamy , one of the best in an american stout i have had yet . carbonation is spot on and makes the beer smooth and thick , chewy and creamy ... .excellent .

s- most hops i have smelled at one time without my face in a bag of hops pellets .  perfect . o : while this was a tasty beer , i have such high regard for the brewery that anything that does n't blow me away really disappoints me .
smell : a lot of sweet an sour grape .  mouthfeel is excellent !

the bouquet is citrus-driven , primarily grapefruit , though it has an enticing mix of apple and cotton candy as well . overall , this has an excellent evolution from start to finish -- a crescendo of hop flavor and bitterness ; it could stand to be even be a little more hoppy and crisp . this has good length and balance throughout and is quite refreshing overall , though nothing that one would n't expect from this style . definitely worth a look .  wow , what a jazzy mouthfeel ! very crispy , peppery yeast , dry ... amazing effect in the feel , very earthy and exciting . sometimes the feel can be energy , and this one delivers it in spades .
2008 vintage pours bright and clear ruddy amber , off white head that leaves nice cap of lacing .  quite excellent . d - the lower bitterness and abv makes this extremely drinkable for a dipa .
on the nose , there are some huge aromatic grapefruit flavors , as well as pine , and some nice tropical fruits and citrus .  m : luxurious and creamy , the carbonation is spot on .
smell -- rich and vibrant cocoa aroma dominates the nose .  big and chewy with a very smooth , creamy finish .
great bursts of citrus aroma coming off of this one . the fresh citrus aroma does n't translate into the flavor profile much .  m- wonderfully creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .
smell is quite interesting . lemon , citrus , wet cardboard , touch of white grapes , floral notes of lillys and lavender .  thick and chewy mouthfeel . this is a pretty solid stout .

it smells good and i know the lakefront brewers work on a good smell ( learned that on a tour ) . great lawnmower beer .  m : thick , very full body , so tar-like it 's almost oily , light roasted acidity , modest carbonation .
a beautiful beer . coal black with a thin brown head .  mouth is very nice , very smooth with sour feeling and a very good level of carbonation .

bomber into nonic , the bottle i got was silk screened with white label and does not match the picture as of the time posted a : nearly black , small amount of light penetrates and shows brown coloration , tiny brown head , one finger max s : malted milk balls and the oak is very clear , vanilla and chocolate , yum !  and this was a grave mistake , as this beer is truly excellent . i noticed the mouthfeel before the flavor : the bottle conditioning mj pointed out on the label made this beer velvety smooth .
this beer starts out almost perfect , dark clear amber with a big off white head , and nice retention with very good lacing .  the mouthfeel is awesome . smooth , check .

the smell amazing ! lots of tropical fruits , mostly citrusy . i just loved the smell on this one . taste is good , but a slight dissapointment after the amazing smell . lots of hops in there with a really filling body . but after such a wonderful smell , i think i expected a bit more .  mouthfeel is excellent ... nice and full . the feel in the mouth is thick , and the flavors really linger in the mouth .
smell : bourbon , oak , chocolate , molasses . definitely on the sweet side but has a slight alcohol burn .  mouthfeel is excellent .
the aroma of this weizen is authentic and truly awesome . i hope this tastes better than their so-called dunkel weizen .  mouthfeel is really lift and crisp .
this beer has the most outstanding color ive seen in quite a while !  excellent body .

real foamy . sourness dominates the nose , and this one is coming off ... maybe with sour grapes ? i think thats the nose i 'm getting . its fantastic . t- the sourness is actually moderate , and unfortunately ... its not really balanced by any hoppiness . disappointing m- its actually pretty thin , and the carb seems really low ... which is weird base on how intense of a head i got from the pour .  really creamy on the mouthfeel with soft carbonation . solid stout , not quite one of the best but good .

beautiful . t : wow the cedar is really powerful in this one . and the smell is just outstanding . it joins the ranks of pumpking , where i could just smell it allll day..  nice and thick on the palate as well ; chewy , chocolate-like , malt sugars stick a bit to the palate , though this beer is in no way heavy . wow , i just checked out the alcohol on this ; this beer drinks way bigger than it is , not because of the alcohol ( which is quite hidden ) , but because of the concentrated malt flavors .

incredible nose - sweet , vanilla , bourbon , malty , brown sugar and a little booze . taste follows nose - this is an incredibly sweet and decadent beer i have to say .  thick mouth feel , chewy with almost zero carbonation .
aroma was very nice .  one of the smoothest barley wines i 've had , and especially for 12 % , it 's fantastic .

smell was great , i love the smell of hops . i could n't pick out a specfic smell other than `` hoppy '' but was very inviting . tasted beer and all i can say is grapefruit ! very drinkable and overall a very good beer .  full mouthfeel , with a medium heavy carbonation and some syrup afterfeel .
smells very hoppy - bitter and citrusy - with hints of malt .  mouthfeel is among the creamiest i 've ever had from a bottle , ever .
pours out beautifully . very dark with very little reddish brown highlights .  feel is relatively full bodied and incredibly smooth and drinkable . this is one damn fine beer .
s - a very balanced hop/malt aroma . o - nose is great but goes downhill from there with me .  the mouthfeel and carbonation are also excellent , as is common in most sam adams ales .

smells of dark roasted malts , brown sugars , oatmeal , bitter chocolate , and espresso . very nice nose ! tastes of bitter chocolates , the hops are surprisingly strong here .  mouthfeel is stunning . this is so light and smooth , and yet the finish is long and nearly endless .

appearance : poured a dark copper with a large , frothy head that retained very well and laced all the way down the glass . a gorgeous beer .  mouthfeel is one of the creamiest i 've come across in a long while . moderate in weight .
s warm booze , brazil nuts , caramel , and mocha .  the mouthfeel was spectacular ! pretty damn full bodied for a porter , and oh so lush and creamy .

) that aside , this pours black and heavy with a great and lasting head ( although this really seemed to depend on the glass i used ; i 'll assume the clean glasses are the default and kept the head intact ) .  body is thin with low carbonation . overall a unique stout , very flavorful and with great mouthfeel .

smell is great , lots of flowering hops , honey , citrusy . taste is awesome but seems impossibly backwards . drinkability is a little low in my opinion for this style due to the sweetness , but an overall good experience .  one of the thickest beer i have ever tasted , equal to the thickest , this is milkshake thick . quite an interesting beer but way to thick to drink in quantity .
this is a decent eipa , and certainly has an enticing nose , but the beer is a tad thin . the nose is very nice and estery floral hops , a touch of orange burst , a bit of pine .  great mouthfeel .

s - so damn good ! for me , this is the way a beer should smell . i loved it and wanted an air freshener out of it . o - great scented beer but just `` knot '' my flavor . i feel bad as this beer has received some decent scores and maybe it is a great beer for apa lovers .  m - thick , full bodied with medium to low carbonation which lends to a very smooth beer .

it might really have one of the best aromas i have ever had the pleasure of enjoying . t : strong spice leads into pumpkin flavor that is quickly consumed by pie crust . the aroma is fantastic , however , the spice lingers on the finish too long and reduces the balance of the beer , adding a bitterness .  t/mf : super clean and carbonation so tightly packed on the tongue it feels almost creamy , solid sweet grassy apple and dextrose like opening with a slight hop twang in the middle with a protracted finish with a good deal of hop oil running down the center of its tongue , the malt bitterness is there as well and the finish is quite long and just a bit nutty , everything is very nicely balanced and the mouthfeel is exceptional . d : pretty nice pils , well balanced and sexy mouthfeel , the only knock here is the rather bland appearance .

poured from a bottle into a tulip a- beautiful dark caramel color , one finger light , off-white head s- smells of caramel and bourbon t- caramel , bourbon , sour , bitter , a bit of barnyard funk , laundry soap ? really funny aftertaste , ca n't get it out of my mouth .  very thick and creamy mouthfeel with a perfect amount of carbonation .
smell : absolutely outstanding . boasting hints of everything from pine to fruit to tropical esters.. this beer had it all .  mouthfeel is quite clean with just a touch of metallic tang .

appearance : poured from the 750ml bottle into a tulip glass . the beer is a hazy peachy-orange color . head is pure white , grew to three fingers thick and stuck around for a while .  full-bodied for sure with light carbonation .
smell : rich caramel , citrus , and apple cider . good blend of sweets and spices .  bold , velvety texture -- magnificent .
very good , light and complex . taste is much like the smell , plus a sharp hop character and a perceptible alcohol finish .  the mouthfeel is excellent and imo is what really makes the beer .

a - about as good as it gets . ginormous thick tan head with tremendous lacing on top pitch black liquid that gently suspends a quaint amount of sediment .  the mouthfeel was so smooth and creamy , amazing texture that added so much to this beer .
poured from a 550cl bottle into a 500cl stein , copper color with large start head and good retention .  silky smooth all the way through .

pours black as night with a brown hue at the bottom of the glass when held to the light . huge cocoa colored rocky tan that leave tons of sticky lace all over the glass .  it was incredibly viscous without being cloying and the finish was amazing .

smell is exceptional - banana and cloves are the predominant forces , accompanied by other spices and maybe some pear . one of the best aromas i have found in a beer .  mouthfeel : rich , velvety mouthfeel . just coats the mouth so wonderfully . overall : bold flavorful taste , velvety smooth , and a very good beer overall .
s : amazing masala and juniper aromas . very good . d. if it was n't for the 9 % it would be perfect .  the mouthfeel is the best in the business and incredibly smooth .
very strong pleasant cherry smell .  incredibly smooth and heavy mouthfeel .

after trying my first brew from this brewery i was hesitant to give this a try but i thought better and decided i cant judge a brewery on just one beer alone and to be honest im glad i did , it pours a murky pale straw hue with sparkling carbonation that leaves behind a crisp , carbonated one finger head and a ring of lacing , the smell to this brew is what really entices me to want to take a nice sip out of it with aromas of pineapple , passionfruit , peach and melon and to be quite honest smells very similar to the cool drink passionna , it has an average mouthfeel for the style which is rather light but yet very sessionable indeed with tastes of pineapple and passionfruit first up followed by a light tropical fruit finish with no bitterness at all whatsoever and to be quite honest i forget that im a drinking a beer its that drinkable its not funny , overall im so glad i gave this brewery another go as it a brew that is made perfectly for our climate and lifestyle and i will definately revisit this beer in a heartbeart very impressed cheers .  m : right about perfect for the style ( or nearly any style ) .

spice , alcohol sweetness , and soft floral hops run the show in the aroma department . while the hopping is faint , it 's definitely more noticeable than other golden ales/bspa 's .  m : rich full creamy body and very moderate carbonation .

qiute complex and very good . taste : roasty , caramelly , ... notes of honey bring a lightly sweet touch to the brew .  in the mouth , it is velvety soft and smooth with a dry finish and a medium to full body ... a bit of plato .
perfect . t : delicious at first ! d : a delightful and drinkable dipa .  mouthfeel - nice and creamy full mouthfeel .
this baby is a complete caramel malt bomb , but i love it . this ranks in my top ten beers ever consumed .  mouth is wonderful , as creamy as you could hope .

( s ) - very fruity . figs , raisin , apple , & pineapple . touches of toffee , caramel , and brown sugar . ( t ) - again , fruity like the smell . drink this fresh , or age it carefully ; clearly a near constant 55 degree cellar did not help this age well .  nice carbonation o - it looks great and has fantastic mouthfeel , i just wish more of the barrel character came out or even more of the citrus ... just a bit one sided .
poured into a tulip . pours a dark caramel color with a finger of creamy white head with sticky lace . pretty good retention on this one .  thick mouthfeel , viscous and sugary .

1st nose : sublime ! spicy coriander and very fresh hops followed by hits of ripe citrus and other tropical fruits ( pineapple , mango , banana ) all seductively blended together into an enticing harmony of complexity . mouthwatering . a firmly textured but dryish beer expresses itself without at all being watery , showing assertiveness . spicy and firm ... agressive beer that will age magnificently . i find its assertiveness and complexity remind me of young examples of westmalle tripel . i think this will age beautifully .  mouthfeel is superb - medium thickness with an amazing finely bubbled carbonation that tickles the tongue .
poured a clear golden amber that left nice lacing on the glass .  m : the mouthfeel is pretty much perfect for this one .

nose : fantastic bouquet here , one of the best smelling ipas i 've had to date .  the taste is a mild roasted malt flavour with a hint of coffee and the mouthfeel is a lovely creamy texture that coats your mouth .

when you smell it , the cinamon , ginger and nutmeg really come out . the taste is equally as impressive .  m : mouthfeel is great . chewy and tasty , yet finishes dry and begs for you to drink more !
great aroma of baking bread with flowery hops on top .  soft and creamy texture , medium body and almost no carbonation . really nailed this .

s - the smell really caught me off guard with this . rather than getting a really bready , thick belgian yeast smell , i get huge noses of grapes and apples . very fruity which mixes incredibly well with the floral , citrus aroma of the hops .  the maltiness is chewy with some lingering sweetness , but it dries out towards the finish thanks to a touch of bitterness , alcohol warming , and some oakiness . this is an extremely well balanced strong , full bodied brew that offers a plethora of rich & creamy characters to the beer lover .

great synergy among the components may be what is so extraordinarily delightfully about the aroma . a bit hot , but i suspect that will improve with time .  mouthfeel - very smooth , agreeable carbonation level , slightly heavy , right on for the style .
a very nice , well balanced ipa .  almost creamy . a perfect level of carbonation .

help up to a light the brew had just a hint of red filter through , while the edges appeared a dark brown .  the thickest mouthfeel i 've ever had - always has been and i still wait for the day something thicker comes along .

overall the really nice smelling hops come through .  mouth feel : it has a thick , rich and luxurious feel in the mouth . there is a light bite on the lip and tongue . the carbonation starts out strong but dissipates quickly improving the lush feel of the beer .

big time grapefruit and citrus smells come out and slap my nostrils , along with some evergreen , maple syrup like malts , and alcohol . i 'm noticing a trend with some dipa 's ; huge unbalanced booziness !  mouthfeel- outstanding mouthfeel .

smell : a real difference . i love ky bourbon , and this beer smelled like ky bourbon and stout . very appetizing . mouth : very good , a little thicker than a traditional stout , but that 's a personal preference and very likeable .  m : another incredible aspect .
big and bold and it 's nice to smell something other than alcohol .  m : the beer feels so good in the mouth .

appearance - pale , hazy straw , one finger head that dissipates quickly smell - wonderful , full of hops , with hay , citrus , spice all mixed together , really spectacular taste - citrus flavors that one expects from an american wheat , but accented with strong hops bitterness and flavor mouthfeel - average , the hops did hang around on my tongue for quite a while drinkability - i almost enjoyed smelling this beer more than drinking it , but i would definitely drink it again and recommend it !  i love the mouthfeel , this one coats the inside of your cheeks and lingers on the pallet , while the sweetness fades and leaves the hop bitterness behind .

pretty delicious stuff . m : creamy and full bodied ; lower carbonation ; very satisfying . d : it makes for a good dessert - pretty sure it 's not something i 'd opt to drink a lot of ... its a real treat , though .  lush and extremely creamy on the palate . super fine carbonation structure ; uncious and smooth , velvety even . the booze becomes a bit burdening , as is expected with the high abv .

smell is fantastic , and much more potent than i was expecting . this is a mild brew in flavor and abv , but has a potent aroma , which is really interesting . it was a nice change of pace from the big ipas i 'm accustomed to , although this one could potentially be a phenomenal big brew .  m - mouthfeel is perfect . silky smooth bubbles and full bodied texture .

s - bananas , oranges , spice , wheat . finally , sam adams has paid attention to the aroma part of their beers . m - good . d - i 'm not really a fan of witbiers . it 's much better than sa white ale , but i find this a tad on the spicy side .  very creamy feel with medium carbonation and body .

lots more sweet malt in the nose , too . very appealing aroma . and lots more sweet malt character in the flavor . i love the smell more than the taste .  a big creamy malt character washes over the tip of your tongue . silky , creamy , yummy . my friend dave said this was one of the best barleywines he has had in a while .

lots of dried and ripe fruit in the nose , earthy raisins and plums , backed by sugary and toasted malt , slight breadiness and alcohol , faint rose-like floral character . the flavour was less vibrant , but still decent . heavy on malts , it had a sugary sweetness with bready yeast notes , sweet raisins and alcohol , banana .  the mouthfeel is particularly noteworthy , and every swig leaves a viscous coating of robust barley goodness on the tongue .
( a ) - pours a deep brown sienna color that produced a huge fluffy off-white head with near perfect retention .  very good stout .
s : very fragrant hops with a slight malt underbelly .  incredibly smooth taste , silky transition from sweet to bitter . feel is silk as mentioned earlier , pure bliss .

s - strong hoppy smell . smell is so strong right out of the bottle . not much of a bite , dry finish , but i was looking for something more , especially after that wonderful smell . mf - nice feel .  the mouthfeel is heavy , yet very smooth . much more full of a body as compared to any other amber ale .
after it recededs i believe this is the thickest stickiest lacing i 've ever seen . it coats the glass like gobs of pudding .  amazing texture ! full bodied , creamy and smooth as silk !

a very dark brown , appears a dark ruby when direct light seen through it . nice frothy head on top sticks around for a few minutes . notes : dissapointed in this stout although the appearance was nice .  mouthfeel is full and round .

malic acid , reminiscent of tart green apples , freshly squeezed lemon juice , peach / tropical fruits , damp hay , and the slightest hint of musty funk meets the nose . great balance ; an almost perfect floral and fruity bouquet . taste is markedly different , though familial to the nose : a straw undercurrent , lemon tartness , a touch of white flesh stone fruits ( e.g. , apricot ) , and miles and miles of horsey , earthy funk .  m : the mouthfeel is nothing short of silken : smooth carbonation , light body , and a clean finish . d : a solid , downright archetypal example of the english pale ale , but only really distinguished by its exceptional mouthfeel .
the smell is very fruity - apricot meets sweet malt .  m : the mouthfeel is complex , deep with myriad bold flavors . the interplay of the raspberry and oak is superb .

lots of carbonation , but the smell was kickin ' some serious coffee with hints of nut and chocolate . i enjoyed drinking this brew , but did hope for something more . i just ca n't get over the smells from this nice beer . it 's sooo very nice and deep . it 's an especially good one that you can sit back and sniff for a bit .  it 's crazy how thick and creamy it is with almost no carbonation to speak of .

s : this is the highlight . incredibly well rounded , quantifiable in each of my most important aroma attributes : malts , hops & yeast . there is an overlying balance in each , such that no single area is so strong or weak to negatively offset another . the malts are the perfect blend of cookie and straw , bread and grain . the hops have a flowery quality , mixed with a subtle bouquet of herbs . and the yeast provides a well incorporated doughy addition . d : dangerously drinkable . and available . a very fine lager and well affiliiated in the american amber/red lager category .  m - smooth as silk , medium-full body . clean , not cloying at all .

pretty sweet in the aroma with some nice earthy aromas taking the forefront here . the flavors here tend to be sweet ; like a chocolate syrup mixed into some burnt coffee .  mouthfeel has a fantastic thick body .
d : this had a fantastic smell and nice taste , and ok body .  mouthfeel is near perfect . rich , full bodied , but it politely excuses itself from your palate and doesnt linger over long .

really . this is pretty crazy stuff . there 's a ton of syrup that hits the mid , and it 's extremely cloying . it 's one strange brew .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , the hops just attack and stay on your pallet .

aromas were wonderful , taste was a bit too hot and one sided , but still pretty good .  this one was balanced and mild overall , the creaminess of the mouthfeel was the most incredible thing about it .

malt is very subdued and its wonderful . t- piney hops , very resinous . o- excellent smelling , decent tasting , okay mouth feel .  a - nice full head ; great lacing along the rim ; color a bit off ; it seems almost orange , two-toned s - excellent hops and florals ; a hint of something stale however t - hops are not overpowering ; nice malty flavor throughout m - the carbonation was surprisingly excellent ; wonderful effervescence on every mouthful d - overall i would say that this beer is not an every day , sit down at the pub , beer .

great smelling beer , really complicated , very impressive . taste is a sweet caramel but very light bodied , and much huge brown sugar on the palate .  velvety ... nice . the mouthfeel really helps this beer out and even saves it .

the beer looks beautiful when first poured with a coppery reddish color and a bright white head .  mouthfeel is wonderful . chewy , sweet up front , sugary , filling out the palate , with a viscous wheat body , and mild tart notes with smoothness running down the tongue with a semi dry finish .

one thing about hop bombs , for all their flaws , is they smell amazing . this does n't disappoint . nice .  the medium body leans on full but is in no way sweet or sticky . it 's very smooth and creamy yet a nice balance is made from ash and roasty bitterness .

like its appearance , it smells `` dark '' with earthy aromas similar to mushrooms with slight sweet brown sugar aromas along with spices similar to allspice .  m : full-bodied and creamy , with low-moderate carbonation , and some alcohol warmth in the throat .
s-molasses , roasted-sweet malt , dark fruit , chocolate .  perfectly carbonated and has a texture that is just right .

awesome roasted and chocolate malt aroma . one of the best smelling brews i 've sampled lately .  m- medium full , and quite creamy in the mouthfeel . carbonation is very unintrusive , but works wonders making this beer full , but light at the same time . o- exceptional drinkability , especially as it warms up .

lots os malt and dark fruit aromas . the taste was just as exceptional with a little warmth from the alcohol .  m - stellar mouthfeel , definitely a slick feel but not oily like some overly-hopped ipa .

appearance : painfully clear light yellow with a frothy white cap that left a lace mark on recession from pour . nice thick lacing all the way down the mug from a long lasting head .  the mouthfeel is easily the highlight of this beer . body is absolutely perfect , full and creamy without getting too big for for its britches and approaching imperial level viscosity .

smell is wonderful . reminds me of alesmith ipa and deschutes hop trip . taste , as i 've found it to often be with wet hop ipas , is a bit of a letdown after the perfect aroma . still pretty good , with a tart grapefruit quality and notes of orange and pineapple .  big boned , with refined carbonation . nice lagery smoothness on the palate . sugary sweet .
this beer 's smell is really nice - citrusy , a little apricot , some yeast & spices - very impressive nose .  mouthfeel is excellent , smooth as butter .
beautiful appearance copper base , puffy head that stays all over the brew , bubbles floating up ... this is pale ale .  mouthfeel is truly exceptional . thick and full-bodied ... well carbonated .

below average head retention & lacing s : licorice , breadyness , & booze as it warms t : licorice , cinamon & breadyness up front . a solid dopplebock , i will say i enjoyed the 7.0 abv german version just as much , if not more  this is a full bodied brew with a smooth , creamy feel to the mouth . it has a modest and enjoyable level of carbonation . very good feel about this brew and well made across the board .

aromas are sweet , bitter dark cocoa , slight hoppy bitterness and pine . i like the smells on this one . taste is really bitter , with strong booze and alcohol .  texture is syrupy , thick , wonderful on that front .

smell - hearty , fruity yeast aroma ( melon , kiwi ! ) with notes of sweet hops . last smell has earthy finish , with malty aromas and vaguely pumpkin-ish notes . fantastic ! taste - this is a seasonal ale with a lot of heart .  cream , creamy mouthfeel .

rich malty , nutty , liquor like smell , unexpected for a beer but nice . my favorite part of the beer . t : nice smooth , relatively thick body with light carbonation . quality wise i put this around the same place as yard 's love stout , though obviously not the same beer .  mouthfeel is silky-smooth and beautiful . this is the beer 's greatest asset .

the appearance was very nice on this beer . nice shade of reddish amber with lots of head .  mouth is medium bodied heavy , awesome carbonation and an amazing blend of fruits and hops that sting the tongue .
the nose is a very strong , well-balanced hop aroma .  the mouthfeel is wonderfully soft and smooth , syrupy and full , just enough fizz to cut the sugary fruit .
floral hops nose . lovely .  mouthfeel : very thick , almost chewy beer . this is a very good combination as well and makes for a very unique drinking experience .
smell -- this smells real good .  m : perfect carbonation / smoothness to this brew .

vinegary bouquet of cherry fruit , mostly sour with some light sweetness also . very much looks and smells like a flanders red .  perfect for winter in the northwest.. and not too spicy like a lot of other winter ales but also warming .
i really enjoy the nose on this beer .  the mouthfeel is right where it should be .

a : pours a slightly hazy orange , thin white head with some retention s : waves of aromatic hops on the front , lots of tropical fruit with features of mangos , tangerine , and grapefruit . mf : light body , medium to high carbonation o : this is an awesome and drinkable apa . it features a nice presentation of tropical smelling hops .  in fact , it 's extremely good . and the thick body solidifies this as a dessert old ale if there ever was one .
poured in to a stella chalice a somewhat murky gold color , with a large two fingers worth of pillowy white heading .  this baby also shines on the mouthfeel .
s : sweetish toffee and caramel malt , a little floral , citrus , cherry and pomegranate notes .  imho : a good representation of the style ; good balance , very sweet with a great mouthfeel .

there are lots of competing flavors in this one : smells range from raisins/dates to caramel and winter spices , although there is strong fruit smell to it ( bananas ) and some sweet candy . really fun to parse out . taste - good , but a little disappointing after some wonderful olfactory notes . a little too bitter at the start , and very , very sweet on the tongue .  truly exceptional creaminess . overall this was a refreshing take on the style with exceptional mouthfeel .

the aroma of fresh hops hits the senses immediately upon opening the bottle .  what a great body on this beer ! velvety smooth with a medium thickness and a superb carbonation level that adds to the experience .

11.2oz bottle poured into a tulip . ( a ) - pours a hazy golden yellow color that produced a great fluffy white head with superb retention behind it . the retention is so great that there was still a large head with the last few sips .  a uniquely creamy and smooth mouthfeel really stands out to me . medium to full bodied . a nice , bitter , warming finish .

the aroma was wonderful - estery , spicy , a lot of cinnamon , very unique . the flavor was good too , with a crisp start that fades into a slightly sweet without being cloying finish .  this beer has an unnatural smoothness to it .
a monstrous clash of pine and floral hops rip and tear across the brew . there is a lack of balance as far a traditional ipa goes .  thick and smooth moutfeel and mildly carbonated .

smell was the best part of the beer . this had a nice malty fruit front with small bits of smokey roasted barley notes . this really smelled like a stereotypical barleywine mixed with an old ale with some roasted hints . taste was good but had lots more smokey bitterness than dark fruit malts .  this is velvety smooth , and absolutely perfect . overall : a fantastic extra from a fantastic ba .
its pretty interesting , i noticed some dms , get rid of that and its perfect .  m : the feel is full bodied and oily ... perfect for an imperial stout .

really good smelling . t - a lot more of the spruce comes out in the taste , there is also a good amount of citrusy bitter hops , and ends with some lemon peel and zest .  m- low carbonation and amazingly creamy d - i 've always thought that drinking guiness was like drinking a loaf of bread -- a can makes a good dinner and this is still the same

the smell is absolutely fantastic . at first it is complete chocolate , but that gives way eventually to a roasted malt scent and alcohol bite . somewhat more alcoholic tasting than i prefer , but still a good beer .  the mouthfeel is rich and thick without ever being sticky .

a nice nose of roasted malt , yeast , banana , chocolate and clove is similar to that of most belgian ales .  taste has bitter chocolate with a hoppy clean finish ; mouthfeel is exceptional and creamy .

a -- pours a fluffy finger and a half eggshell off-white with decent lacing and retention . body lies more on the gold than the copper end of the spectrum -- in other words it 's an orange with more yellow than red in it . s -- spectacular . strongest part of this beer , for me . lots of fall fruit -- young pears , apples , even quince . t -- hoppy , especially in the back . hops boost the fruit into a more acidic profile of them , but the malt really does n't pull through all that , leaving kind of an echo of a breadloaf rather than the thing itself . disappointing in that regard . do n't get me wrong here -- you 'll taste caramel and you 'll taste munich , but it ai n't enough for my understanding of the style . if i liked hops a lot more i 'd order plenty of this , rather than the paulaner , which so far is my favorite in this style .  m : i think this may be the best aspect of it , just a wonderful body .

i also get oaky notes & compost t : tartness , raisins , oaky dryness a touch of medicinal/licorice flavor up front .  thick smooth mouthfeel and mildly carbonated . the creamy smoothness is more apparent and delightful now .

5.0 s : wow , this is an incredible smelling brew . lots of roastiness and probably even more milk chocolate and the two exist in perfect harmony . it is n't the most complex , but it 's in your face and absolutely wonderful . 3.5 t : unfortunately , the quality of the taste is n't even comparable to that of the nose , but it 's still pretty good . there 's semi-sweet chocolate in there , but there 's an even bigger dark roasted coffee flavor .  mouthfeel is perfect , with a light body and a crisp finish that ends semi-dry thanks to a vigorous carbonation level .

the smells are many chocolates , milkshakes , some hops . good beer but it may not be enough for the imperial stout connoisseurs .  m : medium-full bodied and silky smooth . this is one of the creamiest , smoothest beers i 've ever had and is an absolute joy .

it poured a dark ruby/ amber color with perfect clarity . an amazingly dense ivory head .  m : thick but clean in the mouth , almost oily , with a warming alcohol effect down the throat . light carbonation balances the thickness of this brew quite perfectly . d : hmm , i do n't think this beer gets all the credit it deserves .

s : nice aroma to this beer ... lots of fruity notes , orange and grape come to mind .  there 's nothing , i repeat ... nothing bad about the mouthfeel on this one . rich yet dry and even clean for something so huge . full finish gives off a little oatmeal chocolate chip sweetness .

aroma of dry coffee is quiet pleasant with light roasted malt notes also noticeable .  this beer is absolutely in the mouth , and the complexity -- the way the bourbon and hops almost spar with one another across the tongue -- is simply beautiful . just when you think there 's too much here for the alcohol to show through , it warms your mouth and very much adds to the experience .
the smell is fantastic , i wish i had an air freshener that smelled like this !  this beer has a nice full body and a crisp carbonation .

very black . a brew the color of the clothing that i am so fond of wearing . a compact burnt almond foam sits lazily atop the brew , weaving intricate web-like patterns down the inside of the glass as the inky fluid disappears .  mouthfeel is full , thick , viscous , sticky , and hardly carbonated . this is absolutely delicious , but the sweetness really gets to be a bit much .
very enjoyable arome if you like bloody mary 's .  mouthfeel on this beer is damn near perfection in glass .

s- raspberries covered in warm dark belgian chocolate with a hint of phenols in the background . d- decent to pretty good stout overall , it just needs some time to let the alcohol settle . the smell is immaculate and i wish it tasted more like it smelled .  m- thick body , almost barrel aged type of thickness . i thought that this was brilliant about this beer . this is probably the best thing about this beer .

smells of strong bouquet of candied fruit , booze , spices and toffee . taste is an intense rush of alcohol , spice , and what feels a little bit like wine tannins , or oversteeped tea .  really smooth and velvety with just the right amount of carbonation .
seriously great smelling beer ! body is fairly thin overall impression : great nose , but the body doesnt back it up .  o : very good eye appeal and remarkable mouthfeel .

they are not frightening , like the particles i 've found in other beers ( see beer down the drain thread ) there is also a great aroma coming of this beer - hoppy , malty - well balanced . this beer tastes better as it warms up .  m-creamy , rich and wonderful . d-dangerously good . so smooth , a little filling but it goes down well . wow , what a fantastic beer .
guess what i hate this beer very much . although it looks very good with golden color , it smell and taste horrible .  perfect for this style .

although i was left wanting a little more smokiness , i thought this more of a function of just how powerful the smell was . i was hoping the beer rested heavier on the palate , but was slightly disappointed .  strong big bubbles , surprising considering the small shape of the head , pretty full bodied as well , i like that . sweet and easy drinking proposing a lemon slice here and there that grows into a pungent tartness reminiscent of a straight lambic .

the aroma is thick and sweet , full of maple and smoke . it smells much more like a good , smooth bourbon than a beer . it was intensly sweet and very very smokey .  mouthfeel is one the best that i 've encountered ; tart , full and very enjoyable .

one nose full of the aroma turned my issue reaction to the beer around . smells like a tripel should . huge vinous qualities . hints of pale fruit such as pears and white grapes . maybe a little too much going on and the honey qualities are a little too strong . the fruity qualities are overpowered and that is what i like the most in tripels .  m - just perfect . the carbonation dances on my tongue bringing out the flavors .
pours dark brown , almost opaque , though it shines a deep ruby when backlit . light tan , very creamy head lasts all the way down .  thick , rich , creamy , luxurious and full bodied .

a : very nice deep brown color , great thick velvety head s : mild nose , nothing jumps out at me , slight sourness ( old ?  the best part of this eer by far is the mouthfeel and drinkability . nearly flawless , the only problem is that i want to drink it faster than my wallet permits .

( s ) - a light roasted character with some figs and raisin . ( t ) - very similar to the smell with a nice rum-raisin-like kick .  m & d -- mouthfeel 's the strongest of the beers i sampled from sly fox -- super creamy and mellow .

appearance : this belgian pours a beautiful honeycomb color with well stacked off-white head . lots of beading . very clean and tight appearance .  silky smooth malt properties - now that i think about it probably the most smooth wit/hefe/wheat i 've had in ages . orange-y hop burps follow .
aroma : hops , hops and more hops . i detect a bit of honey in the nose , but mostly a piney hop aroma .  the great flavor is held up with an excellent body and mouthfeel .

the nose is killer . you get a multitude of ginger , cardamom , and other spices with honey , tea , and slightly sweet malts . oh my god is this aromatic . it 's almost like a spiced bread pudding . it is sweet yet complex . it drinks medium in body and is pretty sticky on your palate . it was a pleasure to try it .  mouthfeel is thick and lush . wonderful overall , a great scotch ale .
the aroma is perfect . it has a wonderful pale and munich malt scent along with a slight bisquity aroma . it 's rich with a fruity yeast aroma as well ; very nice .  excellent mouthfeel .

smell what a nosy beer ! theres a lot to smell here . dark citrus and spicy fruits mix with deep caramelly herbal malt scents . this will be a superb beer to cellar for several years .  mouthfeel is perfect . the weight of this beer is phenomenal .

this is one of the best ipa 's i 've ever smelled . flavor : burst of hop flavor , which seems to remind me of pepper and oregano , and pine needles , and dried lemongrass . quite fine ipa .  creamy and full-bodied , this reminds me of melted ice cream in a way . smooth , exciting and creative .

appearance : big , white , belgian head , mountainous and snowy with thick , cloudy lace . body is a bright orange-amber with tiny bits of sediment in evenly-distributed suspension . bold and classy .  i love the full mouthfeel on the speedway stout .

still , i really like this aroma . '' i 'm not sure this is the most refreshing beer i 've ever had , and i tend to stay away from most fruit beers in general , but this is a nice berry wheat that i find quite tasty .  it is thick on the tongue and very nice , but with a slight note of the heavy alcohol , but it 's expected at 9.00 abv .
a complex and thoroughly enjoyable nose . t- malty up front , with a lot of pepper and some herbal notes .  this thing has a big body and lots of clingy lace . pretty outstanding and unique brew .

smell : extremely cinnamon with the buttery hints of diacetyl and ringwood yeast just holding that cinnamon sugar spice up on a big pedestal in the aroma arena . it is a pit perfume in it boldness in the nose but i was pleasantly surprised since shipyard is usually so reserved .  mouthfeel is a fantastic creamy yet foamy consistency .
lovely roasty caramel notes alongside peaches , cherries , and a small dose of cocoa .  mouthfeel-plush and velvety smoothe with perfect carbonation ; this beer 's highlight .

smell is lots of spicy , floral hops , but also rather sugary . it immediately reminded me of an ipa that got lost in my cellar where the malt dominated in syrupy sweetness once the hop flavors faded . drinkability is not to high for me , the bitterness is just to harsh , as much as i enjoyed the aroma . probably better fresh , not sure how how old this last bottle i found misplaced at my beer store is , but probably a few months .  very full bodied , but great carbonation makes it slide down smoothly .

i can smell the blueberry aroma from 15-ft away . it still retains a good beer quality without being overly sweet or cloying . fresh blueberries from shatrners farm go into each bottle .  m - thinner than i would have guessed from the chunky nose , but it 's extremely well built and feels weighty in my mouth . the carbonation is almost non-existent , and this brew feels really silky and rich in my mouth .

s : the beer really shines here . strong smell of dates and figs which i 've never picked up on from unaged bottles . a very sweet malty smell as well with vanilla and caramel notes with just a tiny hint of citrus . to bring out new complexity to both the flavor and smell while also probably destroying the head retention .  mouthfeel is absolutely fantastic !

the aromas comming off this beer are very pungent . i pick up medicinal alcohol smells , toasted brown sugar , cinnamon , nutmeg , allspice , clove , and maybe even a little fennel .  m & d : mouthfeel is perfect , medium-heavy bodied with a great amount of carbonation , but not so much that it 's distracting .
nose is very sticky sweet pine hops .  aroma and flavor have some fantastic things going on , and the mouthfeel is wonderful as well .
ratings at this point : 4.5 - 5.0 - 4.5 - 5.0 - 4.5 '03-'04 version : still looks great , smells pretty good .  mouthfeel is fantastic ; carbonation totally envelopes the mouth , tongue and throat .

s- crazy strong apple cider and cherry dark fruit hybrid aroma , superbly enticing . some oak and acetic as well . the aroma is like fresh vermont apple cider mixed with great fruit and even a wine aspect .  m - outstanding ! the smoothest , creamiest brew i have ever consumed , goes down like liquid silk . d - i would come back to this one purely for the mouthfeel , never had anything like it .

nice lacing on the inside of the glass . gorgeous looking beer with a nice aroma profile .  body is quite full with a nice creamy texture , no apparent alcohol and good carbonation . very good overall and easily drinkable which makes this one the best in this series .

aroma is dominated by hops of course but there is also a strong alcohol presence . this is an extremely hoppy beer that is to be sipped slowly .  m : very fine carbonation produces a medium bodied creamy almost velvet like mouthfeel . d : a very mellow beer with an excellent mouthfeel .
smell of coffee and dark chocolate with a twang of citrus .  the mouthfeel is incredible , coating the sides of the glass along with the sides of my mouth .

appearance : poured from a growler with a very large off white super creamy head , it looks like half melted ice cream or whipped cream . it dissipated to a thin layer leaving amazing lacing all down the side of my glass .  exceptionally smooth . velvety and soft with moderate carbonation .

color is almost flourescent copper and slightly cloudy . white head that dissipates pretty quickly with a nice residual layer . beautiful lacing as well .  m - a big body but mainly a great smoothness !
s- this has an incredibly awesome aroma . i get lots of citrus , floral notes , as well as grapefruit for a little bit of acidity .  the mouthfeel is exactly what i like in a porter .
this beer is hoppy and clean . it smells good , like fresh hop flowers , yippee for dry hopping .  mouthfeel is great ! lots of carbonation and it very crisp and refreshing .

this beer has heavy clouding in its body but no sediments ; very thick white head that lasts for several minutes ; caramel-colored body with brown whisps throughout smell is absolutely outstanding : a sugary-sweet , fruity blend of aromas that is complimentary to the rest of the beer and very clean and crisp .  the mouthfeel is one that is well proportioned , having a smooth balance of malt and hops making for a surprisingly crisp quaff .
s - nice hop aroma , quite citrusy .  m : perfect , absolutely spot on , thick , huge and sticky , with a hint of alcohol heat , very dry as well . excellent in the mouthfeel .
it smells like a pretty good saison .  mouthfeel - maximum smoothness , perfect slick oiliness and evenly carbonated .
upon opening it smelled of lovely green apples ( the cork still smells like apple candy ) and it poured out a golden yellow with a nice white head .  mouthfeel is super rich , nice low carbonation .

lots of fruit and citrus , would have expected them to fade a lot more by now . caramel malt is much more present this time around , a few months age on it . no alcohol , lots of hops like maharaja and devil dancer . db- a nice beer but it is still a bit too hoppy even for me , i do n't say that often ( hop dam , devil dancer ) .  taste : mouth feel is perfectly constructed to be both elusive and comfortable .
smell : nice light fruits at first glance - crisp apples and pears - as well as a refreshing citrus aroma .  this has such a beautifully smooth mouthfeel with a perfect amount of carbonation zing .

rich , smoky , chocolaty , coffee-ish aroma has just a touch of sweetness and is very appetizing .  mouthfeel- perfect amount of creamyness , sweetness , and carbonation . outstanding drinkability- for a huge beer , this is pretty darn drinkable .

the nose is malty-sweet with prominent honeyish character and caramel , plummy , raisiny esters while aging has introduced some sherry/port note to the aroma with mineral- earthy hop undertones . in short : an old ale with aroma that significantly differs from the flavor which is too dry and overly hopped .  feels fantastic . good drinkability .

overall : very delicate and balanced . love the way this smells . taste -- more tartness than the nose would let on .  very smooth with a bit of carbonation , perfect for the style , it 's always nice to have a strong stout that is drinkable and not overpowering .

a & s : wow great smell right off the bat . the perfect smell for an apa , although not super complex . t & m : really not at all what i expected , after the amazing aroma i smelled at first . its a bit complex ill give it that , im tasting more of the piney hops way far into the after taste and in the burlps .  m - exactly what i look for .

smells pretty damn good . like most abita 's , however , this is where the goodness ends .  a feel : i actually loved the medium-bodied mouthfeel as it just seemed to have a perfect flow across the palate with the hops and malts doing wonderful things to tickle me.. this is what a doppelbock should feel like.. drinkability : is ok - its a very strong beer and sierra nevada certainly did not try to mask the alcohol too well , nor the hops nor.. well , anything .

appearance : poured black , with 3 finger dark brown head . the head has good retention and has a good thick foam . very nice lacing all the way down .  the taste is mellow chocolate on the front as it glides down with its thick silky mouth feel . almost a fudge aftertaste .

leaves nice lacing and really glows in the light . the aroma is the biggest tropical flavors i have ever smelled in an ipa . has a huge mango , pineapple , and grapefruit aroma . really nice on the palate . really delicious and complex . one odd the better ipas out there .  mouthfeel is excellent , syrupy and smooth with a bit of carbonation .
truly wonderful smell . t = apples , some figs , a bit yeasty ( in a lemony/acidic sort of way if that makes any sense ) , and pretty malty .  very thick feeling , creamy , velvety .
11/12/02 : dark , dark ruby , almost black .  m- this gets a 5 because it had a perfect level of carbonation and a really nice mouthfeel .

rum soaked oranges , fig , aged caramel malt make for a great fragrance . t : sweet toffee malt , oranges , butterrum and brandy .  full flavored , viscous , yet feels so airy and puffy in the mouth .

pours with a very nice large head with great lacing but not really much retention . very clear amber body , absolutely gorgeous and inviting .  the mouthfeel on this beer though is truly exceptional , it is extremely pillow and fluffy like in the mouth it feels great .

unbelievably luscious hop aroma , showcasing nearly everything aromatically possible for hops , but with the pine and grapefruit standing out most . no malt backing and bone dry , making it almost undrinkable , but wow , what an aroma .  m good creamy mouth feel with good carbonation . i love the mouthfeel of this one .
aroma is almost all orangey hops , sweet mandarin oranges , bordering on syrupy . good lacing all the way down .  mouthfeel , once warm , is a splendid rich , full bodied lusciousness .

intense aroma of fresh raspberry and with slight notes of honey and wild flowers just coming through . another amazing beer from founders and worth trying .  quite hoppy , but also with a fairly sweet maltiness , and a great , full mouthfeel .
intense , and hugely enjoyable . the chocolate alone is just stunning . t : spicy , strong , smoky and chocolatey .  m : creamy , perfect carbonation .

there is a wonderfully elixer-like nature to this great aroma . i asked others to smell it and they were universally impressed . the flavor is great but a bit over the top on richness and fullness . but this is a very rich beer , rather like the too-rich nature of a great piece of pecan pie .  perfect . d : too much , and i do n't say that ... ever .

it 's hard to rate this as a belgian pale . massive amounts of oak , cinnamon , unpasteurized apple cider , brett , white wine vinegar , tartness . mouth-watering . t - a lot more subdued than the nose leads . basically starts smooth with a light tartness , and lots of brett notes , and finishes quite clean and slightly dry .  m - nice small carbonation , very soft and smooth .
a : pours a four finger tan head of brilliant cream and thickness . i want this beer to have my babies .  fucking incredible amount of creaminess . good carbonation .

hops hit the nose like fireworks in the air , an explosive aroma . hops only in the nose , void in the body .  incredible mouthfeel - perfect balance of malts , outstanding flavors and carbonation , it rolls onto the tongue like a dark snowfall - light , airy , and it really builds up .
a=rich dark brown , good foamy head .  m : perfection . my words simply ca n't do justice to the body of this beer .

this is quite a contrast from what the rich , boozy aroma promised . m- the moderate amount of carbonation feels just right for this beer , but the body is thinner than i would have liked .  the mouthfeel is very creamy and thick . very nicely done , the nogne i have had to date .
a-pours a brilliant golden color with tons of visible carbonation and a two finger white head .  it glides over the tongue . quite dry .
s - get plenty of piney hops in there , but something like tart green apples as well , interesting . biscuit malt aroma as well .  it 's a very tight , small carbonation that is complimentary .

s : an interesting an striking scent leaps out of the glass on the first sniff , fir trees , nutmeg , cinnamon and other spices abound , with a bit of malt . t : this is one of the more heavily spiced winter warmers that i have had , heavy bitter nutmeg on the first taste , which i was enjoying , but delving deeper into the brew reveals even more flavour . m : a little too much on the weak side , watery and thin , but has an interesting texture from all the spices used to keep it interesting . d : a nice winter warmer to try in january , it brings back the christmas feeling with its unique taste , definitely worth a shot .  the body to this brew is full and creamy which really gives it a nice mouthfeel for a barleywine .
aroma : similar to the tap version . very nice and warming . taste : way too hot and boozey .  mouthfeel is great , big , fat chewy and oily. , imperial stout all the way .
the smell is definitely the highlight for me .  m : more than medium bodied , good carbonation and a nice heavy feel on the tongue . d : a roasted anise monster with a nearly perfect body .

so lets start with saying i am not a huge porter fan ... we got the sampler at the stockton bj 's and we were really excited for the brown ... turns out we ordered the pitcher of the porter after the sampler ... . pours thick and heavy with med to large head .  this drinks exceptional , no way this is 10 % ? ? medium on the body , sugary and tart , bold hops with bitter finish , very creamy and smooth .

when we finally opened it , it wafted aromas : stouty roasted malt , bourbon .  mouthfeel - quite thick and chewy , you will know that much from the pour . perfectly smooth on the palate . slightly below average carbonation .

the aroma is powered by clove and hints od spice . the taste is very good , and follows the aroma of clove and spice ... and backed with a heavy abv .  the beer has an exceptional mouthfeel , and is just luscious .

the color and appearance of this beer are exceptional with a redish brown glow when held to the light . the head is frothy and billowing with large rounded pockets of off-white discoloration .  mouthfeel is perfect , lots of carbonation to keep things fun .

s : great smell - all the wonderful belgian yeast regulars -heavy on the clove and banana esters . no discernable hops . t : hmmm ... .very sweet , big malty flavors but without any hop to balance .  the carbonation was enough to give it life but not bite your tongue . fantastic beer .

looks fine sitting there ... three finger bone white head slightly hazy straw hue ... smells great lemons and brett are present along with some other fresh fruits like mango . the brett is there but hiding very well and all you get is a bit of lemon and then a long seemingly unending note of bitterness ... .from what ? it 's light and easy to drink but the unwelcome surprising bitterness character makes it not something i 'd drink a lot of ... thanks for the chance to try this idatetheforumla allagash i am disappoint ... if it 's between this and interlude , get interlude ...  m : the feel is great . carbonation adds tiny bubbles as you sip and the beer is pretty thick , it coats the mouth as you drink .

the appearance was very good - a deep rich red color that was clear and brilliant . there was lots of head composed of minuscule bubbles which towered over the rim of my glass .  the mouthfeel is exquisite . this is one of the smoothest stouts i 've ever had , and as an imperial , that 's saying something .
s- dark fruit , belgian yeast , smells like most dubbels to me , maybe a bit sweeter .  mouthfeel - full , creamy . very pleasant .

i could smell this one as soon as i popped the cap . tropical fruits , mango , kiwi and , of course , intense strawberry . a very high sense of citric acid , since the smell itself is like sticking an orange up your nose . very champagne-like . nearly no head except for a slight pink ring and central transparent island . i was expecting a more `` off '' strawberry flavor , likening to strawberries about to spoil due to a hint of that smell , but the taste is extremely pure and refreshing .  mouthfeel is great . this one stands out in the mouthfeel department for dipa 's .

s- loved the floral , rich aroma . it really excites your senses and prepares you for the richness of its flavor t- not my cup of tea ... .but it does have a wonderful , rich and complex taste .  ale best enjoyed before 01/09/06 printed on the top label 09id 12:50 big burst of air at open plus a bit of foam from the top appearance dark red , slightly opaque body ; rising carbonation from the basement ; massive cloudlike , off-white head ; lace is modest smell with a bit of a cold the nose is a bit blocked but ill do my best ; yeast , date , raisin , candy sweetness , spice , sour apple , some bread crust and a touch of alcohol taste again , excuse the slighty blocked nose ; yeasty ; apple and a bit of the spice and candy ; a bit of hops at the end mouthfeel big full feel ; a carpet of carbonation rolls into the mouth ; nice crisp carbonation and dry enough for a nice close drinkability for such a big feel , the palate is cleaned nicely at the end corsendonk hits the dubbel as good as ichiro . what a pleasant experience .

smell is really great . taste/mouthfeel - rich roasty malts and dark chocolate with a hint of oak .  the body is outstanding , better than any abt from belgium i 've had , decadent creaminess and perfectly mouth-filling .
smells awesome . t : flavor is n't quite as good . overall : i really liked this .  the mouthfeel is epic , the perfect feel .
very interesting . smelled berri-licious .  great , bubbly mouthfeel that compliments the other traits of the beer ; keeps the sweetness from being cloying and offers it a dry finish .

a - dark copper with a large , well defined foamy white head that slowly fades to a thiner layer that stays throughout .  thick , creamy , viscous liquid that was milky , chocolatey and roasty . big on taste , and big on feel . nice .

potent , sticky icky hop buds . intense dry-hopping leads to a fantastic nose on this one . t- this thing is a hop grenade . d- not for the faint of heart , and kind of a shitty price ( $ 6 ) but very good . good stuff .  m : this mouthfeel is out of this world . extremely creamy and very very smooth . although the alcohol is present in the nose it is very well hidden in the taste and mouthfeel .

s- the smell is the best aspect of the beer . coffee and dark fruits . smells of the best cherries i can think of . t- dry , malty coffee with a hint of dark fruits . really nothing special , but definitely better than `` average . '' m- in my estimation , this beer is medium bodied . d- 1. it is a stout .  m - perfect . low carbonation and high viscosity .

it has a light red core with copper at the edges . the carbonation produces a creamy tan head that settles to a 1/4 finger and hangs around a while .  it has a nice thick feel that i do not often find in wheat beers , and leaves a pleasant and satisfying aftertaste .

pours hazy golden straw color with a nice 2-3 fingers of fairly dense white head with fantastic retention that reduces to a decent sized lacing cap that lasts .  d : another excellent brooklyn brewery creation that cuts down the style boundary between hefe and wit with style and tons of flavor with an excellent mouthfeel .

the nose on this beer is incredible and is easily its best feature . the beer smells very impressive . on the palate , once again one gets lots of milk chocolate .  hits the tongue with an almost velvety texture with little carbonation .
wow , ca n't wait to taste .  mouthfeel is velvety smooth , and drinkability is great .

t/s : lots of flavors - they just did n't mix well ! lots of fruity esthers and sweetness on the bottom , molasses and roasted malts on the top .  mouthfeel is full and creamy with dead on carbonation .

aroma : big floral hops with hints of orange rind and just a touch of sweet malt in the background . very tasty !  m : the label on this beer says its a smooth dark ale ... they arent lying about how smooth this beer is..very nice ! this is a great beer ... was a little bit hesitant to get it cause i do n't really like imperial stouts..its very far from that , a very tasty brew .

it is sour and i like it . i like the aroma but the taste brought a bit too much .  the mouthfeel is awesome too because it has that thicker rich like malt taste that you 'd get in well crafted higher alcohol beers .

a finger and a half of pearly head that left tight knit lacing all the way to the end . pitch black colour . just enough weight to the body ; it was n't watery , but neither was it like drinking oatmeal . the interplay between the creamy head and the robust beer worked well .  m-medium creamy carbonation with a spicy finish .
the smell is amazing . very floral , tons of citrus .  m- unbelievably smooth and creamy with a bit of a alcohol-hop bite at the end . very nice .
s - smells like milk chocolate , really like a candy bar of some sort . smells sweet and yummy .  mouthfeel is amazing with this beer .

the aroma might be the best i 've experienced ... right up there with paulaner . the flavor is pretty good , if a little less malty than i like , but there are still those caramel flavors present that start and finish nicely .  mf : perfect coarseness and dryness for the style .

wow this has a wonderful nose . apricots , peaches , orange peel . it 's complex , a little metallic and very solid . very pleasant . well , the taste is quite a disappointment really . it 's quite drinkable and quite enjoyable , althougha touch simplistic in taste , and a let down after the wonderful smells .  the mouthfeel hit me as exceptional , as the start was crisp and the finish was lightly crisp and smooth on the tongue . the spices last long on the tongue after swallowing .

this beer has a great texture ; creamy , smooth , but has some kick at the ass-end due to the alcohol .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is awesome . full bodied , with mild , low carbonation the produces a lush , velvety mouthfeel .
aroma is fantastic . you can almost taste it .  dark fruit , malt and the zesty yeast combine to flavor the beer , it is rich and full bodied yet not heavy on the tongue .

the beer , red-brown coloured and reasonable head , smells rich ; i smell caramelised malt , some spicy , cinnamon odour , apple and a little alcohol . it should have more depth in it.the taste is disappointing compared to its rich smell .  mouthfeel - very smooth feel , subdued carbonation , right on .
smells very hoppy with hints of oak . definitely smells like it would be very tasty !  the mouthfeel is the best part of this drink .
smell : good smelling beer . let it warm and swirl it and it turns into an excellent smelling beer . taste : very roasty , almost charcoally .  mouthfeel is amazingly thick and rich .

you get the big plum/prune smell that happens when the sweetness of the malt and bitterness of those low alpha hops strike the perfect balance . alcohol is well hidden .  mouthfeel is creamy and rich , but sits lightly . almost ... fluffy , with a bit of a refreshing tang at the finish with moderate even mild bitterness .
smell - dominated by brown sugar and sweet fruits ( dates and pears are what i smell .  lovely soft caressing bottle-conditioned mouthfeel .

the smell i can best discribe as a sugar coated hop cone - very nice . i 'm getting orange peel , sugar cookies and pine .  the mouthfeel is where this beer shines the most ... oh so creamy and full-bodied . just magnificent .

in the meantime , enjoy the aromas . this is definately an american red ... sweet , sweet rich deep malt followed by a citrus hops tang ... really strong nwp citrus hops tang . a little disappointing . citrus to grapefruit hops are n't quite clean nor fresh enough for the beer to be good or memorable . this is disappointing ... .it 's like the brewers efforts are spoiled by use of inferior ingredients .  m : crisp and bubbly carbonation make the drink a pleasure in your mouth .

this tastes more like apple cider than strongbow ! i 'm honestly not even sure how to review this beer . if you want to know taste and mouthfeel all you have to do is carbonate some good apple cider ( the brown kind ) and throw in a ton of cinnamon and there ya go . cool to try , not worth the buy .  the body is fantastic . it is -- just as the name says -- like cream : slick , glassy and wonderful .

for an ipa , the aroma is subtle with hops . this is a hearty and enjoyable ipa .  mouthfeel is the best part of this beer . the beer glides onto the tongue and sits firmly , with just enough carbonation to bring fizziness to both the tongue and the roof of the mouth . easy to swallow .

the nose is quite potent : sweet apples , a definite rice starchiness . nose is quite nice , i really like it .  mouthfeel is full and creamy , the ease of drinking this is quite astonishing for 12 % abv but the plastic is holding it back a bit . fantastic stout overall , although i 'm not sure it measures up with the top tier .
s-smokey nose . chalk , peat , chocolate and tree bark . t-bitter hops and burnt malts are present .  m - creamy goodness !
this beer has great color , a great smell , but is way too watery and thin for my liking from a stout .  a fantastically smooth and creamy mouthfeel that leaves you begging for another pint .

the aroma is quite good and full of cocoa . this is a very smooth , medium to full-bodied and malt-accented porter ; in this way it seems to be a very english interpretation .  the mouthfeel is very , very nice . not too thick , not too thin and with the fine carbonation that you 'd want from champagne .

s : incredibly complex , perhaps due to the age and the infiltration of oxygen ? extremely enjoyable . t : enjoyable body with a solid malt backbone and enough residual sweetness to seem appropriate .  it had a great amount of body nd flavor while not feeling too heavy .

4.5 s : wonderful ! all the best aspects of a brown are here - plenty of nuts , toasty , caramel , toffee , and brown sugar . then the maple syrup kicks in making this unique and the pecans kicks the nuttiness into overdrive . very well done . 4.0 t : the taste is sweeter than the nose suggests .  slick and full in the mouth with a perfect crisp level of carbonation .
the nose is almost overpowering with ginger with some of that heavy honey .  the mouthfeel is amazing for this beer , considering the style and the alcohol content .

one of the best-smelling beers ever ... a very enticing citrus-like aroma . the flavor stays fairly consistent throughout the cycle , but it is n't really a beer or ale flavor -- more like a citrus tea with spice and floral notes .  mouthfeel : very full and creamy .

smell : powerful aroma of ginger can be smelled as soon as brew is poured with honey and cloves present .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy and with huge grapefruit flavors , followed by pine and then resin . beautifully balanced .

smell is grain madness ! ! ! i must say it is a great smell but quite odd for what i was expecting with a double ipa .  the mouthfeel , i am guessing due to the aging , is nearly perfect . just a hint of spiciness on the palate leaves this fairly dry and wonderfully smooth .
a cloudy orangey reddish color with an off white head .  m- very smooth with a good carbonation level . excellent .

big hoppy aroma , hops definitely dominate . lots of pineapple , grapefruit , and general overall hoppyness .  very full bodied and mouth feel complex and nice tastes all around very drinkable stout with nice hop balance

a - pours a fairly clear dark amber with 2 fingers of off-white head . dissipates slow and leaves beautiful lacing .  really big , rich mouthfeel . thick and chewy with a smooth carbonation , which suits the decadence of the flavour well . in fact , this is one of the most perfectly matched mouthfeels i 've come across , so top marks for goose island !
very nice aroma . starts off sweet and creamy .  exceptionally creamy mouthfeel , a bit airy though .
smell : this may be the first beer i 've had that smells better than it tastes . reminds me of banana pudding .  m : very good body given the low abv .

intensly resinous nose with a distinct marijuana notes . honestly , this smells as much like ganja as any beer i 've had . shortbread attempts for aromatic balance , and fails .  it 's rich and smooth , a touch creamy -- flawless mouthfeel .

the aroma of ranger is the highlight . citrus hops greet the nose along with a little bit of pine that rounds out the aroma profile . this is one of my very favorite ipas , mostly because it is so citrusy and refreashing .  mouthfeel is creamy and smooth and aftertaste is creamy dark semi-sweet chocolate and alcohol . yummy !
