s : smelled like the san diego countryside with a touch of saison funk .  the mouthfeel is the best part of this beer .

this was my favorite beer when i went to pittsburg ... the cruch works brewing co. was the craziest brewery/ resturant i have ever been to..its an old chuch..hence the name ... the beer is a dark carmel color with a nice off white head ... the beer was a malt fest in my mouth ... lots of flavors such as carmel , orange , licorice , chocalate and a small amount of hops . this beer is very drinkable..the alcohol is a low 3 % range ... this beer was great to eat with my chicken meal ... complemented very well  mouthfeel : smooth and body-warming right from the start .

when the hell did this start smelling so good ? ! not terribly complex , but such an intoxicatingly good scent . t- too bad that smell dose n't translate to taste .  no alcohol warmth comes through ... m - thick and creamy with a moderate amount of carbonation . this one is deliously viscous ... d - really enjoyed these .
the nose is excellent sharp hops .  4.5/5 mouthfeel - smooth almost has a chewiness . exceptional .

smells very fresh and lively . taste - a melding of malt and hop flavor up front . d'ability - looks great and smells great , but does n't drink great for me .  real big , nice an simple mf/o : super viscous , super smooth , creamy , and velvety . the best feel to a beer that i 've ever experienced .

malted barley , caramel , butter toffee , and a slight metallic note . apricots and peach nectar come through too . t : kind of moot . d : the only thing keeping this beer going besides the aroma is the presence of booze , surprisingly enough .  very little carbonation .

s : hops come out in the aroma here , thick earthy , piny smelling hops . t : roasty sweetness that hits the back of my mouth and leaves a sweet dark fruit ( slight ) .  mouthfeel - this beer is perfectly smooth . i am very impressed with the texture and flow of this naturally carbonated new glarus brew .

very pleasant . quite a bit of alcohol taste and warming , which was n't a surprise for an `` imperial '' beer .  m : medium viscosity , very smooth on the palate with perfect acidity , and with low carbonation .
pretty good ipa . very nice aroma , but the mouthfeel and maltiness could use more backbone .  wonderfully coats the mouth and the tongue .
a ) looks great ... deep dark black with a thick cocoa head .  mouthfeel - very smooth brew , big-bodied with a velvet touch .

s : huge aroma of roasted coffee beans right off the bat . i do n't particularly like coffee ( except the sugary starbucks versions ) , but i 've always loved the smell of raw coffee beans . and this aroma rivals that of the best coffee stouts.. t : mostly just coffee and sweet malts . just damn good beer .  m : hands down..the best mouthfeel i 've had with any beer . perfect !

a wildly complex and divine aroma . deep chocolate , dark fruits , warm alcohol , sweet brandy , tart cherries and raisins -- all these flavors are here and they all mix superbly well together . it 's really something to behold . the flavor is again complex , and my only complaint is that it 's just a little too sweet . the rich chocolate , flavors of cherries , sweet and warming brandy , along with a touch of tartness are really spectacular . a thick and substantial sipper -- but it 's the only mouthfeel that would allow for the substantial complexities found in this beer . so many incredible flavors and aromas all come together for a near masterpiece of a beer .  medium bodied , extremely smooth velvety mouthfeel .

smells wonderful . citrusy , grassy hops - very much like an ipa - grapefruits . great smelling , very well balanced . taste is a little disappointing , however .  black as can be with as nice looking thick tan head.. the head almost looks reddish like many other imperial stouts.smells of burnt coffee , some chocolate and ripe fruit.taste and mouthfeel are topnotch . this brew feels like silk in my mouth .

the nose smelled like sn bigfoot and for those who dont know that means big hops . it smelled so good my mouth watered and i couldnt wait to get a taste . as it warmed the aroma was just stuck in my chimay glass giving me a great blast of hops on every sip . this is a solid dipa .  m - very easy drinking . excellent carbonation .

the best part of this beer is the aroma , it 's a pale yellow in color although i did only pour out a small amount for color review and drank it from the can as intended with this brew . i found the taste bland and for a beer hyped on watermelon with watermelon juice added the sweetness is non-existent .  excellant mouthfeel once again .

lightyellow liquer with an enormous good head . smell exceptional of banana , wheat , coriander and citrus . the smell is allot better than the taste . allthough a nice beer and i for sure think this one is better on a warm sommerday outside than inside a rainy october day .  m- very smooth , silky and full . nice higher carbonation towards the finish .

the smell is very interesting and unique . notes of raspberry , strawberry , caramel , clove , spice , and a huge hit of alcohol heat . as it warms it is getting much better . it is like a beer wine hybrid , very unique .  lovely mouthfeel

smell is a mixture of orange and pineapple juice . also reminds me of fruit coctail .  on the middle palate , this beer really shows off how big it is , coating my whole mouth while chocolate notes come through . as mentioned , this is a big oily coating beer with lighter carbonation .

s - nice roasted malt aroma with a hint of sweetness at the end .  overall , the flavor is very mild , for a craft beer in general and a barleywine in particular , and i 'll admit that 's not normally a plus for me , but i love the rich , creamy mouthfeel and the boozy finish .

it 's pale compared to what i expected , but is similar to other belgian pale ales . the aroma is fantastic ! very spicy and fruity , with distinct apple and citrus aromas dominating . this one is quite easy to drink , while still having a very distinctive hop character and a fantastic aroma !  the body is huge and luxurious with a silky , creamy mouthfeel and oil , mouth-coating texture . very rich and decadent .

smell : the fruitiest hops i 've ever smelled . smells like summer fruit : peaches , pineapples , berries . no wheat malt to speak of which makes me sad , hence the 4.5 .  palate is extremely creamy body , soft ripe fruit & cheese , tart apples , light hops , and again just very creamy & smooth .
smell is superb , unlike the other from yesterday .  nice mouthfeel and great body to it along with quite a flavor punch to your taste buds .

22oz bottle poured into my half acre pint glass ... pours an incredibly thick and hazy pale orange with just a one finger light tan head that leaves a bit of lacing behind ... smells wonderfully of sweet and juicy tropical fruit , pineapple and mango come to mind . juicy , i know juicy is not a smell , but it just smells , well , juicy ... tastes as the smell led on , juicy and fruity , tropical and sweet up front . sticky and resinous finish , very good ... would love if this one was canned along side the regular daisy cutter ...  i feel this beer really shines in its feel . it 's highly carbonated , but still feels rich and syrupy .
almost black with brown edges . the pale brown foam is rich and sticky .  one of the fullest bodied beers i have ever had . very creamy and delicious .

appearance is perfect and aroma is very good , but somehow its more watery than i remember .  anxiously i lift the glass and pour into my mouth , very smooth , very think and velvety . i taste roasted chocolate , i taste sugar , i taste lots of alcohol , and some hairspray ? ? best winter beer out there best stout i 've had so far .
amber color with definite orange highlights . nice frothy white head .  first sip reveals a silky smooth beer with fine slightly tingly carbonation .
aroma was excellent . hops .  the mouthfeel is full and thick with an exciting combination of carbonation that gives this a superb texture .
a - black , looks like coffee . leaves fluffy rings of lacing .  m - creamy and thick . this one is as smooth as velvet the whole way through the bottle .

smell is very good and complex . roasted malts and coffee , and you can smell berries as well . really interesting . tastes like rosated malts with really nice berries flavor with coffe and caramel on the back .  m - right up there with the best i 've sampled in this regard , rich/thick/velvety beer . chewy and smooth .
very nice . very disapointing after the wonderful smell . m : medium bodied and overly carbonated .  m -- extremely smooth ; excellent balance of thick and thin .

date listed on cork : december 2007 served in a pilsner glass pours a dark crimson red color . fluffy head forms on top with little holes throughout . the head sustains and leaves major trails and patterns of sticky lacings all over the glassware .  the mouthfeel is the crown jewel of this beer . light with just a hint of carbonation . simply marvelous .

very nice . t : unfortunately , the taste does n't quite live up to the high expectations brought on by the wonderful aroma . vanilla bean up front with a hint of caramel malt in the background .  beautiful mouthfeel , thick , smooth , velvety , love it .

a : golden , almost orange beer , with a touch of red ; almost the color of apple juice ; very clear and clean , as if looking at the world through orange-tinted glasses ; light carbonation , with bubbles floating to the top periodically ; head pours a white , frothy , .5 finger thickness that quickly dissipates ; soapy lacing minimal , but there s : pleasant , gentle bouquet of fresh , light , citrusy hops ; when i say fresh , i mean same nose feel as when catching a whiff of a dryer sheet for laundry ; really good t : a bit more flavor strength than the smell indicated , but not in a bad way ; the hops are definitely there , bringing crisp , fresh , citrus notes that make me think of summer ; yeast/bread notes ( biscuit ?  it has a creamy full body and excellent drinkability .

damn , things are looking good . lightly sweet pale malt flavor mixes with moderately strong flavor of alcohol .  m : creamy with a very smooth carbonation , tiny bubbles . and what a beautiful body .

s : smoke , bacony , liquorice , sweet malt , burnt red meat . m : a battle between viscous and dry , odd , but interesting . o : overall , it took me the whole bottle and a bunch of input from tasting friends to really try to understand what this beer is .  mouthfeel- super velvety smooth ! drinkability- the mouthfeel alone make this brew worth trying .

very nice lacing s - smells delicious , citrus hops , with a malty sweetness . very inviting t - bitter piney hops , with some sweet citrus , but the bitter hops dominate and linger m - cool and somewhat creamy , well carbonated . i am drinking this on a 99 degree day , so it is very refreshing o - overall , for a pale ale , quite bitter and quite powerful at 6.2 %  m : great mouthfeel , carbonation is flawless . i 'm floored by how good this feels .

nose is lovely , it really has those big oaky , slightly vinous notes of the best american oak-aged examples , with some slightly smoke-tinged notes and dark grain . it 's really , really , nice , and wonderfully complex . lovely .  m : the best mouthfeel in any beer i have ever had . so smooth and with a perfect body .
really impressive . t : definitely not balanced , but i was n't expecting that .  super smooth mouthfeel , awesome , carbonation is light but tingly and perfect for the beer , just right .
the aroma is instant and strong . wow , for a dubel , this one smells so complex . raisons and sugars ... a little booze ... just to name a few .  lovely inviting texture with perfect carb .
pours nearly black , rocky and frothy head with much lacing .  perfect balance and the mouthfeel is amazing . i want to chug it at times .

appearance- pours a hazy dark reddish brown with a beautiful one finger super creamy off-white head . a perfect half finger cap and collar remain the entire beer along with thick sheets of coated lacing .  amazing mouthfeel and good smell but the flavor falls the test of complexity .
simply lovely . clean pour , good carbonation , light foamy top .  amazing mouthfeel - smooth as silk with medium-full body and seamless carbonation .
smells of ripe melon like cantelope , or perhaps midori liquor , also a whiff of straight up booze ( yeah gf !  thick , silky , smooth ... coats the mouth .

smell- what a great smell . alcohol , plenty of esters , traces of red wine and citrus fruit . taste- almost as great as the smell . lots of malt , doughy , but mostly fruity .  me likey this dubbel very much ! full , smooth , mild-mannered , and malty body texture . appropriately low in hops , alcohol causes some warming -- yet it blends in well with the flavor .
a - jet black , opaque , and a creamy , tan head .  mouthfeel is outstanding : creamy with a volume-adding carbonation , medium-bodied .
very nice looking lager .  first sip reveals a smooth silky body and mild carbonation that is almost non-existant .

smell - incredibly strong chocolate smell with fruity notes , both fresh summer fruits and raisins . malt , too , a little , but wow , that 's a lot of chocolate ! i 'll drink it , but i could go on sniffing this beer all evening and still be happy . taste - jesus , that 's a lot of chocolate ! there is black malt roastiness in the finish , and some alcohol .  smooth , creamy mouthfeel that roles over the tongue with ease .

smell : pale and caramel malts are detected up front , but easily the most prominent smell is an incredible dankness . sweet , perfume-like grassiness and florals . extremely nice . smell is world class , and the rest of the beer is very good .  the mouthfeel gets a 5 ... it is so creamy and smooth in the mouth with incredibly soft perfect carbonation .

the deep roasted espresso notes are first and foremost , it 's a very clean , not over-roasted or acrid coffee scent . this is one of the better smelling beers i have had the pleasure of sticking my nose in . the taste is not quite as excellent as the smell , but it 's still good . the roasted coffee flavor is the strongest , and it is balanced by the dark chocolate , vanilla and a slight hint of alcohol sweetness .  m - chewy and delicious . moderate carbonation .

it smells like a funky cherry . i actually really like it . barnyard funk , acidic sourness , and cherries really kind of fight for attention like children wanting allowance . the frist thing i notice is how it feels on my tongue and mouth . the cherries are more tart than michigan cherries , but sweeter than traditional belgian kriek cherries .  a very nice mouthfeel rounds things out . just the right amount of carbonation adds to the pleasing sensation .
nose is absolutely delicious with strong tones of vanilla bourbon , coconut , leather and carmalized malts .  love the feel to this brew .

s - pine trees , juniper , mango , mandarin orange , wafting alcohol , resinous malt , fresh bread , pineapple , apple cider t - intense meaty pine with some tropical fruit essence . some kind of candy , like nerds or sweets tarts , maybe pixie stix . surprisingly mellow with a good bitter that does n't overpower . sweet middle where the malts really shine , and then a good balanced finish for a beer with such high alcohol . the bitter is minimal but still has a good character . o - a really good dipa , quite fruity and satisfying but still with a citric hop character .  the finish is huge and takes forever , the huge body coating the whole mouth with the perfect amount of carbonation .

smell : was terrific on this . one of the best smelling beers i 've had in awhile , smelled like fresh baked bread , with a whiff of fruity esters .  mf : good carbonation , full body , viscous , sticky and chewy with hints of alcohol . near perfect .

the smell is juicy and clovey , spot fuckin on for a hefeweizen . it goes down nicely and is drinkable .  mouthfeel is velvety and cream at the same time . medium weight and somewhat thick the microfine carbonation breaks it up into a quenching and warming brew for a cold and damp night .
nicely balanced . taste is lightly sweet , dry finish .  mouthfeel - perfect consistency , it had lager-level lightness of body without being watery ; a definite pleasure to roll around in my mouth .
flavor is a bit of a letdown after the excellent aroma . it 's just not quite as robust and well-rounded .  sits in the mouth well extremely creamy porter that was very enjoyable .

nice viscosity to this , some lacing , zero head retention s : pears , white grape juice , & juicy fruit gum t : follows the nose up front . more of the same as this warms along with dryness , green banana & lemony hops , slight woodyness , ( maybe the sour wood honey ? ? ) butterscotch/honey notes as this warms , along with some booze warmth .  m : smooth and pleasant , creamy but not thick . just great . d : goes down easily .
3.0 t : the taste is a lot like the nose , only weaker . 3.5 d : the smell is great , but everything else is just alright .  mouthfeel is pure silk with just enough carbonation to prick the tongue .

smell : sweet , fruity , and zesty lemon dominate the aroma . yeasty funk and malted wheat make a strong undertone . taste : matched fairly well to the aroma . starts fruity with some funk and zesty wheat in the middle .  mouthfeel : creamy , and perfectly carbonated .

the nose is very potent . heady-sweet malt ( carmel and brown sugar ) one of the more aromatic stouts i 've had . starts sweet and roasty finishing bitter and a bit `` earthy '' from the hop effect . the enjoyable and sustained excellence of the look , aroma , taste and feel makes this one of my favorite big stouts .  mouthfeel : thick , creamy , and smooth . almost like drinking a smoothie . drinkability : an exceptional stout .
smell : nice belgium aroma here .  m - slick and viscous , with a rich , full body . very nice .

poured into a pint glass from a 12 oz bottle a- as i pour the deep amber beer the fizzy head fills 1/2 of the glass . the beer is crystal clear with an average amount of bubbles rising throughout .  it finishes with a grassy hops note that stands up to the big malts and adds a wonderful balance .

pours out a nice black with a one finger tan head , ,looks creamy.smells just ok , a licorice smell { im not big on licorice } .wow bitter taste as i first sip.has a smoky taste , light on the licorice , bitter lasting taste.has a nice mouthfeel not too thick , not too thin.just an ok beer , no freshness date so i dont know how old this is.i had high hopes for this beer and was let down .  the namesake for this porter is very fitting , perfect actually .
nice lacing left as it settles makes for a great looking beer .  mouthfeel is top notch - full on the palate , but finishes extremely clean .
very enjoyable scent . peanut butter with roasted malt and very light hops .  mouthfeel is nice and thick , and perfectly carbonated for what it is .

( 4 ) ( 4.5 ) d - very good beer that has great refreshing flavors and aromas that stand on their own merit and make a great american ipa .  the body is full . the fullest , most oiled up voluptuous body you can imagine . very light carbonation .

s : the smell is great and the best part of this ale . complex malt , cherries , light mushroom , and spice . t : this certainly a young version at this time and the flavours have n't completely integrated . d : this is a good base to start with as i can see notes of great flavour .  this makes the second founder 's beer i 've found with this creamy mouthfeel .
smell : sweet cranberries , caramelized sugar , molasses , rum , toasted bread and a ton of solvent-like booze .  moderately carbonated , slightly sticky . there is a great warming feel to this .
smell is good - booze , vanilla , oak , and nuttiness . the taste and smell were outstanding , but the appearance and mouthfeel were pretty poor .  m - full bodied and creamy texture on the palate .

wow , very great smell to this one . i get a nice port scent blended in there too . awesome ! t : i get a heavy vodka taste upfront quickly followed by some watery caramel malt . the smell was perfect , taste not so much .  t- super balanced across the board . m- very balanced . d- delicious .
the aroma is fantastic . real belgian fruity spicy yeasty aromas typical of saisons .  m - this is what i want . incredibly thick and full bodied . just an amazing velvet feeling beer .

s : pacific northwest citrous & pine . t : bittersweet . surprisingly , the bitterness even covers the potency of this brew !  just enough acidity . incredibly soft malt base , rediculously soft carbonation .

a : brown/burgundy with no head whatsoever s : figs , raisins , alcohol , molasses , brandy butterscotch t/m : i 'm not going to belabor the point , but the mouthfeel suffes significantly from the fact that there is zero carbonation .  the mouthfeel is very full and creamy , which i appreciate .

very nice taste : rather sweet for an apa . just does n't live up to the wonderful aroma . mouthfeel : medium-full body , dry texture , moderate carbonation .  little carbonation . this is excellent .

beautifully kindles to reveal anise , licorice , molasses , toffee , cocoa . i keep grabbing my glass to take another whiff of this one . d : very drinkable . this is fresh , i think ( no bottle date ) .  the mouthfeel is phenomenal , with high carbonation and light to medium body relative to its strength .

the smell is extraordinary - something like pecan pie . compared to the superb nose , the taste is a bit of a downer - flat and a bit thin ( i have never used such words to describe a rogue beer before ) . there is a nice malty finish , but it just falls short of the best examples of this style .  wonderful body and drinkability , both due to the cask pour .

this is a beautiful looking stout , a non aggressive pour yields a huge 5 finger light brown head with serious lacing .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it has just the right amount of sourness to bitterness ratio to balance it out .

appearance- pours a super thick and robust three finger head into a tulip glass . color is a port like , dep ruby with copper highlights . good lacing and even better retention of the head to a thick film .  m : fantastically smooth .
smells of butterscotch and over ripe peaches . also that classic belgian yeast .  mouthfeel is so creamy and smooth with just the right amount of carbonation .

s : under a decent amount of bourbon and barrel , molasses and toffee ... i get a faint but distinct aroma of my grandmas and mothers christmas cookies . bizarre . d : after the aroma i was expecting great things , and i 've rarely been let down by kuhnhenn ... but things just did n't quite add up .  thick and creamy , really a great feel that i was n't expecting with the hop bite of this cascadian .

a beautiful bottle that absolutely reeks of class . pours a cloudy golden with lots of visible sediment . active head hangs around really well and leaves plenty of soapy lacing has a cask-ish look to it .  the mouthfeel is wonderfully smooth enhancing the overall experience .

smell is amazing ! classic deschutes hop nose - citric , soft and flowery . roasted , melty chocolate malts add a nice balance .  mf : very smooth with rich flavors and a creamy texture . medium carbonation .

reveals a frothy white head that was at least two fingers width thick . great lacing that just caked the sides of the glass with a degree of foaminess . beautiful .  full bodied and pretty sweet which really smooths everything out .
a pretty tasty looking beer .  m-thick and chewy . just lovely . d-one more please !

a nice brown sugar head formed on top and did not run away . there is a great looking skeleton on the label .  m-extremely full bodied , thick and chewy , syrupy and coats the mouth , moderate carbonation , rather crisp finish and even slightly dry . one of the biggest bodies i 've had in any kind of ipa .

appearance and smell are both top notch . pine needles and malt sweetness glide along with an alcohol smell , that is apparent , but not unpleasant .  on the palate the body is simply creamy & full , with enough zippy carbonation to keep it interesting . finish is creamy soft and rather sweet .

smell is very light and fruity : cherries , cranberries , a touch of vanilla , and some a touch of spice . smells a bit like christmas . taste is bright and sweet in the mouth , with a touch of bitterness and alcohol on the swallow .  excellent mouthfeel from this bottle-conditioned brew .

like most corked beers , this one comes out highly carbonated , so watch when you open it . smells very strongly of citrus . lots of citrus , with at least a few different kinds contained .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , creamy and pleasant on the tongue , lips and cheek .
a clear golden color with a huge fluffy white head that lasted quite a while .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with a brilliantly smooth texture and a clean finish .
smell is knockout good , & the taste is bright hops with a great balance of malt in the backbone , but not so much that it kicks the hops in the chops .  the mouthfeel is amazingly thick .

s - a very aromatic nose of lemon zest , bubblegum , and sweet malt with a huge floral profile . coriander , rosemary , pepper , chamomile , and flowers are all present . fantastic nose . t - there 's quite a lot of complex flavors in here , and many carry over from the nose . the floral aspect is again rather strong , with chamomile and rosemary leading the way , and pepper and some cinnamon providing a nice , spicy counterpoint . very crisp and refreshing beer . o - really a fantastic brew , one of the most well-crafted saisons i 've ever had the pleasure to try . easily on par with the belgian masters .  the mouthfeel on this beer is what really impressed me .

the aroma is the strong point of this beer . it combines essences of a fine liqueur with that of yeast and fruit .  m : homerun . double-cream indeed ! thick foamy effervescence that when swished around leaves a wonderful long-lingering , slightly bitter `` roasted '' aftertaste .

the aroma was quite stunning , sweet maple blasts the nose with salty bacon on the back , its a bit smokey which i like as well . it smells like breakfast and seriously smells incredible . the flavor though , is interesting , salty bacon , smokey and salty , its weird having a beverage thats so salty .  m - creamy and luxurious . the bite is done through alcohol rather than carbonation .
tan head with some lacing . s- chocolate .  this is definitely an exceptional mouthfeel for an ris .

'' pours with a viscous used motor oil hue with nary a light splinter finding a way through topped with a frothy sudsy beige cap that takes its good ole time settling down .  a great silky , creamy moutfeel . excellent .

aroma-big , big , big notes of coffee and darkly roasted malt waft over the palette leaving no mistake as to the character of the beer .  the mouthfeel is wonderful - smooth and silky , bordering on syrupy .

great nose ... sugar sweet citrus fruit ... grapefruit coated with sugar ... oranges ... outstanding ... .pours a light brown color ... the head is weak and the mouthfeel is a little light in the shorts too ... great taste though ... .great balance between the hops and the sugary sweet maltiness ... very low carbonation ... .nice tight bitterness on the long finish ... i guess i 'd compare this in some regards to old ho but not quite as good ... different hops too i 'm pretty sure ... i like the hop flavor of this one better but the malt load is not comparable to old ho ... this is more sugary sweet than caramely sweet ... great hop burps ... .  great mouthfeel in particular .

s-really aromatic citrus hops ( orange , and tangerine ) with the slightest hint of caramel malt .  creamy mouthfeel , very interesting , with a perfect amount of carbonation and feeling not unlike a fudge bar that melts in the mouth .

a blast of malt and hops laced with notes of caramel and fruit assaults the olfactory initially . hints of freshly mown hay weave their way through the citrus complex midway but fail to dethrone the resurgent malt and resiney hops . with such a powerful aroma profile , one would expect the flavours and mouthfeel to present an equally potent response , but this is not the case .  has a bit of a sweet aftertaste m : smooth like silk , not sticky or heavy , really nice d : could drink this all night due to the bitter bite in the beginning followed by a sweeter smooth mouthfeel overall : it was a great beer that my roommate picked up as a random pick .

aromas of pungent fruits like apples , pears , green bananas dominate while a softer herbal ester and citric astringent drift between whiffs . big yeasty , bread taste , fermented pear , lightly roasted barley , wheat , and raw sugar sweetness that takes shape as it develops . a little ways down notes of unripe green banana , and fermented oranges , and vinous notes become more apparent .  mouthfeel is rich and creamy . the aftertaste is extremely clean ; not sticky , dry or anything bad .

aroma is very nice . incredibly yeasty , backed by a whirlwind of spices . i love it .  m : perfect , silky smooth , very light carbonation gives a great feel on the tongue , viscous and full-bodied , oily .
pours amber with a large , lasting , creamy white head and lovely lacing .  m : perfect . medium , creamy carbonation on a medium/full body .

s : wow , you can really smell the bourbon in this one . also smells of oak , molassas and even some dark fruit in there such as raisin . t : mostly malty and nutty .  beautiful . d : great in so many ways , but just a little too hot on the finish to be truly drinkable .

wow , thats a shit load of cinnamon and nutmeg in the nose along with pumpkin spice , brown sugar , and booze . i currently have a homebrew pumpkin that smells nearly exact to this ! this , along with good gourd from ccb are probably the best pumpkin beers i have had to date .  on the first sip , the first thing noticed is the smooth , creamy texture . nice body on this one .

12oz bottle to pint glass a : hazy amber s : surprisingly strong and enticing aroma of piney hops . one of the strongest aromas i 've smelled in a while , but in a pleasant way . t : because of the really good aroma and the fact that this is an ipa , the taste was disappointing at first . o : frankly , this beer surprises me as an ipa .  the mouthfeel has an almost perfect extra virgin olive oil and buttery finish to it .

it 'd be nicer if it was a hint of whiskey rather than dominated by the whiskey . its pretty overwhelming . i think a bit of age will make this great though . m- really awesome . little playful carbonation hitting the tongue and introducing new flavors .  m - full bodied . almost a syrupy feel to it . it 's rich , creamy , and my favorite aspect of this beer .

a : straight orange color with an off white head s : sweet smell with fresh pumpkin in there , pumpkin pie spice t : taste is not as sweet as the smell but still on the slight sweet side getting the pumpkin pie spice in there m : medium carbonation with med mouth feel d : every time you take a sip you wan na take another , right away !  mouthfeel reminded me of monk 's cafe on steroids , pretty full and seems to swell and invade every corner of the mouth .

pours a deep brown with ruby highlights thru out almost no head to speak of here , great aroma of cocoa , smoke , and dark roasted coffee very rich and appetizing.taste does not live up to the aroma though somewhat watery but there some smokey flavors and some bitter chocolate.like i said the beer seemed a little to watery thinbut there are some good characteristics for a quality brew going on .  almost limited carbonation lends to the slick feel .

i poured into two large goblets to make the process move faster . regardless . watching the large thick beautiful head recede as it leaves lacing on the glass each time is a real treat . color is a bright golden color , as a bottle conditioned beer there is some yeast particles at the end of the pour . depending on your preference , your beer could end up quite hazey .  perfect to style .
smells wonderfully malty ( sugar daddy ) .  thick chewy mouthfeel with fine carbonation .

head falls pretty quick with some decent lace left behind . aroma is nice fruity malts lightly sweet hints of sour notes . tons of fruits jump out mango , pineapple , banana and cherries that seem lightly sour all mingled in with raisin bread like malt . lord cant put the glass down smell is wonderful they need this flavor in a candle . taste is so different from the nose sadly , lightly toasted caramel malts mingled with chilies that were n't in the nose . overall eh almost buy this one just to sniff it , and where are the chilies in the nose mingled with the spice ?  full in body , w/ a sugary , slightly syrupy viscous mouthfeel that is appropriate considering the high strength and richness .
s- strong citrus aroma to the point where i 'm thinking about skittles candies .  mouthfeel is excellent .

you 'd have to be sitting here smelling this beer to appreciate how impossibly amazing this is . wow , wow , wow . if nugget nectar is the be-all-end-all hop lover 's aroma , then this is the malt lover 's dream nose . taste- malty with a nice , mildly tart underlying character ... it 's rich in flavor without the excessive weight in the mouth . delicious . mouthfeel/drinkability- this beer goes into the mouth without much fanfare , then crackles at the first swish ... it 's lively and crisp without being too aggressive .  rich , smooth , quite full and very fulfillingly bold and rounded with a big tang of roasty , chocolatey , smoked meat tangyness all soaked together in a stew of boldness that seems to last stretch forever on the palate .

s-5.0 : smells sooo delicious . chocolate , molasses , salt , cookies , figs , oatmeal , and some perfectly muted hops .  exceptional mouthfeel , but the high alcohol is too present in the taste to make this an easy-drinking beer .

huuuge milk chocolate drenched in butter , vanilla beans saturated in liquid sugar , buttery pecan , caramel , light roasted malts and a hint of alchohol . big dose of vanilla , buttery milk chocolate , caramel , dry roasted malts , and a nice kick of alcohol , which succeeds in making the sweetness a bit less pronounced . overall , this by far the sweetest beer i 've had to date . it is the epitome of a dessert beer , and i could n't imagine this being drunk on any other occasion .  superb mouth feel , a full sensory experience . the after taste is delicious , tongue coating , coffee , full bodied .
very appealing . first sip reveals , average body with very mild carbonation .  an ris with the perfect looks and sexy mouthfeel .
nose is sweet fruits and alcohol , with something heavier but hard to identify coming through . so far so good .  the first sip reveals a silky smooth texture with gentle rolling carbonation .

s - amazing smell . extremely bready and spicy . t - this is bready and pleasant but its actually so overly spiced that it somewhat wears its welcome by the end of the swallow .  big and thick mouthfeel .

[ smell ] : smells delightful of hops and honey , both very strong . [ foretaste ] : strong yet sweet hops , very floral . [ aftertaste ] : nothing but honey and sugar very nice aftertaste indeed .  the body is perhaps the best part of this beer . feels full bodied with a nice smooth , soft texture . perfect . some truely remarkable parts to this beer .

the aroma is excellent . huge vinous pinot noir notes , blackberries , lactic tartness and funk , and considerable oakiness from the -bals .  feel ( 5/5 ) very effervescent on the tip of the tongue in the initial taste ( almost reminiscent of the more carbonated belgian ales , like duvel in this respect ) . this transitions to a wonderful fullness as it washes to the back of the mouth .

s : dark roasted malt , caramel , toffee , hazelnuts and chestnuts .  m : great mouthfeel . strong , medium/full-bodied , one of the best structured beers in the mouth i 've come across . the lower drinkability score is only due to the fact of the size and full mouthfeel , it was quite enjoyable to drink over a half and hour .
a-pours a dark drown with a one finger foam head . the beer leaves behind a perfect lacing .  m - the feel is extremely smooth . i am very impressed by the silk feel of this brew .

the aroma had nice floral notes along with citrus , undoubtedly from hops , and had a spicy , overall herbal character that was delightful - very nice hop nose !  perfect amount of carbonation , just enough .
appearance - dark copper smell - opening the can and pouring release a huge burst of citrus hop . taste - lots of hop complexity .  m : awesome mouthfeel , thanks to the cask conditioning .

the aroma was outrageously bourbony yet smooth and mellow . sweet , rich , malty and boozy with strong notes of brown sugar and oak . very complex overall . malty and roasty up front with strong indications of brown sugar . at 12 % abv , this beer was quite drinkable .  smooth carbonation slides it over the tongue d- very drinkable but the somewhat thick mouthfeel keeps it from being chuggable
this beer smells tremendous ! there 's a lot of raisin going on with lots of caramel too .  mouthfeel : smooth and kinda creamy . quite complex with pleasant fruitiness and great feel in the mouth .

smells delicious ; smells of pumpkin pie and has a nice spicy earthy hop aroma mixed in to the overall aroma . flavors of pumpkin , nutmeg and caramel slowly melt into a delicious concoction . it sits around 9 % but drinks very , very smooth . nice seasonal !  m : thick , viscous and chewy ; one of the creamiest mouthfeels i 've ever encountered . yes .

that should n't take away from the dreat hop taste and smell that this beer has . nice cascade aroma to say the least . the look is good , not great , not too much lacing at all .  m : thick and almost meaty , nearly chewable .

wonderfully fruity nose . heavy malt-fruit flavors that could use a little more hop balance .  the mouthfeel on this beer is excellent , with a perfect crispness that accentuates the bitterness of the hopping .

the tropical hop aroma is off the charts . just a fantastic aroma . taste is n't bad either . tarter grapefruit notes are next before a tongue tingling resiny pine hops finish this one off nicely . just a fantastic dipa with a top notch , juicy and mouth watering hop profile .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , wonderfully creamy and velvety . overall impression : excellent imperial stout .
s - nice burnt roasty malt with hints of chocolate .  smooth creamy mouthfeel and very drinkable , especially at 5 % .
the smell is still fantastic , but the flavor profile came across as watery .  my favorite aspect of this beer was it 's creamy smooth mouthfeel .

s : smells incredible . very similar nose to a fresh bottle of pliny the elder or pliny on draft . d : so much intensity makes it very hard to finish the bomber .  it 's not too heavy , nor syrupy , just perfect with an appropriate amount of carbonation .

s : spice ! ! ! super hops and a hint of warm malt in there . someone poured pine resin and kind bud hash in my fresh squeezed orange juice and said , `` here : smell ! super grapefruit peel and orange zest flavors that end really bitter and believe or not really good . d : it is awfully strong but i think three of these over cards of ultra spicy snacks is called for .  the spices sit on the tongue and create a festive atmosphere in the mouth .

aroma is deep , caramel and honey malt sweetness . moderate spice and light floral notes .  drinkability and overall : the only thing that makes this any more drinkable than the average beer is that incredible mouthfeel .

smell is distinctively of sweet caramel , red apple , fresh yeast , sweet grape , and banana . rich smell before and after sips . the taste very nearly lives up to said smell , though not completely .  m - exceptional . really no other way to describe this .

the smell is incredible , almost overpowering .  smell - bittery and hop-ish taste - the bitter taste of irish stouts , very well done , but much better from tap mouthfeel - exceptional is perfect . it 's creamy and amazingly smooth .

very bold piney , citrus hop aroma . grapefruit , tangerine , and other citrus flavors dominate with floral and pine , but malt backdrop a bit on the sweet side . nice west coast style overhopped ipa much more complex and fruitier than hop stoopid .  m : very good balance of carbonation and stickiness . perfect !

victory old horizontal appearance : rose amber with a light light tan head smell : syrupy hop with a floral aroma -- very syrupy boysenberry smell -- berry but not , like some kind of undetermined willy wonka type fruit -- unique fruit .  m : just about perfect in my book .

the smell is the best part of this beer with sweet/burnt sugar and coffee overtones that are so appealing . the taste was more of the same , however for a beer that is less than 6 % , i found it a bit harsh on the palate .  mouthfeel is just phenomenal , as this one has a smoothness all its own to go with a creamy , thick texture of oil .

very fragrant . lots of spice - cardamon , corriander . not overly bad , it was just a let down after the wonderful aroma . mouthfeel : very light .  m - the feel is full and rich like an amazing glass of red wine . this has such a rich velvety texture ; amazing .

smell ... did someone just mow the lawn ! needs more malt but it 's still very pleasant . i wish there was some more after swallow flavors as well but the hops are crazy up front .  perfect . absolutely perfect .

i 'm impressed . taste = good malt flavor , a little bland in other departments .  m-on the low side of medium carb the beer is very full and creamy with no detectable oiliness . the texture is possibly the best i have had in an ipa , and although not bitter enough to satisfy true hop heads , the flavor is very interesting and pleasant , and the aroma complex .
the color is incredible . has a reddish tint when held up to the light , but the brown color is soft and full .  nice light-medium body with great carbonation . outstanding mouth on this one .

s- great hoppy overtones balancing the floral characteristics with the citrus very evenly . t- no malt presence at all , this was a very bitter , dry beer , a bit too much so . i also picked up a bit of a funky , skunky almost seaweed like taste . disappointed .  the mouthfeel was ultra creamy , frothy and smooth . the beer felt like a blanket on my tongue .
a : served a burnt dark amber with a thick long lasting film that left great lacing .  it has a perfect amount of carbonation and crispness .
enjoyable aroma and taste .  medium-ish body .

real great smelling porter . this smells real good . boy i was hoping this would knock my socks off from what i smelled but it unfortunately does n't .  first sip reveals a thick syrupy body with very fine tingling carbonation . i actually ponder how this would taste with pancakes .

the smell is the highlight , no doubt , with ample fruits and cream bouncing off the head . some smelly hops as well in there .  this has a nice , smooth mouthfeel , and the foam leaves a good lacing around the glass .

mmmearthy smell ( nice to have something a little bit different ) . very earthy flavora bit too much for me , kind of sour , but bitter at the same time so it is kind of weird .  very nice . mouthfeel this beer has a subtle carbonation and a good thick consistency . its strong which makes it a sipper but its wonderful to taste .

smell : blueberries dominate the nose of this beer . a sugary sweet blueberry aroma accompanied by hints of pastries . a subtle mellowness of malt is detectable , and no hop presence at all .  mouthfeel-medium bodied , medium carbonation . extremely creamy , feels like a root beer float in the mouth . i could drink this for desert .

wonderful smelling , incredibly drinkable , delicious ipa . one of my favorites .  mouth is also as good as it gets for heavy stouts . also with very crisp carbonation . its quite amazing in flavor and mouthfeel , but as far as `` drinkability '' is concerned , its very boozey and powerful .

dark cherries , cherry bubble gum , scotch , dry dark baking chocolate , and vanilla . t- very very long finish of malt chocolate , cherries , and vanilla . very smooth . m- low carbonation that makes me wish it had just a touch more to help build the body .  as it comes up to room temp it really starts to get interesting , the hops appear a bit more at the front , the bitterness is nice , deep rich chocolate is rich and full . m- very mild carbonation , delivers nicely , smooth , good creaminess .

best smelling chocolate beer i have ever sniffed . t : the chocolate taste is n't overwhelming , apart from the belgian abbey character , chocolate is the only thing that comes through -- which is a good thing . overall i like it a lot , it is n't the best abbey beer i 've ever had , but it is the best chocolate beer i 've ever had .  m - heavy body and flavor with moderate carbonation . slick , velvety , feel with a good bit of dark roast lingering through the finish .
aroma is off-the-charts incredible , consisting of extremely fresh heavily-roasted coffee beans .  m - great body for a porter but what impresses me is how active this thing is on the palate .
hops play a part up front , too , making the smell interesting . very warm and inviting smell . bread and spice .  mouthfeel : one of the best textured beers i 've ever had .

s : brown sugar/candi sugar , molasses , raisins , dark fruit . t : molasses cookies upfront , with soy sauce , dark candi sugar , fig , prune , date , smoke , and a spirituous amount of alcohol , reminds me a bit of sam adams triple bock , which i liked .  mouthfeel : this is one of the best feels i have gotten from an ipa . unbelievably creamy , with a light level of carbonation .

one of the better american fruit beers on the market . strong blueberry aroma that can fill a room when poured into a pint glass .  great hops character and aroma , beautiful amber color and a great mouthfeel .

pours almost jet black , with crystal clear dark brown at the edges , forms a nice meringue like 1/8 '' head of very fine dark tan bubbles .  the mouthfeel is marvelous , again especially for a bottle . full body , silky texture , very low carbonation .

the aroma is fantastic . unique and one of a kind , the bouquet on this brew is phenomenal . the phenolic character is a little too much for my taste and i 've had a lot of saisons that were a lot cleaner ( saison dupont , hennepin and something from two brothers off the top of my head ) .  this brew is full bodied and creamy smooth .

12 oz stubby brown bottle , great label to an imperial pint bottled on february 4 2010 a : a standard pour showed lots of carbonation and resulted in a 3.5 finger cream colored head that left beautiful ring lace down the glass . the head was retained very well eventually reducing to a frothy cap . color was amber and clear .  the rye comes out mainly as an aftertaste , but that 's ok. mouthfeel : just the perfect amount of carbonation to bring the hop flavors alive on my tongue .

the appearance was very nice , pouring a murky reddish brown , with an off-white head and decent , kinda sticky lacing on my glass .  mouthfeel- silky smooth , even though it was more tart than i usually liked in my beer .
a : nice adrk brown with really thick head .  mouthfeel - smooth and crisp , right on target .

it smelled like a delicious like malt and cherries . this is an amazingly drinkable beer .  m - fuller side of medium body with a nice level of carbonation . incredibly smooth and creamy feel with a nice slickness . the mouthfeel is excellent though .

a - outstanding appearance ; the most lustrous translucent shade of mahogany with garnet hues peaking through , fantastic eggshell head and lace , recording every sip with a encircling strata of lace like the growth rings on a tree .  creamy , delicious , full body and nice .

s- very nice , plenty of coffee and roasted malts , some dark chocolate . nice differentiator is the prevalent sweet dark fruit that is expected from the aroma , currants come to mind . love the price as well , see it for $ 5/bomber locally .  full bodied and syrupy yet amazingly smooth .

this aroma is surprisingy invigorating and fresh smelling . the flavor starts with a mildly sweet malt but is very well-balanced by just a hint of graininess and a subtle piney/leafy hop finish .  mouthfeel was full bodied and silky smooth . a nice amount of carbonation .

nose is deliciously complex and full of dried fruit character . an amazing nose with endless esters and perfumes making themselves known .  the body on this beer was absolutely fantastic . the mouthfeel on this one elevated the rest of the beer for me .
the head is really quite amazing , as it stays for quite awhile before gradually dissolving .  really excellent mouthfeel on this one .

n : fresh and dopey hops , and a bit of malt . the complexities are marvelous . p/m : a bit thinner than what the nose promises . slightly watery .  m - love the feel of this beer . it has excellent balance d - ca n't give it too high of a score here as it is n't very sessionable due to the abv and the bitter factor which is large and in charge for this one .
the second i turned the cap i knew the aroma was a perfect score .  as it warms , the mouthfeel becomes very pleasant and smooth .
pours a nice dark brown with a perfect light brown fluffy head , it looks like crema on a perfect espresso , fantastic .  perfect ipa mouthfeel , crisp , dry , and perfectly carbed up .

my first aroma hit reminds me of winter 's evenings and warm spiced wine ... ca n't say as to why just being poetic . probably because of the nice tea-like floral quality . man , you could bounce around a zillion adjectives but i 'll settle on `` playful '' . quite nice oktoberfest . very german , very balanced , very drinkable .  the carbonation , while lacking in the glass , is perfect on the palate . the mouthful is fantastic .
nice banana smell , some wheat , clove and caramel . smelled great , but taste was marred a bit by a strong boozy finish at times .  mouthfeel - very smooth , zesty carbonation , outstanding .
appearance : dark cherry red with a light tan rocky head . good retention .  though the beer looks a bit on the thin side after pouring , it feels perfect in the mouth .

this smells wonderful ! roasted grains mixed with spicy citrus hops some chocolate , burnt sugar and a touch of alcohol on the edges especially as it warms . i like my imp stouts to be thick and chewy and this one is not that . i think the aroma fools you a bit into thinking this is going to taste differently than it does .  i can tell by the haze and head that this one is gon na have some exceptional mouthfeel due to some protein action . very full bodied .

smells of coffee , caramel , and chocolate being most dominant . mouthfeel is medium to full and is quite complex . as it warms , the coffee and chocolate flavors increase , as well as a nice hop bitterness .  mouthfeel/drinkability- as perfect as perfect could be , the texture in the mouth is simply sublime . the initial microscopic , tongue-prickling carbonation immediately smooths out and becomes a rolling , exquisite foam of effervescence .
i would call it a black ipa . a - very dark .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect punt of carbonation .

heavy malt sweetness , very fruity and deep . taste was big , no , make that huge on malt sweetness , thick and heavy with a very big mouthfeel .  m : medium to full bodied with low to moderate carbonation . o : a solid offering from alesmith here with an outrageously smooth and silky mouthfeel .

smell- an intersting mix of odd juniper bitterness and sweetness with hints of lingonberries . reminds me of a decent gin . mouthfeel- very syrupy .  taste is medium to heavy bodied , great mouthfeel to it .
the nose was pretty impressive . very earthy and grassy .  mouthfeel is thick , smooth , with virtually no carbonation .
aroma is great as it showcases the lemongrass and rye sublimely well . another winner from free state !  perfect for the style .
as opposed to artificial flavoring , i smell a nice , hearty ris .  the mouthfeel is excellent , zesty bubbles , not overly thick , incredibly smooth .
s-smells of chocolate and dark chocolate with some roasted coffee notes .  this amazing and smooth stout is aged in a burbon barrel for a year . it is amazingly smooth , warming you up instantly .

( s ) - nice aroma of raw honey , sweet malts , and a really refreshing flower-ish bouquet . a spice component adds another nice addition to it , which is almost cinnamon-like .  mouthfeel was good , clean and somewhat refreshing to drink ( if apa is your thing ) .

the smell is divine with ample coffee , chocolate , and malt . taste is a little more subdued than the smell but still has all those same things , plus a little tart zing and a pretty long finish .  m : good carbonation , medium body .

s : big time orange peel , leafy hops & biscuitty notes & a touch of honey malt , super nose ! t : initial tastes math the nose , then leafy hops , & breadyness . a bit of dryness , more breadyness & grapefruit as this warms . finishes with nice citrussy hops , leafy hops , & nice biscuitty malt & a whisper of booze soaked tangerines mf : fairly chewy with low carbonation & great balance very easy to drink style & abv-wise , my first from this brewery , nice complexity as well . well done flossmoor !  mouthfeel was creamy and smooth .

what an unbelieveable smell ! ! i can say i have never smelled a beer with this much aroma . it has a tremendous rasberry bouquet , much like a beaujolais nouveau .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with a good creaminess .

spotty lacing left all over the glass . s - very strong tropical hop aroma . hops are certainly the center of this one . pineapple is the primary fruit that comes through in the nose but i alos pick up a little mango and a light candy sweetness . t - candied pineaplle and other assorted tropical notes . very hop forward without being a tongue buckling hop punch .  mouthfeel : refreshing .

appearance of this beer is superior , in my opinion . inviting , jet black , and a fine , thick off-white head on top .  m - slight carbonation , smooth and silky d - i would n't suggest this beer to anyone really , glad i tried it for trying sake but it is not very drinkable .

s - the amount of mead qualities i 'm picking up are impressive : floral , spice , dry and sweet base . d - i really liked the nose on this brew , but in the mouth i was not quite so impressed ... seemed underwhelming , but for a style so rarely done , i love to see it .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel and very smooth .

) intense fresh hop bouquet of apricot , vanilla , and lime juice . i think it needs polish and some special magic to it , but it is nonetheless neat .  creamy , soft medium body and very light , prickly carbonation .

a : pours a straw color with a fluffy white head that lingers s : nice spice notes , a very clean , refreshing pear/green apple fruit aroma , a bubble gum sweetness t : at first , a big blast of sour , which then turns into a refreshing , slightly fruity sweetness , and finishes with an apple skin sort of dry , fruity finish .  full bodied with moderate , fine carbonation .

s - very impressive mix here . lots of roasted coffee beans , hints of chocoalte and a surprisingly big citrus hop nose . very unique smell , even by mikkeller standards .  m & d : very soft in carbonation , light-bodied , but the flavour shows too much impacts of the pear-ish sourness .
amazing dark black color with great head and retnetion .  mouthfeel : light bodied and crisp with moderate carbonation .

the smell includes vibrant apple character that is seemingly candied and sweet smelling .  the body is n't half-bad , a soft , creamy medium with prickly carbonation that matches the cherries , whose tartness grips the sides of the tongue between sips . perhaps these are n't the right cherries for this beer .

particles floating around .  a- hazy golden with minimal head and zero lacing s- astringent citrus with sweet malt t- very quick bitterness but the malt comes in too fast to distinguish any type of hop flavor m- by far the best part of this beer . the high ibu is noticeable on the tongue .
the pour is black with a rich brown head , as usual .  but then the flavor ... ..sweet and roasty at first , enjoyable medium body and carbonation , and then the aftertaste !

this beer is beautiful . the color is damn near black and the mocha head came from nowhere and grew like someting from a b-movie . awesome lacing .  m - medium body , ample carbonation , finishes dry .

color is a light golden straw , solid yellow , hefty tall white head of creamy froth that sits like a mall santa in his red chair the day after thanksgiving . good lacing in layered strings and ink blot patches that stick like glue .  very drying , nice carbonation .
motor oil.. midnight black body , the head looks like chocolate milk .  m : medium and creamy . d : this has a kick-in-the-head hoppiness .
this one pours a nice jet black with a finger of tan head that falls to cover the beer .  mouthfeel is full bodied and thick ; really syrupy , hot with alcohol , chewy , with decent carbonation .

the aroma was a big nose full of of sweet piney resin with a mild earthy note . i 'm really impressed by how clear and rich the smell is , damn . the flavor diverges surprisingly , with a much grassier , citrus rind flavor - likely the belgian element kicking in . like most really good beers , it could still be more complex , but this is a beer worth seeking out .  lively carbonation . mouthfeel is full . finish is clean and smooth .
great appearance , the best aspect of this beer no doubt .  mouthfeel is well carbonated and medium bodied .

beautiful crimson brown color . excellent clarity .  feels raw and boozy , needs more taste and less hootch . mouthfeel - nicely smooth and creamy , leaves a pleasant residual to help fight off that alcohol burn .

smell : strong . chocolate , apricot , raisins , yeast , alcohol , nice dryness hidden among the sweet overtones . good and calling this an `` extreme beer '' is a good thing .  m. the mouthfeel is a nice smooth creamy feel that finishes off with a nice dry feel .
i was intrigued by the complex smell of the grapes mixed with the spices and the faint belgian yeast aroma .  it has a full body , lightly-syrupy-turning lightly-dry texture , and low carbonation .

i was very impressed with the appearance of this beer . beautiful dark amber color . however , the appearance is a not high on my list for why i love a good beer .  mouthfeel is fine , crisp and medium bodied .
great scent - west coast fruity hops and berry , mixed with molasses , raisin , and leather .  mouthfeel is pretty good for the style though .
wow ! great aroma with an awesome balance of sweet and spicy . t : big time wood and earthiness .  body & mouthfeel was nice but the flavor killed it for me .
this is real nice .  m : the body is medium with a lively carbonation and a crisp , lightly bitter finish . this is probably the best part about this beer .

this ale pours a striking walnut brown with a light tan head . the head is full of carbonation and clings to the sides of the glass leaving a nice lace pattern .  taste is watered down and a bit corny but not offensive , mouthfeel is light and crisp .

the beer pours a pitch-black color with garnet high lights , the head preposterous in size , spumescent in texture and a medium tan or light chocolate color if youre so inclined , the lace forms a thick and glutinous sheet to seal off the glass .  the chewy mouthfeel will keep you around to finish the pint you ordered , but i doubt you 'll want another .
just phenomenal . t - the taste is just like the nose . extreme pumpkin beer .  mouthfeel is smooth and moderate-to-thin in body . an amazing first half , with a terrible second half .
s - very complex . citrus , pine , resin . d - very drinkable . it 's a complicated beer but if it 's up your alley you 'll love it .  no complaints , perfect wino beer . tecattteee

salt and coriander are listed as ingredients ( presumably dodging the purity law by calling the product a beer-specialty , rather than a beer ) . distinct spicey nose , with the coriander mixing pleasantly with the citrus of a usual german weizen . the coriander is not overpowering , but is definitely present .  md thick mouthfeel and strong carbonation .
very cool looking .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thicker side with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

the body is a dark ruddy brown with a firm , creamy and quite lasting off white head . very attractive beer . no real stellar pluses either , save the beautiful appearance .  m - good coating with a tingle on the sides.of the tongue and top of mouth .

beautiful floral and fruit scents . you can easily pick up the coriander and wonderful herbs . mouthfeel : the finish can throw you off , but once you get into the beer , you start to drink it down smooth .  m : medium body with nice , full carbonation .
first whiff was of chocolate coffee and alcohol .  mouthfeel it has a nice full body and medium-low carbonation .

batch 4 ... a light honey gold pour , decent carbonation at first but falls quickly with very light lacing ... the aroma is pretty nice , brute lite ; acidic but lightly bready , small oak notes , white wine ( sauvigon blanc ) characteristics ( light grass ) ... the taste is a bit of let down , displays too many of the white wine qualities in taste and feel .  mouthfeel is quite good , low carbonation means it 's super creamy .

this is a beautiful beer . it is a dark cherry red with a thick cream colored head .  i think if you put this brew inside a bud light bottle the ratings would go from a b+ to a d. nice mouthfeel , though .

pours a three finger light tan head that fades very slowly to a thin layer , leaving a good lace . black color , no highlights .  m - thick . oh god , is it thick ! carbonation is surprisingly high . it is a little bit refreshing , but it also leaves a residue in your mouth .

s : huge , complex aromas of licorice , vanilla , smatterings of coffee and an overwhelming bourbon nose . t : also huge and complex . roasted , bittersweet chocolate . the bourbon and alcohol burns as it slides down ever so smoothly . vanilla and caramel add to the already sweet flavors . i feel like i wanted a little more balance to the taste , but still enjoyable . m : consistency of motor oil .  m : silky smooth , low carbonation with a slight alcohol burn .
nose is milk chocolate , chocolate syrup ( i.e .  medium-full body with a smooth low-mid carbonation .

the nose on this brew is amazing . i 've smelled hops before , but int his brew you can taste the hops when you breath through your mouth near the beer !  aroma is grapefruit , thick and gooey bready malt and magic hat buttery yeast . taste is equally alright but nowhere near worthy of the promised hop onslaught . grapefruit and agave hops with hearty malt balance . the real ale feel of this beer is enhanced by prickly hop resin . never has 100 ibus seemed so small .

appearance is awesome , motor oil black . this thing poured black , and very few imperial stouts can boast something like that . no lacing , but with 11 % you can not really complain .  it 's a struggle for me to judge this beer as obviously a lot of craft went into it 's production , and yet i have to acknowledge that it makes me want to vomit . i will qualify all of this by saying that i hate eggs because i can not bare the sulphurous stink that i experience when they are cooked in any form . it get 's easier with each swallow but to me this tastes like someone is pouring a skunky heineken down my throat just after i 've had a swig of a very nice brew .

s= truly and incredible aromatic experience . this ale was truly bursting with aromas of fresh hops , grass , pine , and citrus . t= compared to the smell , quite a disappointment . there was a decent malt base underneath some solid hop bitterness , but there were some unpleasant features as well . overall , the good outweighs the bad on this one , its just not where it ought to be .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with plenty of carbonation .
the aroma is sour , dark cherries along with something like chocolate .  it had a good body , not too thin , with a bit of carbonation .

smell-wow , citrusy with a boatload of hops ( cascade ? ) that jump right up the nose , you can tell from the smell this is no ordinary beer . taste-hop heaven , i was into it , a large amount of hops , a big bang with an edgy flavor , i wonder if it mellows with age but i 'm not sure . in any case , tasty and edgy with the alcohol a late but strong addition .  the mouthfeel is full and creamy . all in all , it just seems like an average barleywine/dipa..

poured in my trusty duvel tulip , and bam a fat head fills the glass . huge and pillowy white on a appropriate duvel like straw golden color . sporadic spongy lacing down the glass .  m : mouthfeel is crisp and carbonated ; refreshing .
amazing lacing .  m - medium-full body , lower carbonation , a slightly grainy texture , with light residual stickiness .

nose is vanilla , chewy/nutty maltiness , and maybe some molasses . overall quite nice - even on a summer afternoon .  mouth : oily and thick . very good . taste : hazelnuts . after a few sips , i got used to it , and it settled down to a good stout but , i could n't get the thought out of my mind , it was suntan lotion . spicy , peppery finish .
aroma is amazing , very hoppy . fruity sweet and rich . taste is awesome and sweet , very hoppy and smooth as well .  feels pretty full .

i think i just sat here and took in all the aromas for 20-25 minutes before i had a drink . this is probably the best smelling barley wine i know of with a citrus grapefruit , pine and floral odors .  medium body with a little astringency for cleanliness . leaves you with a good flavor and a touch of weight on the aftertaste . this is a complex and beguiling brew that every time i think i have it figured out , i am thrown a change-up .

imported from my ratebeer.com profile - jan 3 , 2008 pours a dark , opaque black with a wonderful frothy and creamy head that lasts forever .  mouthfeel is nice , gently prickly and medium-light body .

keep in mind that if there were a fragrance that smelled like hops i would buy it ... i really like this beer ! the hops aroma of this beer was ridiculously overpowering , like sticking your nose in a bag of hops . awesome ! the taste was unbalanced like other raters have said , and could use some more malt to strengthen it overall , but i will totally buy this anytime i need a hop fix .  medium bodied with good carbonation .
huge sticky and rocky tan head , a very impressive sight which makes it even scarier .  light body and easygoing feel when cold .

it poured a nice black that you could barely see through and an amazing head that stuck around .  for such a warm & wintery smelling/tasting beer , the sensation is awfully sharp & has a prickly & active mouthfeel . interesting .
clear ruby iced-tea body , & an inch plus of light tan head , which in turn leaves me plenty of sticky , ugly , soap scum-like lace ( a good omen ) .  mouthfeel is smooth .

very striking black with red highlights and topped by a heavy tan head .  mouthfeel - about right for the style ... the style being a flavored american wheat beer and not a witbier , as listed of course .

weihenstephaner korbinian is a solid , crystal clear , brown-red beer with an oily , bubbly , beige head .  the flavor is very light , watered down even . m : light in body , creamy in texture , smooth finish . its not bad , better than i had expected , but compared to your typical micro-brewed porter , its pretty average .

this is an almost colorless , crystal clear beer with a glowing golden hue . it easily supports a thick , spongy , white head .  mouthfeel : light to moderate carbonation , smooth with a lightly dry finish .

a- the classic cascading bubbles of carbonation leave a 1 finger tan head that never really falls and leaves all sorts of sticky spots on the glass . the body was a very dark brown , nearing black .  it 's not bad , necessarily , it 's just totally wrong for the style . that said , the mouthfeel is smooth , thick and rich , and the 6.3 % abv is nicely concealed .

aroma-heady , intoxicating aroma featuring dark and dried fruit aromas of plum , prune , grape , and currant , with hints of raisin and caramel . light bready notes and substantial perfumy alcohols round out the awesome bouquet . i swear you could get drunk just smelling this . flavor-sweet with caramel , toffee , and dark fruits ( prunes , raisins , currants ) up front . this is a damned fantastic beer , though i will say that i wish it finished just a bit drier .  its light-medium and creamy with mild carbonation .

s - just a blast of fruit continually streaming from the glass . tons of papaya , mango and peach . after a while , some lemon and tea started to come out . t - super fruity with sweet honey . perfectly balanced with the hops , which were accentuated by the fruit . o - one of the best non-sour fruit beers i 've had . midway is solid , but the paw paws took this beer over the top . so much flavor , yet perfectly sweet and bitter at the same time .  a little too spicy for my liking m- thick , with a malty character . goes down smooth d- a little tough to handle all the spice .
a - a perfect reddish brown complexion allowing traces of light to pass . it 's color is medium tan , almost caramel colored .  smooth and light bodied .

i find this beer to have a beautiful brown cloud color that made my mouth water .  mf : thick body , somewhat syrupy , very low carbonation , nice for the style d : very thick and and hearty , a bit hot on the booze , could use some age , .

it pours a beautiful clear copper/amber color with a small white head .  it comes is sweet , with a medium body , and the bitterness really does clash a bit too much with it . not bad , i especially like the smooth mouthfeel , but i think that aftertaste is going to stick with me for a while .
smell was strong and very nice . fruity and piney at the same time .  medium bodied with good carbonation .

one finger of stark white head recedes leaving just a touch of soapy lace . the aroma is very fruity and sweet . lots of oranges and lemons . the flavor is quite a bit muted compared to the nose . all these flavors are very tame and fall rather flat .  mouthfeel : pretty nice actually . soft , nicely carbed .

on the pour : looks light for an ale..pale light gold with a white head , fads fast with little lacing , but the nose on pour was great , flowers and hops . on taste citrus , and malt on start , then ginger and lemon grass , malts and hops in the finish , a real nice beer .  beer coated my mouth very uniformly with a honey taste in the front of my mouth and bitter taste in the back like a barelywine . the flavor alcohol is the only quality that counts against this beer .

smells absolutely fantastic with hints of apples , bananas , play dough , red liquorish and an over all dry smoothness .  alcohol is strong and a bit rough with a potent orange , passion fruit , and sour berry edge riding the edges of my tongue . mild carbonation and thick dextrinous mouthfeel that evaporates in the end in a pleasing way .
s : very interesting aroma , has a nice spicy smell almost musky . honey and grapes are evident in the aroma , enticing me to take a big sip .  mouthfeel is quite good .
it smells amazing . the cascade/centennial/chinook grapefruit hops overpower the nose . it smells amazing . i think i inhaled at the lip of the cup for well over a minute .  it is highly carbonated .
poured from 12oz bottle into glass a- love the look . a fluorescent orange appearnace with a great foamy head .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean .
smell - fantastic , deep aroma .  m : very tingly on a very full body .

nose is exceptional . deep dark chocolate , a touch of cream , and hints of ground coffee . wow ... this really does smell wonderful . surprisingly bitter tasting and kind of harsh .  medium mouthfeel works fine .
presented in its own branded glass , the beer has a medium golden yellow color and a big , fluffy white head .  lots of carbonation , medium body ... very drinkable very nice mouth feeling .

the smell is strongly citrus - sweet lemon and grapefruit . it 's enticing and i could smell it as soon as i opened the can so big points for smell . taste : not what i expected from the smell .  m : light-bodied with moderate carbonation . clean finish .

batch # 3 ( bottled feb. 2009 ) very pleasing aroma , smells creamy and rich . medium brown coloring with a ton of particles floating in it .  i hate to review this brew cuz i love columbus brewing . decent carbonation and some lace . ok if you like fruity beers . the only thing is it says it has a nice hop finish ... nah . hot a hop in the lot .

a : pours with a huge thick creamy light brown head , similar in look to a guinness but more porous . good lacing . deep but clear black in color .  the mouthfeel was great though , oily , hoppy , slick on the tongue .

an absolutely amazing hop aroma . this stuff is da bomb . starts out sweet , finishes full and hoppy and bitter . this is by far the best ipa i have ever tried .  mouthfeel - like most porters it has a nice smooth feel . actually impressed with the feel of this porter considering taste .

sweet , hoppy and pungent with guava , and passion fruit in the aroma along with grapefruit and pine needles . the aroma in this beer is outstanding . taste is spicy , bold , yet subtly alcoholic , although i know better . clingy , resiny finish for this dank delightful beer .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with creamy carbonation .
white pillowy head with great retention and lacing .  m : best part of the beer , light-bodied , light carbonation , pretty nice .
the slow nitro pour produces a deep dark and just plain black as night hued brew .  full bodied and carbonated well .

it is full of big hop aromas ! the taste is n't quite as overpowering as the aroma was , but it still provides a decent hop-kick . it is a very good ipa , and definitely worth having every so often .  mouthfeel was light and fluffy on the palate with a fine , spritzy , lively carbonation . practically champagne-like .

great big grassy , citrusy aroma-we are talking full frontal hop assault . good body-has a tad of a `` soapiness '' feel to it .  looks beautiful in its golden splendor , smells too estery and one dimensional , metallic finish , nice mouthfeel and i may or may not finish it .
citrusy and enticing . t- tasted alot like it smelled which was nice .  mouthfeel is pretty good .
this is quite an exceptional warm flat beer .  mouthfeel : crisp and tingly . this is where i think it stands out as just another average wheat ale .
12 oz bottle a : excellent clear amber under a pretty large head after a vigorous pour . good head retention and excellent lace .  m : fairly thick , sticky , and medium carbonation .

the look is awesome , with a dark brown head , about 1/2 inch high , leaving a cap and lace all the way down . darkest head i have ever seen on any beer .  the mouthfeel was pretty pleasant though , smooth , ( unfiltered ) .
smell - very pleasant ! the hops are there to greet you at the first whiff !  body and carbonation are good .

ok , the aroma is amazing . it smells like wood , alcohol , malts and liquor , like bourbon . it smells amazing . hmmm ... .taste ... .well to start the beer is medium to low bodied , there is n't any bitterness or carbonation to sour it out .  m ) lively carbonation , smooth but strong . refreshing .

smell is very juicy sweet pineapple with the expected belgian yeast twang of clove and banana . nice sharp bitterness upfront . muddled with a twist of pineapple but any other flavor is kind of muted .  light-medium body and moderate carbonation .

color- a beautiful hazy light yellow . smell- sweetness , subtle tropical , citrusy fruit taste- incredibly light malt , paired with the same fruitiness smelled , all of this is very slight , theres not much there intensity wise . smooth , creamy , sudsy , slick and effortless as anything ive ever tried .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with a creamy carbonation - probably one of the better features of the beer .

aroma is extremely spiced with cinnamon and cloves , even a hint of mint present , very appealing . flavour starts off with a big spice bomb , cinnamon is there , but is held back by the other spices , i.e .  just a poor finish . a solid mouthfeel for the style .

poured pitch black with a large tan head which quickly diminished .  mouthfeel : the thing that 's done correctly with this brew , as it 's full , creamy , and has enough carbonation to make me crave the other wheat flavors and aromas that are too obfuscated by the boysenberry flavors and aromas .

the scent seems almost bang on , along with a touch of coffee aroma . a great smelling brew . t + m : just like the aroma for the most half , with 'added chocolate chips ' the sweet tooth loves it , though i suppose under some circumstances , it could be come a little cloying .  mouthfeel is very full , carmelly throat coating with an alcohol burn following .

a - copper red with a thin white head that stays well and laces nicely .  i suppose that could be the hops , since i 'm getting no other hop scent at all . pear flavors are more pronounced , some wheat , and some herbal sensations .
a - super cloudy gold with a one inch white head that has excellent retention and intricate lacing down the glass .  mouth feel is smooth and clean , with a low carbonation level .

wonderful aroma . alot of hops contending for top of the hill here . bit of pineapple too , that 's how i keep describing nelson sauvin , i better smell a pineapple to make sure i 'm getting it right ... interestingly you seem to get the real bittering stuff up front .  mouthfeel is spot on , maybe a bit heavier and not quite as ethereal as some others , but good . if you have n't tried the style and want to see what its all about , save your money for the deus or the malhuer brut .
a ) pours with a thick , two finger head that settles slightly . lacing is sticky and tan in color .  creamy medium-full body with very light , tingly carbonation . full and heavy in the mouth .

the stout 's body was a dark red-black color , more reddish at the narrower points of the glass . atop the black body was a white , slightly tan , head that stayed in place throughout the pint . visually stunning , regardless of how it may taste .  upfront its smooth with a thicker creamy mouthfeel and moderate carbonation .

ok retention but i was messy on my pour , good lacing ... despite my sick stuffy nose i 'm instantly hit with wonderful citrus aromas , orange peel , citrus acid , laced with strong undertones of pine resin . ca n't get any better than this for an ipa ... the taste loses a lot of the orange , i 'm slightly disappointed about that .  light bodied , smooth and refreshing .
