pours a dark brown color with a three inch head that has better then average head retention .  nice light body and sparkly carbonation .

s : strong roasted malts and freshly brewed coffee , quickly followed by a blend of chocolate , raisin , and vanilla . t : the taste is slightly sweet to start , with a touch of vanilla and bittersweet chocolate .  mouthfeel is good , slick and medium bodied , but drinkability is rough as this one just did n't do it for me at all !

after two more pours , i finally have the glass filled with an impenetrable black beer and a finger and a half of frothy , off-white head .  t_very rich fudge is the best way to describe this . m_a bit viscous with a light but hard carbonation . works well here .

s : an awesome aroma of tasted caramel malt , chocolate , smoke , and dark fruits . it become a bit cloying after a bit . the nose is just amazing , but it kind of falls apart from there .  the mouthfeel is nice , thicker than many beers without being syrupy .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into a snifter ... a : the beer pours a nice brown color , maybe dark brown with a small head , and very nice lacing ... s : the aroma on this beer is weak , but its got some faint darker fruits , and a light spicyness ... t : the taste is also weak .  as the malt bill is substantial , this beer has a nice heavy body . the carbonation is moderate , and overall it has a nice feel .

aroma is delicious , a mix of light , creamy coffee , chocolate malts and bananas coated in fudge . expertly crafted like most ng 's .  light body , medium to high carbonation has a very nice mouth cleansing feel , the highlight of this beer .

a- deep rusty dirty copper color with a gorgeous wrinkly sticky cap of beige foam . lace is freakin everywhere , coating the glass like like a thin covering of new fallen snow .  m : quite a big body with a creamy texture . the mouthfeel is really good , but for some reason it does n't go very well with the flavors .
the nose had a really nice sweet biscuity smell with a real nice malty base and floural hop hint .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

aromas of clove , cinnamon , allspice , white pepper , ginger , banana , pear and orange zest . taste is full of flavor . more of the same from the aromas . i could certainly use a little more `` zing '' to liven this up a bit more and subdue those strong spice notes . this beer reminds me of october and i feel it would pair excellently with pumpkin pie .  3/5 m : medium/full body , warm and smooth going down . 4/5 d : too sweet for me to have more than 12 oz .
very enjoyable ipa .  md body and strong carbonation .

the aromas is spectacular . ripe , sweet tangerine , orange juice , tangy pine ( but not too much ) . very natural ipa nose ; not too forced .  still average overall . mouthfeel/overall : light bodied with pleasant carbonation . pretty smooth drinking and not overcarbonated .

the aromas are of orange peel and coriander and floral yeast . overall there are better belgian style triples , but i have also had worse ones .  i got this bottle from a friend who went to the brewery in michigan . i do n't know if this bottle was stored poorly or something but ipa is the last impression i got from this beer . smells of deep caramel , candi sugar , some sweet citrus hops are barely there and theres some hints of biscuit and chocolate . this already smells like a dubble belgian ale and it taste even more like one . it 's exceptionally sweet , almost like a mild ipa that was aged for far to long . it 's got caramel and raisen notes along with some prune and apple . there 's a little hint of hops but you honestly have to search for it . i really think travel took a heafty toll on this beer .
this is one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen . it pours a ridiculous translucent orange .  mouthfeel is about right ; it 's not bone dry and spritzy , but not thick and chewy , either .
wonderful . t : quite a bit different than the aroma . but after that smell i was disappointed in the flavor .  medium body , low carbonation .

smell is juicy , citrus , piney hop , slightly floral as well . good finish , slightly dry .  very nice mouthfeel , which is immediately hit with a taste of the bubblegum yeast , followed up with notes of clove , chai , and maybe some cinnamon .

my score 4.5 the smell is very strong . plenty of alcohol there with a ton of dark fruits , mostly plums , and a definite woody aroma . now some sherry like smells are coming into the picture as well as some caramel malt sweetness , though the latter is tough to pick out .  4.0 m : medium body . good moderate carbonation with a pleasant creaminess .

canadians out there will know what i mean when i say this smells exactly like a tim horton 's canadian maple donut . it has that really nice maple flavour , with an underlying sweetness and a light breadiness . the maple flavours come through very cleanly , and have n't transformed into something else , as maple sometimes seems to do .  the mouthfeel is good , not too light and not overly heavy either .
the smell and appearance do n't disappoint .  feels light and clean with a nice density . big bubbles in the carbonation stay locked in and add a lot of life to this one .
nose is just what i want from a stout -- lots of dusty flour , vanilla , toasty grain .  m - solid coating with a medium amount i 'd tingle on sides and under tongue .

the aroma is amazing , vanilla , creamy milk chocolate , burnt malt , coffee , and bourbon , with light notes of wood . roasted malt and dark chocolate up front , with a sour boozy kick shortly afterwards , then sweeter milk chocolate slowly swells up towards the middle where it starts melding into notes of capuccino and light vanilla , and somewhat of a sour cherry finish .  moutfeel is nice and crisp due to a decent amount of carbonation .

nice head . very opaque . how i think a good beer should look .  m- light and bubbly with a little creaminess it feels good in the mouth with crisp carbonation . d- without the skunk this would be a nice beer , it feels good in the mouth and smells and looks like most lagers , but that skunk flavor is a killer .

aromatic : spicy , powdery and sweet bordering on syrupy . after the outta-the-ballpark aroma , i was let down by the flavor .  carbonation is all but absent , the aroma is too faint to appreciate , and it loses suds early . its one redeeming feature is its fully textured mouthfeel .

this beer pours a dark , mirrored obsidian with a frothy film of creamy tan that stuck around for a while . just a sliver of brown came through the dimple at the bottom of my tulip .  m - smooth , thin , extremely refreshing .

by far one of the best smelling beers i 've had . drinkability - the absence of big flavor makes this one an easy drinker on a warm day , and the unbelievable nose makes sure that the drinker will be constantly raising the glass for another sip overall - although my aggregate total may not reflect it , this is one of my favorite beers based solely on it 's incredible scent . would score much bigger on my ( and many others ' ) list if it were pulled into better balance by tweaking up the malt content for overall taste and body .  m ) i actually thought it had a very nice mouthfeel .

its aroma is sweet and phenolic . i smell plum , figs , raisins , trail mix , spice , and candy . tastefully phenolic . the flavors are not as complex as the aromas , but both are very well balanced . medium bodied with nice carbonation .  mouthfeel is pleasant : medium bodied , smooth and lightly carbonated .
s : wonderful floral and earthy smells with hints of citrus .  m- full body . high carbonation .

pours a gorgeous gold that glows brighter than anything i 've ever seen . it leaves tremendous , sticky webs of lacing all over my glass . a huge 3 '' head reduces to a thick , condensed 1 '' head that sticks around for the remainder of the beer .  mouthfeel : does have good mouthfeel .
it 's really hoppy , which i enjoy , but the hoppy taste feels forced as if it were a product of an extract rather than brewing .  it has a medium body and nice carbonation considering .

amazing ! t : sort of mild in flavor but there is a semisharp bitterness on the end , which i find too dominant .  this light bodied beer has a creaminess that is hidden in the appearance and aroma , however it does feel pretty good in my mouth .
pretty clear with a little carbonation visible , about 2 fingers worth of head that settled to a ring , with wonderful lacing ... great looking beer .  medium bodied with a soft , creamy mouthfeel .

a : pours a cloudy orangey yellow with a light fluffy white head , very good looking beer s : has a delicious sour and brett smell , it literally made my mouth start to water when i first smelled it , perhaps the perfect aroma for a wild ale t : taste is n't exactly what i had hoped for after the incredible smell , but it 's still pretty solid ; it 's both sour and bretty , but it 's also a little on the spicy side , perhaps characteristics of the base beer that i 'm not familar with ?  taste & mouthfeel - first things that come through are a smooth malt , followed by a piney hop bitterness . a crisp refreshing taste , ends nicely in a sweet smooth finish .
s - heavily chocolate with some roasted malts and coffee .  m : it was nicely carbonated and i enjoyed the feeling of this in my mouth .
it smells like a bar ; rather , the apple-and-hops smell always makes me think of a bar ( same thing occurred to me with ephemere ) .  medium to full bodied , tingly and warming .

smell : like thick , chocolate pudding -- it is super smooth and creamy , and it seems like pudding with bittersweet chocolate shavings on top ; touch of coffee roastiness , and it is a little reminiscent of a jamocha shake from arby 's ; slight touch of alcohol as it continues to warm ... i ca n't believe i 'm smelling a beer and not dessert . overall : a sweet beer that would make an excellent dessert ; abv would lessen the drinkability as it seems a little higher than the standard american stout , but i 'm glad to have tried it .  m - good carbonation , fairly large amount of bubbles .

not very complex , but darn good ! t - fresh bushels of strawberry are quite the unique experience in a brew .  the body is light and not too watery , but the hop bitterness is further accentuated by the resins in the feel . the carbonation is nice and light though , as a cask should be .

the black label , combined with a fantastic motor-oil color , gives this beer a foreboding character before the bottle is even opened .  m : a medium mouthfeel . the feel is the best part to this beer , there is a nice smoothness to it .

absolutely fantastic . t : exactly as above with some freshly shaved lemon/orange zest .  01.14.10 at city beer store a : was surprised by the light copper color ; for some reason , i remember this beer being lighter s : wet-sock kind of of funk t : kind of a metallic , alcoholic finish m : really nice carbonation d : not my favorite , but then again , not my favorite style .

s : the aroma is a heavy , ramped up coriander , honey and subtle tartness . t : the most significant change in this beer from the regular saison is an increased tartness .  the taste up front is somwhat sweet with a carbonation presence providing plenty of creamy thicker mouthfeel without all that carbonation sting to the toung .

a : copper colored , good clarity , s : a great mix of fresh melon-y hops and sweet malty minerals .  mouthfeel is just below medium with average carbonation and very subtle alcohol warming towards the end of the glass .
black as night with minimal head .  m : fair body , pleasant carbonation d : doubt i 'll finish this - there 's other stuff i 'd rather drink now
deep , dark black-brown body with a huge cake-like head . a thing of supreme beauty !  m - mild coating with a high amount of tingle . tingle around the body of the tongue and behind the bottom lip .

an amazing aroma - sweet barrel aged brandy like caramel malts with a touch of an alcohol aroma to end . the aroma is so good it sets the anticipated taste bar very high .  mouthfeel is good . forgettable ris here .
appearance is better than anything i 've seen - very dark , beautiful brew , 3/4 inch head so thick it seems you can walk on it .  mouthfeel is good , maybe a bit over carbonated but still smooth .
poured a nice golden yellow with a bit of cloudyness , and a huge pillowy head , great lacing and retention .  good moderate carbonation .

s : smells predominately of doughy , bready yeast with some faint hops and sweet caramel . i really liked the smell , and was impressed with the glass .  however , the carbonation is good and the beer is thick and full-bodied ... maybe even a bit too much for an ipa , but not bad .

pours out clear lemon yellow with a white , frothy head that puffs up to 3 fingers , then does a belly flop , fading to a thin , but persistant ring . aroma is sweet tropical fruits , yeast , sugary malts , pinapple , oak , cinnamon , vanilla , coconut , and a twang of something tart . flavor begins with ripe tropical fruit , spicey yeast , peach , pear , green apple ( tartness ) . slowly fades into the oak induced notes of vanilla , creme brule , cinnamin dust , bourbon , coconut , and sandlewood .  m - light and crisp . high carbonation .

it smells delicious . remeniscent of pte , but i dont want to try and compare directly . this beer has some really enjoyable qualities .  m- very creamy texture , surprisingly light ( but not *too* light ) body .
very good looking beer .  mouth- i like the feel on this beer a lot . it 's very sweet and creamy but not at all like a double stout . something new and it was probably better fresh .
strong citrus and piney hop aroma . pretty good , bitterness is not overwhelming .  the beer has a creamy and smooth body , but that delivers in an awkward way with the flavors this beer has .
pours a three finger cream head that fades very slowly leaving an excellent lace . clear amber color .  m : medium bodied with decent carbonation .

just by looking at the artwork you know you 've gotten yourself into something serious , kinda like a mix between , satanism/black magic/and an orgy . the appearance is jet black .  app - copper , carbonated head of minimal size and dissipating rapidly smell - hoppy , piney taste - a little hoppy bite but a more than overwhelming caramel biscuity malt taste that i guess balances the offering but not when there are so few hops to begin with.. mouthfeel - kind of cool and different on this one , kind of coats the mouth in a silky fashion overall - not too big on this malty aftertaste , etc . the carbonation is more than i prefer

$ 8 for a half pint at billys on burnet . the aroma might be the best aspect of this beer . smells like brandy with a lil oaky bourbon . bitterness is there but hop presence is mostly faded . honey dipped pineapple . some molasses and fig too . very drinkable , but the price makes me savour it and sip slowly .  when you swallow it , the hops hit ... and to be honest i did n't like 'em . mouthfeel 's fine and i 'm sure if you like the flavor profile this would be a fine brew .

a - very dense 2.5 finger of off-white foam that lasts forever .  last night i brewed a big ipa , and as tradition dictates - `` drink what ya brew . '' upon opening the beer and taking a sniff i was a little disappointed . where are the hops ? maybe a bit of floral notes , but that could be the yeast . first sip and i get the bitterness of the hops , but not as much flavor as i 'd like . if this were labeled as a pale ale , i would have given it much higher marks . however , as an ipa , it just does n't hack it .

a - pours a pitch black with a tan foam that just quickly disappeared to spotty tan bubbles s - big roasted coffee aromas , coffee , coffee & more coffee like no other bottled coffee beer i 've had before t - its the equivalant to drinking cold coffee .  the flavor was just a bit too harsh , which is odd becuase to the palate it is a beer that has a pleasant feel to the mouth .

nice aroma on this ! deep dark chocolate with cocoa , lots of cocoa . smells wonderful ! chocolate , cocoa , coffee , walnuts with a hint of vanilla and a nice hop bite . this tastes great !  a bit of hoppy bitterness , but otherwise not much ... not really my thing m + d : rather smooth , semi-creamy mouthfeel - one of the better aspects to this .

aromas include the fresh grape notes of a sauvigon blanc , oak barrels , a little hint of the barnyard must and a strong dose of alcohol .  however , it goes down smoothly and the carbonation is just right .

from notes : pours a deep dark brown , pretty much black , with a thick two finger frothy light beige head that has very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap . sporadic chunks of lacing left behind .  mouf & gt ; good . easy .

massive carbonation delivers a clean wheat and apricot nose . hints of vanilla behind the fruit remind me of those orange sherbet push-ups .  i do like the syrupy mouthfeel , but it does n't compensate for the taste of alcohol .
smells of fresh pumpkin & fall spices ; ca n't get enough of this aroma !  mouthfeel is hot and crisp . very interesting , and it worked for this particular beer .
beer is a very attractive hazy gold with an ivory head .  medium mouthfeel .

there is a very nice sweet malty , almost bubblegum quality , banana and clove aroma . the smell is quite pungent and is indicative of things to come .  m : medium smooth body with just the right amount of carbonation . this is the beers best aspect .

it smelled of piney and citrusy hops .  the flavor profile replicates the nose fairly closely , but is clearly dominated by the molasses and prunes , as well as the dry sherry and more wood . the finish is fairly dry and sherry filled in this otherwise moderately sweet , full flavored beer . drinkability is where this beer really falls apart , and in fact i was unable to finish even the 8 ounce wine glass serving i received at the g & g . while not hot , the beer is heavy and a bit tiring on the palate , and it was just a chore to get this beer down given the sweetness , wood and sherry flavors .
pours an insane head with a nice cloudy orange color . retention sticks around forever .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and medium carbonated .

s : wow , definitely this beer 's strongest attribute ... smells of roasted pumpkin innards , bread crust , nutmeg , caramel malt and maybe a pinch of some other autumn spices ; huge aroma here . t : hmmm , not quite as exciting as the aroma ; heavy pumpkin ( again of the roasted / cooked variety ) and lots of bread or pie crustiness . interesting , yet in my opinion , not that appealing . d : the flavor of this beer just does n't do it for me ; that being said , i would n't have more than one - although , i might give it another try before its gone for the year .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . keeps good with the style o : stays within style guidelines for some of the aspects like appearance and mouthfeel , but really lacks the flavor and bitterness that is usually present .
the beer had a beautiful jet black color with a long lasting silky 1 inch head of beige foam .  carbonation is light & fine . feels creamy without being heavy .

pours a very pale straw colour , translucent champagney-look but with big frothy head sunk to a modest white crown , but dense . leaves massive clumps of lace . seriously though , looks great .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with good carbonation .
beautiful appearance !  m. medium to full bodied with decent carbonation . coats the mouth decent , definitely all that sweet malt .

the smell of this brew is great . citrus and pine all the way , a very noticable northwestern hop profile . overall a fantastic beer .  brewed in honor / sacrifice to mother nature after floods in the area around the brewery . good lacing . maybe some slight floral hops but i 'm really reaching . hides the abv incredibly well . light and smooth , caramel malt sweetness in the main , hops very subdued again . a bit of oomph from the malt in the finish , but this could nearly pass for an ordinary bitter . as it warms the finish has a bit more yeast character than it should really . would like a bit more hop character ( no surprise there ) to match the dominant malt but certainly an easy drinker .

nose is amazing , the raspberries are fresh picked and squeezed in this one - or so it smells . sweet , though perhaps a little artificial .  aroma was very complex , spicy , pungent . flavor was just a mass of confusion . sasion ? triple ? wtf ? the reason this `` triple is so hard to nail down is absolutely flabbergasting . the brewer was very proud to tell us that 9 different strains of yeast were use to ferment this concoction . why 9 ? what was there about each that he hoped to add to his beer ? the real answer is that for a triple , you triple the malt bill .

very dark brown in color , with a beige head that lingers about a half inch over the top of the liquid , and leaves rings as the glass is emptied . the dark inviting color is deceiving .  the infection has n't totally killed the other flavors quite yet and there are still some bourbon notes that save the beer mouthfeel : medium body with medium to low carbonation overall : i really want to try this one when it is not infected .
the smell was pretty nice , kinda had a pepper kick to it with bit of a fruity aroma .  nice clean mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation .
this baby is pitch black . and it 's got the most incredible lacing and legs i 've seen in a while .  despite the lack of carbonation , the feel is good for the style , quite smooth and silky .

big aroma on this bad boy . as soon as i popped the cap off robust hops jumped up my nose : spicy , floral , piney , and a subtle note of citrus . a rather amazing bouquet of nearly the entire hop spectrum ! generous hops lean mostly floral and piney . `` fresh '' really does describe this beer .  good mouthfeel .
a - this ale looked beautiful . the nitro-can pour cascaded into a bright amber color , leaving a thick and solid head of inch and a 1/2 white foam .  m : thick and chewy body .
a : cloudy amber , it poured with a big fluffy , sticky white head with lacing . if it was n't cloudy , this would have been a 5 .  mf- a nice medium bodied beer that has good carbonation level .

first whiff is pumpkin pie spice -- cinnamon , nutmeg , faint clove -- lovely , with a bit of malt in the background .  nothing overly sticks out .. m : lighter side of medium body , high carbonation , crisp clean feel .

a- a beautiful pour . rust color , with a bright head right out of the bottle that settles down and then leaves a nice lace down the side of the glass .  goes beyond anything recognized as beer , anywhere ... no , it 's closer to port , and should be consumed as such . thick on the tongue at first , then mild , still with a sweet , treacly coating that trickles down the throat .
2011 pliny the younger : pale yellow , medium body and carbonation . smells like pine and grapefruit .  the mouthfeel is thick and fairly creamy , not bad at all .
this beer pours a very nice crystal clear dark gold color wihth a slightly off white head .  nice body , its just not balanced or enjoyable to drink .

appearance- golden orange color , very cloudy ( ca n't see fingers on other side of glass ) , 2 fingers of huge bubbled head that dissipated quickly . lacing was very thin and rings formed around head as well . nice appearance !  m - nice carbonation , creaminess .

smells sweet , fruity and belgian with quite a delicious and glossy spice to it as well . really rather delicious . taste is similarly fruity upfront , with melon and orange peel character , the latter of which lasts through to mid-palate . decent notes , but it just falls a bit short .  long aftertaste as the sweetness lingers quite a while . medium-heavy in body .

a - pours a deep black with brown twinges on the edges . the head is big and brown , yet my only gripe is the length of time it stays around .  mouthfeel is light , crisp and on the smooth side with high , fizzy carbonation , a very light body and decent drinkability .
the smell of this beer is top notch . you can really get a noseful of hops from this one , victory got that part right .  good carbonation .

s : what a stellar nose ! bready and biscuity malts , fruity esters and underneath all that ? citrusy hops ... a little bit of everything and none of them so strong that it drives away the others . nice and hoppy , well worth having at least once .  mouthfeel : just interesting enough to make me want to drink another in 5 years .
a : the appearance of this beer is just awesome . it is a deep ruby red color topped with a frothy light tan head .  the finish was clean , mouthfeel was crisp .

it poured better , looked better , smelt better and tasted better than the leffe tripel . after pour , the head of this brassy-coloured beer sticks to the glass and leaves a beautiful lacing as you continue to drink , which adds nicely to the presentation .  mouthfeel : light crisp from start to finish .

smell is big and hoppy , classic pnw profile of resinous citrus , spicy , with some sweet malt , making it a bit gingerbread like . for an ipa it 's great , more assertive then plenty of dipas , at least ones not from the west coast ! drinkability is pretty good . not really my style of pnw ipa though , i prefer more complex hop flavor and less bitterness , but it 's still a well done example of the general regional style .  m : soft , nicely carbonated , fairly substantial . nice .
huge dark tan head the recedes ever so slowly to thick chunky lace .  m : medium-light mouthfeel .

amazing . sometimes i even swear i smell apple pie . lots of spices in here still making it almost borderline harsh . o : great christmas beer . honestly the taste was almost a letdown after smelling it , but that speaks more to the amazing aroma than anything .  medium bodied with good carbonation and a nice malt flavor to compliment the banana flavors .

a - minimal head , cloudy swirls , and yeasty chunks flow through this deep golden-orange brew , very pleasant looking .  pleasant carbonation and smoothness , soft sweet and slightly bready aftertaste .
smell : rich malty aroma , hints of apple and a whiff of alcohol .  fell is slick and full bodied .
a midnight-black appearance with a nice , thick off-white/grey head .  m - well carbonated , probably the most enjoyable part of the beer , other than the looks .

s : malty , sweet and a spread of honey and butter . toasted cashews with the aroma of a streussel topping that would be on a fresh baked pie . t : salted buttered popcorn at first , not a good start . the malts give some structure as i sip through it and lends to caramel , not all of it great . i do enjoy the malty flavors that develop and reminiscent of a good nut bread .  the mouthfeel is pretty solid . medium bodied , decent carbonation , moderately sticky .

the nose comprises rich bourbon , chocolate syrup , roasted malts , molasses , and oak . smells like the hype might ring true .  t- citrus , mild bite , little hops , with a warming alcohol feel and a sweet aftertaste . m- full with very nice carbination .

smell : deeply citrusy and richly resinous with a background layer of candy-coated breadiness . overall : it 's a nice , easy-going apa with a great nose on it .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a firm feel to the carbonation and an all around smooth feel for 6 % .

complex and rich . lighter body than i would have guessed , going down quickly with little resistance .  light in body and carbonation level . smooth , crisp , and refreshing - exactly what you 'd expect from a blonde ale .
smells very strongly of honey and crystal malt with a bright hop note .  the feel is bright and fizzy , with a moderately full feel .

huge , great looking head .  carbonation drops to the bottom in a cloudy haze that clarifies as the head settles thickly atop . reminds me of fundip poweder candy . ingredients list scots pine and spruce sprigs and this is a pine ale but i question the wholesomeness of the ingredients .
smells funky and tart . a really nice lemony sweetness . love the aroma . oak is strong . love it . tastes tart and oaky .  body is a creamy medium .

500ml bottle this is an odd one , pours withh very little carbonation , just like the st patricks best bottled , slightly creamy head forms but only with some aggressive pouring , body is a light amber smell , very fresh , apples some hint of pear , maybe bananas taste , wheaty and biscuity , dry and fruity .  m- full body with low carbonation .

smell is delicious . hops hops hops and more hops . and more than one kind . a nice complex hop aroma .  i had to check the bottle to note it 's 12 % abv . it is smooth though for being such a big beer . those guys at dfh know what they are doing with big beers , but i am thinking maybe those 10,000 gallon palo santo tanks they built are past their usefulness . i really am grateful a great ba was kind enough to send this to me and in no way want this review to reflect on doublesimcoe 's generosity . also , american brown ale . maybe american strong ale is a better fit for this brew .

but alas , this is all that is available : - ) exceptional appearance , crystal clear , light golden hue and good head ( considering ) .  took a little swig at first , assessing the carbonation . very bubbly , which i like . felt really smooth in my mouth .
looks fantastic . s - smells of belgian yeast , raisins , bubblegum , grapes , and a mild malty sweetness .  m : well carbonated , medium bodied , and has smooth finish .

appearance : a brilliantly hazy , orange-tinged golden body with brilliant tendrils of yeast stretching from top to bottom . up top , a big , fluffy off-white head that leaves patchy lacing .  m : a medium body with a low/medium carbonation d : i really wanted to like this beer ... .

make no mistake -- i 'm not disappointed to get to try another tasty offering from new belgium , but it seems like they might have left the fall 'saison ' linger on a little more ... in any case , this is a handsome amber beer with a thin head and a bouquet bursting with pine and citrus . i thought for sure that nb had released a winter ipa when i got my first whiff of this , but the flavor itself is quite mellow -- balanced by a strong , bready maltiness in the middle of the palate , this seems to sit more comfortably in the amber genre than the esb one . the overall impression is that of a competent brew , though the bright aromas of the bouquet got me excited for a more assertive and bitter flavor .  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

s : very good , with lots of bananas and cloves , white pepper and black pepper , very yeasty , very estery , with a bit of sweetness to it as well . d : a good hefe , drinkable , just nothing that i 'd go out of my way to get .  m : crisp and a little smooth , light-to-medium body , medium carbonation , finish is clean .

a-deep amber with low head and decent lace . s-exceptional very rich and malty , carmel notes with sweet cinnamon also some nutty undertones t-again very high marks everything in the nose is very boldly revaled again in the flavor .  there are some citrusy hops and the slightest medical brett presence . kiwi pineapple and lemon from the hops , bit a biting bitter hop tang mid-palette . ov- another miss by mikkeller . there are aspects that are intriguing but to put this ridiculous level of hops with candi sugar , a bruiser abv and brett ? it 's like dumping jalapenos on a raspberry chocolate torte . if you happen to purchase one of these , sit on it for 3 years in hopes that the hops fade and brett blossoms .

pretty sure this is from one of the original batches ... a - pours into my duvel tulip a crystal clear light straw hue with a massive fluffy three finger head that slowly faded to leave big side lacing and a dense creamy white blanket . just excellent .  the mouthfeel was pretty good , it went down rather smooth .
overall a rich scent that can get too much for me , but still impressive . t - sweet malt , toffee and alcohol , .  this has a medium body and medium to high carbonation .

this rye ipa looks beautiful in a glass . a perfectly clear beer with no murkiness or hazy and a pretty orange brown tone with nice head .  i enjoyed the carbonation the most as the mouthfeel made this really refreshing and light .

wonderful banana , bubblegum , clove aroma that surrounds a beautifully looking beer of slightly cloudy brown ale covered by a full rich frothy tan cap .  overall : medium bodied with a smooth mouthfeel , this porter is better paired with food rather than drank as a session beer . minimal carbonation holds back its potential .

big beer , big aroma . reallly big aroma . gobs and gobs of sweetness here . it 's interesting . not so sweet as to overpower though , as in their doppelbock .  m - nice carbonation balances out the beer , medium bodied .

batch 70 a - pours deep dark brown with burgundy highlights , huge cappuccino colored head with awesome retention and lacing , a truly awesome looking beer s - kind of weird , but this smells exactly like the pit-smoked beef brisket i had last weekend , lots of smoke , hints of port wine and figs as well t - a lot like the nose , smoked beef brisket up front and on the midpalate , stronger notes of port wine and caramel , some fig and tobacco , lingering smoke and woodiness on the finish m - fairly full-bodied , moderate carbonation , pretty well balanced finish , alcohol warming effect d - definitely a sipper , the taste is intense and not condusive to quick drinking really unique beer all around .  a - one inch off-white creamy and fluffy head ; light copper/bronze colored ; clear appearance with visible carbonation ; small patches of lacing s - floral , herbal , and perfume-like aroma of hops ; butterscotch lingers in the background t - very floral , perfume-like taste up front that reminds me of bubble gum ; diacetyl buttery flavor is also noticeable beyond the floral/perfume characteristics ; taste becomes more leafy and vegetable-like at the end of the taste with diacetyl still present - this taste lingers on the palate ; somewhat bitter towards the end of the taste m - light to medium bodied ; moderate carbonation ; fairly smooth mouthfeel that 's a little dry in the finish o - i 'm not sure of the last time i had an english ipa , but maybe i 'm just not a fan of this style .

the nose is amazing . real tart scents of cranberry and mild oak . a bit over carbonated but seems to work with this weird concoction .  m. fairly thick with restrained carbonation . d. a bit thicker and lighter ( in terms of hops ) than i 'd like in an apa .

aroma- has the freshest and most unbelievable piney and citrus infused hop aroma possible ! very sweet background also but this hop aroma could n't get any better ! has a nice orange colored body that has very good clarity . has a very clean finish to it . the hop aroma was so great , i could order this brew and just promote it on the basis of the aroma !  mouthfeel is creamy and full , with large bubbled carbonation .
a- quite a looker ! bright gold and crystal clear .  mouthfeel : light-medium bodied with lots of carbonation that works for this beer .

aroma is actually quite nice : some toasted malts with some frosty vanilla . the taste is not nearly as nice as the aroma . when tasting , the malts seem burnt , like starbucks coffee .  off the pour , this doesnt look like a pale ale i 've ever had . it resembles a beer poured in a non beer bar that makes a point to not place any head on the beer . taste is filled with unfermented honey , biscuits , straw , light earthy hops bittering mildly with a lemon lime zest to the flavor . hop bitters come long after the swallow on the linger and contain a touch of rind and plenty of amarillo aspirin flavor . i still dont understand how this is a pale ale . a bodacious pils with ale yeast maybe ...

really amazing . very nice red-mahogany colour with a small , foamy , light tan head . it does n't seem as complex as the aroma and is just a little harsh . i still like it . medium-full body with moderate carbonation . right on . a great beer . lots going on and really , really tasty .  mouthfeel is medium , with medium carbonation creating a creamy texture .
very interesting . spicy and a touch fruity with some interesting , musty notes from the sorachi ace hops .  has a thick malty backbone with a bitter finish m- smooth mouthfeel .

dark brown body , almost black ... red at the bottom of the glass . probably one of the prettiest beers i 've seen in a glass .  the softness of the honey comes through in the middle . th creamy textue is captured in theabout thirty seconds after the sip . it slowly shows that faint dollop of cream .
a- fresh fruity snap . kinda mellow , compared to some ipa 's which send off grapefruit pith and pine resin .  nicely carbonated , at least .

a nose that is rich with maltiness . lots of caramel and toffee here . decent notes of nutmeg and a light trace of cinnamon . not bad , just interesting . the nose on this one had such potential , but the flavor does not deliver , sadly .  i capped this one to save the nice carbonation and in the hopes that i would drink it later to get the value of the bottle .

tan head leaves an amazing spider web of lace .  a clear medium honey small head leaves quickly slight soapy lacing s slight malt vert subtle smell t medium malt bitter slight tinny finish but not bad claen in end m medium body nice mouth good carb d first spanish not tiring - a nice beer to get in 6 pack form when visiting europe .
the best looking beer i have had to date . thick foamy head that lasted a long time with thick lacing along the glass .  mouthfeel has good carbonation and light body .

appearance : pours into my victory willibecker deep brown to black with a huge , frothy , light brown head . it drops a bit initially but still holds on to its full , firm cap .  m - medium body and low carbonation .
f***ing green bottles . this one was skunked pretty badly . the head was impressive and the taste was good .  crisp carbonation .

nice . but , overall decent drinkability and very pleasant aroma .  m - the feel is smooth , soft and easy . ~ white it smells and feels the part , the flavor holds the most weight here and unfortunately i ca n't say its something i 'll every purchase again , nor will i recommend this beverage to a friend .

on tap at the source pours a dark brown that borders on black with a creamy tan head that shows incredible retention and decent lace .  do n't really feel like writing a full review for guinness ... 1 . ) because everybody knows what it tastes like and 2 . ) i 'm only gon na drink it on st. patrick 's day anyway because it sucks !

a nice , sweet floral and wheat smell appealed to me instantly .  it 's really smooth and i appreciate the level of authentic bourbon present in the nose . and it is n't the bourbon that is overpowering , it 's the abv of the beer itself . it just drinks really , really boozy .

s the smell is quite wonderful . dark chocolate , some coffee , dark fruits ( raisins ) and some malty sweetness t follows the nose a bit . d almost sickeningly sweet and too little carbonation , half of a bottle was more than enough .  if you hold your nose its actally not a bad beer , the mouthfeel is solid , the taste is n't bad ... the only problem is it stinks .
s : this beer has an incredible danky hoppy aroma . there is a definite marijuana aroma in this beer and by no means is that a bad thing .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is pretty good .
this beer is beautiful . definitely one of the best looking beer 's i 've reviewed so far .  full bodied with appropriate carbonation .

disappointing s- there 's a real pleasant citrus aroma coming out of this one that absolutely tickles my nasal passages ... lots of orange in this t- the bitterness is strong in this one .  mouthfeel is pretty light bodied with nice dry , crisp and refreshing qualities . a session beer for sure .
dark brown , almost opaque colour , big , soapy and lumpy beige head with generous lacing . looks are about as gorgeous as they could possibly be , ill admit .  mouthfeel is fine .

aroma is rich and smoky with coffee and molasses undertones . flavor is not as strong as other stouts i have tried but still pleasing - smoky with coffee undertones and a hint of molasses .  mouthfeel-medium body , moderately high carbonation .

truly a fantastic and somewhat intimidating looking beer .  this is pretty creamy with a carbonation zing to the tounge , slick hop oil like feel . at the swallow it becomes a bit more bitter , to an almost un appealing bitter rotten cheese flavor , mixing with hot alcahol solvent flavors . some hops stick it out , but are overtaken with alcahol solvent .
the nose on this is incredibly potent . lost of biscuity malts up front with some nice faint hop aromas to compliment .  m -- pretty good . smooth and crisp .

very decadent , very dessert like aroma . d : really good . love what jackie o 's is doing , glad we have mark here in tampa to bring them all in for our group to sample !  the sweet , roasted malts came out nicely in the tail end of each sip with a lingering dryness in the finish . the mild carbonation and fruity flavors coated my mouth nicely , but the drinkability just was n't there for me .

it has a massive fluffy white head that forms a round peak over the top of the glass . this one has excellent retention and pretty nice lace , i will admit this one surprised me nice looking beer s not as nice smells of grass , mild floral hops and some rice t fairly bland , nothing offensive but pretty basic flavor , much better then our big name beers but that 's not hard m good carbonation but pretty thin not far off for the style d no real problems with this beer i just wish it was a little hotter outside i did n't mind this beer but compared too how it looked everything else was going to be a bit of a let down .  light bodied and smooth .

a - amber with fantastic clarity . large creamy head that settles to a nice layer .  m : a pretty light a crisp mouthfeel that was refreshing and good for the style . d : a pretty good mouthfeel for the style , but the taste could use a little work .

the nose on this beer is phenomenal . loads of barnyard and wild funk , just a touch of vinegar and a nice woodiness . much more balanced , cola with hints of dark fruits , a nice woodiness , a light tartness reminiscent of apples and lemons , a dash of vinegar - flanders bruin ? edgy carbonation further detracts and pulls away the chance for flavor to savor .  t-it 's very good , but honestly my first taste almost choked me-i was n't expecting something so overwhelmingly sweet . reviewing the guidelines for the eisbock , it fits very closely except for how sickeningly sweet it is . m-slick and oily-smooth , with low carbonation and a dry , warm , alcohol finish . if you want a much , much better example of eisbock , get a kulmbacher eisbock .

first off , i 'll be the first to admit , i do not have a ton of experience with barleywines so i 'm going to try to be as objective as i can . not much for head , but great lacing left over on the glass . love the smell . yet some bready malts with maybe a hint of alcohol scent .  m - pretty creamy texture with a nice effervescence . finish is a little dry and quite bitter . d - pretty nice mouthfeel , but overall not too impressed with this one .

the aroma hits all the marks of the style . grapefruit and rich caramel malt . pine and citrus . nicely citric but the malt lacks character . it 's a tad biscuity and toffee like but it leaves me wanting .  very smooth mouthfeel .
pours out beautifully with a golden hue and huge white head that laces nicely .  mouthfeel is nice , lots of sharp carbonation .
aroma at first pour is all about spicy , pungent hops .  the mouthfeel was clean and crisp .

pours a medium/dark brown from bottle but is somehow nearly jet black in glass . gorgeous light tan head forms and lasts until bottom of glass : pillowy , fine bubbles .  mouthfeel : smooth , mild carbonation , actually just right . good mouthfeel , but sadly everything else not too good , which is disappointing since to date i 've liked everything else from this brewer .

2011 vintage bottled 3 weeks ago pours dark dark brown . almost black . a full finger of brown frothy head that disipates quickly leaving a thin layer of brown bubbly goodness across the surface .  m - good body with a moderate carbonation that knows its place .
nice . can smell this one a few feet away .  this beer has a smooth mouthfeel although i personally do n't find it really drinkable .

chocolatey , roasty aroma , bittersweet and milk chocolate , malted milk . pretty good , but the flavour did n't quite live up to the promise of the aroma .  mouthfeel is good with a little creaminess and noticable carbonation .

a visually perfect beer . in an imperial pint glass it was a hazy straw color , nicely carbonated , with a thick white head .  mouthfeel is good , and the beer is very drinkable for the 8 % but i just dont enjoy drinking this .

appearance : darker yellow , almost brown with a nice white thinned head aroma : this beer smells awesome . i smell grapefruit and peach with that nice fresh hoppy smell behind it . just a great fresh clean smell palate : flavor sits on the tongue with the carbonation as well . overall : very good beer by aa , probably my favorite by them .  mouthfeel was surprisingly good , enough body and crispness that if swigged from the bottle i could be convinced this was `` refreshing .
pours a clear , pale gold , with two fingers of huge , white marshmallow fluff head . scant lacing .  nice feeling in the mouth .

the head is about two fingers and frothy and foamy . the head resides to a half finger and it leaves nice gobes of lacing all the way down with a ton of visible carbonation the aroma is of breadiness and earthy and citrus hops it also has a slight tea aroma to it .  nice moderate carbonation , could be a little higher .

rich , peppery , full-bodied aroma , with hints of sweet , juicy grapefruit . overall , far more pedestrian that the pour and aroma would indicate .  m : light bodies and medium carbonation that feels pretty good in the mouth - not too aggressive .

woiw , is what i think of when all the aromas reach my nose . like fresh baked sweet bread , carmalized malt , toffee , vanilla and esspresso . this brew is no where near as tastey as the nose lead me to believe . it really lacks the creamy roasty richness that i would have loved to have had accompany the nose . it does show a little bit of aht carmalized malt on the mouthfeel .  the mouthfeel is on the thicker side with low carbonation . i like low carbonation in big stouts , this one might be getting a little close to nothing though .

it starts with a bready , buscuity scent , and as it sits the floral hops and citrus fruits really come out . i had heard good things about this beer but to my surprise the taste is much closer to an ipa than your traditional american pale . the best thing about this beer is how smooth and drinkable it is . it 's an india pale ale trapped in an apa 's body , yet still delicious in its own right .  actually , the dryness of the finish is probably the most remarkable thing about this beer -- it 's a style that can be cloying , but hooker 's no nonsense where that goes .
appearance : surprisingly huge and ever lasting white head upon a clear gold body .  the mouthfeel is fine . it is a low bodied beer with good carbonation .
appearance is a very dark brown with a thick pillowy stick around head and nice lace .  medium body , carbonation is goot .

fresh juicy oily hop aroma with lots of earthy dank floral , dry piny and sweet citrus character . the aroma is my favorite characteristic of this beer . unfortunately the mouthfeel and flavor do n't live up to the aroma . fuller end of medium body with plenty of dry earthy hops with sweet citrus notes but the malt backboe is a bit too strong for my liking and there is a sweet alcohol presence mid palate that is a bit harsh . pretty hop forward with dry pine nd sweet citrus notes , mostly lemon peel and grapefruit , followed by a sweet caramel/graham vracker malt backbone and a sweet alcohol presence mid-palate that lingers into a dry piny hop finish . well balanced but probably too much so . decent but not that exciting .  the mouthfeel is the creamy nitro , and definitely the most pleasurable aspect of this brew .
the smell is amazing . sweet and fruity and can just barely smell the alcohol .  low carbonation with a medium and very creamy mouthfeel . malty and watered down .

there is little malt in the smell but the hops just smell so inviting . they over-take the aroma and invite you in . taste : this is not as apealing as the smell but it is good .  m : medium body ; medium-high carbonation ; slightly creamy texture , but very much a lager feel .

n : rich and spicy butterscotch brownie malt , spiced hot cider , molassas , and even a touch of stewed red cabbage ( in a very good way ) . totally different from any of the other oktoberfests i have tried so far this season but a little wild and smile inducing . p : powdery malt with a bit of spice that waits several beats before it introduces itself . where are those lovely flavors the nose promised us ? but what a nose , i 'll tell ya !  taste & mouth feel : very smooth and creamy with a solid malt palate , hop bitterness is followed by a mildly astringent grain . chalky yeast .

the aroma is bready with fruity rum cake and vanilla evident . some mild hop bitterness dances in the background , hope aroma is herbal and also very restrained .  m : the body is medium with a medium to high carbonation .

wow , i really mean wow ... im not a pro , but i`ve tried a few dopplebocks and i thought i will never taste a better dopplebock than the salvator ... a . it is a dark `` amber '' color . it shines for itself , and when watched behind a light it turns in a scale of browns , from the darkest in the bottom of the glass ... to the lighter one in the top of the glass .  taste let me down , alot . something was n't right at all . the hops was right up front with the rye but there was a bit of a funkiness with it . maybe i 'll get another and see . this does n't compare to other ipa 's at all . sorry for the bad review , but it did n't do much for me .

verdict- it looks great , and the aroma is complex and alluring . the taste does n't quite live up to the promise , though .  m- medium to high carbonation with some nice foaming action . a little astringent and moderately dry .
absolutely beautiful . taste : solid pine upfront , very fresh tasting . overall : quite impressed .  has a medium body with a well matched carbonation that keeps the ale light without being fizzy .

got this beer at the flying saucer in charlotte nc . smells of intense pine and grassy hops . very dry smell with very little malt undertone .  a little more coffee flavor than i expect from a lager , chocolate and coffee flavors overwhelm . m- despite the taste , this is a well formed stout , nice and creamy , not too heavy and definitely smooth .
nose has tons of cinnamon and spice , with cooked apples -- very aromatic .  m : crisp , active , refreshing . the best part .
on the nose is sweet wintery smell , berries and rye , very nice !  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

smells like a seriously juicy hef straight off the bat . deeper in i get all that macerated wheat , as well as some pineapple . chalky yeast , but that juicy aspect does n't disappear .  medium bodied and relatively smooth .
smells of apricots , rasins , plums , chocolate , and other christmas treats . very , very nice .  1.5 m : pretty good actually . wholesome .
great rising two finger head that recedes to a great film of foam and leaves loads of lacing .  m- light in body and good amount of carbonation .
pours a dark , dark brown color with a one-finger head into my glass .  the mouth feel is medium bodied with decent coating and weight .
pours out a bright clear copper hue , two fingers of creamy off-white head with okay retention .  mouthfeel/drinkablity- mouthfeel with solid and adequately carbonated .

nose has some pumpkin pie without the crust ( innards of a pumpkin pie ? some light creamy and milky character that really adds a nice touch . light body that 's somewhat watery , but still has some pretty good pumpkin pie 'innard ' flavour .  medium bodied , effervescent mouth feel , with a dry finish .

serving : bomber poured into tall snifter appearance : almost black , ca n't see through it even when held up to light , very minimal off white head smell : first off i must say this beer has an impressive and wonderful aroma but it is all wrong for an imperial stout . black coffee , chocolate , roasty . notes : i thoroughly enjoyed this beer but i am afraid someone must have switched the labels .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .
poured an absolutely gorgeous orangish amber color with a beautiful head . maybe it was just a perfect pour , but i thought it was one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen .  good carbonation .

framboise pours a deep red-brown color with a light pink head with very good retention and lacing .  m : mouthfeel is fine , leaving out the rest . it has a nice malt backbone of thickness , then hits you with great carbonation for this hefty of an ale .
i love storm king , so was pretty excited about this .  mouthfeel is slickery smooth , and drinkability is okay for what it is .
appearance - a light straw colored pour with a nice rocky head . the head was n't the huge , incredible pillow of the `` regular '' duvel , but it was still nice .  m : well carbonated , crisp .
this brew pours a very bright light golden color with a very mild head over top . the clarity is so good , it looks like it glows .  mouthfeel : medium body with a good carbonation .

citrus , earth , leaves , grass , fruits , all of this just blends together to one of the most perfect aromas i have felt . the taste isnt either all that bad , surprisingly balanced with fruity and citrusy notes on the one side and bitterness on the other with an intense taste lignering on and on , but oh my , is this a hop fix .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with a smooth velvety feel most beers of its style do n't have .
very pleasant grassy/flowery/hoppy bouquet ; probably one of the best-smelling beers around .  m : medium-bodied and decently carbonated .

s : smells great ! coffee , bourbon , chocolate pudding , bit of oak . almost a charred quality with burnt aspects , but very subtle . the flavors are all very subtle ... m : bit thinner than i would have thought , but as the beer opens so does the body . much better porters out there imo .  i bought this one at new beer distributors in nyc , a non-conditioned warehouse with a great a great selection ... im worried that its gone bad : a. pours a cloudy dark amber , with almost no head s. smells like sweet and sour yeast , malts , and a hint of bitter fruit t. sweet up front with some light malts , hints of sour , and finishes with a slight oakey , bourbony alcohol warmth m. medium and chewy d. not very , too sweet , this one is a sipper this beer does not taste very fresh -- it was aging in hot warehouse , probably for over a year , reminds me of a sweet bruin aged in oak barrels .

s : heavy on the citrus smells , and knowing this beer 's brewing process , with fresh oranges throughout , it makes sense . the wheat comes through nicely as well . not sure about that , but a solid wheat ale . might try it again if i was in the mood for a citrusy pale ale  mouthfeel is good . just under medium body .
a-rich dark brown with a nice dark tan head .  body is smooth , rich , lightly carbonated , and slightly decadent .

pours a sludgy pitch black color that is completely opaque with a one finger frothy dark mocha head . good retention , slowly fading into a thick lasting cap that leaves spots of lacing behind .  mouthfeel is clean and refreshing . light bodied with good carbonation .
very nice tan head that recedes slowly , leaving decent lacing .  feels really good on the tongue and throat though and goes down super easy .
nitro tap at fat heads pgh a : pours a thick dark brown almost black color with a thick two plus finger foam head . lots of lacing all down the sides .  medium mouthfeel with a decent carbonation .
the smell is outstanding ! smells of bakers chocoloate with slight roasted coffee and vanilla .  m/d - mouthfeel is good . medium with nice prickly carbonation .

smell wow , theres a lot in this nose ! dark citrus scents abound complimented by spices , honey , cherry , nutty , malty and caramelly smells . substantially complex . nothing noteworthy on the average finish . drinkability the taste didnt keep up with the smell , and while i enjoyed this beer , ill not go out of my way to look for it again .  m : nice mouthfeel . good carbonation , medium bodied .

s- the smell is quite complex . very rich aromas of cocoa , vanilla , and toffee with hints of rich , dark malt , malted milk balls , caramel , oak , and a touch of delicious bourbon-y goodness . t- the taste is n't quite as pronounced as the smell .  nice mouthfeel .
appearance : brilliant ruby colored pour with a sudsy white 1-finger head .  mouthfeel- very light carbonation and smooth .

very unusual and interesting . taste is a little flat . orange and orange cream , that 's what was cloying ! definitely worth a try based on its strong fruit character , but it 's not wildly complex .  smooth body is a bit under medium . super crisp , snappy , a bit drying .

tons of fresh grapefruit and orange in the nose . great hop flavor throughout . odd . nice addition , not a rye beer , but just a touch .  mouthfeel : medium to full , slightly dry , fair amount of carbonation .

a-red oak colored ... .looks impressive ... .minimal head ... s-fantastic aroma ... .bourbon ... vanilla ... oak ... some sour yeastiness that reminds me of cherries ... .brown sugar ... . t-flavors begin strong with vanilla , caramel , brown sugar , and bourbon ... .then a hit of slightly tart cherries ... .quite an interesting concoction and a tasty one at that . m-medium bodied ... .a little slick and sticky but this is a doppelbock ... not tremendously big but pretty close to what i expect in a doppel ... . drinkability-i like this ... certainly unique but tasty ... i 'd definitely buy this one again ... .  good lace , creamy mouthfeel , fizzy carbonation .

sweet and fruity ( berries ) aroma with malty undertones . very sweet and fruity ( berry ) flavor with a slight maltiness and a touch of hops .  mouthfeel/overall : this beer is just under medium bodied and very creamy . good here .
very nice .  medium body with a good bit of carbonation .

appearance : pours a dark , dark brown , that looks black in the glass and lets no light through . two fingers of a chocolate brown head that receded fairly quickly , but left a decent bit of lacing . it looks beautiful , but goes downhill from there .  m : very smooth . the best part about the beer for sure .
pours an outstanding , craggy head . opaque throughout the glass .  the palate is very smooth .

a : two finger width head , which dissolves into 1/2 . golden yellow much akin to a pear . has a strong lace that stays throughout the life of the brew .  mouthfeel is medium , smooth and soft . not great but a decent dubbel .

bottle : poured a pitch-black color ale with a dark brown color head with great retention and some very good lacing .  the body is ok , somewhere in the medium range and the carbonation is done right .

it poured a light amber/orange color a huge , foamy , white head filling half of the glass . head retention was pretty good and the lacing on the glass was excellent .  feel was full-bodied , smooth , with a nice creaminess . lacking a good balance of maltiness to offset the powerful punch of hoppiness .

this beer poured beautifully . their was a giant rocky pure white head that emerged when poured into an oversized wine glass that made it look very appealing .  i like the body and mouthfeel , but the distinct alcohol burn and slight metallic aftertaste distract from the nice simcoe hop flavor .

pungently hoppy aroma , a good amount of pale malt sweetness lending an almost candy-like effect . fruity and floral in it 's hoppiness , very bright and vivacious . fruity banana-like esters , a whiff of sweet higher alcohols .  the mouthfeel is good , thicker and only slightly carbonated .
big chocolate and coffee flavors in the aroma . taste is roaty malts , bittersweet chocolate , espresso .  medium mouthfeel .
amazing retention , this is one of nicest looking heads on a dipa i 've ever seen .  light bodied with decent carbonation it is a very easy drinking brew ideal for a hot summer day .

pours a huge white head , the color of the beer is a little lighter than expected . head retention is excellent .  m- very full feel . moderate carbonation . while well hopped , there was n't a bite in the mouthfeel .

fantastic smell . coffee , vanilla , creamy - truly smells like a creme brulee , also reminds me of a white russian drink .  the flavor does have raspberry hints but not what you would get from say an authentic framboise . this seemed like an amber ale with raspberry syrup added to it . the alcohol was noticeable which was strange for a 5.6 % brew . this was not bad but there was also nothing really good about this beer other than the appearance .
aroma was off the charts tropical , dried papaya , mango , citrus and dank green hop vegetation . for now i prefer dreadnaught , but this was fun to try .  good carbonation .

poured from a 12oz bottle into a dt tulip . the head quickly grows from nothing into a lovely cascade that spawns two fingers of some of the best retaining head i 've ever seen . rings , sheets , and specs of lace were left behind in a beautiful mess !  t : imagine a dark nutty , little toffee hefewizen and this is what you have here m : nice body , very drinkable and tasty o : a hybrid of styles but it was both tasty and appealing .
a : great smelling beer !  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation .

2009 ( now 8.5 % , reviewed on 01-12-10 ) : pours black with a nice tan head . the foam and lacing are a beautiful tan cream colour .  tastes like mocha syrup , very very sweet , then finishes with some alcohol burn . slick , low carbonation .

served in a saison dupont becker a-beer has big white fluffy head that leaves thick amounts of lacing . color is a pale gold with very active carbonation .  mouthfeel is full , with plenty of alcohol showing up .

nice grapefruit and apricot aroma mixed with a hint of pine and hints of bready malt somewhere in the mix . nice pale ale with huge amounts of hop aroma . i would n't mind a touch more body here , but i could also see myself cutting the lawn with one of these too .  mouthfeel is crisp and well-carbonated .

this smells amazing . t-comes in with a very bitter taste of creamy hops and a touch of grapefruit along with other tropical fruits .  m - good level of carbonation , not too light or heavy , nice feel .

smell : piney and lemony . some apricot also comes in , which is a pretty nice little change from the usual grapefruit flavors we 've been seeing lately .  the carbonation is moderate low which is appropriate for the style . the carbonation adds smoothness to the beer .

a : perfect amount of carbonation , 1.25 inch head with tiny to small bubbles . plenty of rising carbonation . dense yet warm and bright yellow in color .  m - light to medium body and moderate carbonation .
smells amazing . t - tastes of bourbon , oak , chocolate , vanilla , dark fruit .  nice feel .
the beer poured a cherry cola color with 2 fingers of frothy light brown head that seemed to last forever . it was a really nice looking beer .  mouthfeel is good , rich and creamy .
pours a hazy dark amber with a mountainous foamy head that exceeds my glass .  m : feels refreshing , average carbonation .

pours an absolutely gorgeous bright copper with a massive creamy off-white head that left huge amounts of beautiful lace on my glass . this is a truly beautiful beer . the flavour is very nice - do n't get me wrong , this is a very nice beer - but after the truly great appearance and wonderful aroma , i was expecting a bit more .  light bodied . mouthfeel is clean . finish is crisp .

a- darker than expected , a nice robust brown , not too dark , but several shades darker than i was picturing . nice , thin , but lasting head . very nice formation .  in the end there 's a soap hoppy bitterness ( more soap than hop ) that sticks on your tongue . in fact , i want to wipe my tongue and mouth off . maybe it 's something in the colorado water . i 'll have to ask coors ! for that reason , drinkability is low for me , although if this is your thing , it 's a truly smooth brew for the abv and the category .

an excellent aroma , do i detect a hint of chocolate , a hint of coffee ?  carbonation is active and lends a crisp , clean finish . very easy drinking but if i am paying import prices i am getting something a little more exciting .

its slightly-hazy golden body has an orange-ish cast ; and it teems gently with streams of tiny bubbles beneath a billowy white head that holds surprisingly well given it 's 11 % abv ; and leaves wonderful sheets of lace about the glass !  finishes dry and crisp . quite refreshing .

there is a unique quality to the taste and aroma of the beer that is too rare in brewing ( i would not mistake this for any other beer ) .  this possesses a pretty good mouthfeel , it 's very satisfying , but the flavour department is n't really home right now , it 's crisp , but the taste seems to be muted .
the head is beautiful tall with a dark khaki cascade . s lighter than expected .  feels pretty good for the style .

hazy ruby-red with a fantastic head that really sticks around . looking down into my snifter is like peering into the milky way .  jolly pumpkin boasts that their interpretation of a saison made the top 25 cut for men 's journal 's best beers of the us . this is a very dry and slightly sour version of a saison , a quality that helps downplay some of the lemony bite , and the final result is a beer that is thirst quenching , if not entirely satisfying . i 'd like to see this beer in a few years , as i 'm hopeful that captain ron and company will be able to broaden the flavors in this brew . until then , i 'll keep drinking la luciernaga , listed on this website as a belgian pale ale ; however , it is clearly a saison , and a better one than bam biere .

the head was impressive , like a big , white , soapy , sea foam from a heavy surf . the term lacing is insufficient , since thick clumps of foam clung to the sides of the glass like cotton balls .  mouthfeel was creamy and foamy , reminded me of beers with honey in them . drinkability is poor , i could n't drink a bunch of these like i could with hoegaarden .
red bottle , poured into a chimay chalice , of course , a : pours a dark red with a full off-white head with great retention and mild lacing .  medium-light bodied with a moderate carbonation .

the beer pours with a pale/light orange color and smells very unique . the aroma smells very estery and resembles grapes , apples , and also has a cidery scent .  nemesis is full-bodied , and very viscous . slick and chewy , with a dry , boozy finish . not a drainpour ... thorn telling rabbit to `` well , finish it up '' after a syrup chug victory in super troopers comes to mind , somewhat appropriately .
monty pours a nice golden amber with a gorgeous frothy foam head .  body is decent , light but not too thin .
strong hoppy citrus aroma , grapefruit , pineapple , very nice . smooth and creamy on the tongue with an almost immediate bitter bite .  the mouthfeel , however , is quite full .
good balance here .  the mouthfeel is pretty nice with some mild carbonation and a smooth overall feel .

it 's uncanny ... i would n't be surprised if bananas were an actual ingredient . still , the alcohol content is very well masked and the beer becomes more palatable as it warms ( i would recommend leaving it out of the fridge for awhile before even opening it ) ... or maybe i 'm just saying that because i 'm rather drunk after finishing 4/5 of the bottle .  crisp yet smooth in the mouth with tact carbonation ; nothing strong nor faint ... quite good . body is light enough for the style , but isnt ' watered down at all .

i poured very gently into a slightly wet snifter and the head just grew insanely big ( 3+ fingers big ) . light brown , frothy/foamy , and it did n't recede ... when it finally did start dissipating , it became very pillowy . body is pitch black . leaves good lacing .  mouthfeel was just right , light enough to be refreshing with enough heft not to be wimpy . the mouthfeel was actualy the best attribute of the beer .

it has a great smell , lots of caramel and toffee , also : coffee , chocolate , and some dark fruits . thick and rich scents . let it oxidize a bit and it turns out pretty nicely . this one is pretty impressive .  mouthfeel is very smooth with a medium body .

aroma- very nice . citrus ( oranges and limes ) and very fragrant blossoms . one of the best aromas i have ever smelled . flavor- malty , grainy , bready beginning follows through to lemony yeasty earthy flavors . some herbs/spices are present as well- the knids of things found on really good herb bread ( whatever that is ) .  mouthfeel is light , silky with a good hop bite . nothing special , but a good quencher on those warmer days .
as soon as i poured this beer from bottle to glass i got a strong citric , fruity aroma . almost like a starburst .  a good creamy mouthfeel does not make up for the poor flavor of this brew .

s : very roasty in the nose - grainy and quite chocolaty . dark chocolate and plain cocoa are quite prominent . a light coffee note , along with some faint charcoal . d : a nice , if somewhat unrefined , american porter from crooked river .  m - leaves a pleasant malty aftertaste with a hint of toffee sweetness .
bottle appearance - clear , deep crimson amber pour capped off by a fluffy 2 finger beige head . looks pleasant and rich .  mouthfeel is fine , nothing objectionable at all .

its a beautiful thing . a slight touch of chocolate but over all its all coffee .  the mouthfeel is thick and coating with low carbonation . the mouthfeel was my favorite part about it , i usually love big imperial stouts with this type of mouthfeel .
the nose was just superb . very fruity with citrus , and some other notes that i just could n't lay my finger on .  thick body , moderate carbonation .

do not know if it is just a bad batch after reading some of the other reviews ? nice amber color with a great head , good looking beer . looks is all i got out of this beer .  mouthfeel is smooth , medium to full bodied , medium carbonation .

very sharp appearance to this bottle . poured into tulip a : black as night . excellent head formation and retention . this is exactly how a stout should look in the glass .  m : a very nice , light and crisp mouthfeel that was very pleasant and easy to enjoy .

appearance : as served the beer is slightly hazy apricot color with a `` creamy fine bubbled off-white head that leaves foam on the sides as it recedes to about `` and then remains at that thickness for a while , fed by the steady streams of effervescent carbonation .  mouthfeel is medium , creamy and good though in it 's own right . .

smell : this is where the beers begins to show its true character and shine . initial hit is all chocolate , coffee , espresso . as it warmed the beer begin to show signs of dark fruits and a lingering alcohol smell .  the mouthfeel has medium-high carbonation and a nice bounce to it .

nose is wonderful - lemongrass , floral and yeast phenols . nothing funky or farmhouse about it , a 'clean ' smelling saison . light crackery malt , but the sorachi ace hops are the main show here , it seems a perfect fit for the beer . delicious . lemony hop flavor with some wheatgrass and clean pilsner malt .  really smooth , the consistency of this beer has been my favorite part .

s - like a pumpkin ale should but the spices of the rim made it hard to distinguish if it was the beer . t - awesome . the spiced rim made it a treat and even after i got around the rim it was rich in flavor without having too much hops which i hate in a pumpkin seasonal .  the mouthfeel was good for the style , not great and the drinkability was average because of the high abv and the fact that it is n't a great beer .

pours brownish-black , incredible huge , rocky and dense tan head that stays around for the duration , lots of lacing .  medium body pretty stragihtforward mouthfeel a slight bit oily and a good level of carbonation its to boozy for me to say i would want another one or that its easy to drink .

s : sweet and spiced . delicious . t : very hazelnut indeed , especially as the beer warms .  m : thick mouthfeel with strong taste of alcohol , the 8 % alcohol comes out strongly , not covered up well by beer itself .

s : hops . extremely aromatic citrus hops with some floral background . this is what an ipa should smell like .  tatse : too low on hops , even for an english ipa mouthfeel : medium light & true to style .
pours a beautiful dark reddish copper color with a monster head , so-so lacing , excellent head retention . great looking brew .  creamy mouthfeel . again , dry finish .
great looking beer !  mouthfeel is nice - thick and creamy .
this beer is one of the nicest looking beers i 've ever seen .  m - surprisingly good mouthfeel .
this poured an opaque black with dark tan head .  m : medium-full bodied , with relatively low carbonation tingle , and a syrupy feel .

quite complex for a never-before-heard-of beer . a nutty finish is touched with alcohol , but enjoyably so . drinkability : i did n't expect to find such a great brew coming out of this bottle .  ick ... m : heavy carbonation . good .
the aroma of the beer is a strong level of juicy american citrus hop , with a bit of malt coming out underneath it .  m-full bodied , syrupy and chewy , good carbonation to balance .

so much carbonation s - bright and lemony with a nice tartness . i really ca n't say that i 've had a better smell on this style , it 's phenomenal . if the taste follows suit i 'll be very pleased .  mouthfeel was very good and lively .

aroma : very yeasty . fruity , banana . banana bread . taste : brown sugar , cloves & spicy , yeasty flavours . it reminds me of guava ( a tropical fruit ) juice .  not what i 'd expect from an ipa m : feels crisp , not slimy .

a very dark red.it smelled like raspberry 's and you can tell it is very fruity .  sure , this beer is innovative ( although right brain brewery did a better version last year ) but the flavors just do n't mesh too well . the rosemary , sage and thyme are nice , but i swear the parsley ( which dominates with grassy chlorophyll ) was just thrown in to match the simon and garfunkel song . and , while i generally love saisons , the slight sourness makes everything even more confusing . while this is appealing from a novelty perspective , palate fatigue sets in about halfway through one beer .

poured into a pint glass , a deep copper color . generates about two fingers of off-white , creamy head while leaving a generous amount of lacing and has good head retention .  the mouthfeel is oily , allowing the hops to stick to the mouth also allowing the heat to remain . its an interesting beer and i am glad i tried it but it is clearly not something you would drink more than one of .

this is tough to review cuz it tastes like a nice hoppy ipa and yet i cant really taste any apricot other than sugarry texture on the mouthfeel . it does have a fabulous smell which i am now giving a 5 . seems like it would be a great one for the peanut butter combo that is so good with hoppy ipas  no hops . as it warmed , i got a little alcohol harshness in the aroma ( and something just a little funky ) - not terribly appealing , but under control and generally consistent with the style . taste : thick and sweet , but with just a little bitterness that seems more malt than hop . it 's ok . and it 's an ok bock overall , but did n't give me anything impressive . follow-up : i got to the bottom of the bottle , which contained some downright nasty sediment - large , *dark* particles , among the tan yeasty stuff . yuck .

s - a nice , malty aroma with notes of honey and bread . d - the malt and hop character are quite nice and the aroma is actually very enjoyable , but there are some significant flaws present in this beer .  ) m : clean , crisp , and refreshing .

n : excellent bourbon and vanilla notes waft up right away . finishes with whiskey booze , charcoal , dirty oak and notes of smoke . o : judging from the excellent appearance and nose i was rather disappointed with the taste and especially the mouthfeel . although it 's very complex it 's also very boozey and the mouthfeel is really thing for an imperial stout . warming effect is extremely pleasant . chocolate and vanilla notes are very nice but they tent to get covered up with the booziness .  m - dry finish with a medium body and medium carbonation . o/d - nothing overly interesting .
appearance - cloudy mahogany , thick cream colored head that laces incredibly .  m-creamy , syrupy feel , full bodied and chewy with a moderate carbonation .
great copper pour unleashes a bouquet of dry hopped nose busters .  m : thick , and oatmeal engrained . sticks to my teeth and relays a film on the tongue which does not disappear .
a- cautious pour yields a huge white head that mountains out of the glass . the beer is a bright gold color .  medium to full-bodied with a slick texture . smooth finish .

absolutely beautiful appearance once it settled down . it was poured from a widget can , meaning it was meant to be drunk straight from the can , so it initially poured all foam , but it eventually settled into an amber colour with a centimeter or so of off-white head that remained , and it was perfectly flat and uniform , like it wanted to be seamless .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

poured from a bomber into a pint glass , this beer pours with a smell like you are actually peeling a tangerine . i 'm impressed so far . picture perfect for a wheat . as i said before , it smells like an actual peeled tangerine . when you get your nose deep in there you get some effervescent versions of the citrus smells , and the constant flow of bubbles also shows a high level of carbonation . with the nose of this beer , i was almost expecting a mouthful of orange crush , but the citrus aspect was a nice balance rather than an overpowering ogre .  mouthfeel is fine though with good carbonation garnering some points .
