more fruit when it 's cooler : a really pineapple-y citrus tartness , then more resin and spice as it warms . alcohol comes through but it 's unobtrusive . taste follows up nicely on the aroma , with an aggressive hop bitterness balanced by a slight malt syrup and liquored-up piney character .  mouthfeel is full . finish is clean and slightly dry .

the smell is amazing , mocha caramel and hints of dark ghiradelli chocolates . nice to look at and warming on those chilly days , but a true stout will make you crave it all times of the year , this was not one of them .  the body is nice but i 'm still not crazy about this beer .

s : this has an incredibly intense aroma . the smell of sweet vanilla dominates . it quickly progresses to the vanilla noted in the smell and has a smooth sweet finish . it is good , but something i would n't drink too much of due to the sweetness .  mouthfeel - a nice medium heavy mouth that is very pleasant .

poured a deep murky dark straw hue with a full fist full of foamy white head . there was excellent retention and good lacing .  described as an ale that was just a little less bitter then an ipa , at the brewery . i 'm a little confused why this is albled as an american amber/ red ale . upfront though before the hops some mild caramel , toasted bread , great malt flavors and then the wooshing of hops to flip flop it to all bitters . finish is super overwhelming , hop bitterness .

smells fantastic with huge port and dried figs , some darker fruits as well , prunes and golden raisins . a very mature nose actually , with multiple layers and a suggested sweetness under it all . it all balances out with notes of red dessert wine , mainly port , but not as strong a prescense as in the nose , but still , it contributes with a very comfortable warmth in combination with the alcohol in the back .  mouthfeel is good and creamy . very oily and probably lots of dry hopping on this one .
smell : smelled great . can definatly tell that there is chocolate in it by the smell .  m - thick with a slight carbonation tingle , goes down fairly smooth .
1.5 inch light tan head after an aggressive pour .  the feel is smooth like honey , and buttery like an ale .

s- delicious nose ! creamy and solid cocoa and coffee and i can actually smell the peppers . really looking forward to tasting this beer .  a medium body goes down smooth if not for the syrupy vanilla .

aroma is huge amounts of hops , piny , citrus , resin , floral , with a hint of the malty goodness.flavor is crisp and bright , citrusy , spicy and floral hops , quite resiny , a little grainy , a , nice malty side , just enough to keep things in order , not a sticky mess or a bitter bomb , just a really nice show of hops , medium carbonation , full body , loads of sticky lacing , a long hoppy finish , this is very good stuff , i will buy this again .  feels highly carbonated on the tongue , but beer slides good down the throat with a slightly heavy weight .

12oz brown bottle poured into a nonic glass . clear , coppery/ruby color with lots of very tiny particles suspended . very generous off-white head , thick turning chunky with good retention leaves a pillowy layer and thick webby lacing down the glass .  m : actually very good if i can get by the skunk taste . medium body with just enough carbonation to give a creamy feeling in the back of the throat .
it pours with a nice two finger white head that has decent retention .  m - medium body , moderate carbonation .

s : amazing nose on this one , grapefruit , citrus , very intense t : the big hop nose had me anticipating a hop bomb , so imagine my surprise when a thick caramel malt body greeted me .  i 'm not an expert in belgian style ale 's but this reminds me a lot of a hefeweizen that 's been skunked , has way too much banana or was otherwise mis-handled . however , if you remove the banana aspects by switching yeasts to a more standard ale yeast i think it would be a great belgian . it 's on the malty side , but with a balanced hop presence . if you like banana you 'll love this one , it 's just not for me . it 's going on my `` i need to offer a beer to someone to be polite but i really dont know if you 're worth a good beer so have one of these '' shelves in the beer fridge right next to the bud light wheat .

smells of tasty nutmeg and cinnamon spice . it 's very bland , although i think the blandness my taste buds detected was influenced by the rich smell . really the only flavor you get is spice .  impressive carbonation .
nice ... real nice . nose goes beyond bacon ... lets go with whole smoked ham ... double smoked !  m- medium bodied with ample carbonation .

the aroma of this beer is so powerful ... spicy , phenolic . quite unique for my experience .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . moderate carbonation . mercifully , it 's not as nauseatingly tongue-coating as most malt liquors .

smell : juicy citrus and a big helping of biscuit malt . deliciously fresh and delicate . little bit of resin and bread crust . nice level of balance . taste : grapefruit and orange flesh . nice sweetness coupled with an almost straight bitterness . the fresh hop nature is assertive .  m : dry , crisp , well carbonated .

appearance - a cloudy orange-brown color . looks very rich and appealing smell - subtle scent of rich hops taste - strong and hoppy as an ipa should be , but i feel this one dies a little short .  m : very good carbonation , and decent viscosity .
poors as dark as anything i have ever seen , with a thin brown head , that kinda hangs onto the glass .  mouthfeel is good for a wheat .

the smell is excellent ; full of big hops and some pine . at first taste it showed me the big angry hop flavors i was craving and a little bit of that pine i could smell but the more i drank the more the pine came out and and became overbearing . now i do n't dislike a little pine flavor but by the end of the bottle this tasted like half beer half pine sap- yuck .  mouthfeel - fairly crisp and fairly smooth , too .
smells of pumpkin and spices , just as one might expect . overall this is a really nicely balanced , very drinkable beer .  mouthfeel is medium with good carbonation .
a : black liquid , gorgeous large creamy light brown head which .  m - solid feel . i can say with confidence that i enjoy having this beer in my mouth .

aroma of blueberry hit me from across the table , all of us around the table could honestly all smell it . very clear , bright smell - blueberries ! both the aroma and flavour were very authentic . no sythentic or syrop detected , true blueberry profile . it smells like blueberries before , and taste like blueberries after - but the whole middle part is beer .  m - actually quite good .
highly impressive is the outstanding pattern lacing all the way around the glass .  is tasty but is this an ipa ? m - syrupy and thick in the mouth , moderately carbonated .

seriously , there is a bit of graininess to it and a nice tart dose of blueberries . t : a little bit of a letdown after the nice aroma . the taste of the blueberries becomes a little sweeter and the `` beery '' aspects fall down .  mouthfeel- medium-full body with thick creamy carbonation .
fresh coffee bean smell intensifies as the beer gets warmer .  m : medium body with mild carbonation .
quite good aroma with nice complexity . the flavour is a bit weird when served cool but the aroma is great .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .
s : complex , strong , dangerous .  coupled with the very thick mouth , this is so thick in your mouth in sweetness and malts that i just ca n't finish my glass .
aroma explodes from the glass : creme brulee ( duh ) , vanilla , semisweet chocolate , cocoa , and brown sugar . otherwise a very good beer .  mouthfeel is soft with a medium-heavy unfiltered body .
amazing hop aroma of pine , citrus , resin and spicy hop notes . i was really impressed when i popped this open and took a whiff !  mouthfeel is thickish and syrupy with decent carb .
golden amber with fluffy white head that leaves nice rings down the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit creamy yet light at the same time .
loved the smell of this one . sweet toffee , butterscotch , toasted malt , light metalic edge . wonderful and inviting . wtf ? worth a try if the price is right .  definite bandaids .

bought a bomber based off some good forum talk . enormous hints of grapefruit and sweet malt . it really jumps out at you . it 's definitely hopped up t- delicious grapefruit and sweetness collide .  m : medium body with a heavy carbonation . a mild creamy finish .
22 oz bottle a : pours a clear golden under a foamy white head . excellent lace and excellent retention .  the mouthfeel was medium thick with a creamy nitro-like feel .

smells fresh and hoppy . glazed donut and pink grapefruit round out the beautiful bouquet . starts off tasting like those hallertau hops in liquid form ( duh ) .. follows up quickly with a punch of sweet malt sugars . rough finish and slight chalkiness take a few points off the overall.. $ 7 for 16 ( or is that 22 ?  m : creamy and full bodied . nothing harsh about it d : meh .

a tremendously chocolatey aroma . again , perfect . a sweet and bitter chocolate stout . it 's not as sweet as the nose would suggest , which i actually think is a good thing . it 's nearly perfect . chocolate lovers all over the world need to be introduced to this beer .  nice , full body with good carbonation .

s- this is the good part . pineapple , orange peel , coriander , nutmeg , egg nog , paradise seed , white pepper , sweet wheat and barley malt , yeast , alcohol . t- initially malty , with a canned fruit salad ( complete with the half-cherries ) that follows quickly . next comes pepper , a result of the paradise seed , i 'll warrant ... and tons of spice along with it . the finish is pineapple , strong alcohol , and orange peel . m- smooth and almost buttery at first , giving way to one of the most intensely warm and dry finishes i 've had to date .  smooth mouthfeel .

s - smells so fresh ! citrus , pine , herbs , and wet earth all come to mind . malt is a bit subdued but does add some bready flavors . an interesting and delicious ipa from sierra nevada .  m : probably the best part of this beer to me is the texture . while the sweetness is off putting to the taste , the round sugary syrupy feel to it is nice .

smell : very strong and exellent smell on this beer , i can smell it as it sits on the table like a vase of flowers . lots of fruity esters , white grapes , floral , bit of a white wine scent , beery yeast , barnyard undertone . lots of fruity flavor , white grape , some tartness , flowery/perfumey qualities , some musty/earthiness , bit of phenols and spice , hint of lemon , yeast in the finish . there are some flavors that i ca n't seem to describe as well , complex . mouthfeel : very effervescent , light drinkability : a very drinkable and truly unique balgian pale ale . very floral and bubbly , complex and delicious !  medium light body with controlled carbonation .
the colour is absolutely gorgeous - a terrific red-amber .  m : on the full end of medium with a low to medium carbonation .

i poured half of this 750 ml bottle into each snifter ( as indicated on the back of the bottle ) and observed a beautiful huge tan head rise form the dark , almost ruby body . the lacing was phenomenal , and the head took minutes to dissapate .  feels good in the mouth with a decent carbination for a dark beer .

22oz bottle poured into maudite stem glass . appearance : pitch black with thin caramel brown head .  m : not to thick , not to thin , the right amount of carbonation as well . probably the best part of this beer d : the more i drink it the more it makes me think of old coffee , i will not be getting this beer again .

a : pours a cloudy amber body with orange tones against the light . has a fairly generous 2 inches of head with pretty good retention , taking between 5-10 minutes to collapse into a lighter cap on top of the brew before i can start drinking .  carbonation is creamy but the beer itself is incredibly light and goes down smooth .
it smelled of cocoa , caramel and coffee .  the mouthfeel was good balance body and bitterness .
beautiful looking brew smelled like an american version of an oktoberfest .  mouthfeel is actually kinda impressive . best part of the beer .

large vanilla scent dominates the profile that holds malt , esters , and some hints of fruits . this is the vanilla scent all those candles and airfresheners strive for , or at least they should . strange .  mouthfeel is silky smooth but not too heavy .

this whole thing sort of reminds me of tiramisu with pecans sprinkled on top . just an awesome aroma . taste gets weird . almost nothing like the smell . man this is bitter . nice for a beer like this . i just wish this beast tasted as good as it smelled .  m : nice feel . feels good .

very complex and awesome ! t - light and complex ( no where near as potent as the aroma sadly ) yet delicate . amber and caramel malts with the slightest touch of banana and clay earthiness .  surprisingly , this has a great mouthfeel . lighter carbonation than your cheap macro swill means it is easy on the old tastebuds .
smells include bubblegum , allspice , cloves , and cherries .  good mouthfeel , fizzy but not foamy .

pours a jet black color with a thick and dense cap of light brown foam . good looker .  no mention of `` ipa '' . big sorachi ace presence dominates the flavor profile . so much so that the hop oils coat the tongue heavier with every quaff . halfway through the pint my palate was fatigued by the intense lime peel/citrus bitterness . hop bitterness overtook the rice and malt and held their presence to a minimum . this was my first experience with sorachi ace hops . this beer is out of balance and too hoppy to thoroughly enjoy .

the smell is near perfect - a blast of piny and grassy hops , like a walk in the alpine forests of aspen . the mouthfeel is nicely clingy and viscous , fixing that piny finish to your mouth . either this beer has gotten hoppier or my tastes have shifted in the last 18 months .  mouthfeel is very carbonated , nice and refreshing .
really a very complex and interesting nose on this beer .  once you swallow , it feel like the beer evaporates in your mouth , very smooth .

a - pours as a cloudy mesh that takes forever to rise to the surface form , ing a nearly perfect one finger whipped cream like head atop this pale copper brew . decent lacing coats the glass .  m : nice , medium body , perfect carbonation .

hazy apricot , with a dense slightly off-white head that wants to hang around .  the mentholipus becomes strong in the aftertaste and my belly is warm from either pepper or alcohol burn . thick body is making it hard for me to finish the bottle .

i ca n't say i 've seen a beer look this dark and thick , while pouring it was opaque before hitting the glass . a large foamy chocolate malt coloured head forms and lasts a long time .  m. medium body with high carbonation .

got a pitcher at the tap room , into a pint glass this beer is pretty much the exact same as the nitro can version . the only difference is that maybe the mouthfeel was a bit more chewy and thicker , and the darker malts were , well , maltier .  m : mouthfeel was fine . medium carbonated , medium thickness .
this brew pours with a beautiful amount of light tan foam .  mouthfeel is a full body with some carbonation .

the off amber-golden color is awesome and the smell is absolutely exceptional with hoppy goodness . if you just look at it and smell it then it is exceptional . the moment it passes the lips and then goes down your throat it lets you down a lot .  given its high ibus and abv , this is not meant for easy drinking .

a - looks great . caramel brownish-red swirling .  the gouden carolus triple ( it says triple on the label , not tripel ) frankly smells awful , sour yeastiness combining with a potent alcohol character to create a nasty odor . '' but it always is that bad , like ketchup , vinegar , and everclear mixed together . there 's a bit of unpleasantness , but there 's also your typical tripel breadiness . the aftertaste moves from the breadiness of the initial flavor into actual bread -- it literally tastes just i just ate a slice . it looks and feels like a good tripel , tastes like a slightly off tripel , and smells like bear shit .

first thing is the absolute massive duvel-esque head that forms with even the softest pour . it 's really quite beautiful floating atop the cloudy peach body of this brew and though it does dissipate in time , it still leaves a huge dimple filled marshmallow island and sporadic lacing everywhere and for the duration of the session .  a cheap porter is like a bad shortcut : seems like a good idea at first , until suddenly you find yourself in a swamp of murky flavors and wish youd taken the trouble of keeping to a more sure-footed path . the mouthfeel is plump and has good roll , and lace makes a solid appearance . the best thing i can think of to do with this beer is take the label off and tell your friends you brewed it yourself .

hazy copper body is topped by a moderate tan head that showed excellent retention .  lighter bodied for the belgium beers and surprisingly light for the 7.5 % . the carbonation is good giving a creamy body here , a touch too carbonated but very acceptable all things considered .

appearance this lager is orange in color , a little on the lighter side of the spectrum , with a wonderful , full head that pitted quite well . its one of the better esls that ive seen .  m- medium body and carbonation .

a : pours with a two finger thick , off-white and chunky head . the beer is clear , bright , deep amber with small bubble streams raising to the top - an attractive beer to look at . suds rings form through the duration of the drink , leaving a hard crusty film on my imperial pint glass . m : medium-bodied with a semi-crisp finish - highly vicious overall .  heavy body and thick smooth mouthfeel . medium carbonation .

appearance : big chunks of tan foam stick to the glass , lace thins out a bit but the retention is great . the pitch black colour lets no light through .  mf- nice level of lower silky carbonation in an oily substantial body .

22oz bomber $ 7.25 . sweet fruity citrus hop aromas with notes of peaches , oranges , pine and tropical fruits of delight . doughy aromas from malt also add to the pleasure . body is full , syrupy and slightly sticky .  md body and modest carbonation .
topped by a fluffy , bright white head that fades to a film leaving trails of lace .  mouthfeel is light/medium with good carbonation .
floral , perfumey hops fill up your nose to the point where you feel like sneezing .  m-good body from all that malt !

pours a spectacular , clear , brassy-hued honey . thick , creamy , off-white head sports great retention -- pockmarks appear as it slowly fades , leaving thick , nealry opaque curtains of lace .  m : biting carbonation , crisp and refreshing , light/medium-bodied .

a = great amber rich color , had to comment to wife right away that this was a beautiful color of beer . poured a slight head from bottle to glass .  the mouth is highly carbonated to an almost harsh level .
pours a cloudy orange color with a fluffy head that has nice retention and leaves some lacing on the glass .  very sharp and astringent . borderline flaw area .

a : beautiful ruby red/orange color with a thin white head made of lots of tiny bubbles .  when i walk in and see that all they have is watery lite/light beers i look for the darkest one . it has good flavor , but it 's so thin that you forget you 're drinking a beer . after a while the aftertaste begins to build up in your mouth and you wish you had some clorox to gargle . so this beer is n't great , but it 's better than drinking miller lite , bud light , or coors light all night .

s : smells of sweet caramel dominate , a sweet cream layer beneath and some nuttiness . t : a big sweet and toasted malt greets the tongue , along with some hazlenut , finishing in a pretty good bitterness .  upon pouring , there is absolutely zero carbonation . maybe if this was carbonated i might enjoy it some more , but there really was n't much there to win me over .

poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass . a : nice woody dark amber color with dense , clumpy 1-2 finger off-white head with sheets of lace down the glass s : mainly fruity malt esters and a bit of hops spice t : very sweet with lots of bready malt flavor with plenty of brown sugar , toffee , and caramel flavors layered on as well . hops make a minimal appearance , with a mildly earthy , spicy spot at the end .  the flavor is bland , it is very fizzy and quenches summer thirst when served ice cold from a can . a-b products are usually not my thing but the michelob line is alright .
loved the smell ! i took a whiff and my nose was treated to a cornucopia of scents . enjoyable , but not up to par with the smell .  quite thin and without backbone .

on tap at the houston flying saucer . dark ruby body that , in the relatively low-lit bar , could be mistaken for black with an off-white , moderately sized , and creamy head .  mouthfeel : kind of watery for a stout .

clear amber , with a rich and frothy head .  the taste was also a fairly sweet , but faint , chocolate , and was undone by the watery mouthfeel of this thin-bodied beer . the finish was also highly influenced by the thin body , and was short , watery and a little stale .

a-pours black with a rocky two finger mocha colored head that has very good retention and leaves copious amounts of lace . looks darn near perfect .  m - light , almost watery body . d - a touch too sweet , and the super thin body is too light on the palate .
beautiful black body topped with a full tan head and perfect lacing . looks better than i remember .  m ) tasted flat ... .

a crystal clear straw-colored pils that pours with a voluminous rocky head with just a touch of hop spicy aroma on top of fresh malt . i pour some of this beer and the head rapidly rises , i let it settle and pour the last third of the bottle to form a huge rocky head .  2000 vintage after the pour i came to beeradvocate to see if i had a bad bottle as this was flat as water . very dark , good taste but this is just a little to out of the norm for me as far as a drinkable beer .

appearance : a hard pour produced 3 fingers of tan foam that displays great retention .  had on-tap at the one-and-only wolski 's in milwaukee , wi . cheapest beer per pitcher , so we were looking forward to getting `` blatz-ted '' on something cheap . ) , so no high expectations . to be honest , it was n't too terrible , with good drinkability , not to mention a ridiculous name . not so fun- the hangover this thing causes is no joke

looked like glassware more easily associated with chemical experimentation . nice big frothy head , darker shade of golden brown , plenty of carbonation smell of sweetness , bit of spice , alcohol quite distinguishable taste is full , deep , malty , slightly spicy , but waaayyyy too sweet : like pure white sugar as opposed to honey feel is nice : carbonation feels soft in the mouth but leaves swiftly drinkability is surprisingly good for this strong ale , goes down very well overall mad and interesting presentation , great drinkability , but could be less sweet  the taste was very blah with a very slight taste of hops for just a second , with an after-taste of carbonated water .
pours a thoroughly dark brown/black with a brown and foamy head that reminded me of the head on a rootbeer float .  mouthfeel - flat . stale on the tongue .
jet black in the glass , maybe the ever so slightest crimson around the edges . giant dark brown/caramel frothy head .  mouthfeel : light and not much else .
significant carbonation behind nutmeg , allspice , vanilla , maybe some cinammon . an aroma experience . 9 % not perceived .  very thin with a dry finish .
appearance : great head and head retention .  mouthfeel is far too thin , indeed it 's rather watery .

review adapted from notes taken 10/18/10 appearance : a nice orange gold with some sticky yet thin white lacing smell : simply amazing - i honestly thought this was an ipa based on the smell alone - this is a citrus , resin , leafy , herbal , explosion of hops - smelled super fresh and delicious taste : very hoppy - again , i feel this could pass for an ipa - citrus , tangerine , orange , tropical fruits - bitter , dry , and almost leafy - moderately bitter - malts are very subtle - ridiculously overpowered by the hops , but there are some hints of pale malts and biscuits - barely enough to hold the whole thing together , unfortunately mouthfeel : very light - i know this is supposed to be a session ale , but i felt that the body was missing something overall : a very tasty experiment that i would like to see more of in the future i believe that a slightly higher malt bill would do wonders for this beer . however , it is still very impressive . i would be more than happy to see more breweries experimenting with hoppy session beers .  m thin .
a half finger head with lots of lacing on a clear light golden body .  absolutely no carbonation ! mouthfeel was way too heavy for this , as i had problems wanting to finish up .
really nice looking pour .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery , with none of the grittiness present in the nitro-bottle .
poured a dark chocolate brown with a monstrous head , dark brown bubbles which hung out for a long time with long spiderlegs after settling .  m - mouthfeel is rather thin and watery .

a - standard hand-pump appearance - gorgeous in any case . big creamy white foam settles to a thick persistent cap , leaving plenty of sticking lacing behind . lightly hazed bronze body .  finish is not crisp enough and the mouthfeel is too full bodied and too much carbonation for such a thick light styled beer .

this was an '04 it pours a dark red-brown with a tan head , almost like a brown ale .  a syrupy , darkly sweet malt and molasses tang on a watery , thin body . much more watered down than it looks , and disappointing overall .

very pretty beer , deep red/gold amber with a sticky , barely off white head . great cling and retention and slow , sparatic bubbles of rising carbonation .  low carbonation and a very thin mouthfeel .

the top is solid white , thick , frothy and never seems to completely go away . the appearance is just exceptional . smell is a little more subtle than i would have expected but there are definitely some spices and sweet malts present .  simply too light in body for the style .
very pretty mostly pinkish with a slight purple edge to it , nice pink head , very frothy and big at over 1.5 '' .  feel : thin and sweet with some bitterness but not much .

pours a nice dark brown with a creamy , half-inch head , which soon disappears .  i think that the lack of carbonation ultimately hurts this beer ; the extra carbonation would add sum much needed body to this beer , which would help balance the sweetness .

aroma : delirious perfection ! rich , roasted coffee at first , then anise , big-time , spice , molasses , dark rum , more , ... i drank it in the nose long and deep , savoring every sniff ! barely pierces the palate , this one , and the finish is far too short and forgettable . i want a good porter to wrestle a little with my tongue , and more importantly , to really get comfortable and rest happily on the palate , spreading flavor all around the mouth , creating an overwhelmingly unctuous experience .  carbonation levels are acceptable but for the sake of the caramel flavor and it 's classification as a porter , the mouthfeel is far too thin .
s : wow a chocolaty sweet milk aroma . m : medium body and decent carbonation o : nice beer !  carbonation is too high .

poured into my ayinger stemmed tulip glass a vividly clear cinnamon-hued copper color with a bulky , loose light beige head that settled at 1 '' . gorgeous smatterings of blotchy lacework all the way down .  maybe it was just the bottle i had , but the beer felt very flat in my mouth .
very dark brown black colored beer , with a smooth , well layered tan head .  the thin body makes me think that lack of adequate malt is the issue here .

appearance - beautiful browny-red colour , 1 finger of head which reduced .  aftertaste is very bitter coffee and incredibly dry mouthfeel : thin and watery , no body at all overall : well , nice to try once , not my favorite beer of this style at all

edmund fitzgerald pours a very dark , almost black color with nice ruby highlights when held to the light .  i think i 'd enjoy the taste more if it were n't for the super thin mouthfeel . drinkability and overall : while this beer has it 's strong points ( robust flavor being the biggest one ) , the mouthfeel is killing me .

appearance : head is delicious with nice lacing . head retention is strong . color is a cloudy brown with hints of amber .  this beer is way to carbonated for my liking i do n't know if it 's the bottle i got or if this is normal .
pours pitch black with health viscosity . huge deep mocha head forms and holds for quite a bit .  entry seems flat and introduces a mouthfeel which seems thin and uninspired .

out of the bottle this brew was a light copper color with a huge , foamy , tan head . great retention and it left sticky ribbons of lacing all down the glass .  a bit uneventful up front and not very complex , quite thin in body and overly carbonated ( reflected in low points for drinkability and mouthfeel . she has a theory that the champagne-like carbonation of the unibroue beers makes them more appealing to drinkers in tropical climates .

pours a lighter amber with a half finger of white head . moderate lacing . looks great .  light to medium bodied with a thin watery mouthfeel . a light , refreshing taste despite the watery mouthfeel .

poured 4-6c into a tulip ... in hindsight not the right temp node serving vessel : ) a : deep reddish brown and crystal clear . lots of nice head that laces beautifully .  carbonation is almost nonexistant after the pour .
picked up in montreal pours a slightly hazy golden/orange , thick off white head , very rocky , nice chunky lace , good retention .  only downside is the lack of body here .

hazy to milky shining yellow body with a perfect head and a banana-nose . looks and smells great but i had my doubts due to the rice listed among the ingredients , which finally passes unnoticed . actually the whole keeps a rather low profile except for it 's looks : not very malty or yeasty , drinkability is smooth as is the finish .  fizzy body that detracted from the taste .

appearance- orange-amber colored pour with a 1/2 inch head . head is nice and chunky with excellent staying power and excellent chunky and patchy leftover lace .  fair warning : it smells like the brewers trapped a skunk fart within the bottle , and , to swill it between your cheeks reminds me why i need to get my cavities filled . it 's an unpleasant , sour taste that warms all too quickly . however , i think it pours pretty well and has a great taste when drank from a glass . the aromas are much more pleasant when let out of the dank green bottle . as far the appearance , it seems a little too much on the light side for a beer that tastes as heavy as it does .
a great smelling beer , but any good flavor that it might have is squelched by the acidic mouthfeel .  feels thin and needs more flavor , tad watery feeling in the end .

aromas begin and end with rich , fresh raspberry fruit aroma with a touch of tartness . the best fruit beer aroma on the planet , period . the tastes ca n't quite compete with the aroma but is still quite stellar . raspberry compote with just the perfect balance of pleasing sweetness and tartness ; no where near the level of a sour ale or lambic , really just as it says on the label , a fruit beer . overall i really enjoyed this experience . i can say , quite categorically , that new glarus raspberry tart is a phenomenal , incredibly delicious beer . it 's a damn shame all fruit beers ca n't be this good and that they do n't distribute out of wisconsin .  m : surprisingly light in body live a clean , watery finsih .

deep amber `` coffee '' appearance with a huge spitting white head that left an impressive lace .  this beer is way too carbonated , it ruins most of the other aspects of it , this one is very hard to enjoy .
s : excellent , good smell of toffee , nuts , and oak , with a hint of vanilla .  f : not there at all . way too watery for a scotch ale and the carbonation is near non existant .

pours very dark with a big pillowy brown head . nice cascade effect if poured down the center .  341ml bottle poured into tulip 26/6/11 a particles chunk sized to tiny suspended little guys floating around in a dark amber body with very little carbonation and zero head or lace even after an angry pour s peaty candied fruit with some vanilla and booze , smells sweet with some smokey toffee t a little grapefruit rind on top of what i smell but little in the way of a dipa , lots of barrel aging evidence but not heaps of peat but woody whiskey notes are there for sure m flat and watery , this one has no life to it at all , there 's a medium body but nothing else o as a dipa its pretty average lacking all the characteristics i normally associate with the style , as a strong ale or a similar style perhaps something more but as a dipa pretty average i do n't get the barrel aging dipa 's and i doubt i ever will , i did n't mind this beer but grading it as a dipa is a little hard . other then the complete lack of carbonation this could do well as something other then a dipa but what can you do ?

the deep red/mohagony body of this brew is topped by a thick off white head with a good amount of lacing left behind .  very light and watered down . any good flavors fade out quick and leave a tea-like taste in your mouth which equals a bad aftertaste .
it pours an awesome looking murky copper colour with a big creamy head that 's sticky as hell . this one just looks damn good all around .  mouthfeel is way too weak , no carbonation .
a - pours a golden orange opaque color . thick white rocky head .  very little body or mouthfeel .
giant tan , rocky and creamy head that was fully lasting . the lacing was phenomenal .  thin mouthfeel , no aftertaste .

they are typically very fresh tasting and create that killer guinness cascade upon pour . creamy head lasts through the pint ( 14.9 oz actually ) .  appearance : gold with a 3/4 '' white head that dissipates quickly ; transparent smell : blueberries with a malty lager smell taste : blueberry mixed with a pale ale ; little bit of banana flavor too mouthfeel : very thin : ( drinkability : light and pleasant flavor so you could do two or three in a night
pours a virtually opaque black with a great tan head that sticks around .  mouthfeel is thin and tinny .

appearance : copper-tone red , thinly and attractive ; the head was a definite mtier -- idle-some and busily foamed . looked wonderful . taste : exactly what a pale ale should familiarize with ; it was agreeably pure : the right essence when you take a swig .  the mouthfeel is watery and awkward .
half way through i am noticing some epic sticky lacing ! this beer is awesome to look at i can give it that .  mouthfeel was surprisingly thin for the style .

lunacy is a real looker . a cloudy amber/caramel color lies beneath a creamy white head and waves of billowing lace .  taste : far too faint in the mouthfeel to really count as a porter , this enters the mouth limply , and exits just as weak . really needs to have bigger body to be a porter worth it 's roasted barley , and this ai n't working .

appearance : tall , frothy , meringuey head with great retention supported by a column of bubbles , rising like little sparks , in the center of a light , peachy whisky-colored body .  kind of watery overall , almost no `` mouthfeel '' beyond the simple taste .

appearance is excellent - apple amber with a fantastic , 2 '' foam that could hold up a set of stripper 's ta-tas . beautiful drapey , pimitive lacing . none of this dissipating vanishing head - i still have some foam at the end of the glass .  thin body , weak on wheat malts and a fluid mouthfeel . nothing off or offensive here , just understated for the style .
pours a dark copper color with a nice lace a head .  the body is way too light and this beer could use a little higher mash temperature .

poured from the bottle into a tulip . pours a dense/hazy orange with a nice 2-3 finger white head that fades to a nice pillow with excellent lacing .  it is thin and watery , with just some lingering salt in the aftertaste .
a : very nice looking beer .  no mouthfeel . very watery and hardly any body .
superb . t- in the mouth it 's the bourbon that grabs you first .  m - disappointment . light viscosity and fullness in mouth matching the original smell .
pours a clear , bright golden with a big bubbly white head that lasts quite awhile .  m : thin and watery .

this beer looked great , right from the start . nice nitro cascade as it was poured , resulting in a 2 finger thick creamy head that left a heavy lace from start to finish . color was an inviting gold/amber .  same with the mouthfeel , it was forgettable .

smells like old orange , sweet cherry , some wood , perfume , vanilla and oak , very soft and sweet with a bit of belgian yeast .  m : thin viscosity and low carbonation . o : a decent schwarzbier that could benefit most from a better mouthfeel .

exactly as the style should appear ; jet black body incapable of allowing light to pass through it , cocoa-colored head that leaves a generous amount of lacing behind .  and the carbonation is too high , like a warm coca-cola in the mouth and thats not okay with me .
aroma : absolutely invigorating grapefruit aroma rolled in oily lemon hops . the finish is acrid , though not intense .  aside from the bitter , it tastes a bit like carbonated water .

*best by date - 09/07/11 pint glass a : lake erie monster pours a glowing golden straw color with a nice 2 finger creamy tan head . slightly hazy and some decent window drapes of lace .  lightly bittered , yet overtly dry due to the high attenuation . thin in body and only a notch above watery . a simplistic and unimpressive dunkel .
retention is pretty nice and there is tons of sticky lace . good looking brew here .  m : low due to virtually no carbonation .

perfectly clear appearance , amber-brown in color . a beige - nearly tan - head lasts right to the last drop .  smells of light hops , corn , and water . tastes average really , nothing good about it but nothing bad , better than most american macro brewed lagers , especially the light ones , i think it gets a bad rap but it is n't that undrinkable .

pours a one finger frothy tan head over a crystal clear orange and rust liquid .  body and mouthfeel were watery and light . carbonation was adequate . overall this is absolutely an entry level stout not far removed from ye olde classic guinness ( but for guinness has a far superior body and mouthfeel ) .
pours dark red with huge fluffy pink head , awesome colors , awesome retention with thick cotton candy lacing .  mouthfeel - very thin .
a good looking beer , no doubt .  thin very one sided mouthfeel .
appearance : pours a beautiful clear mahogany with tow fingers of tan head and good retention .  very flat on the tongue .

pours a thick black with a duvel-esque dark tan head which lasts for ages and settles down to a permanent half-finger at the top of the glass .  mouthfeel is way too light , especially for the style .
poured into a snifter , this beer pours brilliantly clear copper with a thick , ample off-white , beautiful !  feel is very very thin .

the smell is roasty-toasty with one heck of an alcohol-laden cherry on top . mmmmm . the taste itself is something of a letdown after the smell . the mouthfeel is very thin and the flavour is dominated by the roast character , without too much sweet malt to back it up .  m : too thin .

thanks to jrnyc for this one look : pours a pitch black with a brown ring around the bottom of the glass great 1 inch head and excellent retention and some very nice circular lacing .  1 dimensional . flat bland like water . creamy .
nice amounts of light tan head , which lasts almost all the way through a half liter pour .  mouthfeel : very effervescent . light , close to watery body .

s - insane . rum , wood , hops , hops . this is really different . tarted very hoppy and shifted to the rum sweetness . just find a few people to share it with because it is definitely overpowering .  this is a pretty dark lager.it 's honey colored , but the head is small and disappears fast.this smells a little hoppy , with some fruitiness and yeast.this is n't a bad tasting lager.it 's hoppier than most with a hint of cooked veggies or fruit.the big problem with this beer is the weak head and the poor m/f.this is very weak and watery , which leads me to say i do n't think i 'd buy this again .

appearance - a fine caramel amber pour . lots of sticky light mocha head , two fingers at least . puts up lots of weaving lace patterns on the glass .  mich ultra amber , 5.0 abv , 114 cals p12ozs reviewed as a `` light lager '' , poured bottle & gt ; tulip style glass a 4.0 - solid amber/malty/copper color , very unique for a light lager , very small head gone quick s 3.5 - almost non existent smell , but was not skunky like some american light macros can be t 4.5 - clean , mild balanced amber taste , much more taste & body that many american light lagers , a must try on the taste for this light beer , it 's a surprise mf 2.0 very light body , high on carbonation , very thin body d 4.5 - this is a very solid session light beer , great price , great on calories , and great on abv @ 5.0 % .

a : the beer has a fabulous appearance . the liquid is completely opaque and extremely dark.the head is thick and dense , standing in at nearly two inches thick .  m : the mouthfeel is dull , lacking in any bubbly , effervescent aspects .

appearance : this beer pours a black with a slightly red tint to the edges.following the liquid i received a very profound tan head.from the side on my glass i can see thousands of tiny bubbles , but from the plan veiw it is a creamy , pillowy cover.lots of laceing.exceptional appearance for a porter in my opinion .  syrupy , lifeless mouthfeel is incredibly viscous and oily that it lends very little to this brew , even though it 's expected .
it 's not overly complex , but it smells wonderful . t : the taste is very similar to the smell , but not as impressive .  this beer is very weak , thin and watery .
pours a very nice amber/orange color . very impressed by the apperance of this brew .  m - under carbonated and watery .
beautiful amber color .  slightly flat . ends up feeling a bit watery .

anderson valley poleeko gold on-tap at world of beer coconut creek , fl a- best head i 've ever seen on a beer . golden hazy color gradient in pint glass , white head 1.25 '' . m- wow , so creamy a smooth with the great head medium-to-light body ale . d- very drinkable and only 5.5 % abv i really could have had a couple more that night .  very thin mouthfeel .
appearance : deep black in color with a thick 2 '' milk chocolate colored head .  the palate feels thin for the style and the flavors that it 's supporting .

a- this one pours out a glowing golden orange colored body with the slightest haze to it . the head is just about a full finger and takes its time falling . a solid wall of lacing is left behind .  not much to it really , kinda thin .

perfect light golden amber with a massive 4 finger white head that melts to very thick sticky lacing .  m - the biggest disappointment of this beer - very watery thin mouthfeel that makes it seem like a macrobrew with the ipa flavor added in .

beautiful opaque yellow body . you cant see anything through this beer ; its like looking at a glass of off-white orange juice .  tastes sweet and watery . becomes somewhat more flavorful as it warms , but still fairly watery . very drinkable , though . and very cheap .
murphy 's irish stout used to be my favorite beer . and it 's dark , with a ton of head on it at all times .  nor is there any body to it , thin and watered down seems to be a theme here .

a : it pours a hazy orange color with a huge , three finger head of ocean foam that holds and laces exceptionally well .  overall considering there was nearly no carbonation , this is a good example for the style . although there was no carbonation , there was a medium body .

pretty nice overall .  it 's looks nice enough with a pitch black body . again , there 's the big , black grains along with a distinctly english yeast milk or cream-like flavor . but there 's an awful astringency that throws it all off and makes me frown and put my glass down .

this brew pours a brassy tea color with a one inch creamy tan head that dissipates down to a respectable skim .  m - i think the mouthfeel is where bud really missed the mark . thin , watery , and fizzy .

pours a golden apricot and honey hue with a vigorous inch head subsiding to a complete coating of bubbly lacings . very attractive hazy with rustic sediment .  the taste has similar notes of the aroma but the beer is so light feeling that it is distracting to the drinker . i want a fuller feel . however , the feel and finish just destroy this beer .

appearance - pours an opaque black into a belgian glass . slowly she falls , unevenly , leaving a peaks-and-valleys landscape across the top of the beer . thick walls of lace adorn the side of the glass .  m/d : a light body that is thin and watery .
an exceptional looking beer .  slick , somewhat buttery mouthfeel ; the diacetyl really detracts from the texture .
the coffee aroma in this one is stellar . the aroma indicates dark chocolate and strong vanilla notes . love the aroma ; reminds me of kbs .  m : rather unbalanced .
this is a very nice looking beer .  however , this is very thin , making this taste rather stale . this beer is light in body , moderately carbonated and a little watery to boot .

substantial head with rings of lacing .  its light bodied and very effervescent and a touch watery . its an okay beer but lacks many body and malt characterstics that i find desirable for my sessionable , drinkable brews .

smells very good .  the aroma is lackluster , the flavor is completely out-of-balance , there is no discernable mouthfeel and the only reason i can think of to try another one is to make sure i had a representative bottle .

perfect pour , nice thick fluffy head , dark brown color with a reddish hue when held up to light .  theres a fruity sweetness up front , and a very light hopiness . overall , id describe this beer as watery and uninspiring.another gimmick beer .

22oz bottle the apperance is definitely exceptional . a nice hue of red mohagany . big frothy , frothy head with plenty of brussels lace to go around ( the whole glass ) .  does n't really linger in the mouth at all . it says it is a light beer , and it is certainly light . this is a slight step up from water and just as easy to drink . nothing really interesting about this lager .

a- a very hazy , luminescent , orange liquid . a few floaters and a lot of streams of rising carbonation . the head is thick , fluffy and white . very pretty and hearty looking .  m- thick , syrupy , and too sweet . carbonation is too low for my tastes .

very pleasant . i ca n't remember trying a beer where the taste was so far separate from the smell .  t : more of the same from the nose , and as watery as expected . m : not much going on here . i imagine leaving a club soda open for an hour and then drinking it would feel about the same .
pours with a red-brown/mohagony body topped by a thick foamy head with a good amount of lace left behind .  this beer tasted and felt watered down .
it generates an awesome glow even though it comes across as being thick as paint . a marvelously picturesque color !  m - i was not impressed . seemed watery and thin .
the aroma however was very nice . malt , plum , vanilla and a hint of licorice .  m : carbonation is fairly high , but it does n't stop this beer from having a pretty unpleasant mouthfeel .

beer is a nice clear amber color , with a decent head .  it steals the flavor as the mouth is filled with bubbles rather than beer . the aroma was fantastic for this beer , the foamy mouthfeel highly reduces the overallness of this beer .

bottle , cue 'life is a highway , ' the name reminds me of that classic snl sketch , a : pours a translucent gold to light amber with a huge pillowy fluffy ice cream cone like head , with great retention .  watery . mild . not much other than the head and lace . almost no character . what finish ? go elsewhere if possible .

pours into my stange with a nice fluffy white three finger head . it sticks around for awhile before leaving some very nice lacing behind . this beer is pale pale gold , and very clear and bright . it looks like a stalwart german pilsener .  m - watery , thin , and weak .

leaves some great bright white lacing down the sides of the glass . awesome initial appearance .  m : the major weakness here . the taste was off earlier i feel due to the watery nature and the lack of carbonation d : an easy drinker , i could down a bunch of these .
poured a cloudy light copper hue with a four finger white foamy head . there was excellent retention and excellent sticky lacing .  m : thin d : so thin , it is almost like water !

possibly the best smelling ipa i have ever sampled .  a carbonation that reminds me of ginger ale and the consistency of pumpkin bread , though a lot thinner . consistent throughout , but a little dry on the back end , rolling into a soft , creamy finish , with the exception of the lack of body .

appearance : great looking beer !  mouthfeel/drinkability- disappointingly watery in the mouth , and very lightweight overall . frankly , it does nothing to improve or accentuate any aspect of the beer at all ... it just falls flat . interestingly , the carbonation of this beer diminished so quickly over this tasting that by the end , it was almost completely gone .

poured out a decent head that never receded , and left spotty traces of beige lace . guinness always has great head retention , but head size seems to lack when served from anywhere but the tap . the color is a solid opaque black .  this beer was not meant to be on cask , or it was not treated properly , because it has zero carbonation .
the head on the other hand is awesome . huge 2 '' frothy white head . fades pretty slowly and leaves some awesome lacing .  the mouthfeel was thin with a bitter finish .

thick , pitch black liquid ( if i can call it that ... ) with a mammoth crown of sticky , brown foam that takes a while to settle . head is the consistency of meringue .  giant stiff beehive of a head in a tall pilsener and a shorter glass . very flat in the mouth , though . quite drinkable , but carbonation melts in your glass , not in your mouth .

the bouquet is very potent and says `` hey , im a fermented peach . '' i 'm trying to decide if it was too sweet or not .  mouthfeel : light body , weak carbonation that ends up being a bit lifeless .

pours a two finger frothy tan-yellow head over a crystal clear red-amber liquid . head settles to a very sticky layer that left stellar lacing .  thin to medium bodied , though undercarbonated and a touch metallic .
but the aroma is brilliant ! it 's just like opening a large bag of fresh whole flower hops - pungent , grassy , floral , lightly minty and a touch citrusy .  almost a watery feel .

a - medium-tan colored head starts out at an inch and a half . it retreats at a medium pace to about a half inch where it levels off a bit leaving a thick hummocky top . the body is dark brown , and when held to light has a purplish hue .  on tap at rb ... this pours a super dark gold straw but its still very clear ... the head is totally dead , nothing at all there ... the taste is also super light , ca n't taste anything but light skunk . its not bad per se just boring , why drink this ? overall , an easy session beer but nothing special .

a : poured a light , faded black with great carbonation , nice dirty white , creamy cap from the nitro pour s : a berry nose meshed with some cocoa and roastiness .  the mouthfeel is medium but the carbonation is nonexistent .

brown in color , surprisingly big head . really nice looking for a flanders beer .  body is thin , too thin for my liking , it tears apart the balance of the beer and make all the nice spiciness and candysugar appear to be less intense .

poured into a snifter , this beer pours hazy deep golden/light amber color with a thick , clingy off-white head that retains nicely and leaves copious amounts of lace .  m - starts off well with a medium body and carbonation , but it quickly dies to almost no carbonation , and a watery mess .

this beer , while fruity and slightly girly , has a unique and definately uplifting flavor . would rather this than a glass of any red vino ! there is a great appreciation for belgium and its lambic here in the cincinnati area , unlike back home in california where they are too stricken on alcohol % over flavor .  mouth : first thing that just destroys the experience is the mouthfeel .

magic hat jinx is a hazy amber ale with a huge , fluffy , cream coloerd head . the retention and lacing are excellent .  i think the lack of carbonation did n't allow the flavor to fully penetrate my tongue upon first sip because the following sips are great . the carbonation is missed but i guess thats not a problem with taste . m= really smooth i wish it had carbonation . the carbonation problem is the only downfall for this beer . could be one of the best in the world but , well as i already mentioned it has no carbonation .

a -- pours a near black that only shows color when held directly to the light . full two fingers of light brown head that recedes slowly leaving a layer on top of the beer and thick lacing down the pint glass . awesome .  mouthfeel a bit thin for a stout with too much carbonation .
appearance : deep coppery-brown color . a careful pour yielded a generous one finger of dense , creamy , off-white head . excellent head retention .  the taste , is quite watery and thin .
a good amount of both head and lace remains .  the mouthfeel is hurt by excessive carbonation and fizziness .
very nice . t : some spicy notes at first followed by a somewhat piny bitterness with a touch of citrus rind flavor .  m - light body . slightly watery finish .

color was true dark copper that would be expected from an octoberfest but the expected qualities ended there .  m= this is the biggest problem here i think . it finishes too dry and the carbonation is too low .

pours an opaque , deep copper rust color . head is exceptional . if it was n't for the weak nose of the beer i would be forced to delve into drinking it before the enormous thick ice-cream like head settled . several small icebergs of thick foam and a little belgian lacing is at that remained .  mouthfeel was the most disappointing part - it was thin and watery , and a little fizzy .

pours a dark brown with some red highlights . has a large tan head that has good retention before settling to a thick cap . moderate amount of sticky lacing is left on the glass .  the feel is too light and way too unassuming . like drinking watery seltzer water .
the yeti imperial stout poured pitch black . an amazing dark creamy coffee looking head . loads of lacing is left on the glass .  the palate is thin .
a great pour . very dark and a brown head . i will stick to the tap version of this stout .  beer was incredibly flat and not full and heavy which caused a poor mouthfeel .
i smelt chocolate and coffee and at this point i was very intrigued and ready to try this beer .  mouthfeel is thin and watery and low on carbonation .

the inappropriately named `` session beer '' pours a not too sessionable-looking clear copper color with a large whitish head and great lacing . looks excellent really .  it had hardly a mouthfeel to it so i suppose i 'm being genorous in my rating , hardly any of the `` chewiness '' i 'm used to in porters .

pours amber with a very full head and excellent lacing .  it 's bitter but not much on the hop flavor side n m- very thin with medium carbonation o- this is very underwhelming , beer is thin and one demensional .

6th glass has a beautiful color spectrum : deep , rusty garnet to brilliant grenadine to bright peach - like a reverse tequila sunrise when held to light . head hardly diminishes and settles into a blanket of lumpy foam .  no mouthfeel but easy to finish and perhaps order another .

poured light orangy amber , cloudy with bubbles continuing to rise to the top , almost white head , leaves truly stunning lacing , plentiful , striated , scatered and fine .  however , it also had a quite a watery mouthfeel which was remiscent to me of yoohoo , which i did not greatly appreciate . mouthfeel was watery .
pours a brilliantly clear orange , topped by a nice one finger fluffy white head , takes its time to recede .  mouthfeel the carbonation also failed to show up at crunch time .
amazing . taste is also sweet and citrusy .  almost no mouthfeel whatsoever . this beer needs more body to be truly drinkable . too damn thin .
great retention .  mouthfeel was thin with a caramel-nutty flavor in the mouth and none of the cloying sweetness that i had experienced in the others .

from a 750ml crown top bottle . very dark ale with a beige head , with a good head retention .  i only drink this beer because its what my grandfather and father drank . it can be found around the tri-state if your local beer store really likes you and will order it in . as a whole it is the typical macro , not much taste , typical appearance with little to no head to speak of . but , with that being said , this is my everyday drinking beer and goes down nice without any cheap beer side effects .
this puppy pours out the thickest most opaque black i have ever seen .  watery mouthfeel with no sweetness left on the tongue .

very nice aroma . inviting .  my major criticism of this brew is the carbonation - there 's virtually no carbonation in this thing , and it leaves the beer a bit flat ( no pun intended ) . do n't get me wrong - i 'm not asking for a tingler here , but this thing could use some more carbonation to give it a bit of life . something needs to be done about that mouthfeel before i give this one another look - just too flat .

torpedo into a pint glass color is charcoal black with finger 's thick creamy head .  it gave me cotton mouth a bit . the mouthfeel was disappointing . it looked well carbonated but it drank like it was flat . this beer would 've been ten times better if it had better carbonation and increased complexity .

pours really dark brown and separates beautifully into a thick creamy tan head and a very dark almost black beer . good retention s - not very strong .  bottle from jessethehutt - atleast 4months old pours jet black with 2 finger tan head that has good retention and left plenty of lacing smell is coffee chocolate milk and some roasted malts behind all that taste - wow kind of a big let down - coffee then sour milk - has some roast and chocolate but that sour milk flavor is awful mouthfeel is watery thin - thinner then nitro guinness !
awesome pitch black pour with a nice brown head .  m - strangely , for a ris , this is pretty thin . too much carbonation .

appearance is really dark , not quite coffee colored , but close .  m - big mouthfeel issues with this brew . the carbonation issue i noted earlier is especially apparent in the thin , watery feel this beer has .

had this , remarkably , from a cask at the hopyard in pleasanton , ca a-pumped a light , clear amber-brown with a thick , rich delicious looking creamy almond colored head , 1.5 fingers thick . left a rich sticky lace that clung to the glass all the way down from top to bottom as i drank it .  perhaps this is partly attributable to its flat mouthfeel that has very little to offer in the way of carbonation , less so than one might expect from a german white .
poured out the bottle this beer displays an attractive head of foam that takes awhile to settle out .  not much in the way of a mouth feel , but almost watery though .

12 oz bottle poured into a weizen glass a - red like color with 3.5cm of light tan head .  there was no hazy color ; no dough/wheat/spice in the aroma or flavor ; no spicy/tingly mouthfeel ; and no chewy/thirst quenching finish .

a gorgeous , white , cascading head sits on top of a bright apricot body . body is very cloudy , but shows golden highlights around the edges . damn good retention and decent lacing .  way too thin and carbonated . the mouthfeel really limited my enjoyment of this beer .

awesome appearance , just as i expect from troegs and stone .  m : ugh . all the spicy , fruit goodness of the body is gone and i 'm left with a weird sticky , slick cloying taste in my mouth . worst part of the beer .

a : poured a wonder black with a nice thick dark tan head that settled to about half size quickly then slowly worked itself away .  this is a fizzy raspberry soda . funky and thin , this is a waste of time .
smells completely delicious , but i could n't drink too much of this .  m - the feel is maybe the worst part of this beer . it 's grainy , harsh , and rough .

i can see belgian monks scratching their heads over this . sm : rich chocolate , wonderful subtle roast , caramel , nuts , and toffee . a moderate strength aroma .  the body is quite thin and watery and is lacking in the body that i would expect from a well made sour beer .

stayed with me all the way down to the last drop , leaving an amazing ring lace . check out my twitter for the picture , it makes me very happy .  there was a slight hiss when i popped the cap , but there 's really no carbonation which detracts from the creamy , silky mouthfeel .

black as midnight with a caramel head this is impressive as hell . you know , there is a lot of hype surrounding the fff stuff and i 've always wondered if it was warranted . this beer is a dessert .  kinda reminded me of natty ice , ok maybe its not that bad , but it really did not have much flavor m - thin , very fizzy d - oh ya .

750ml bottle , split appearance : photogenic pour in hopleaf tulip - bright orange body , steady white cream head with full retention smell : tart apricot , oak , spicy yeast taste : really nice - tart apricot , peach , funky , white pepper , belgian yeast , tangerine , bright caramelized sugars .  mouthfeel : watery .
it smells of roasted nuts and expensive chocolate .  very little carbonation , making it pretty watery .
s : it smells like lemon , banana , pepper , and the lovely belgian yeast character .  m - light ; very thin , watery mouth feel .

brown-black body with a milk chocolate/cola head that is bubbly and holds steady quite a while at 2 fingers . lots of lacing also .  a pretty weak mouthfeel , similar to the big guys , kinda disappointing .
pretty good . 2.5 t : unfortunately , the taste is n't nearly as good as the nose .  thin mouthfeel .

s : oak comes through above the sweetness and candied fruit . t : personally i could taste the oak at a good level , and this was the best thing about the beer .  it subsides a bit after a while , leaving it flat with a little acidity . meh .
pours a very nice , somewhat coppery color with a very decent head . perfect looking pint .  m - sudsy o - i think it a good ipa , but my first choice .

33cl bottle poured into my st. bernardus goblet ; a - cloudy amber almost brown color . there was a stiff 2.5cm tall off-white head that disintegrated into pillowy lumps that looked like a scale model of a group of sand dunes s - yeast , spice , cherries , apples , oranges , lemons , and grass .  m - holy cow is this thin . and watery too .
jet black . nice thick lacing .  the mouthfeel is thin and sudsy .
a- clear light amber with a full finger thick head of foam .  weird . mouthfeel : disappointingly thin and transparent .

very refreshing sweet porter with a hint of vanilla a- dark garnet red , almost completely opaque . beautiful creamy 3 inch head that leaves great lacing s- not much smell but do get a vanilla and roasted caramel malts t- taste is great .  mouthfeel is certainly damaged by the high level of carbonation .

appearance - looked good nice and dark with a good head . was the best part of the beer .  a little malt and a little hops , pretty plain . the flavor has a caramel malt character , but seems really watered down . hmm . flavor would be ok , if they would n't use so much water .

smells just about perfect for the style - lots lf sweetbreads and undeniable belgian esters . drinks all too well , thanks to each sip being charmed along by that wonderful smell and finish .  it was carbonated but all of it vanished . tastes like dead yeast . watery and thin , floral .

it smells great , btw .  light to medium feel that is for the most part flat . nearly all of the beers i have had on tap this year have not only been way too cold ( to the point where the mug that has been hanging on the wall is even overly chilled ) and the beer is almost completely flat .

330ml bottle poured into my darkness glass ... black pour with a huge light tan head . really light for such a dark body , good retention and lacing ... subtle but pleasant aroma , lots of roasted malts .  mouthfeel of quickly fading , no presense beer .
looks pretty nice in my snifter , almost too good to drink , almost .  feels a little thin and watery -- and oddly gritty .
pours a hazy copper gold with a big creamy off white head that retains well and leaves a lot of lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and a bit watery .
it has a really nice nose . the flavor is very solid as well .  thin , watery and bland .
the dense , rocky tan head holds very well and leaves some spotty lace .  the body truly was its downfall , perhaps a weak setup with the carbonation at the tap ?

nose is amazing : breadiness , sweet cookies , roasted coffee and light citrus hops . lots of dried fruit . surprisingly hoppy - drying , bitter roasted malt rolles right into the citrus hop backbone . good , not great . overall , a really solid brew , although honestly a bit of a disappointment . next i got ta get my hands on that racer x ...  mouthfeel was kind of thin and it tasted like drinking watery cocoa powder mix . i guess that what bugged me was its thin mouthfeel and its lack of ooomph in terms of flavor .
a - a bit of red around the edges , tall creamy tan head .  too much carbonation , as bubbles were racing from the bottom of the glass throughout .

beer is yellow and clear . forms an impressive head that falls away to a monolayer and leaves lacing on the glass , nice . carbonation is moderate and steady . looks good . we went there one night and drink 2 $ of red stripes in 2 hours .  the mouthfeel also loses it for me .
great head retention with a lacing ring of head for every sip . exceptional looking beer . smells good , but not very strong .  m/d : light and watery feel with lots of carbonation .

sierra nevada northern hemisphere pours out a clear but light brown color into a snifter . i get two fingers of off white head that have some legs and leave amazing lacing .  the mouth feel was dryer than expected with too much carbonation .

the aroma is intense . smells quite lactic with an alcohol boost . interesting . smooth with a lite burning sensation on the finish .  mouthfeel : hugely carbonated , paired with such a strong showing of sour lemon it 's almost sickening . no real body on this one , just very light and carbonated .
it 's very nice looking color , a darkish , red tinted .  mouthfeel is pretty poor , actually .

a - dark , black as night with a ridiculous amount of foam despite a rather gentle pour . solid 4 to 5 fingers of light brown foam sits on top of just a smidgen of beer . head slowly fades and leaves chunks of foam on the glass .  mf 2.0 super carbonated , thin body , watery taste , hints of grainy salt texture ?
aroma : mild but pleasing . chocolate ( malt ) , smoked oysters , salty sea air , wisp of smoke . incredible after it warms up .  mouthfeel : it 's very thin . it feels a bit watery .
reviewed 12/22/2005 ( 750ml bottle ) : pours a golden cloudy yellow-orange colored body , with a very large white head , and good lacing .  body was surprisingly thin .
a huge beige head forms and takes a minute to recede . spiderweb looking lace is left all the way down the glass .  m : way way way too carbonated .

good creamy head and dark rich appearance , as you expect from a porter .  feel : it honestly feels like a light fizzy water with a bit of prickly sensation , not all that enjoyable really . it has a nice flavor , but it does n't work well with the thickness or the level of carbonation and it really makes it almost undrinkable .

brilliant straw colored with an enormous dense frothy rocky aroma is yeasty and earthy , with hint of spice taste is warming and solventlike .  mouthfeel is watery , thin and has no body . bubbly artificial carbonation is harsh and not welcoming on the tongue .

serve from a bottle to a wine glass as it 's the closest thing i have to a tulip glass a-fabulous ! the greatest beer i 've ever seen .very thick head , probably around 4 fingers thick , murky gold because of the unfiltered yeast left in the drink s-this is tricky .maybe i 'm still not at that level to understand smell but i got some slight banana smell , some hops t-fabulous down the throat !  mouthfeel is way too thin and bubbly for me .

a : pour a cloudy glowing tangerine color with a huge , thick , billowing , and oily looking light cream colored head that took forever and a day to fade into a rocky layer of foam while leaving a sticky network of dense lacing down the glass .  most disappointing is the watery mouthfeel .
this is one of the best looking beers i have seen , it pours an obsidian black , 100 % opaque with rich amount of creamy tan head , pretty dark colored head .  mouthfeel is thin , insubstantial .

smell is great , some vinegar , caramel , nice funky sourness , vanilla , oak , brown sugar , tons of fruit , great sourness . mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation , very dry and astringent finish , totally overoaked . woody character was too overpowering , enjoyed every other aspect of this beer though .  t : a mix of esters and hop bitterness m : thin and oily d : i 'm a big fan of most lost coast offerings but this ipa is not one of them .

pours a gorgeous amber/rust river red with a nice tan head that dissapates into the glass . lacing is great , frothy foam will stick to the glass as you partake in this creation .  big sweet amber malt scent , touch of bitter hops mixed in there . the thinness immediately strikes me . the malt and hop tastes are kind of underwhelming , there are some fruit and yeast tones that are fairly pleasing though . im not really a major amber guy to begin with , but this one seems like they forgot to put in half of the ingredients .

* rich , malty aroma full of raisin , chocolate , cloves , fruit ... wow . i 'm finding it hard to get past the high alcohol content , but as my palate acclimates to it , i 'm struck by a very sweet , almost cloying malt . i know there 's more here , but i 'm overwhelmed by the alcohol and malt alone .  its hard to believe i enjoyed the taste so much even through the harsh mouthfeel . this beer is way too carbonation .
pours into the glass with a rich dark amber , almost blood red , body topped by a thick head with a good amount of lacing left on the glass .  the mouthfeel was woefully thin for the style .

pours amber with a a 4 fingers+ fluffy sand colored head . great lacing & head retention s : a hint of caramel & malt t : sweet malt & herbal/piney hops ; finsihed prickly & semi-malty mf : light/medium bodied with pricklyness , not balanced drinks average , this is a different beer than bottled version ; i 'm so confused ?  tastes very flat , not what i remember of this brew . where is the carbonation ? aftertaste is good but wish this had more body .
this is a brassy colored beer with a massive , spongey , head that leaves a rich and layered lace .  mouthfeel : light , almost watery .

smell is unusually impressive for what i expect of this kind of beer -- fruity , especially blueberry and mango notes , with hop tang and characteristically malty flavors evident in equal parts . mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , a little thick ( like a dark lager ... blech ) , and generally mediocre .  mouth feel is your basic club soda .

a-this is the absolute blackest beer i 've ever seen . decent head , but it 's hardly noticeable because of the body .  nothing offensive taste wise , a tad bit of hops and more of the caramel malt , but the mouthfeel and body are just too weak/thin to make this a great red ale .

12oz bottle pours out a nice amber brown color and almost looks like a cola during the pour . the pour produces a slow growing brown head that hangs around for a while and has nice lacing .  dayton , oh alefest : a small sized ivory head that consisted of fine sized bubbles that was mostly lasting.the body was clear and carbonated.the hue of this beer was yellow and the nose was malty , hoppy and also of alcohol.it had a lingering bitter flavor and it was also acidic.this beer had a burning sensation as i was drinking it.there was virtually no lacing with this beer .

pours a hazy yellow-orange colour , nearly opaque with sediment . medium-low carbonation evident in the glass , and the massive creamy three-finger hefe head that i expected to see .  i had the same problem as shiloh ; absurdly huge head and way too much carbonation .

pour : light , golden yellow , hazy translucent with the thickest , creamiest , beaten egg whites stiff peaked head i 've ever seen on a beer . does n't lace the glass so much as frost it as the head lasts til the final sip .  very watery feeling . no body at all . the carbonation is very low . feels like bleech .
good looking beer with a large head that leaves impressive lace all the way . looks tasty .  m : really watery mouthfeel .

pours out to a hazy burnt orange , forming a tall off-white head with superior retention and nice thick sheets of lace .  a typcial american lager . pours out with medium light carbonation and a short lived head . refreshing flavor of a straight forward lager - a touch on the watery side , but none the less tolerable . this is supposed to be the beer of texas , and if that is so , i would n't mind living there all that much . recommended for those who like macro-regional brews .
pours pitch black with a good three finger of puffy light brown head . the head lasts a good ten minutes .  m : medium body . old krusher finishes way too crisply for the style .

s : light honey and caramel , lots of nose , some sweet , roasted nut smell as well , very rich and complex t : light caramel touch , then overwhelmed by dryness from the carbonation , and bitter and citrus hops .  mouthfeel : sorry ... . i do n't like the watery , yet creamy nature of these nitro cans ... give me some more carbonation .

bottle into a tulip glass . pours a slightly hazy golden hue with a massive billowing head of white foam that rises eagerly and holds on to the walls of the glass with all its strength as it fades and settles to a thick pillow on the surface of the beer .  the mouthfeel was thin and the drinkability was okay although i did n't really like the beer .

poured a hazy , orange/copper coloured brew with an incredibly nice head that produces some beautiful lacing . looks absolutely marvellous .  mouthfeel : not so good here . thin and watery with a dissatisfying tingle of carbonation , but not enough to break the beer by any means .

mild aroma in a black body with an energetic head of light brown fine bubbles . near the top of the head below the beer line a continuous flow of small bubbles can be observed .  not much in the way of carbonation , which wold have helped this beer , imho .

a : hazy blonde , thick foamy head s : malts , grains , with a bit of sourness too .  sticky and drying , but completely flat . very tasty , but so flat that it hurts the beer tremendously across the board .

2 fingers of white head that leave great lacing and half a finger of head . very impressive and delicious looking .  this is definitely a flavorful beer , but the feel in my mouth and stomach is pretty similar to that of your bmc lager . thin , watery , and generally just empty feeling . overall i 'd call this one very average .

( served in a chalice ) batch 002 a- this beer pours a dark warm brown body that is opaque at the top of the glass but lets light in the bottom 1/3 of the glass . there is a thick creamy light tan head that last and last and sticks to the side of the glass like a milkshake . there is a strong carbonation of microbubbles supporting the big smooth head .  m - really , really watery d - this beer had a very weak flavor and a watery feel to it .

poured cold from the can to a foothills brewing 12oz pilsner a deep dark milk chocolate brown nearing black with a super badass finger and a half micro bubbled creamy head with incredible retention and a sheet of lace to the rim .  cloying sweet & way too thick for my taste . it tasted more like a thick tart wine than a beer - carbonation , where are you ?

it is impressive .  taste is ok - same roasted chocolate malt that was in the nose again no coffee - weak flavors - i have had stronger porters mouthfeel - a very thin light body with low carbonation overall - maybe this was past its prime or i got a bad bottle - but after drinking this i would not buy this beer again

a : looks magnificent in a glass , burnt yellow-orange , with a big puffy , white head with oustanding lacing as the beer is drunk .  malt dominates the nose , sweet as if honey , clean and fresh to the senses with a sweet malt laden start , top is thin and a bit to watery for me .
pours extremely dark with a light brown head .  the mouthfeel is pretty disappointing .
the tracktown was a good looking beer . it poured an orange hazy color with an aggressive 2-3 finger foam head with some sweet sticky lacing .  medium mouthfeel way too thin for a wee heavy .

poured into a tulip glass . a- amazingly beautiful fluffy and rocky head .  the beer seemed to `` fizz out '' a little when i poured it , and as i drank it seemed thin and definitely lacking carbonation .

nice aroma . the taste leaves something to be desired after a wonderful aroma . still a very nice flavor , though . remarkable smell , predictable taste .  m - there 's a huge amount of grittiness and carbonation burn - it actually makes it very difficult to taste anything , as all i get is tingle , burn , and grit .
great looking medium-copper colored brew , with an excellent , full , frothy , creamy head , which just would not go away .  mouthfeel - thin and under-carbonated .
