bight hazy yellow ... nice white head ... .the nose is very inviting ... seems to suggest a nice balanced spicing profile ... corriander , some orange peel , perhaps a little nutmeg ... outstanding aroma . taste is a slight let down ... more bitter than i like my whits ... a lot citrus on the taste ... also some peppery like spices.. body is on the ligth side of medium .  m : carbonation dominates . watery .
it poured a midnight , oily black with a dark , dark khaki head .  m= flat as a board . wish it was carbonated but there is nothing here . flat as a board .

appearance drags down an otherwise fantastic beer s : rich pumpkin pie spice , cinnamon , mace , nutmeg & some pumpkin flesh as well , superb nose t : follows the nose ; nutmeg , all spice & general pumpkin flavor up front , along with some herbal hop bitterness . one of the better pumpkin beers out there imo  pretty sweet on the tongue with plenty of dms butterscotch flavors . does have substantially more hop bitterness than your standard macro , but the label claiming 'pilsner ' is a bit farfetched . loses alot of carbonation when poured into a glass and imo tastes better straight from the can .
pours a dark , ruby-amber with a nice tight , foamy tan head that sticks around throughout the drink almost like a nitro pour .  mouthfeel - not so great . it does remind me of soda .

poured into a pint glass , this beer has a massive head that stays throughout the beer.the nose is of sour cherries , caramel , brown sugar , with a hint of chocolate.i think this bottle might be older , because there is very little hop presence other than a blunt bitterness in the finish.it is relatively dry with dark fruity esters , brown sugar , and caramel/chocolate , a little bit of coffee as well.as previously stated , the finish is bitter , slightly leaning toward a coffee like acridity.as the beer warmed further , in had a slightly citrusy hop finish though .  mouthfeel : thin for a dark beer but syrupy to the point where it sticks to your cheeks .
22oz bottle into tulip glass . a -- -it poured black with a creamy tan head .  this is one beer that truly needs some carbonation .
a - pours auburn-orange with two fingered off-white head . dissipates slowly , with nice lacing . very impressive .  mouthfeel is very weak and watery , however , leaving me quite disappointed .

pours a brilliant , bright copper color ... almost orange with the assistance of some natural light . a full finger and a half of white head ... fades fast , but leaves behind some thin lacing that covers the glass nicely .  m- way too watery , especially for a stout d- its average , not bad but not great . this beer is way too thin , too watery . this beer has potential , especially if they give it a little more mouthfeel and a little more cocoa .

rusty brick red with an amazing head , the kind that rises an inch above the rim of the glass and retains very well .  the taste , mouthfeel and drinkability are the same : watery , thin , and forgettable . i was going to whip up some extra spicy hot sauce into some chips and salsa to pair with this beer , but i do n't think there 's a hot sauce on earth that would justify how watery and thin this beer is .
this beer pours an absolutely gorgeous blackness with a darker tan foam that hangs around quite well .  the mouthfeel is unexpectedly flat and heavy on the tongue .

a- pours a very dark brown , nearly black ... some light seeps through , but not a whole lot . head is 3 finger , a very light brown ... nice and puffy . lacing is fantastic , all the way up the glass .  mouthfeel too thin , in my opinion .

this poured out of the foil covered 750 with ludicrous foam . the bottle was split in a duvel glass and a maudite glass ; the head was to the top of each and almost never receded . finally , there appeared an iceberg of chunky white tan foam in the center .  mouthfeel was terrible . very thin and unusually high in carbonation .

750ml capped brown glass , high-shouldered bottle . a slow , careful pour produced 4 inches of fluffy tan head ! opaque brown and seems clear .  s - um ... leaves something to be desired , a bit skunky and reminescent of a pharmacy t - much better than the smell let on , pleasing malts , a little corn m - not impressed with the mouthfeel , really light , carbonation comes through too weakly for a adjunct d - totally average , no place for taste in this bottle
pours a hazy reddish amber brown with a huge rocky off white head that retains well and laces the glass .  way too watery for a stout .
another beer from this brewery that is a beauty to behold in the glass , crystaline bronze and glowing .  m - the porter felt a bit flat and thin in my mouth .

s : pumpkin pie in a bottle , it 's pretty incredible . massive spices : cinnamon , clove , nutmeg , etc . as it warms a bit , it really does taste like pumpkin pie . the malt shows itself first followed by a really faint hop appearance .  mouthfeel is a disappointment , with a nearly flat , slick character . [ note : upon opening the can i noticed nothing that would indicate problems with carbonation . aside from the weak mouthfeel , this is a solid take on the style that first got me into craft beer several years ago ( altbier , that is , not `` american amber ale '' as denoted on this website ) .

epic lacing & near epic head retention s : faint woodyness & even fainter figgyness t : figgyness & leafy hops , & some mineral hops as well up front .  this is canada 's version of budweiser and it does n't even come close to the king of beers . the only thing different in their process must be where they are getting water from . the water from lake ontario must not be as fresh as the water in st. louis ( or where ever my local anheuser-busch plant is ) because this stuff tastes like pond water .

16.9oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a massive light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a good amount of retention .  mouhfeel is crap , with absolutely no carbonation to add any bite .

bottle poured into a tulip . ( a ) - pours a cloudy orange amber color that produced a good fluffy off-white head with some good retention .  carbonation could be likened to seltzer water . body is light , thin .

pours pitch black , no light shows through whatsoever , looks for real like crude oil . unbelievable depth in this beer , with a new flavor coming out every few moments .  mouthfeel imo was extremely light .
a beautifully looking beer .  but the body was too thin and the flavors were too weak .

look : deep brown with traces of red throughout 1/4 inch head and no retention smell : dark fruit notes especially dates and prunes some molasses and a sweet malty nose .  fewer hops than corona as well . bland , bland , watery , bland . there are worse beers out there .

a disappointingly small amount of lacing is the only thing keeping this beer from a perfect appearance .  m- thick . extremely rough . i 'm puckering as i type this , mixing my beer with a bottled water .
pours a rich black , with a finger and a half of head , and the most prominant lacing i 've seen for a porter .  very watery body .

the beer is a deep mahogany red , topped with a huge off white head . excellent clarity , with a couple slowly rising carbonation bubbles . great head retention , standing about half an inch thick all the way through the pint , leaving tons of clumpy lace rings all the way down .  m - feels very thin and watery .

s : booze , coffee , booze , chocolate , booze , earthiness , and booze . hugely alcoholic , and yet somehow also hugely appealing . t : cloyingly sweet here , and that 's about it . crazy . m : thick , sticky . o : i was really excited to try this beer ( obviously enough ) , and was n't sure what to expect . all the complexity of the aroma got washed out in a massive wave of underattenuated sugar , so much so that it resembled beer-flavored pancake syrup more than actual beer .  also suffers from a somewhat odd mouthfeel , finishing with a dryness that offsets oddly the sweetness that it starts off with .
nice retention on the head , amber color , crystal clear , with tiny carbonation bubbles .  mouthfeel : thin for a red ale .

it 's a reddish orange color , like a bright sunset with a small white head . good retention and creamy pooling on top of the beer .  mouthfeel : it is watery and needs more body , it really does n't have a finishing burst of flavour .
one of the most gorgeous beers i have ever seen .  m : thin , watery , not really much to talk about , but not horrible either .
appearance - super cloudy yellow body . decent to low stick .  m : low carbonation , too bitter for a chocolate stout d : i wo n't be buying this in the future .
appearance is deep , dark brown , almost black with ruby highlights . lots of light brown lacing throughout .  damn near flat . with ample carbonation , this would be a nice experiment .
a : this beer looked great , but looks can be deceiving . a wonderful clear amber color , and a thick white head .  mouthfeel is probably the weakest point . light body .

aroma is like a whiff of pumpkin pie . cloves , cinnamon , nutmeg , ginger , and biscuit make it happen . a pretty good pumpkin ale from cottonwood but i wish the taste had the punch i found inn the aroma .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

a - bottle conditioning manifests itself as a frothy fist-full of head . nice wide range of foam density that leaves creamy peaks . great lacing with chunks of froth clinging to the sides of the glass .  feels rather insipid and severely lacking . this really is missing body , sweetness and depth . it tastes watered down and not particularly inspiring .

a beautiful deep , chestnut pour with a billowing pale tan head is what you get here .  m- thin and watery in the mouth ... which was completely unexpected from the appearance . the carbonation was moderate and reasonably soft ... but the thin mouthfeel was a big turn-off .
reddish brown and and cloudy . moderate head with good retention and lacing .  watery thin body , low carbonation , and somewhat tart finish .
11.2 oz served into a pilsner - 2007 bottling - cellar temp appearance : pours a very dark brown with red highlights .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with no carbonation .

pours a light copper/orange colour topped by a thick beautifull head . this beer has an excellent appearance but i think that that 's just it . it 's a shame really such a beautiful beer to be `` killed '' by the taste and aroma .  in terms of mouthfeel , this beer was way too carbonated .

amazing . perfect tall white head on top of golden straw colored lager . i have not seen a pilsner look like this since i left germany .  mouthfeel : very water , very highly carbonated , very unwanted .
appearance : clear yellowish orange color with a 3 '' fluffy head that lasts . some nice lacing developed during the session .  mouthfeel is thin and watery with a mouth-puckering astringency .
the brew poured up a beautiful black body with a 2 finger off white head that was a beauty to behold .  mouth feel : thin , with aggressive carbonation , a bit rough .

aroma of nutmeg , vanilla , fresh bread , and nuts . i feel that st. bernardus prior 8 might have been much more flavorful than this ...  the mouthfeel is too thin , though heavy and oily , and somewhat under-carbonated .
none the less : i love the way it looks , ... rock solid tan head of two fingers , dark molasses color with a bit of red in the right light .  mouthfeel : pretty much like straight water .
good lacing leaving little beads on the glass .  mouthfeel : overly carbonated and thin . not the best and close to the worst mouthfeel on a winter warmer i have had .
poured dark brown with a tan head.aroma dark fruits , nutty , toffee .  m : flabby , sticky and syrupy , with enough effervescence to make it tolerable .

this beer pours out of a beautiful ceramic bottle . included is a rubber seal , but i 'm pretty sure that any ba wo n't need to use it , as they will finish it in one sitting ; ) the color is a dark complex brown , with layers and floaties much like a quad .  m : very thin and astringent , not full at all .

all aromas are mellow and quite nice . t : a water and slightly wheat flavored beginning gives way to a pina colada tasting brew that finishes clean and with the slightest of hop , yet not enough to round out the mildly tart and fruity taste . the smell is damn good though .  mouthfeel - kinda thin , kinda lifeless . some weak bubbles make it feel kind of watery , too bad .
in my glass , this beer sits handsomely , almost black , with a finger-thick dark brown head that slowly recedes to a disk . solid s : another relief - no obvious infection !  thin bodied beer .
pours jet black , complete darkness .  light bodied with a thin texture .
a wonderful , frothy head grows on this and breaks down in cascading rolls . very nice .  carbonation is way over the top , too prickly .
clear sharp orange amber , nice tight tan head with great retention .  mouthfeel is thin for the style , and drinkability is average .

wonderful balance . the bourbon really makes a showing , playing carefully off the roasted , charred malt flavors here .  in the mouth it is thin and watery lacking concentration of flavor and depth .

a : poured a dark ruby color with an inch of fluffy caramel-colored head . it had long-lasting retention and left huge gobs of foam down the sides of the glass .  as for mouthfeel - holy carbonation , batman . so spritzy in the mouth it 's like soda , which really detracts from the flavor . mouthfeel is medium-bodied otherwise but it 's too overcarbonated .

a : dark brown , almost completely black but when held up to natural sunlight beautiful cranberry red color shines through . nice half finger layer of mocha colored head that quickly dissolves .  not even much belgian character m : thin ... would expect a bigger mouthfeel d : this one is drinkable ... but not great per the style .
nice smell . t : lots of dark fruits .  mouthfeel equals water thus it is easy to drink but not enjoyable to drink .

overall , the everthing else about this one particularly looks great for appearance , color , and smell .  mouthfeel is too lightly carbonated ; almost flat . too sweet , strange mouthfeel and an unappealing lactic aftertaste .
a - thick , well layered head which was maintained throughout . extremely dark .  the palate is thin .
a : crystal clear with plenty of fluffy white head . adequate retention for some very nice lacing .  this has a water thin mouthfeel too .
the smell is now very deep , rich and fruity with a subtle alcohol undertone .  mouthfeel is watery - like any other light beer .

out of the bottle it looks beautiful . dark walnut colour with a monster big , good looking head .  taste is also on the light side with lots of sweet malt , a quite thin body and no discernable bitterness at the end .

aroma is very complex with robust figs , plums , brown sugar and port wine notes . makes me expect a fairly boozy beer from the nose . a pretty solid beer that i enjoy a lot , but the nose seemed to promise a little more than the flavor delivered .  mouthfeel is extremely thin/watery .

appearance beautiful dark copper body with a fluffy , lacing head .  thin and watery feel yet quite quaffable with no negative flavors . surely better directly from the bottle removing the look and aroma from the equation where it 's smooth and pleasant .
pours super dark almost black with tons of frothy mocha brown head that takes time to dissipate .  mouthfeel is too carbonated and thin .

poured into the perfect pour samuel adams glass a- very pretty ! pours cloudy and clears into a red-copper with a clean white head s- some cherry , not a whole lot else ... t- some tart cherry up front and a full malty finish m- full bodied , thick , good carbonation d- limited availability limits its mark here for me , but otherwise it 's something i 'd come back to quite often !  well for a macro beer this one 's probably my favorite . but for a good old quantitiy beer it can 's be beat- does a good job cleansing the palate between real beers , is never offensive , it 's always on sale cheap , and is well tolerated ( at least by me ) meaning it does n't go straight through me like a lite and has a curious lack of the crappy physical effects most macro beers have .

pours with a big billowy tan head that grows well after the pour . the top of the head looks like a milkshake .  i felt it was mostly malt but had a thin watery mouth feel . nothing special but went down pretty easy .
gorgeously clear amber color with a creamy tan head . this is a beauty to see in the glass .  it is water with a lingering bitter finish . it was also pretty flat , but enough to keep me interested .
smell - great smells of citrus and hops . flowery .  very thin body with high carbonation . the weak body dooms this brew .
wow ... fantastic aromas going on here ... citrus , cherries , raisins , cinammon .  mouthfeel was a thin tasting carbonated drink - at times with an oily feel .
smells nice . very nice .  the mouthfeel is just wrong . fix the mouthfeel and get back to me .
appearance : the thick foaming light brown head leaves big sticky chunks in the glass , the colour is a shade or two from pitch black .  m/d : mouthfeel sucks , like weak carbonated water .

poured into tulip style fischer glass rapidly to yield a pale yellow body and a good fluffy white head that fills the glass from the 12 ounce serving .  mouth is pretty thin and flat feels like drinking a flat coke to be honest .
smells of holiday cheer ! decently drinkable .  after a few sips , the burps from the fizzy carbonation began to set in .

a pint at island creek oyster bar in boston . black , nice head , good lace , good retention .  unfortunately , i think this is the best part of this beer - the smell is weak , neither raspberries or beer , but a lot like a mike 's hard cranberry . the taste was just as unimpressive - a lot like drinking water , and if it was n't for the slight ( and i mean slight ) buzz i caught off of it , i 'd swear i was drinking a watered down raspberry smoothy .

bottle : poured a bright golden color ale with a huge foamy head with good retention and great lacing .  it was watery and thin , but no off flavors - just a little adjunct flavor on top of the water , and lo and behold - i actually percieved a mild gummy hop bitterness and aroma ! i 'm used to seeing empty cans of these piled all over my brother 's sleeping body when i peak in on him most saturday mornings .
large creamy off white head . moderate head retention , heavy lacing .  mouthfeel , what mouthfeel ? watery .

pours into pint glass an amazing opaque pitch-black , with an exceptional creamy , bubbly light-brownish/tan head about a half-finger thick , leaving an impressive thick and sticky tan lacing .  mouthfeel was thin with a honey-like lager sweetness on the tongue .

almost bubblegum like nose , citrus , and coriander . a superb beer .  mouthfeel is medium-full bodied and the sweetness is just too much . none of the crispness or dryness that a saison should offer .

s : toffee , butterscotch , light caramel , molasses , and hints of diacetyl are what i notice immediately . everything is well integrated , though a bit lacking in the deeper caramelized malts that i would expect from such a noted scotch ale producer . t : a bit of a letdown after the nose . not nearly as complex , as a bit of roasted nutty caramel takes over the beer , leaving a bit of lingering bitterness .  i was a budweiser drinker for many years before getting into craft beers . its funny , after several months of nothing but good microbrewery beers , you 'd think your taste buds would have developed and you would notice a huge difference between bud and miller lite . and i have to give some props to miller lite after all these years of neglecting it in favor of budweiser .
exceptionally clear , bright yellow beer with a big fluffy white head that settled rapidly .  mouthfeel is pretty close to water .
pours out to a clear black , forming a good-sized dark brown head with very good retention and pretty , delicate sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is diluted by the alcohol content and lack of carbonation .
from memory ... a : muddy black , supple tan head that left some great lacing and a moderate cap throughout the tasting .  the mouthfeel is flat and not fun .
it looks great , with a big flaffy light tan head floating on the bronz brew , but i found it went down hill from there .  very watery . low carbonation .

pours a burnt orange colour with large cloudy haze and a lot of streaming bubbles . head is voluminous , beige , sinks unevenly on top , made up of small but visible bubbles . large clumps of lace around the glass .  mouthfeel is just way too carbonated to enjoy the beer , it makes it a bit too hard to drink .

pours opaque black with faint coffee . tan head that clears quickly , but leaves lots of lacing on the glass . watery taste up front , almost like a tap water taste .  unfortunately , the look and smell of this beer were the best part . it 's bland to the tongue , blah to the mouth . calling it kenya 's version of budweiser is too mean , but i could probably reproduce the flavor of this beer by mixing singha , budweiser , and water .
pours a hazy amber orange with lots of creamy , sudsy , fluffy white head 3+ inches .  .could benefit from slightly higher alcohol mouthfeel : thin . watery . .carbonation seems high .
pours a dark amber with a rediculous two finger head that sticks around and eventually leaves a crazy lacing .  mouthfeel is very watery .
extremely foggy light copper . excellent head retention .  m/d : very thin , and almost under carbonated . way to watery and lifeless . the sharp/astringent hops is to much , and too thin of a body .

got this at de bierkoning in amsterdam ... drank from a trappistes rochefort glass ... pour : one of the most beautiful colors i 've seen on a beer ... thick head with awesome lacing ... abundant carb ... smell : earthy tone ... hops and yeast ?  mouthfeel - medium light body , watery .
wonderfully sour pineapple-like aroma with some , but not overwhelming acetic character and lemons shining through .  mouthfeel is way too thin for a ris .
guinness extra stout pours black , with a tan head , that is large .  way too carbonated and pretty thin for the style .

that said , it poured a large invigorating tan head with fine-small bubbles into my glass .  i drank this from the tap into a snifter . the aroma does n't exist , ca n't smell anything.the taste is the same with hardly any flavor and its way to watery . all you can taste is a little hops .

this beer was poured from a 12 oz bottle into a tumbler , revealing a gorgeous orange amber color , with a 1/4 '' head that lasts a few minutes . a ; very subdued surprizingly .  quite a harsh carbonation which obscured what i think was actually a decent flavour , genuinely reminiscent of the belgian strong dark ale style .
sierra nevada bigfoot barleywine style ale 2010 pours a bright cherry color with a huge , almost too huge head .  palate is extremely watery and hurtingly bitter .
incredible appearance overall !  mouthfeel : indistinguishable from budweiser , not much thicker than water .
pours a brilliant , opaque mahogany color with a billowy tan head that retains impeccably .  carbonation on this is tough to handle for me . very fizzy .

what a good start s- strong piny citrus . smells like a hopheads dream t-woah tons of piny hops . i got this bottle very fresh .  ) the mouthfeel on this is watery and flat.. again an apple juice likeness . i would have preferred more carbonation and either a lighter or denser mouthfeel .

a : this brew looks phenomenal . almost completely black with a large light-brown creamy head that sat on top for a long while .  mouthfeel- thin and watery , carbonation is appropriate for a light beer .

cap date : 08.10.13 a : pours a beautiful hazelnut ale with exceptional clarity . 2 fingers of peanut skin skin foam falls soo slow and even then leaves a wonderful stack of quilted equivalence of the same . great resonance and the finish is silken . it 's really fine bubbles that create the exceptional feel .  mouthfeel- thin , watery with hard water , highly carbonated , low hopped , and medium light bodied .

lots of bead action from below , different sizes of bubbles racing each other to the top . the result is a slowly receding head that plants a solid layer of lace all around the glass .  quite thin bodied , bit of a hop bite , not too much else .

appearance : pours a hazy golden yellow color with a huge 3 '' + head that slowly fades .  whoa , i could only take a small sip at first , massive liquid smoke feeling in the mouthfeel . ugh . if you like smoked beers , then check this out .
deep , rich cloudy red with about two inches of foamy , off-white head that took a while to dissolve and left noticeable lacing on the snifter .  unsatisfying feel .
